<HEADLINE>
DRAFT DAY LIVES UP TO EXPECTATIONS FOR CLAIBORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ US cornerback Daylon McCutcheon had to wait about
six hours longer than teammate Chris Claiborne to hear he had been
drafted Saturday, but he was just as happy, after being selected as
the first pick in the third round by the Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the longest days of my life,'' McCutcheon said.
``It was long but it was exciting. I'm really happy.''
</P>
<P>
   McCutcheon spent the day watching the draft in Pasadena, and
wasn't sure when he would be selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew they were interested, but I didn't know they were more
interested than any other team,'' he said. ``It's a lot of pressure
off my chest.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Claiborne had a much less stressful day, hosting
about 30 friends and family at a swank West Los Angeles hotel.
Despite a couple of early trades that shook up the draft, Claiborne
was selected by the Detroit Lions with the ninth pick overall,
which was exactly where he had expected to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been calling lately. They tied me up all morning,''
Claiborne said. ``The good thing about Detroit is I can be on a
good team and be in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Claiborne was slated in some early mock drafts to go as
high as fourth, he wasn't complaining about going to Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've enjoyed the process because I'm able to fulfill my
dream,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Claiborne was also happy the Lions run a 4-3 defense similar to
USC's. He thinks he can start at middle linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger adjustment might be the cold weather he'll experience
for the first time in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always adjust. It doesn't matter,'' Claiborne said. ``It's
something new. It's something different.''
</P>
<P>
   It was impossible for even his closest friends to detect any
nerves from Claiborne on draft day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was real calm, considering what he was up against. It
wasn't like he was nervous,'' said former USC cornerback Brian
Kelly, who plays for the Tampa Bay Buccaneers and who attended the
draft party.
</P>
<P>
   Also in attendance was UCLA point guard Baron Davis, looking as
though he were taking mental notes for his own future party, should
he decide to enter the NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   McCutcheon's situation could be interesting. He is going to an
expansion team that will have plenty of veterans, but could start
rookie Tim Couch, the No.1 pick in the draft, at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Browns) have a great tradition,'' McCutcheon said. ``It
gives me a chance to go in there and prove we belong in the league.
Now it's up to me.''
</P>
<P>
   McCutcheon leaves Thursday for Cleveland's first mini-camp. As
for Claiborne, he has one more piece of business. He's having a
post-draft party Monday night at the Key Club in West Hollywood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
