<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL BOARD REFORM STILL A BIT WOBBLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID PARRISH  
 and JODIE SNYDER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly a year into the latest effort to reform the state agency
that polices doctors, officials at the Board of Medical Examiners
acknowledge that, on the surface at least, their performance to
date looks shaky.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's backlog of cases is at nearly 1,000 _ and growing.
Reports alleging physician misconduct are taking longer to resolve.
Some cases have been so poorly handled they must be reinvestigated.
</P>
<P>
   But to Claudia Foutz, executive director of the medical board,
those apparently negative indicators are actually evidence of a
turnaround for the troubled agency.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking charge of the medical board last May, Foutz said
she has struggled against a bureaucracy that favored quickness over
quality and found it easier to review medical charts than listen to
patients' concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to build this organization from the ground up,'' she
said. ``Now we have the infrastructure in place _ the quality is in
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, the agency has come under a steady stream
of criticism from legislators, good-government groups, patients and
even some doctors _ all charging that the Board of Medical
Examiners, or BOMEX, has not effectively policed errant physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Burke, executive director of Arizona Common Cause, said
that because of the state's high number of retirees _ who often
require more medical care _ and an aging baby-boomer population now
creeping into its senior years, it's important to have a competent
medical board.
</P>
<P>
   ``BOMEX is increasingly not there when people need it,'' Burke
said.
</P>
<P>
   To change such attitudes, Foutz said, she has imposed more
thorough and professional investigative standards. Three
experienced investigators were hired this month _ bringing the
total to seven _ all in an effort to improve the handling of
complaints made against Arizona's 14,500 licensed allopathic
physicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say, check back with us in a year to see what we have
accomplished,'' Foutz said.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for the problems at BOMEX to be remedied has been a
decadelong vigil.
</P>
<P>
   Three successive state auditor general reports have accused the
medical board of what amounted to regulatory malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent report _ released last September _ auditors
revealed that out of 117 cases reviewed, only four patients had
been interviewed. Complaints were not fully investigated, and the
board often issued toothless ``letters of concern'' to physicians
when stiffer disciplinary actions were warranted, the report
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1998 report, auditors did note some small
improvements from past reviews.
</P>
<P>
   The backlog of unresolved complaints _ 862 _ was high, but that
was a 40 percent drop from four years earlier. Also, the time it
took the medical board to resolve a complaint was down to an
average of 200 days _ still above the agency's stated goal of 180
days.
</P>
<P>
   Foutz said rebuilding the medical board has slowed the agency
down in the short term and has even reversed the modest
improvements cited in the 1998 audit.
</P>
<P>
   Since the audit, the backlog of complaints has climbed by 14
percent, to 984. Medical board staff members conceded the average
time to resolve cases is no longer 200 days cited in the September
audit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll guarantee you, we'll be above it,'' said Eric Nickell,
the board's compliance manager.
</P>
<P>
   Those in the Legislature watching Foutz and her impact said it
may take longer than a year to turn around an agency as
dysfunctional as the medical board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy to hear about a backlog of a thousand cases, but
I recognize things were in bad shape when she took over,'' said
Rep. Herschella Horton, D-Tucson, the ranking Democrat on the House
Health Committee. ``Two years is not too long to clean it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Susan Gerard, chairman of the Health Committee, also
expressed concern about BOMEX's increasing backlog and length of
time to resolve complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had basically a non-functioning system, so you have to
give them some time,'' said Gerard, R-north-central Phoenix. ``I
would definitely say in a year, if there is not significant
improvement in the backlog of cases and getting the case time under
200 days, then something would have to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to the resurgence in the backlog has been the
attention now being paid to the quality of the investigations,
Foutz said.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 completed investigations recently had to be reopened
for a more thorough review just before they were to be decided upon
by the agency's 12-member board.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have determined that under past leadership the way in which
cases were investigated, the way in which people were interviewed,
the choices of who to interview and who not to interview, are not
the standards that we apply today,'' Foutz said.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly 1,000 backlog cases _ all in various stages of review
_ also will have to be examined individually under the new
standards, said Thomas Adams, who was hired in January to head
BOMEX's enforcement operation after retiring from the Washington
State Police, where he oversaw the investigation division.
</P>
<P>
   The new investigative standards require _ among other things _
that all patients who make complaints be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past we were very good at doing record reviews, but we
were not very good at doing interpersonal contact and
information-gathering,'' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   After re-examining one complaint, they found that the wrong
doctor had been investigated in the case of a misdiagnosis of a
patient's cancer. Past investigations had zeroed in on the doctor
who referred the patient, even though it was the radiologist who
said there were no signs of cancer. A second radiologist did
discover the cancer, but it was too late for effective treatment,
and the patient died, Foutz said.
</P>
<P>
   Later this year, after the new investigators are at full speed,
the backlog of cases should be whittled down, Foutz said.
</P>
<P>
   But given the cumbersome legal structure and lean staffing
levels, she said, BOMEX won't be resolving complaints significantly
more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the vary nature of the regulatory design here in Arizona,
you have a built-in six-month delay,'' Foutz said.
</P>
<P>
   And the board's goal of resolving the average case in 180 days?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think 180 days is unrealistic, given the statutory
framework,'' Foutz said.
</P>
<P>
   That legal structure would be changed under House Bill 2487
before the Legislature, allowing the BOMEX executive director to
dismiss cases deemed meritless without sending them to the board.
</P>
<P>
   Because the board meets only six times a year, it often takes
four to six months to resolve even the simplest cases, Foutz said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which Gerard said seem likely to pass, also would give
the executive director the power in particularly serious instances
to send the case to an administrative hearing for a license
suspension or revocation &UR; _ without first having to get approval
from the agency's board.
</P>
<P>
   Burke of Common Cause said that ultimately the agency may be too
small to deal with a booming state population.
</P>
<P>
   ``Restructuring _ that's like rearranging the deck chairs on the
Titanic,'' Burke said. ``The real central issue is expanding their
personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   Foutz said that after restructuring issues are dealt with during
the current legislative session, she plans to approach the
Legislature next year to ask for more staff, something previous
executive directors have shied away from doing.
</P>
<P>
   Those monitoring the medical board's progress, like Horton, seem
willing to give Foutz some more time to make the necessary changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now I have confidence in her,'' Horton said. ``I'm not
ready to throw her out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
