<HEADLINE>
NO U.S. GROUND TROOPS, CANDIDATE FORBES SAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Steve Forbes joined the growing debate among GOP
presidential hopefuls on the critical question of what to do in
Kosovo, saying American ground troops should not be used in the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said Friday the United States should arm and train
Kosovar gue rillas to fight the ground war and continue the aerial
bombing cam paign. The ultimate goal of the war, he said, should be
the removal of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milo sevic and the
installation of a democratic government in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' comments came during a campaign stop in Arizona, a state
whose Republican primary he won in 1996. This time, however, he
faces an uphill battle, largely be cause Arizona Sen. John McCain
is in the GOP primary race. McCain has also become the most
forceful advocate of using American ground troops to end the war, a
move Forbes sees as foolish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should send in American ground forces,''
Forbes said. ``With proper leadership, we don't have to. You have
the Koso vars.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes comments came the same day that another presidential con
tender, Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, said that any intervention in the
Balkans _ by air or ground _ was not in the national interest.
Kasich made the comments in an op-ed piece in the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes argues that it would take four or five months to deploy
American soldiers, which would be enough time to train and equip
the Kosovar resistance. He ripped Presi dent Clinton for his
``drift and bad judgment'' in foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those that are skeptics, look what the Afghans did to the
Soviet Union on their own terrain when they were armed. That way,
the aggressors know they can't wear out a NATO peacekeeping
force,'' Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes was less specific when asked how military leaders would
ensure arming the ``right'' people and not extremist groups who
could end up further destabilizing the region. Many of the weapons
that the United States supplied to Af ghan rebels ended up in the
hands of terrorists throughout the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said the CIA and other intelligence agencies need to
deter mine whom to arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``You support those who are the real leaders. You have tens of
thousands people now willing to fight. They know what the stakes
are,'' Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experts tell us it's going to take four or five months to
put in ground troops, anyway. So instead of putting in Americans,
why not use the four months to train the people who know the
ground, have the motivation to fight. . . . They'll do the ground
fighting, and we'll fight them from the air.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidate downplayed con cerns that arming the resistance
would inflame tensions in the re gion, including in Russia, which
opposes the NATO action. Russia, Belarus and Serbia have talked in
recent days of forming a Slavic alliance to fight the West.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians also oppose arming the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said the actions need to be part of a diplomatic effort
to make it clear that all of Europe opposes the genocide of a
``murderous nationalist'' in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be a very positive impact on Russia and give
heart to the democratic reformers there,'' Forbes said. He said
Russian nation alists would soon get the message that the rest of
the world would ``pass them by.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And while the kleptomaniacs in the Kremlin and the old-line
com munists in the Duma can beat their chests about their brother
Slavs, remember _ Serbia is not even bordering Russia . . . and if
they want to beat their chests because they did it 50 years and 80
years ago over Serbia, then fine. But I think most Russians have
more pressing matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes chided other Republican candidates who were slow to take
a position on the war in Kosovo, including Texas Gov. George W.
Bush and former Transportation Secretary Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether Bush was being too reluctant to discuss
issues by avoiding the questions until after the Texas Legislature
adjourns, Forbes responded, ``The fact that you're asking the
question is the answer,'' Forbes said. ``Look at our Web site. Call
him up and say, `Where's yours, Governor?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bush led the GOP field in Arizona in a recent poll, beating
McCain by a margin of 9 points. Forbes was well back in the pack,
but he vows to hotly contest the state.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes also returned to his theme of tax cuts and tax reform
during his stop in Phoenix, pointing to his 1996 call for the flat
tax as evidence his campaign is setting the agenda this year.
Nearly every GOP candi date now has a plan for tax reform, Forbes
said.
</P>
<P>
   The publishing magnate is about to launch a major media campaign
next month in several early primary states, including Arizona, Iowa
and New Hampshire. Many Republicans criticized Forbes in 1996 for
spend ing millions in attack ads against the eventual GOP nominee,
Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said the ads are in produc tion. But he emphasized that,
while they would not be negative, the spots would spell out his
positions on issues and where other candi dates stand. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
