<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-RACE-FOR-THE-CURE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DAUGHTER FACES HER FEAR FOR MOTHER'S SAKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ I wasn't sure I really wanted to run in the
Race for the Cure yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   I ran because I am afraid of what will happen if I don't.
</P>
<P>
   Fear is strange like that, at once both motivating and
paralyzing a person.
</P>
<P>
   And there is no fear as motivational or as paralyzing as the
fear seen reflected in your mother's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   I know.
</P>
<P>
   For four years, it stared at me.
</P>
<P>
   The fear was of the body that had betrayed her. The fear was of
the cancer that ate away at her. The fear was of the chemotherapy
that they said would cure her.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, the fear was of dying, of becoming a statistic, of
becoming one of the thousands that cancer kills every year.
</P>
<P>
   She fought the fear every day.
</P>
<P>
   The fear became motivational for her. The woman who literally
wore out the phrase ``It's nothing I can't handle'' transformed
herself into a fighter.
</P>
<P>
   The fight was mostly subversive, as simple as a smile in the
waiting rooms she prepared to enter for chemotherapy, and yet as
hopeful as believing a cure was just a little activism away from
becoming a reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to find a cure,'' she'd say in a way that made
you really believe it was true.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't come in time for her, though.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Francis Paoletti Floyd died on June 8, 1997, after a
four-year battle with cancer. She was 50 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Her fears then became mine.
</P>
<P>
   My biggest fear is that one day it will be me.
</P>
<P>
   So, I ran yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   I ran through downtown Fort Worth with 12,000-plus other women.
It wasn't until I started running, though, that the enormity of the
disease hit me.
</P>
<P>
   I was surrounded by daughters and wives and sisters and mothers,
people just like me, people who were affected by cancer. The
reminders came in the pink signs pinned to their backs. There are
two kinds _ ``In memory of ... '' and ``In celebration of ... .''
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to remember those already gone and to celebrate
those still fighting.
</P>
<P>
   There were 22 names on the ``Star-Telegram'' sign I wore on my
back. Eleven are survivors. Eleven already had died. My mother was
just one of them.
</P>
<P>
   I found myself reading the names on other people's backs as I
passed by them. I wondered what their lives were like? How long had
they been sick? What was the doctor's prognosis? Did they still
have hope? Did their families?
</P>
<P>
   But they were, still, just names.
</P>
<P>
   So, I kept running yesterday, thinking it would be just like my
daily runs.
</P>
<P>
   And it was.
</P>
<P>
   Then at around the first-mile marker of the race, I passed a
woman in a pink T-shirt. Everybody gets a white T-shirt for
running. The pink T-shirts are special, reserved for survivors,
women who had or have the disease and are still fighting it.
</P>
<P>
   The sign on her back didn't have a name. It simply said: ``Seven
years cancer free.''
</P>
<P>
   I read that, and I wasn't quite as afraid.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of women out there still fighting, fighting the
disease, fighting the fear, fighting for themselves and fighting
for women like me.
</P>
<P>
   If my mom were still alive, I knew she'd be running. too.
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, I ran because I was afraid of what will happen if I
don't.
</P>
<P>
   I also ran because I could.
</P>
<P>
   I ran because by running, maybe one day, if I have a daughter
she won't have to.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Floyd is a sports writer for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
