<HEADER>
A3051 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     04-18 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS LOSING PATIENCE WITH WINLESS CLARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Doug Melvin's genius has given the Rangers
John Wetteland, Rick Helling and, at crunch time last year, Todd
Stottlemyre, a resume any general manager would be proud to own.
</P>
<P>
   If only he could hide Mark Clark under a rock somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin spent $9 million of Tom Hicks' money to sign the free
agent right-hander for two years when he couldn't lure Randy
Johnson or Roger Clemens to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   After his third consecutive pounding yesterday, this one at
Network Associates Coliseum, Clark is well on his way to being
Melvin's worst decision since: (a) extending John Burkett's
contract for two years or, (b) signing Kevin Gross.
</P>
<P>
   Can you say bust?
</P>
<P>
   The A's slapped Clark senseless in a four-run first inning en
route to an 11-3 victory over the Rangers. Whatever good feelings
the Rangers might have accumulated after a three-game sweep of the
Mariners have quickly dissipated in the bloody reality of two
merciless beatings here.
</P>
<P>
   This is particularly disturbing because the Rangers have now
seen every team in the AL West and they know they should dominate
this division.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, without Johnson, aren't half the team they once
were. The A's, despite what we've seen in the first two games here,
are still too young to contend. The Angels have their own Care
Flight helicopter standing by.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, if they were playing anywhere near their
capabilities, could have this division wrapped up by the All-Star
break.
</P>
<P>
   Instead they have seen their starting pitchers post a 3-6 record
with a 7.93 ERA while giving up four or more runs nine times in
their first 12 games. And the middle of their vaunted batting order
is producing more temper tantrums _ Juan Gonzalez sent a stack of
paper cups flying after struggling again in batting practice _ than
hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't just blame the pitching,'' second baseman Mark
McLemore pointed out. ``We still have to go out and score runs to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after the three-game sweep in Seattle the atmosphere around
the team has been strangely tense and uneasy. Manager Johnny Oates,
not bothering to hide his irritation, publicly questioned starting
pitcher Aaron Sele's pitch selection after Friday night's 8-2
shelling by the A's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some people are a little uptight,'' McLemore admitted.
``But I'm not sure it's the players.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager? Maybe so. But try standing in his shoes, watching
his starting pitchers put his team in a hole almost every time out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to figure out a way to play better from behind,''
Oates said reflectively. ``You can do that occasionally, but it's a
difficult thing to do every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the 11-3 beating, Oates was smiling and relaxed, a stark
contrast to Friday night's obvious unhappiness with Sele. There was
little reason to smile about Clark's performance, however.
</P>
<P>
   Signed because Melvin thought he would at least give the team
innings, Clark has failed to last beyond the fifth in any of his
three starts. That his earned-run average actually ``dropped'' to
10.68 yesterday after he allowed five runs in five innings tells
you all you need to know about the quality of those innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen much different in any of his three starts,''
Oates said. ``He's gone about five innings in each of them, thrown
about a hundred pitches. He's had a lot of 0-2 counts that turned
into deep counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Giambi hit the first of his two home runs on a hanging,
batting-practice slider to give the A's a 2-0 lead in the first.
Instead of closing the door there to keep his team in the game,
Clark softened again, allowing a single to John Jaha and walking
Ben Grieve. That set up Mike Macfarlane's two-run double off the
left-field fence on a pitch Clark said he put right where he wanted
it.
</P>
<P>
   So did Macfarlane.
</P>
<P>
   If the first was critical, the sixth was almost equally so.
Rafael Palmeiro's two-run homer in the top of the inning had cut
the A's lead to 5-3 and Oates asked his bullpen to hold it there.
No dice.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the left-handed hitters they have in the lineup, it's
a perfect opportunity for our left-handers to give us a couple of
innings and let us get back in the game,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Good idea, bad execution. The A's immediately put up a 3-spot
against Mike Munoz, the rout was on and Clark very deservedly took
his second loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I gave up the four runs in the first, I thought I
threw the ball much better today than I did in my first two
starts,'' Clark said. ``On this club, if you go out and keep the
club in the game, you're going to win a lot of games.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a good theory. Melvin, among others, might feel a
little better about that $9 million if he'd put it into practice.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
