<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEPT OUT BY A RIPTIDE OF VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shortly before 9 a.m. Saturday, a firetruck loaded with portable
stadium lights, each folded in half like an enormous silver tulip,
slowly pulls away from the 54th Street exit of the Sierra Palms
apartment complex in Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   Just inside the high block walls lining the street are the
garages, carports and parking spaces for the complex's numbered
buildings, stacked like hotels in a Monopoly game.
</P>
<P>
   Yellow plastic police tape stretches from parking spot No. 348
past spot 360, angling over vehicles and around the trunks of newly
planted trees, keeping the curious away.
</P>
<P>
   Technicians and investigators move in and out of a downstairs
apartment, some carrying bags, which they place in nearby police
vans, others with camera equipment and light stands.
</P>
<P>
   They've been here all night, and the muted talk among them is
about packing up and getting a little breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be a chance to spend some time together away from the
scene, and talk. Or not talk.
</P>
<P>
   An elderly woman walks along the curving sidewalk next to the
building and approaches a man with a press badge pinned to his
shirt.
</P>
<P>
   With one hand she manipulates a wooden cane. In the other she
carries a package of disposable children's diapers. Around her neck
is small necklace made of sea shells.
</P>
<P>
   ``They called me from the office yesterday afternoon,'' she
says. ``I baby-sit my grandchildren, you know, and my husband was
at the grocery store. They told me to lock up and wait. I heard a
boom and a loud commotion. I suppose that's when the officer was
killed. Do you know how old he was?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-eight, she is told.
</P>
<P>
   He had three children and a grandchild. His name was Jim
Snedigar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll pray for him,'' she says. ``I suppose that's all we can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Another resident of the complex, Andy Weis, cautiously
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   He'd spent most of the evening outside the complex's walls,
where officers kept residents while they searched for jewel thieves
trying to lose themselves in the maze of pink stucco and twisting
sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   They found one in the apartment where Snedigar was shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only been here two months,'' Weis says. ``I came out here
to get away from the city. Guess it didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   People visit a place like this the day after a tragedy because
they want explanations.
</P>
<P>
   Only there are none, or at least none that make sense in the
face of a second police funeral in less than a month.
</P>
<P>
   Still, something about what happened must be explained, so they
go to the spot where it happened. A few weeks ago it was an
industrial park in west Phoenix where Phoenix Officer Marc Atkinson
was fatally shot.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's this apartment complex in Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, this land was pristine desert. Initially, it was
carved into rectangles and transformed into farmland. It stayed
that way for years, until the fields were replanted with houses and
apartments, which sprout up in rows of pink stucco buildings with
red tile roofs.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Palms has the look of a medieval city, walled and gated
and set off from the surrounding countryside.
</P>
<P>
   There's a McDonald's restaurant at 56th Street and Ray Road. And
a Circle K across the street. And a Club Disney nearby. And Danny's
Family Carousel car wash. But there is no neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The outskirts of Phoenix are surrounded by walled enclaves like
this, each built for privacy and protection, its block walls
butting up against roads and freeways. Which lead to downtown.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the city's ocean laps against suburbia's
shoreline, its rising tide swallowing a little more peace and quiet
each day.
</P>
<P>
   More on some days than others.
</P>
<P>
   Too much on Friday, when a sudden wave of violence swept onto
the beach and dragged a good man out to sea. &QL; 
 &UR; E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
