<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-CARDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFENSE IN SPOTLIGHT ON 1ST DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - They had just settled into their seats in the
draft room Saturday morning when Indianapolis threw a haymaker
Cardinals officials.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts bypassed Heisman Trophy winner Ricky Williams and
chose the player the Cardinals expected to get _ Miami running back
Edgerrin James.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of panicking _ trading away the eighth pick overall
_ the Cardinals stayed put and performed a rebounding exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   They took the best wide receiver available, Ohio State's David
Boston, and then watched as Eastern Michigan offensive tackle L.J.
Shelton slipped closer and closer to them with their second
first-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   Once Seattle, picking 20th overall, traded the selection to
Dallas, which was seeking defensive help, the Cardinals knew they
were going to get Shelton with the next pick.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ferguson, vice president-player personnel, celebrated by
waving his arms over his head like a winning prize fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it could have turned out any better,''
Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals then added Florida linebacker Johnny Rutledge in
the second round and Wisconsin pass rusher Tom Burke, who led the
nation with 21 sacks, in the third.
</P>
<P>
   With seven more picks in Rounds 4-7 today, it's too early to
grade the draft. But Gary Horton, former NFL scout who is the
editor of the ``War Room'' draft publication, gives the Cardinals
high marks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, they look like smart sons of guns,'' Horton said.
``What they did was just great. They not only know their own
(draft) board, but they have a feel for other teams' boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at both of their first-round picks and you can see
that they know the strengths and weaknesses of the draft. As much
as I like (Brigham Young offensive tackle) John Tait, had they
taken him, they wouldn't have gotten a wide receiver at Number
21.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals considered taking Tait with the eighth pick after
the Colts shocked everybody by taking James.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Rams then made another surprising move when they
passed on Georgia cornerback Champ Bailey, considered the top
defensive player in the draft, to take North Carolina State wide
receiver Torry Holt, a favorite of the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were disappointed in some ways earlier today because we
thought we would get a shot at one of those top guys,'' Ferguson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals listened to two offers to move down from the
eighth pick, including one from Minnesota, which picked 11th and
coveted Arizona cornerback Chris McAlister.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals officials debated whether to take Tait, the Tempe
McClintock High School product, or Boston until the final three
minutes they were on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know whether to take a Butterfinger or a Baby Ruth,''
Ferguson said. ``Then, I did what I always to _ I took a
Butterfinger.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson described the decision as ``very, very difficult,
particularly since the team is looking for a young left tackle to
replace starter Lomas Brown, who left in free agency for Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we (had) a great need for an offensive lineman and
there was a great player (Tait) sitting there who wanted to be a
Cardinal,'' Ferguson said. ``But you have to be able to score to
win. If you don't have a shooting guard, you won't win basketball
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to build an exciting football team. We want to have an
explosive offense. . . . The decision came down to who is going to
score touchdowns. We've added 50 pages to our playbook in getting a
player like this guy. This gives us many weapons to possibly win a
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals think Boston, who averaged 120.9 yards receiving
last season, is fast enough to stretch defenses. He recently was
timed in the 40-yard dash in 4.7 seconds. He also could be their
punt returner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see my role being the domino-type (role) of Randy Moss at
Minnesota and how he complemented Jake Reed and Cris Carter,'' said
Boston, 6 feet 2, 208 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said the Cardinals had Boston, a 20-year-old junior who
turned pro with a year of eligibility remaining, rated almost even
with Holt.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very, very close,'' Tobin said. ``Holt is a guy who
has done it for one more year, his senior year. He is a little bit
more mature than David Boston, but, really, David Boston has more
measurables than Torry Holt. He's bigger and stronger and he's
faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like Ricky Williams and Edgerrin James. It's a
kind of pick-'em type thing, depending on who you talk with.''
</P>
<P>
   Valley sports fans remember Boston. His game-winning catch beat
Arizona State and quarterback Jake Plummer in the Rose Bowl three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Boston recently listed Plummer, now starting quarterback as the
Cardinals, as the opposing player he most respected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I never had been on the same field with somebody who
showed the amount of composure and type of leadership he showed in
(the Rose Bowl),'' Boston said.
</P>
<P>
   After the Boston pick, Ferguson assured Cardinals fans he hadn't
forgotten about the offensive line. ``We will find an offensive
tackle,'' he said. ``I'll stake my job on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals, who had rated Shelton second at offensive tackle
on their draft board, thought they might have a chance to get him
after the Oakland Raiders chose Georgia offensive tackle Matt
Stinchcomb at No. 18 and the New York Giants took Notre Dame
offensive tackle Luke Petitgout with the next selection.
</P>
<P>
   During the next 30 minutes, the Cardinals received six calls to
trade the 21st pick _ four to move down and two to move up.
</P>
<P>
   They again stayed put and took Shelton, 6-5, 322 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you guys can't accuse me of being a defensive coach after
drafting two offensive guys in the first round,'' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals used their top two selections on offensive players
for the first time since 1993. They hadn't taken a wide receiver
first since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting (Shelton) was a really big hit, and I think we got a
hell of a player,'' Ferguson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-99 0054EDT &QL; 
