r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-SHELTON-AZR     04-18 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-SHELTON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TACKLE ATE WAY OUT OF 1ST LOVE - BASKETBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ - L.J. Shelton, newest contender to become guardian
of Jake Plummer's backside, didn't make it to professional sports
with his long shot but as a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   Until his senior year in high school, Shelton, who was chosen
21st overall by the Cardinals in the NFL draft on Saturday, fancied
himself as a shooting guard. He was adept at jacking up
three-pointers and dreamed of a career in the NBA, just like his
dad, Lonnie Shelton, a 10-year power forward who was on the Seattle
SuperSonics 1979-80 world championship team.
</P>
<P>
   Although an all-area prep pick in basketball-rich Michigan his
senior year, Shelton had grown to 250 pounds on a 6-foot-5 frame.
He loomed rather large in the backcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more football scholarships available than basketball
scholarships,'' Shelton said. ``There comes a time when you have to
make a decision about the way you want to go with your life.''
</P>
<P>
   He was just looking for a free ride to college. He never
imagined he would develop into a first-round NFL draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are excited that he yielded to ``natural
selection,'' as Shelton describes it, and traded in the sneakers
for shoulders pads at Eastern Michigan. He developed quickly as an
offensive left tackle and became something of a natural selection
for the Cardinals on Saturday. They have a need after seven-time
Pro Bowler Lomas Brown bolted to Cleveland via free agency and had
Shelton rated higher than two left tackles who were chosen just
ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have two other prospects at Shelton's position but
neither, to borrow a phrase from Shelton's past sports life, is a
slam dunk. Anthony Clement, the largest player ever drafted by the
Cardinals (6-7, 355), was selected in the second round last year to
be groomed as Brown's successor. Then Clement, who didn't miss a
snap in college, suffered a herniated disk that required surgery.
He missed all of 1998. It remains to be seen how effectively he
will come back. He has not yet been cleared for the minicamp that
opens April 29, offensive line coach George Warhop said.
</P>
<P>
   Also on hand is Matt Joyce, who continues to improve but who
never has played regularly at left tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton will have an opportunity to leap to the front of the
line when training camp opens July 30 in Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they have a promising guy at quarterback in Jake
Plummer, so I'm honored that they trust me to protect his blind
side,'' Shelton said.
</P>
<P>
   After the reality sank in that he wasn't going to be the next
Reggie Miller, Shelton began knocking the stuffing out of defensive
ends around the Mid-American Conference. In 33 successive starts he
made 25 touchdown blocks, 69 downfield blocks and averaged an 85
percent blocking efficiency per season.
</P>
<P>
   Further, as the protector of quarterback Charlie Batch's
backside, Shelton was on the field for 2,312 snaps and gave up only
eight sacks in a passing offense.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton said that five-years of weightlifting and indiscriminate
training-table dining allowed him to bulk to 322 pounds from 250 _
``a natural selection thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My body just grew,'' he said. ``When I weighed 250 I knew I
had the frame to hold more weight. I've kept my mobility and
agility.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to rough up the best of the MAC, but NFL scouts
weren't convinced he was big-time until they observed him in a week
of practice at the Senior Bowl, where Shelton made the best
defensive prospects look like just another MAC pass rusher. His
draft projection skyrocketed.
</P>
<P>
   He was regarded as the second-best left tackle in the draft to
Tempe native John Tait, who was chosen 14th overall by Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   But tackles Matt Stinchcomb of Georgia and Luke Petitgout of
Notre Dame were chosen 18th and 19th by Oakland and the New York
Giants, respectively just before the Cardinals grabbed Shelton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to keep calm,'' Shelton said. ``I knew I had a rating
above those guys. It was just God doing his work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals thought so, too. Warhop breathed more easily when
Tampa Bay did not choose an offensive lineman at No. 15, and then
Seattle didn't at No. 20. That coupled with the Raiders' and
Giants' somewhat surprising picks set up the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of what you like,'' Warhop said. ``There
were a bunch of tackles who were so close together in rating. As I
was watching it unfold, I said, `Please, God, let one of them be
there at 21.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ferguson, Cardinals vice president for player personnel,
gushed about Shelton's size, footwork and athleticism. The caveat
is that Shelton played only three games of football in high school
and 33 in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't played football that much but he's smart, he's
tough, he's got a nasty streak _ things we like that are going to
help him become a good pro,'' Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton said the mean streak comes from his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a mean player, and I like to emulate the way he
approached the game, which was with a lot of intensity,'' Shelton
said. ``I like to model myself after him in that way. But at the
same time, he had to watch out for technicals. I can just let it
go.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-99 0055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
