<HEADER>
A3056 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-BICKLEY-AZR     04-18 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICKS AFFECT TEAM, STADIUM, FER GUSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - On Friday night, Bob Ferguson didn't sleep.
</P>
<P>
   He strolled around a lake near his home in Gilbert, smoking a
cigar. He listened to the words of his wife, imploring him to come
to bed. And even when he relented, rest was fleeting.
</P>
<P>
   There is more to his job than you ever want to know.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Cardinals strung together another wonderful
draft. An exercise in risk and recovery. Made possible by another
stroke of fortune, an organization continuing its long waltz with
Lady Luck.
</P>
<P>
   But if you ever wanted to see the dynamics of a unique family
facing a daunting and daring future, this was the day.
</P>
<P>
   All afternoon, they disappeared and reappeared. Ferguson with
deep bags under his eyes. Mr. Beige dressed in black. Bill Jr.
crewcut replaced with rebellious long hair. Michael in jeans and an
ever-present beeper. And, of course, the old man, the picture of
calm. All wearing stickers saying ``YES! to Rio Salado''.
</P>
<P>
   A five-headed monster reaching consensus on four picks arising
from three intertwined futures. And it was the tenuous start that
opened the windows to an organization.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the phones and rolling the dice, they selected a wide
receiver _ Ohio State's David Boston _ with the No. 8 pick. They
had passed on Chris Claiborne, a linebacker who would've closed the
book on Jamir Miller. And they passed on John Tait, an offensive
lineman whom Ferguson loved, one who could be a genuine superstar
at left tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very player sitting there that wants to be a Cardinal as
much as I do in the future,'' Ferguson said at the time. ``It will
be debatable in the next few weeks, by the way . . .''
</P>
<P>
   As Ferguson explained the pick, he immediately pointed to a pair
of drawings decorating the room. Colorful renditions of the Rio
Salado Project propped up on easels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to have this,'' Ferguson said. ``These aren't just
pictures of something we want. To look at and wish will come true
one day. All of this is designed.''
</P>
<P>
   David Boston, pizzazz pick. Designed to stoke the voters.
</P>
<P>
   Three different futures: The new stadium. The football team. And
that of Ferguson, whose contract expires next month.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to build an exciting football team here, and we're
going to have an explosive offense to run the engine,'' Ferguson
said. ``Now, we can line up as well as Minnesota.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, before he was done:
</P>
<P>
   ``We will find an offensive tackle,'' Ferguson pledged. ``I'll
stake my job on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Cardinals got lucky. In the matter of three
hours, a thorny debate had disappeared. A bizarre abundance of
quarterbacks pushed down the talent. The Raiders and the Giants
chose a pair of tackles that inspired no one. L.J. Shelton, a
tackle rated just behind Tait by most experts, had slipped all the
way to No. 21.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals pounced, and everyone walked away happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it could've worked out much better,'' Coach
Vince Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that more problems don't exist. They must sign Miller. Like,
yesterday. They must stay ahead of the suddenly surging Redskins,
who took advantage of Mike Ditka's infatuation with Ricky Williams.
By sending the Redskins seven draft picks, four of whom they
shipped to the Bears in order to acquire cornerback Champ Bailey,
Ditka immediately altered the future of the NFC East.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Redskins are ecstatic, and they probably should be,''
Ferguson said. ``But I'd like to see David Boston vs. Champ Bailey
any day of the week. And we're going to get a chance to see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside every war room _ one of the worst cliches in sport _
there is dissenting opinion, mixed agendas, battles over whom to
select. But the Cardinals are different. Theirs is an interlocking
of three futures. The combination worked on Saturday, a cooperative
effort that might be an important step in the evolution of a
dinosaur.
</P>
<P>
   The football team made off fine. The draft can only help Rio
Salado. But in the long run, the future of Ferguson might be the
most important issue facing the team. One that's finally turned the
corner. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
