<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3058 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-CASSTEVENS-     04-18 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAFT DAY A SUCCESS, BUT AREN'T THEY ALL? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - The Arizona Cardinals tried to trade their top
draft choice to Mesa for 5,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   When that failed, the team invested in its future by selecting a
fast young wide receiver and a left tackle as big as Eastern
Michigan, where he played.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Tobin, wearing a ``Rio Salado Crossing ``Yes''!'' button,
announced he was pleased with the choice of Ohio State's David
Boston. He was just as happy with L.J. Shelton, who measures
6-foot-5 and weighs 322 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ferguson, also wearing a Rio Salado button, emerged from the
draft room and thrust his arms into the air like a prize fighter
who had just scored a first-round knockout.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, he said, has ``great hands'', which is a plus for a
receiver. Shelton is blessed with ``great feet'' and ``a nasty
streak.''
</P>
<P>
   Head coach and player personnel director felt good about what
they had done, so much so they made a brief appearance on stage at
the Cardinals' draft party at the Rockin' Rodeo nightclub in Tempe.
Some fans had been watching big-screen TV coverage of the NFL draft
since 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Fans cheered and toasted their arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Vince nor Bob had to duck flying beer bottles, further
evidence that the Cardinals are far more popular than in years past
and a sign that their draft strategy met with public approval.
</P>
<P>
   It is too soon to grade the Cards' performance, although the
media is obligated. This is the age of instant coffee. Instant
pudding. Instant analysis.
</P>
<P>
   So here is mine. Even though they didn't get either player they
wanted with the No. 8 pick (Indianapolis beat them to running back
Edgerrin James; St. Louis got receiver Torry Holt) the Cardinals
deserve high marks.
</P>
<P>
   Boston can back up Frank Sanders and Rob Moore. More
importantly, the Ohio State receiver who is only 20 years old gives
the offense the flexibility of using more three wide-out sets.
Boston also returns punts, filling another need.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton was rated the second-best tackle in the draft, and he
was the best one available when the Cardinals picked again at No.
21.
</P>
<P>
   The guess here is that most Cardinals fans will endorse the
additions because they favor any personnel moves designed to
protect Jake Plummer and help him succeed.
</P>
<P>
   This was by all accounts a wonderfully successful draft. Of
course, they all are, aren't they?
</P>
<P>
   Every spring, every team selects the players it wants. Every
team addresses its needs. Every team is upgraded, improved. To my
knowledge, not one NFL coach or general manager ever stood before
the public and said, haltingly, ``I . . . I don't know what to say.
We ``really'' screwed up. I'm deeply sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Cardinals, and for every NFL team, draft day is the
happiest day of the year. The Cleveland Browns started the fun by
selecting Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch. Team president Carmen
Policy said Tim is a ``solid human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Next up, Philadelphia also chose a quarterback. Eagles Coach
Andy Reid called Donovan McNabb ``a fine person.''
</P>
<P>
   On and on it went. As one team after another offered
testimonials to the high character of its top selectee, one began
to wonder how many, if any, model citizens would be left on the
board by the time Arizona's turn came.
</P>
<P>
   The Cards might be forced to draft the Best Available Athlete
without regard to his citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin knew whatever they did couldn't create the excitement the
New Orleans Saints provided. Trading up to get the fifth pick, the
Saints selected Texas running back Ricky Williams, the Heisman
Trophy winner. To get him, New Orleans happily gave Washington _
which drove a hard bargain _ all of the Saints draft picks this
year, plus their first and third next year, along with a Mardi Gras
float and 200 pounds of shrimp remoulade from Antoine's restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   As the Cards patiently waited to make their first pick, Mike
Ditka appeared on ESPN. Dressed in a brightly colored sports shirt
and smugly puffing a footlong cigar, the Saints coach looked as if
he could have been vacationing in Honolulu.
</P>
<P>
   Ditka had said all along Williams was ``the'' player he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things happen for a reason,'' Iron Mike said, thankfully
stopping short of _ yet coming the closest of any NFL coach in this
draft _ suggesting it was God's will. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at (602) 444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
