<HEADER>
A3060 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DRAFT-ARIZONANS-A     04-18 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-ARIZONANS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-DAY NOT A GAMBLE FOR SOME  
 MCALISTER, TAIT GO IN TOP 14 PICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - For Chris McAlister and John Tait, D-Day offered
potential wealth and no big surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Who said the NFL Draft was a crap shoot?
</P>
<P>
   The where and when almost came up like loaded dice for
McAlister, a University of Arizona cornerback, and Tait, an
offensive tackle from Brigham Young University who played at
Tempe's McClintock High School.
</P>
<P>
   McAlister figured to go among the first 10. Sure enough, the
Baltimore Ravens picked him at No. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Tait's agent, Eric Metz, figured he'd go between Nos. 10 and 15.
The Kansas City Chiefs took him at No. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Two more players from the state, center Grey Ruegamer and
fullback Jeff Paulk of Arizona State, went in the third round.
Ruegamer went to Miami as the No. 72 pick overall. Paulk, also of
Tempe's Corona Del Sol High, went to Atlanta as the 92nd pick
overall.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-5, 304-pound Ruegamer is noted for his aggressiveness and
versatility. Aggressiveness is also Paulk's trademark. At ASU, the
6-1, 250-pound back was nicknamed ``Jurassic Paulk.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the McAlister and Tait picks, there were some of the
speculative winds that regularly blow through these draft
proceedings. McAlister had talked to the St. Louis Rams, who had
the No. 6 pick, and to Arizona Cardinals, who held No. 8.
</P>
<P>
   The Cards were tempted by Tait, whom some scouts and fans still
think was their best bet to protect quarterback Jake Plummer. Tait
was still on the Cards' board three minutes before they announced
they would take Ohio State receiver David Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But, in the end, both teams and players were happy. Everybody
seemed to get what they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   For McAlister, that appears to be a starting job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any intention of stepping in and not starting,''
McAlister said. ``I plan to play my best ball and earn the job.''
</P>
<P>
   McAlister's hopes are bolstered by a philosophy held by Ravens
owner Art Modell, who told the ``Baltimore Sun'' that he expects a
first-round pick to start as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   With McAlister, the Ravens are expected to move veteran
cornerback Rod Woodson to safety, while second-year player Duane
Starks will line up at the corner opposite of the 6-foot-1,
206-pound McAlister.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens weren't scared away when news of an old charge for
petty theft during McAlister's 1995 season at Mount Sacramento
Junior College (Walnut, Calif.) resurfaced. He appeared in court
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens also took McAlister despite an evident need for
offense. Last season, they finished last in the AFC in total
offense. They took cornerback Starks in last year's draft, also
with the 10th pick.
</P>
<P>
   The motivation behind the Ravens' choice was clear. They
couldn't resist McAlister, a 1998 first team All-American who has
the size, speed and strength to be a ``so-called impact player.''
</P>
<P>
   McAlister's 18 interceptions rank third in UA history. He is
only the seventh player in college football to ever return a
kickoff, punt and interception for a touchdown in the same season.
</P>
<P>
   Some scouts say he could be the next Ronnie Lott.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: He and Tait will be among football's next
generation of wealthy men.
</P>
<P>
   Based on last year's rookie contracts, McAlister can expect a
four-year deal that is worth at least the $9.5 million landed by
Starks.
</P>
<P>
   For Tait, the ballpark expectation is the $8.56 million package
that Carolina gave to Jason Peter, last year's No. 14 pick from
Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-6, 317-pound Tait was the first offensive lineman taken.
His size, agility and evident maturity _ he spent 1997-98 on a
church mission _ was very tempting for the Cardinals, who wound up
taking Eastern Michigan tackle L.J. Shelton at No. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got their tackle a little bit lower and a receiver,''
Metz said. ``It's a subjective process, and they went with who they
liked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're biased, and we think Jake would be lot better
having John Tait protect his back side than the Eastern Michigan
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   All along, Kansas City showed interest in Tait, who went
shopping for a Chiefs cap after he was picked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They spent a lot of time with him at the Senior Bowl and at
private workouts following that,'' Metz said. ``They were really
hoping for a shot at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they would do anything to get this guy. They said he
could be a 12-year starter. They were pretty clear-cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Time will be the real test, Tait said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years from now, if people say John Tait was the best
offensive lineman in the draft, I'd be happy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tait could move into the Chiefs line opposite their first pick
last year, Victor Riley, who started as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like a great fit with a great organization,'' Metz
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-99 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
