<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3064 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DRAFT-SCHOENFELD-     04-18 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAFT-DAY BLITZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Five teams that &QL; 
 &UR; improved the most &QL; 
 &UR; 1. Washington Redskins: Love that trade with cigar-smoking
beach-bum Mike Ditka, coach of the New Orleans Saints. He might
have saved a franchise that is ownerless and has a coach (Norv
Turner) and general manager (Charley Casserley ) who could be
headed out of town. The Redskins got the player they wanted,
Georgia cornerback Champ Bailey, and much of the Saints' draft this
year and next.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2. Detroit Lions: They watched teams deal above them and then
stayed pat and took Southern California linebacker Chris Claiborne,
one of the top players in the draft. Then, they moved up into the
first round in a trade with Miami and were able to get massive
offensive lineman Aaron Gibson of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 3. Chicago Bears: Sure, they got lucky. But after years of
being the bumbling Bears, who's complaining? Still, if Indianapolis
doesn't bypass Ricky Williams and Washington doesn't trade down
with New Orleans, the Bears could have had a disastrous draft. But
then they made a deal with Washington, got four of the seven picks
the Redskins obtained from New Orleans and still got the
quarterback they were desperate to have _ UCLA's Cade McNown.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 4. Cardinals: Passing on Brigham Young offensive tackle John
Tait at No. 8, or at least not trading down and then taking him,
was risky. But when Eastern Michigan offensive tackle L.J. Shelton
was there at No. 21, everything fell perfectly. Earlier, they got a
speedy wide receiver (Ohio State's David Boston) to give
quarterback Jake Plummer another weapon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 5. St. Louis Rams: Coach Dick Vermeil is another coach who
better win, especially after they got Indianapolis running back
Marshall Faulk in a trade and North Carolina State wide receiver
Torry Holt at No. 6 overall. Nobody improved more at the skill
positions. &QL; 
 &UR; Five teams &QL; 
 &UR; that stagnated &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 1. Philadelphia Eagles: Unless the Eagles are putting in the
veer offense, Donovan McNabb was not the choice with the second
pick overall. Eagles fans said it best, as they chanted, ``We want
Ricky (Williams),'' for an hour before the draft.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 2. New England Patriots: Who's going to start at running back?
The Patriots, who had two first-round picks, had to get a back with
one of them. Instead, they got a center and a middle linebacker.
Finally, with their third selection, they got LSU runner Kevin
Faulk.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 3. Oakland Raiders: Their needs were outside linebacker,
defensive end, running back and quarterback, yet for the second
year in a row, they took an offensive tackle. Georgia's Matt
Stinchcomb will fill the Oakland-Alameda County Stadium. Or is that
the Rose Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 4. Minnesota Vikings: Central Florida quarterback Daunte
Culpepper won't help the Vikings get the Super Bowl. He's a two- to
three-year project. Why didn't they take a cornerback with their
other first-round pick? The Vikings, usually brilliant on draft
day, outsmarted themselves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 5. (Tie) New York Jets: Love their first-round pick. Hope Coach
Bill Parcells was worth it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; San Diego Chargers: Love their first-rounder, which went to the
Cardinals in last year's trade that brought Arizona Andre Wadsworth
and others. Chargers fans can't say, ``See you next year.'' Tampa
Bay has their 2000 first-round pick. &UR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Best trade &QL; 
 &UR; Washington: Getting New Orleans' first-, third-, fourth-, fifth-,
sixth- and seventh-round picks this year and Nos. 1 and 3 next
year. They will have three first-round picks next season unheard of
in the league. The Redskins then traded back up with the Bears and
got Bailey at seventh overall. &QL; 
 &UR; Worst trade &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans: See above. What was Ditka thinking? He mortgaged
the franchise for Williams. &QL; 
 &UR; Best pick &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bears were afraid they would have to take McNown with the
seventh pick overall and get ripped. They got him at No. 12 and
also a bushel of draft picks from the Redskins. &QL; 
 &UR; Worst pick &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis never should have taken Miami running back Edgerrin
James fourth overall. Trade down, if you want him that badly. The
Colts traded away Faulk and bypassed Williams. They could hear
about it for years. &QL; 
 &UR; High-dive award &QL; 
Florida linebacker Jevon Kearse, projected to be a top-10 pick,
slipped to Tennessee at No. 16. &QL; 
 &UR; Wish-I-had-laid &UR; -off-the-donuts award &QL; 
Williams, the Heisman Trophy winner, was considered the top player
in the draft before the season, yet got overweight and slipped to
No. 5. &QL; 
Steve Schoenfeld can be reached at (602) 444-8334 or at
steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
