<DOCNO> NYT19990418.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3065 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-STARS-AZR     04-18 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-STARS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES PULL OUT HARD FOUGHT VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - They've played here before, but considering the
circumstances, maybe it shouldn't have come as a surprise that when
they blasted the cannons just prior to the pre-game introductions
at America West Arena, a few of the Dallas Stars players
instinctively ducked.
</P>
<P>
   There weren't too many places to hide once the puck dropped,
either, in a penalty-filled, emotionally charged and taxing game
Saturday that saw the Coyotes literally pound out a 2-0 victory
over the new team they love to hate the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough not being out there today,'' said Dallas Drake,
the Coyotes' gritty, do-anything right wing, who was given the day
off by Coach Jim Schoenfeld. ``In a game like that, it's pretty
hard to hold your emotions back _ even from where I was sitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You bet I wanted to be involved, especially after seeing Keith
(Tkachuk) out there fighting, but there's no reason for me to be
out there running somebody and then risk being out for the first
couple playoffs games.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing in their final regular-season game before opening a
best-of-seven series at home against St. Louis on Thursday, the
Coyotes (39-31-12) let it all hang out in a four-hour marathon that
featured 31 penalties, 119 penalty minutes, two game misconducts
and six 10-minute misconducts.
</P>
<P>
   It also included a whopping 64 hits and several tense moments
when one almost got the feeling veteran referee Terry Gregson might
pull the plug and end the game early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the game was really on the brink of getting out
of control,'' said Schoenfeld, who guided the Coyotes to the
second-best finish (90 points) in their 20-year history. ``There
were some hard hits, but I don't think it was a situation where
there ever was a danger of a bench-clearing brawl.''
</P>
<P>
   That's debatable, especially after Stars goalie Eddie Belfour
inexplicably skated out near center ice during a break and daringly
slew-footed Coyotes captain Tkachuk, who had his back turned at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cross checked me,'' Belfour said, explaining why he did it.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour got nailed with a two-minute minor for tripping and a
10-minute misconduct. He later picked up another minor for
cross-checking Tkachuk twice in the back, which led Tkachuk to turn
around, swing a flurry of punches at Belfour's face mask and then
clean the clock of Dallas defenseman Darryl Sydor, who had jumped
in to protect the goalie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did what I did. I'm glad I did it,'' Tkachuk said, noting
Sydor paid the punishment for Belfour's crime. ``Yeah, I saw
Belfour's face on Sydor's head.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Reichel and role player Stephen Leach accounted for the
scoring, Reichel burying a second-period, one-timer with the
Coyotes enjoying a two-man advantage, and Leach tapping in a Juha
Ylonen feed in the third, in which the crowd let Belfour have it
with mocking chants.
</P>
<P>
   The league-leading Stars (51-18-12), whom Phoenix could meet in
the second round if both teams advance, were booed lustily
throughout the game by the spirited crowd of 15,836. The loudest
chorus came when the pre-game scratches were announced and Derian
Hatcher's name was heard.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Hatcher learned he was suspended for seven
games for his controversial hit last Wednesday that prematurely
ended Jeremy Roenick's season and left the Coyotes star center with
a shattered jaw.
</P>
<P>
   The swollen-faced Roenick watched the game from the stands and
probably wasn't surprised that the first period featured only 310
seconds of five-on-five hockey and just 396 seconds of the same in
the second. And Belfour's 14 minutes of penalties?
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't surprise me about Eddie,'' Roenick said of his
former Chicago Blackhawks teammate. ``Eddie's a rambunctious kind
of guy. He's a different bird.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour's antics nearly overshadowed the solid play in nets from
his All-Star counterpart, Nikolai Khabibulin, who stopped all 27
shots he faced in recording his eighth shutout _ a club record _
while also improving to 32-23-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good way for me to end the season and go into
playoffs,'' said Khabibulin, whose performance helped the Coyotes
snap a five-game losing streak. ``At the same time, I don't think
we should get too excited about this because they didn't play a lot
of their better players. But we did have a good team effort, and we
played pretty good defense, I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Coach Ken Hitchcock rested his four leading scorers. Joe
Nieuwendyk and the Stars' entire No. 1 line of center Mike Modano
and wingers Brett Hull and Jere Lehtinen were healthy scratches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
