r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-CHAMBERS-AZR     04-18 1429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-CHAMBERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THRIVING SUNS OWE CHAMBERS THANKS  
 1988 SIGNING PUSHED CLUB TO BIG TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nov. 8, 1992  &QL; 
San Diego _ Newly acquired forward Charles Barkley scored 32 points
and grabbed 16 rebounds as the San Diego Suns made their debut at
the sparkling new Southwest Airlines Center by beating the
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Clippers, 111-105. ...
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix _ City Council members discussed the growing transient
problem in Phoenix's downtown, particularly in the abandoned
warehouse district near Third Street and Jefferson. &QL; 
 &QL; 
We'll never know if that's the way it would have turned out.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little doubt that the Phoenix sports landscape
dramatically changed when the Suns signed Tom Chambers to the first
unrestricted free-agent contract in NBA history on July 5, 1988.
</P>
<P>
   It was the final piece in a dramatic overhaul of the franchise
that began in the wake of a 1987 drug scandal, when Jerry Colangelo
put together a group to purchase the Suns and hired Cotton
Fitzsimmons as player personnel director.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzsimmons engineered a trade that would bring point guard
Kevin Johnson from the Cleveland Cavaliers and a draft pick the
Suns would use to take Dan Majerle.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo named Fitzsimmons head coach, and the club signed
Chambers, one of the league's most feared scorers, to pair with
Johnson, the lightning-quick playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   A franchise was reborn.
</P>
<P>
   The club will honor Chambers, a special assistant to Coach Danny
Ainge, at halftime today of the Suns-Seattle game at America West
Arena _ a building that might never have been erected if Chambers
hadn't arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers, a 6-foot-10, 225-pound forward who could shoot with
range, score inside, run the floor like a guard and finish at the
basket as well as anyone, will join Connie Hawkins, Dick Van
Arsdale, Alvan Adams, Paul Westphal and Walter Davis on a new
``Ring of Honor'' along the south rim of the arena's upper tier.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzsimmons, a senior executive vice president with the club,
has photos on his office wall of the handful of players he believes
are responsible for turning around the franchise and getting the
arena built.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers and KJ are the two most important links.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry (Colangelo) might dispute this, but if we hadn't turned
it around and had to stay in the (Veteran's Memorial) Coliseum, we
might not have the Phoenix Suns today,'' Fitzsimmons said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might not be having this conversation in this building.
That's just what I think with the way this (pro sports) business is
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo always has denied that he was prepared to move the
Suns if the club didn't get a new arena. And the groundwork was
being laid for an arena before Chambers signed.
</P>
<P>
   But with Chambers and KJ running Fitzsimmons' beloved two-man,
screen-and-roll game on the wings, the Suns made the biggest
turnaround in NBA history at that point, improving from 28
victories in 1987-88 to 55 in 1988-89.
</P>
<P>
   That club started a playoff streak that is at 10 years and
counting, and it reached the Western Conference Finals before
falling to the powerful Los Angeles Lakers of Magic Johnson and
Kareem Abdul-Jabbar.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers averaged 25.7 points a game and KJ more than 20 points
and 10 assists. That started a string of four consecutive season of
50-wins or more. The Suns were fun to watch. Their games were the
place to be seen. And it started the momentum toward a new home for
the team, which set attendance records at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers was the centerpiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom played a big role in our ability to build the new arena
and in all of the other things that kind of dominoed from that,''
Colangelo said. ``Tom was an absolute perfect fit at the top of his
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he and KJ teamed up, it was a beautiful work of art. We
owe a great deal of gratitude to Tom. He was a pleasure to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambers came to Phoenix with a reputation for being aloof and
for having a nasty temperament on the court.
</P>
<P>
   He once punched out teammate Tim Perry, and during a comeback
attempt last season he got into an altercation with the team's
strength coach, Robin Pound.
</P>
<P>
   He was criticized in 1993 when, after the Suns moved into the
new arena and reached the NBA Finals, he didn't show up for a
parade.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers has said he regrets that day, and he has become a
quieter, more religious man since his playing days ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to when he played, he's mellowed 100 percent,''
Fitzsimmons said. ``But I wouldn't have wanted him mellow when he
was playing for me. He was fiery, confrontational.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was part of his competitiveness, and that's what
made him as successful as he was. He got mad. He got a lot of
technicals. That was fine with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo said the team knew Chambers was temperamental when it
signed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say he came with a little bit of a reputation,''
Colangelo said. ``But the fact is, from time he came to Phoenix he
felt loved and appreciated. He was a happy guy, and he performed
accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambers asked the Suns to hold the ceremony today so that
Westphal, now head coach of the Sonics, could be present. Westphal,
then a Suns assistant, was the first to call Chambers to tell him
the Suns wanted him on their team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a plan,'' Chambers said. ``And they wanted me from
Day One more than anybody else. I really wanted to start from
scratch, and be a part of a team that was building itself back
up.''
</P>
<P>
   But few imagined how well Chambers and KJ would meld.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if anybody envisioned that,'' Chambers said. ``I
knew KJ was going to be an All-Star. The things he could do,
breaking people down, passing, hitting the open shot, you could see
he would have a great career.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I knew I wanted to be part of that style of play, running
up and down, trying to score 120 points a night. It obviously
played to my strengths. I was always a runner.''
</P>
<P>
   If KJ envisioned it, he isn't saying. He didn't return repeated
phone calls for comment. Maybe only Fitzsimmons saw the potential
for a two-man game that would rival any that have played in the NBA
_ including John Stockton and Karl Malone of Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could not possibly defend those two people,'' Suns Coach
Danny Ainge said of the Chambers-KJ pick-and-roll. ``People don't
give Tom enough credit for being one of the most gifted athletes
who has ever played in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't expect a guy who is that big to be able to run, and
jump and shoot and do all the things he could do. He was one of the
greatest scorers I've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzsimmons, who once coached ``Pistol'' Pete Maravich, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a late bloomer,'' Fitzsimmons said. ``He's tell you he
wasn't that good in high school or even college. But he became one
of the great scorers of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he and KJ had spent their entire careers together, you'd
still be talking about Stockton and Malone, but you would be
talking about Chambers and Johnson, too.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 24, 1990, Chambers set the Suns' record for scoring in
a game, chalking up 60 points in a game against the Sonics at the
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had been forced into the eighth row of Section 208,
Chambers still would have swished it from there,'' wrote ``The
Arizona'' ``Republic's'' Mark Armijo that night.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers was around long enough to enjoy the new building he
helped build, serving as sixth man during the 1992-93 Finals
season. His career wound down after two more seasons in Utah,
another in a pro league in Israel and a couple of comeback attempts
with Charlotte and the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   Now 40, Chambers has undertaken another building project:
Phoenix rookie Pat Garrity and the club's other young players. The
once fiery, confrontational temperamental and supremely talented
forward has become the mentor and tutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' Chambers said. ``I always thought when I was
playing that when I was done, I was done. I didn't imagine myself
coaching. I love spending time at the ranch (in Utah) and with my
family. But I'm one of those people that needs to be doing
something.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've been around something for 20 years, there are some
withdrawals. It's like an addiction. I couldn't be any happier with
the way this has all worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad I was part of this. A lot of things have
happened in this city involving sports. And I love the fact that
I'm mentioned, along with KJ and our teams, when people talk about
what has evolved. I take a lot of pride in that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
