<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3067 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GRETZKY-IMPACT-AZ     04-18 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETZKY-IMPACT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHL OWES GREAT ONE EVERYTHING  
 GRETZKY PUT NEW FACE ON SPORT THAT HAD ONLY REGIONAL IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 Analysis 
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Wayne Gretzky is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Not about retiring, which the Great One will do today amid a
cavalcade of celebration and sorrow. He's leaving the game on his
own terms, something nobody has the right to question.
</P>
<P>
   But Gretzky's wrong when he says the NHL owes him nothing. It's
a line No. 99 has been using all season long, at every stop in
almost every NHL city, when the obligatory question was asked if
this might, indeed, be his final tour of duty.
</P>
<P>
   But he's wrong. The NHL owes Gretzky everything. ``Hockey'' owes
him everything.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, he brought hockey out of the dark ages. He put a
face on a sport that didn't really have much of an image outside of
Boston, Detroit, New York and Chicago _ the four U.S. teams of the
original six.
</P>
<P>
   He made it popular enough to bring expansion to the Sun Belt,
for teams not only to survive in places like the desert and the
Florida coast, but flourish. He saved franchises in Edmonton and
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   He packed arenas. He invented new ways to score goals. He set up
teammates with passes from impossible places. He gave a name to the
space behind the net. They call it the office. Gretzky's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He changed the game,'' Gretzky's former teammate, goalie Grant
Fuhr, said. ``What else can you say?''
</P>
<P>
   You can say thanks for the memories. The Coyotes were smart
enough to recognize that Saturday during their regular-season
finale at America West Arena. Before the pre-game introductions,
the team strung together a touching tribute of highlights in honor
of the greatest player who ever lived.
</P>
<P>
   The packed crowd watched with eyes glued to the giant television
monitors as a fitting ballad was softly piped over the speaker
system. It was Fan Appreciation Day in the Coyotes' den, but the
fans were the ones exuding most of the appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still can't believe he's actually going to hang them up,''
said Adam Keller, the former general manager of the Roadrunners,
who got Gretzky to play for his team during an exhibition game in
the Valley not long ago in a game against Gretzky's Los Angeles
Kings.
</P>
<P>
   And to think, Gretzky almost played in this town for real. Three
years ago, after leaving the St. Louis Blues and becoming an
unrestricted free agent again, Gretzky seriously entertained offers
from the Coyotes to make Phoenix his final NHL home.
</P>
<P>
   How close did it come to happening?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about it a lot,'' Gretzky said earlier this season.
``It would have been interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it would have. But in the end, the Great One was easily
swayed to New York and a chance to play in the biggest U.S. market
on the biggest stage. He was reunited with close friend and former
teammate Mark Messier, and he liked his chances of winning another
Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   But Messier left after one season. The Rangers missed the
playoffs the next. And this season, with a tired, banged up, but
still effective Gretzky, they missed the postseason again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 27 teams that would have loved to have had Wayne
Gretzky,'' Coyotes President Shawn Hunter said Saturday. ``The fact
we were close three years ago was very exciting. He definitely
would have launched hockey in Arizona to new heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, I think we can feel pretty good how this market has
received the NHL. In three short seasons, we've established Phoenix
as a premier NHL city.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, had Gretzky signed on with the Coyotes, and
joined forces with the likes of Keith Tkachuk, Rick Tocchet and
Jeremy Roenick, there wouldn't be a retirement party to go to today
on Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he still felt like this was the time to call it quits
and leave the game he changed, the 61 records he set, the millions
of fans he turned on to hockey, he'd still be playing beyond today
if he was playing for the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   He'd be getting ready for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true,'' Hunter said. ``I didn't think about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky said it would take a miracle to change his mind. The
closest that came to happening was his wife, actress Janet Jones,
and his agent, Mike Barnett, trying their hardest to get him to
reconsider and play at least one more season.
</P>
<P>
   C'mon, just one more year. One more year to let the fans see you
play. One more year as an ambassador in a season when the league's
new big-time television contract kicks in. One more year because
the NHL still needs you.
</P>
<P>
   But Gretzky knew he was done. He said he gave it serious thought
around Christmastime. The days, the weeks and the months that
followed only helped cement his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the year, after a bad game, I said to my kids in the
car, `This is my last year,' '' Gretzky said. ``The next day I was
getting phone calls from the school that I was retiring. And that
was in October.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody wants it to end. But it couldn't last forever. The
records will. The memories will. The history will. The classiness
will. So should the number. Here's yet another call for the NHL to
permanently retire jersey No. 99 and hang it from every rafter in
the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will never be another player like Gretz again,'' said
Fuhr, now of the St. Louis Blues. ``He's one of a kind. Nobody
could ever do the kind of things he did and nobody probably ever
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Wayne. The NHL owes you. Hockey owes you. And just saying
thanks doesn't even begin to cover it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-99 0113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
