r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-GIANTS-AZR     04-18 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-GIANTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING LIGHT COSTS D-BACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Before the Diamondbacks' first day game this season at
Bank One Ballpark on Saturday, third baseman Matt Williams jokingly
suggested the roof stay closed only when they batted to keep the
shadows from playing havoc with their vision.
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Tony Womack would like to have seen it closed,
period.
</P>
<P>
   The roof stayed open halfway, enough for Womack to lose Barry
Bonds' high fly in the shadows with two out and nobody on in the
first inning.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Giants scored four runs after that, pushed
across another four in the next two innings, and kept the
Diamondbacks from breaking even for the first time in franchise
history with an 8-5 victory before a paid crowd of 36,674.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks (5-7) wrap up the three-game series this
afternoon. With the sun peeking through and Womack working on
judging shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Womack's transformation from infielder to outfielder hasn't been
easy in his first week with the club since coming off the disabled
list.
</P>
<P>
   He misplayed a line drive in the Los Angeles Dodgers' series.
Saturday, he said he saw the ball off Bonds' bat. Second baseman
Jay Bell drifted out but couldn't find the ball. As it kept sailing
upward, neither could Womack, who raised his arms helplessly, as
the ball dropped behind him and Bonds trotted into second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's another learning experience _ the hard way,''
Womack said. ``There are no excuses. I didn't build it (BOB).''
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Andy Benes blamed himself.
</P>
<P>
   A slow starter, Benes worked hard in the off-season to pick up
where he left off last season, when he closed with 27 scoreless
innings and a three-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much for that,'' the right-hander said.
</P>
<P>
   After three starts, Benes is 1-2 with a 12.08 earned-run
average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel sorry for myself,'' he said. ``I feel sorry for
the people who had to watch that.''
</P>
<P>
   Benes gave up six hits, eight earned runs and a pair of homers _
two-run shots by shortstop Rich Aurilia and catcher Scott Servais _
in three innings. His day was done.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter said he's not concerned with Benes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he had good stuff to start the game,'' Showalter
said. ``He's going to be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't after Womack lost Bonds' ball.
</P>
<P>
   Benes walked Jeff Kent, grazed J.T. Snow's right forearm with a
pitch and got behind Ellis Burks, who doubled in three runs. Benes
then walked Charlie Hayes, who was booed profoundly before each
at-bat after charging and swinging at pitcher Todd Stottlemyre in
Friday's game. Again, Benes fell behind in the count, and Servais
singled in Burks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has to work off of the fastball, and, to this
point, I haven't been very good with it,'' Benes said.
</P>
<P>
   Benes, the Giants killer who had a personal seven-game winning
streak against the club end, said the lost ball in the first was no
excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody scored, and I had all sorts of opportunities to get out
of the inning, and that's my fault,'' Benes said. ``That's nobody's
problem but mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Relievers Vladimir Nunez, John Frascatore and Greg Swindell shut
down the Giants on three hits after the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks wasted opportunities to edge closer, leaving a
runner on second in the first inning with one out and had runners
on second and third with two out in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Womack hit a line drive that was inches foul along the
third-base line that would have scored two runs. But, a pitch
later, Womack grounded back to pitcher Kirk Rueter to end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   With two down in the fifth, left fielder Bernard Gilkey was
thrown out trying to steal third base with catcher Damian Miller
and his productive history against Rueter at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernard has played long enough to know not to go there,''
Showalter said. ``That was a lapse of judgment on his part.''
</P>
<P>
   Rueter, who came in with a 14.85 ERA after two starts, wasn't
brilliant but good enough to earn his first win. He gave up eight
hits, walked three and struck out three. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
