r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ASU-SPRING-RECAP-     04-18 2086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-SPRING-RECAP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU FOOTBALL USES SPRING BALL TO PREPARE NEW LOOK FOR TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Look out. Arizona State may just nickel and dime
you to death in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The changing face of the Pac-10 has forced league defenses to
re-evaluate their schemes. With the Sun Devils likely to face
three- and four-wideout offenses on a regular basis, finding a
multitude of quality defensive backs was a priority in spring
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``This league has really changed,'' defensive coordinator Phil
Snow said. ``Five years ago, everybody just tried to knock you off
the ball and play-action pass. Now there are still two or three
teams trying to run it, but for the most part, it's a one-back
league now, and we've had to adjust.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive breakdowns played a significant role in a
disappointing 5-6 finish in 1998, and the secondary took much of
the heat. While other factors played a part _ an inconsistent pass
rush and struggles at linebacker _ the Sun Devils did not get the
production it wanted from a position riddled with injuries and
depth problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've added some things to the package, and in some ways we'll
look a lot different than we have,'' Snow said. ``You need to do it
anyway, because if you run something for three or four years, and
don't change much, the offenses will catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils appear to have found a quality assortment of
defensive backs with the addition of junior college players and the
development of several quality underclassmen, especially safety
Alfred Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The coaching staff also used the spring to shift several players
on defense. Stephen Trejo is back at outside linebacker, Eric
Fields is playing in the middle and safeties Christon Rance and
Courtney Palmore are corners.
</P>
<P>
   ASU's work is far from done. The spring gave no real indication
that the linebacking unit will be more productive in 1999. And
despite the likely return of Tariq McDonald, and the promise showed
by Justin Taplin, the staff may be more concerned about their
inexperienced receiving corps than it's letting on.
</P>
<P>
   One bit of good news: The Sun Devils' recruiting class appears
to be in good academic shape, and all have a good shot at
qualifying. That hasn't been the case lately.
</P>
<P>
   ASU Coach Bruce Snyder said he left spring football with a good
feeling about his team's personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, I like the attitude, chemistry,'' he said. ``This team
did a really nice job of responding coming off winter workouts and
maintaining the momentum we created.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also realize as a coaching staff we've still got a long way
to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a position-by-position look at ASU based on the
productivity in spring football: &QL; 
Quarterback &QL; 
The pressures Ryan Kealy felt last season did not come from
blitzes. They were internal, the result of a sophomore trying to do
too much when things around him were breaking down. The bottom line
is this: Kealy is a quality quarterback when he just goes out and
plays.
</P>
<P>
   The old Kealy _ the one that set numerous freshman records _
returned during the spring with a little more attitude. A shortage
of team leaders set the Sun Devils back in 1998, so his take-charge
approach thrilled Snyder.
</P>
<P>
   He also experienced some knee tenderness. The staff said it's
not concerned, but it's ominous enough that a capable backup needs
to be ready. Watch for that job to be won in Camp Tontozona.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Cooper, a 6-foot-4 redshirt freshman, finally got some
repetitions in the spring and showed potential. Did he appear ready
to take charge in a Pac-10 game? No.
</P>
<P>
   Junior college transfer John Leonard is expected to give Cooper
a run at Tontozona. Cooper will have the edge in familiarity with
ASU's system, but Leonard has college game experience, even if it
is at a lesser level. He passed for 2,765 yards and 31 touchdowns
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Walk-on Griffin Goodman did enough in the spring to warrant a
look. &QL; 
Offensive line
</P>
<P>
   The only sure thing about the line in 1999 is its bookends:
tackles Marvel Smith and Victor Leyva.
</P>
<P>
   It's a solid foundation to begin with. The 6-6 Smith is so
dominating he may not stick around for another season, and Leyva
has done everything ASU has asked.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Peters, a freshman All-America, is also a lock to start,
but where? He seemed to be the sure replacement for Grey Ruegamer
at center, but after spring ball, offensive coordinator Dan
Cozzetto wasn't ready to commit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends what happens during the summer and how everything
else falls in place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Peters was impressive as a 10-game starter at left guard last
season but Cozzetto wants to see whether other players step up at
the guard spots. The top candidates on the left side include Korey
Ramsey; junior college transfer Kenneth Williamson, who looked
solid in the spring but may not be ready to take over; and Kyle
Kosier, who has moved from the defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Right guard could go to senior Thomas Schmidt, who played at
guard and tackle last season, but don't be surprised to see some
incoming recruits make a case for one of the guard spots.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils have what is believed to be the biggest class of
offensive line recruits to come to ASU. The five freshmen average
6-6, 308. Additionally, two junior college transfers, Steve York
and Marquise Muldrow, will report in early August. &QL; 
Running back
</P>
<P>
   J.R. Redmond is the heart and soul of this offense, and now that
he's healthy, he'll carry the load. Watch for his role to expand to
receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Daveron Hightower and Gerald Green will get their minutes, but
the forgotten player in the mix might be Delvon Flowers, who was
the considered the No. 1 junior college player in the nation by
several recruiting publications. Flowers is a fast, flashy runner
who may find his way onto the field. &QL; 
Fullback
</P>
<P>
   Of all the departures, the loss of Jeff Paulk may hurt the Sun
Devils most.
</P>
<P>
   Paulk's contributions often went unrecognized because he did
little in terms of catching or carrying the ball. But as a blocker,
there are few better.
</P>
<P>
   ASU has considered going to zone blocking, which is similar to
what the Dallas Cowboys did when Daryl Johnston went down, but the
emergence of Terrelle Smith may force the Sun Devils to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be the surprise of the spring,'' Cozzetto said.
</P>
<P>
   The senior, who gave linebacker a run last season, is a fiery,
determined player who is aching for minutes. He showed promise in
the spring, especially with redshirt freshman Darrel Turner
sidelined and sophomore Jack Each not making a strong enough case
for the job yet. &QL; 
Wide receiver
</P>
<P>
   No position was hit harder. ASU lost its top three receivers,
who combined for 77 percent of the wideouts' receptions.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald, who missed spring ball in order to regain his academic
eligibility, should start after averaging 14.2 yards per catch and
grabbing four touchdowns. Also seeing time will be Taplin, who
didn't have a reception last season but made a lot of noise in
practice.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Sun Devils hope to keep up with the Joneses, and line
up more than two receivers on occasion, they'll need some players
to step up at Camp Tontozona.
</P>
<P>
   Among those battling for roles include Brian Forth, Joey Graves
and Clifton Jones, and junior college transfers Ryan Dennard and
Richard Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Dennard was slowed by an injury in the spring but showed promise
when he got healthy. Williams won't report until August, but he
watched almost every spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Boyer, who ASU hoped might regain his academic
eligibility, appears to be all but out of the picture. He has yet
to qualify. &QL; 
Tight end
</P>
<P>
   If ASU feels comfortable about a spot, it's this one.
</P>
<P>
   The staff has acknowledged that it failed to get the tight end
the ball enough last season, and considering what the Sun Devils
have to work with, it's probably right.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Heap made a handful of circus-like catches, finishing with
12 receptions and four touchdowns. He's as sure-handed as they
come.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget Kendrick Bates, a 6-6 senior who got lost a bit in
the Heap excitement but is capable of big plays.
</P>
<P>
   Long snapper Brian Jennings will also work his way into the mix,
primarily as a blocker on the team's short-yardage goal line unit. &QL; 
Defensive line
</P>
<P>
   This unit was a mixed bag last season. The development of junior
college transfers Erik Flowers and Junior Ioane was a highlight,
but the Sun Devils still need to prove they can consistently put
pressure on the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   No one looked better in the spring than Flowers. The rush end
treated each practice like a game and sacked the quarterback four
times in the spring-ending scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils are disappointed that they went through the
spring without Ioane, who barely missed being eligible, but they
feel good about the progress the tackle made in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end, ASU hopes for a big year from 6-8, 245-pound
Quincy Yancy, who has made strides each season but is due for a
breakthrough year. He'll be pushed by 6-5, 256-pound redshirt
freshman Mike Pinkard, who is clearly talented but inexperienced.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Reilly, a 6-2, 300-pound senior, continues to find himself
in the starting lineup even though he's not the biggest or
strongest lineman available. His work ethic and knowledge of the
game keeps him in there.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Townsend, who was a redshirt at Southern California in
1997, will step in as a backup. He's not a dominant pass rusher but
demonstrated he can be a capable tackle.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils are anxiously awaiting the arrival of 6-4,
300-pound tackle Tony Aguilar, one of their most coveted recruits. &QL; 
Linebacker
</P>
<P>
   Finding the right mix at linebacker, and enough healthy bodies,
was a problem for ASU last season, and it proved to be one of the
team's least effective positions.
</P>
<P>
   The shuffling is under way again and the Sun Devils hope this
mix works. Sophomore Fields, one of the team's most promising
players last season in seven starts outside, moves to the middle
even though he has never played the position.
</P>
<P>
   Trejo, who has played all three linebacking positions at ASU, is
back outside in what the Sun Devils calls the Sam spot. The team is
still waiting for a big season for the junior and hopes this role
is what will prompt it.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Archuleta, who had 18 tackles for losses last season,
returns to the other outside spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had three linebackers back that have played, and we wanted
to put all three of them in a position for them to start because
they understand the package,'' Snow said about the shuffling.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils won't know until the fall what they'll get from
junior college transfer Adam Tanke, who was sidelined with knee
problems during the spring. Another JC transfer, Jamall Anderson,
and recruits Solomon Bates and Josh Amobi, will get close looks at
Tontozona. &QL; 
Cornerback
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils' pass defense fell to seventh in the Pac-10 and a
shortage of healthy players at cornerback contributed to the
problem. The shifting of several players from safety and the
addition of several junior college standouts could rectify that.
</P>
<P>
   ASU returns starting cornerbacks Courtney Jackson, who is one of
the Pac-10's best when healthy, and J'Juan Cherry. Cherry may be
the team's most athletically gifted player, but he needs to
fine-tune his technique to fulfill his potential.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils get depth now that Courtney Palmore and Christon
Rance have moved over from safety. Palmore's 5-11, 185-pound frame
is more suited for corner, and Rance likes his new position.
</P>
<P>
   And in the fall comes junior college transfer Nijrell Eason, who
may prove to be the most talented of all the recruits. Look for
Eason to make an immediate impact. &QL; 
Safety &QL; 
No position was more contested in the spring. Overall, the results
were promising.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Williams, Brandon Falkner and Craig Koontz all made
strong cases for time at free safety, and Willie Daniel and Monte'
Franks duked it out at strong safety.
</P>
<P>
   With the demands the Pac-10 now places on defensive backs, all
these players should see time. &QL; 
Kicking game
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Baker stepped in as a freshman last season and gave ASU
one of the few consistent areas on the team: punting. He finished
17th in the nation in net punting, and his 45.7-yard average per
punt set an ASU single-season mark.
</P>
<P>
   Baker's security at place kicker will be challenged in the fall
by incoming recruit Mike Barth. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
