</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-CART-LONG-BEACH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANAAN WINS POLE ON TWISTING COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ What time is it? It's Tony Kanaan time.
</P>
<P>
   Kanaan, one of nine Brazilian drivers starting today's Toyota
Grand Prix of Long Beach, won a career-first pole position Saturday
after a speedy 107.454 mph qualifying run over a twisting 11-turn,
1.824-mile seaside street circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Kanaan also won something else.
</P>
<P>
   Wrist watches. Lots of wrist watches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like watches,'' said Kanaan, whose 1-lap burst during a
30-minute qualifying position slid provisional pole-sitter Dario
Franchitti (104.412) to an outside front-row starting position for
today's 85-lap race. ``When I woke up (Friday morning), I bet my
engineer I'd do better than (1 minute, 2.5 seconds). I did, and I
won his watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a bet with all the members of the team (Saturday) that
if I make the pole, I wanted all their watches. I said, `If I
don't, I'll buy dinner.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody want to buy a Rolex?''
</P>
<P>
   Ha-ha.
</P>
<P>
   Kanaan, however, hopes he's still laughing all the way to the
bank following what promises to be a white-knuckle race of
survival.
</P>
<P>
   Course officials have reconfigured a portion of the twisting
seaside layout, some of which is bordered by the Pacific Ocean, and
what emerged is road racing's version of a Rorschach test.
</P>
<P>
   Turn 1 of the 11-turn pretzel now is a sneaky left-hander
instead of a right-hander, and Turns 2 and 3 are
enter-at-your-own-risk corners, hardly wide enough to fit one of
those road-hogging Sun City golf carts.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, watching cars wiggle through the squishy turns was
like watching a bunch of shoppers jam the neighborhood supermarket
on quadruple-coupon day.
</P>
<P>
   `` ``Cleanup on aisle six.''''``''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bryan Herta, ``The track has a much different feel going
into Turn 1 as you set up for the left-hand turn rather than a
right-hand corner. It's like driving into a tight tunnel. There is
only room for one car in that area.''
</P>
<P>
   Ha.
</P>
<P>
   There's barely room for the corner worker with the move-over
flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new part of the track is really tight, just as you'd
expect on a street course,'' said Paul Tracy, a former resident of
Scottsdale and Parker. ``Everybody's going to have to be careful
through there, because if a car gets sideways in there, you're
looking at a red flag.''
</P>
<P>
   There already has been a slew of incidents during two days of
practice and qualifying, one of which was a costly crash involving
Franchitti.
</P>
<P>
   During morning practice Saturday, Franchitti smashed into the
wall in Turn 2 and sustained major, unfixable damage to the Team
Kool Green Reynard-Honda primary car.
</P>
<P>
   Forced to use a back-up machine, Franchitti still managed to
improve Friday's qualifying speed. But what he didn't do was
improve it enough to keep Kanaan from atop the qualifying ladder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be on the pole,'' Franchitti said. ``I'm not very
happy that I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   Kanaan's happy. He also is concerned about today's start, which
also has almost everyone else concerned, too.
</P>
<P>
   Following a rolling start, the high-pitched screaming champ cars
will reach speeds upward of 160 mph before drivers have to slam on
the brakes and downshift to about 50 mph entering Turn 1.
</P>
<P>
   The problem will be when more than one driver tries to enter the
corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go to the drivers meeting, and everybody is going to
agree not to make a big move in Turn 1 because it is so tight,''
Kanaan said. ``Then (today), everybody will forget about it.''
</P>
<P>
   They better not forget about it, said Herta, who starts on the
inside of the second row next to Max Papis.
</P>
<P>
   If drivers do develop a case of amnesia, he added, motor racing
hell is going to break loose.
</P>
<P>
   But with so few places to pass, anxious drivers are likely to be
more brazen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably going to take a little cooperation or a mistake
to make a run on a guy,'' Herta answered when asked what it would
take to make a clean pass.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it might take even more than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passing places? I don't think there's any,'' Franchitti said.
</P>
<P>
   Uh-oh. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
