<HEADER>
A3075 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-CART-LONGBEACH-NB     04-18 0330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-CART-LONGBEACH-NB-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANAAN WINS POLE, EYES HIS 1ST VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Pressure? What pressure?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tony Kanaan, a promising second-year driver from Brazil, won a
career first pole position Saturday in the the Toyota Grand Prix of
Long Beach and now hopes a career first trip into victory lane soon
follows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud, I'm happy,'' Kanaan said. ``But I know I have a lot
to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (sponsor) McDonald's came aboard, it gave me the
opportunity to do a lot more testing. Last year we only had 10 days
of testing. We've already had 20 days this year. (Team manager)
 &UR; Steve (Horne) said I asked for more testing and money, and now I'm
under a little bit of pressure to do well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Kanaan finished ninth last season in the final driver's
standings, scoring the most rookie points since  &UR; Nigel Mansell in
1993. Kanaan also is ninth entering today's race. &QL; 
Neville shines &QL; 
 &UR; Chris Neville of Scottsdale captured a career first pole position
in BF Goodrich Trans-Am qualifying. Neville (88.268 mph)
out-muscled
 &UR; Brian Simo for the top spot during the session's final three
minutes. Each drove Ford Mustang Cobras.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we had a car that could get the pole,'' Neville said.
``I just needed one clean lap to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Neville got it and then did it. &QL; 
Pit stops &QL; 
Here's what awaits today's winner: The past three drivers to motor
into Long Beach victory lane have gone on to capture the driving
title.
</P>
<P>
   CART officials had a change of heart and increased today's race
from 80 laps to 85 laps. The total mileage also increased to 155.04
miles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Buddy Rice of Phoenix finished fourth in Saturday's Toyota
Atlantic race.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Daryn Kagan, a former Valley television personality, finished
14th in a Toyota Pro/Celebrity race field of 18.  &UR; Donny Osmond
crashed and flipped upside down. He was unhurt. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-99 0120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990418.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3076 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-PADRES-LA     04-18 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PADRES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT PADRES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Technically, one at-bat isn't enough to break out of
a slump. However, what Devon White did to the San Diego Padres
should go a long way toward pulling him out of a horrific stretch
at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   White's pinch-hit three-run homer in the sixth inning broke open
a tie game and lifted the Los Angeles Dodgers to a 7-3 victory
Saturday over the Padres in front of 56,568 at Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   And wouldn't you know it, the reason White was on the bench in
the first place was because of his struggles with the bat.
</P>
<P>
   White hit .440 during the Dodgers' season-opening homestand. But
before connecting for the three-run homer off Padres reliever
Carlos Reyes, he was 1 for 19 on the road trip that began Monday.
His only other hit was an RBI double off Arizona's Randy Johnson on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield added a pair of homers and
three RBI. It was Sheffield's 12th multi-homer game of his career
and first since July 1997. He leads the Dodgers with five home runs
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers right-hander Chan Ho Park (1-1) recorded his first win
of the season, allowing three runs on eight hits in five innings.
He walked two and struck out six. Park got help from three
relievers.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes (0-1) pitched one inning but took the loss.
</P>
<P>
   After getting shut out by Andy Ashby in the series opener, the
Dodgers wasted little time in getting to San Diego starter Sterling
Hitchcock. An RBI single by Eric Karros in the first inning gave
the Dodgers a 1-0 lead, and two innings later Sheffield homered to
center field with Mark Grudzielanek on base for a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Park held the lead until the fifth, when the Padres broke
through by doubling their hit total for the game. Chris Gomez led
off with a single, moved to second on a wild pitch and advanced to
third on a groundout. He scored when Quilvio Veras lined a Park
pitch through the middle. Park got his glove on the ball but
couldn't corral it.
</P>
<P>
   Park struck out Reggie Sanders, but hitting machine Tony Gwynn
doubled to the wall in right-center field to score Veras. It
appeared Dodgers center fielder Jacob Brumfield, starting for
White, could make a play on it but he jumped too soon.
</P>
<P>
   That inning also cost the Padres Hitchcock for the rest of
night. He was lifted for pinch-hitter Eric Owens and left after
allowing two runs on four hits in five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Joyner then singled to right to score Gwynn and tie the
game 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   Prior the game, Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said he was going
to rest White either Saturday or today, partly because of the day
game following a night game and in part because of White's hitting
woes.
</P>
<P>
   In White's place, Brumfield got the start and got a little
retribution when his one-out single in the sixth moved Adrian
Beltre to third. Brumfield went to second on the throw.
</P>
<P>
   It brought catcher Paul LoDuca to the plate, and for a moment
Park was in the on-deck circle. But when LoDuca, hitless in 11
at-bats this season, fell behind in the count, White appeared in
the on-deck circle.
</P>
<P>
   LoDuca struck out, but White didn't miss Reyes' 2-1 fastball
over the plate, hitting hit it 406 feet to give the Dodgers a 6-3
lead.
</P>
<P>
   With Park no longer available, Johnson went to his revamped
bullpen to chew away some innings. Antonio Osuna, activated from
the disabled list Friday, made his first appearance of the season.
He was infallible, retiring all three batters he faced with the
kind of ease Johnson was hoping he'd see.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers upped the lead 7-3 in the top of the seventh when
Sheffield greeted reliever Brian Boehringer's first pitch with the
barrel of his bat, lining a solo homer to left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
