r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-YOUNG-AZ     04-18 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-YOUNG-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESEASON PREDICTION STILL HOLDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NBA's 50-game schedule is grinding down to the last two
weeks, and the playoff picture is starting to shake out.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, there have been few surprises. In the Western
Conference, the Portland Trail Blazers have been better than most
expected. The Suns haven't been as good as many anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   In the Eastern Conference, the New Jersey Nets have been a bust,
and the Orlando Magic has soared to the top of the standings.
</P>
<P>
   But who will emerge when the top 16 teams end the madness that
has been this lockout-altered season and return to a normal NBA
playoff routine?
</P>
<P>
   Portland could wind up with the best record in the league.
Orlando may hold home court throughout the Eastern Conference
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers, with talent and the galvanizing
influence of Coach  &UR; Kurt Rambis' decision to tell  &UR; Dennis Rodman to
get lost, will be a popular pick. Houston, with three of the NBA's
all-time top 50 players on the roster, has been lying in wait. And
in the East, the Miami Heat is an experienced team with a coach,
 &UR; Pat Riley, who knows how to get to the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   But it says here that the two preseason favorites are headed for
the showdown, Utah from the West and Indiana in the East.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz is easy to dismiss. The team is forgotten every year
for sexier picks. But the combination of  &UR; John Stockton and  &UR; Karl
Malone is the most difficult to defend in the West. Without Rodman,
the Lakers again will have nobody to handle Malone.
</P>
<P>
   And Portland will find that its vast advantage in depth will
have less impact in the playoffs, when teams have days off to rest
and prepare, than it did in the hectic regular season. Plus, the
Trail Blazers haven't gotten past the first round in the past six
years.
</P>
<P>
   In the East, Indiana has slogged along all season.
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; Larry Bird has ripped his team on several occasions.
Guard
 &UR; Reggie Miller is having a so-so season. The players are unhappy
with their minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be fooled. The Pacers still could wind up with the best
record in the East. They, too, have depth and talent. And they have
vast playoff experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was telling everybody how good they were because I really
wanted them to play with a lot of pressure on their backs and be
the team picked to win it all,'' Bird said recently after a loss to
Charlotte. ``I thought they'd come out, work hard every day and
prove it to people. It backfired. Obviously, they can't handle the
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers are equipped to handle the pressure because Bird has
been putting it on them. They've been to the conference finals in
three of the past five years. And Utah has been to the NBA Finals
the past two season and the conference finals or beyond in four of
the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   Barring injuries, they're the teams to beat. And it says here
that, in a seven-game series, the Jazz wins its first title. &QL; 
Bargain hunting &QL; 
Based on a list the ``Chicago Sun-Times'' published of the league's
payrolls, the Jazz is the league's best bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Utah's payroll of $31.350 million ranks just 25th in the league,
and it's challenging for the best record. The New York Knicks, at
$69.4 million, have the highest payroll and are in danger of not
making the playoffs at all.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's No. 1 team in spending, the Chicago Bulls, ranks
last this season with a payroll of $29.45 million.  &UR; Michael Jordan
made more than that all by himself last season. Of course, Jordan
often scored more than 49 points all by himself, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns, by the way, rank near the middle of the pack. Their
payroll is reportedly $36.96 million. They had the 16th-best record
going into Saturday's games.
</P>
<P>
   The worst deal? Take your pick between the Washington Wizards
($44.4 million) and the New Jersey Nets ($41.96 million). Neither
will make the playoffs. &QL; 
Who knew? &QL; 
It figured when the Charlotte Hornets traded  &UR; Glen Rice to the
Lakers that former Los Angeles guard  &UR; Eddie Jones would have an
impact on the Hornets. But surprisingly center  &UR; Elden Campbell, the
other player who came to Charlotte in the deal, has had made a more
substantial contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Given more and consistent minutes, Campbell has become the
team's first option offensively, and the Hornets have fought
themselves into playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know he was as good as he is,'' interim head Coach
 &UR; Paul
 &UR; Silas said. ``He really makes a difference for us. The last few
games he's been our go-to guy, and he seems comfortable with it.'' &QL; 
Runnin' on empty &QL; 
Players are starting to feel the full effect of a demanding,
lockout-shortened schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been feeling like I've been in a fog for a week,'' Golden
State's  &UR; Bimbo Coles said. ``You don't know what the date is, or
what day of the week it is, or anything.'' &QL; 
Trash Talk &QL; 
Comments from Nets guard  &UR; Stephon Marbury, who long has made it
known he wants to be the Knicks' point guard, were well publicized
when Marbury ripped Knicks playmakers  &UR; Chris Childs and  &UR; Charlie
Ward _ even though his team had gotten whipped by New York and he
had eight turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still need a point guard,'' Marbury said. ``They'll never
win no championship with them two guys. They'll never, ever win.
They're just not the guys you need to win a championship. They
might not even make the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Childs shot back later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until you win a championship, and prove you're playing the
game for love and not for money, you shouldn't be making comments
like that.'' he said. ``I was cocky at that age, but I never put an
opponent down or gave him extra incentive to kick my butt. That
kind of thing carries over to next year, the year after that. We're
all professionals, some of us have better days than others, but we
all try hard. And the person who is defeated should admit it and go
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Childs knows full well that Marbury wants his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fine and dandy,'' he said, ``but he can't have it this
year.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob Young can be
reached at 602-444-8271 or at bob.young(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
