<HEADLINE>
JAGR SHOWS WHAT'S GOOD ABOUT NHL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somebody wandered up to  &UR; Keith Tkachuk the other day and asked
him which player he'd pick for the Hart Trophy if he had a vote.
The Coyotes captain, without hesitation or ever looking up from
untying his skate laces, didn't even think about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotta be  &UR; (Jaromir) Jagr, right?'' Tkachuk said. ``I
mean, who else is there?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, there's the two mightiest Ducks from Anaheim,  &UR; Teemu
Selanne and
 &UR; Paul Kariya. Then there's the popular choice of Canada, Ottawa's
 &UR; Alexei Yashin. But Tkachuk's right, the choice for this year's Most
Valuable Player seems pretty cut and dried.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh's Jagr has run away with the NHL scoring title,
taking 41 goals and 124 points into the weekend, and he's the
reason why the financially burdened Penguins have remained above
water. It's an easy pick.
</P>
<P>
   With a few exceptions here and there, so are the rest of the
selections for the NHL's major postseason awards, which will be
announced in Toronto on June 24.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, here's the way I see it:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hart Trophy (MVP): 1. Jagr. 2. Yashin. 3. Selanne. Coyotes'
candidate:  &UR; Jeremy Roenick.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Norris Trophy (top defenseman): 1.  &UR; Al MacInnis, St. Louis. 2.
 &UR; Ray
 &UR; Bourque, Boston. 3.  &UR; Scott Stevens, New Jersey. Coyotes' candidate:
 &UR; Teppo Numminen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Selke Trophy (best defensive forward): 1.  &UR; Jere Lehtinen,
Dallas. 2.
 &UR; Craig Conroy, St. Louis. 3.  &UR; Bob Corkum, Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Calder Trophy (top rookie): 1.  &UR; Chris Drury, Colorado. 2.
 &UR; Brendan
 &UR; Morrison, New Jersey. 3.  &UR; Mark Parrish, Florida. Coyotes'
candidate:
 &UR; Daniel Briere.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Vezina Trophy (top goalie): 1.  &UR; Curtis Joseph, Toronto. 2.
 &UR; Dominik
 &UR; Hasek, Buffalo. 3.  &UR; Eddie Belfour, Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jack Adams Award (Coach of the Year): 1.  &UR; Jacques Martin,
Ottawa. 2.
 &UR; Robbie Ftorek, New Jersey. 3.  &UR; Pat Quinn, Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lady Byng Trophy (sportsmanship): 1.  &UR; Wayne Gretzky, Rangers.
2. Wayne Gretzky, Rangers. 3. Wayne Gretzky, Rangers. Coyotes'
candidate: Gretzky (Hey, he almost came here).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Masterton Trophy (comeback/perseverance): 1.  &UR; John Cullen,
Tampa Bay. 2. Kariya, Anaheim. 3. &UR; Steve Smith, Calgary. Coyotes'
candidate:  &UR; Greg
 &UR; Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a few more unofficial awards we'd like to submit:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Most exciting player: Selanne. He doesn't have the power or
maybe even the one-on-one capabilities of Jagr, but his speed and
knack for the puck make him the player I'd pay to watch every
night.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Up-and-coming star: Pavol Demitra, St. Louis. When the Coyotes
start the playoffs on Thursday, you'll see it for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Biggest bust: Chris Gratton, Tampa Bay. Philadelphia finally
realized it made a mistake sinking so much money into this
overhyped, underproducing center, whom they traded back to the
Lightning. He had eight goals and 25 assists entering the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Best moment: Gretzky being named MVP of the All-Star Game in
Tampa and announcing he was keeping the free truck that went along
with the award after giving away the 14 or 15 automobiles he's won
over the years. Remember, we told you there probably was a
significant reason behind that.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Worst moment: It'll come today, when No. 99 skates around the
ice one last time and finally returns to the locker room, where
he'll unlace his boots and ship them to the Hockey Hall of Fame in
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall will waive its five-year waiting period and induct
Gretzky within the next 12 months. &QL; 
Dollars and sense
</P>
<P>
   Team presidents don't usually make comments like this, but  &UR; Tim
 &UR; Leiweke of the Los Angeles Kings didn't mind sharing his feelings
as to which team he hopes wins the Stanley Cup this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Ottawa wins it all,'' Leiweke said. ``They've done it
the right way, building through the draft. Or a team like New
Jersey, building through their development system.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiweke said that should be the new standard operating procedure
by NHL clubs because he speculates that only three or four are
actually going to make money this season. The Kings, he said, stand
to lose $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The owners have only themselves to blame,'' he said. ``I'm all
for what Detroit did, but at some point, everybody has to look at
themselves in the mirror and ask whether it's all about buying a
Stanley Cup. To go out and write checks for the Stanley Cup
destroys the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiweke compares the Red Wings to the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a crime,'' he said. ``I see no suspense in
baseball, either.'' &QL; 
Is anybody home?
</P>
<P>
   When the Carolina Hurricanes open the playoffs at home this
Thursday, there is a good chance they won't sell out either of the
first two home games at the Greensboro Coliseum, a building where
the seating capacity already has been purposely reduced to 11,059.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 6,790 showed up for a home game against Washington a
day after the 'Canes clinched the Southeast Division title.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have only 6,000 fans in our building for the playoffs, I
think maybe we should play all the games on the road,'' left wing
 &UR; Gary
 &UR; Roberts said. ``Obviously, it was disappointing to the players.
Nobody was happy about the crowd of 6,700.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you can't get excited about the Stanley Cup playoffs,
you can't get excited about anything. People experience a whole
other thing in the playoffs. They should want to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the question should be, why is the NHL there? &QL; 
A Great memory
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jacques Demers, the head coach and general manager of the Tampa
Bay Lightning, recalled a tale on the eve of Gretzky's retirement.
Ten years ago, Demers' son,  &UR; Jason, was struck by a car and
suffered a broken leg and a collapsed lung.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the accident, Gretzky sent Jason some autographed
mementos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't ask and I don't know how he even found out about
it,'' Demers said. ``He just did it. That's the kind of guy he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``After my first year of coaching in Quebec (in 1979), I was
scouting and out of my (coaching) job, he sought me out after an
exhibition game in Moncton and told me to hang in there, that I'd
be back in the league again. To stay with it. He didn't have to say
that. He didn't really even know me.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via e-mail or at (602)
444-8326. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
