<HEADLINE>
HATCHER GONE FOR 7 GAMES  
 COYOTES WANTED LONGER SUSPENSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Dallas Stars captain Derian Hatcher was handed the
longest playoff game suspension in NHL history Saturday, but it did
little to ease the Coyotes' pain of losing Jeremy Roenick for the
Stanley Cup playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher was given a seven-game suspension, including Saturday's
game against Phoenix and today's season finale against Colorado,
plus the Stars' next five playoff games. He was charged with
leaving his feet, elbowing and boarding Roenick, whose jaw was
broken in three places and who lost eight teeth, during Wednesday's
game in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension also costs him $90,731 in lost salary. The
previous longest playoff suspension came in 1996 when Detroit's
Dino Ciccarelli was given three games for sucker-punching Enrico
Ciccone of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of factors were considered,'' said Colin Campbell,
director of hockey operations for the NHL. ``It is clear that Mr.
Hatcher intended to deliver a blow to the head by leaving his feet
prior to the hit. The severity of the injury was considered, as was
the fact Mr. Hatcher has been suspended by the league on previous
occasions.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith wanted a stiffer penalty,
considering Roenick will be taking his meals through a straw for
the next five weeks and is out of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't do anything for our team,'' Smith said before the
Coyotes' 2-0 victory Saturday over the Stars. ``It's not much of a
punishment for the Dallas Stars. They will face an Edmonton team
they have a 40-point lead over going into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edmonton is without (top two scorers) Bill Guerrin and Josef
Beranek. The net result will be a well-rested Derian Hatcher for
the playoffs, and an incident that was deliberate, premeditated and
vicious has cost our team its top scorer for the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he understands Campbell faced a gut-wrenching
decision and he did what he thought best, but it wasn't enough
considering the teams could meet in the second-round of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had Hatcher's playoff suspension been split between the first
and second rounds, it would have been something that could have
helped us and possibly hurt Dallas' chances to win the Stanley
Cup,'' Smith said. ``It was an unprecedented event, and the league
would have been well within its jurisdiction to do something
unprecedented.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher said, ``I'm surprised and disappointed. They told me I
didn't lead with my elbow. My hit wasn't any worse than Eric
Lindros on Daniel Alfredsson, or Roenick's on Mike Modano.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Roenick's hit on Modano on March 23 that left Modano with
a seven-stitch cut over his eye and ill-feelings between the teams.
</P>
<P>
   Roenick, looking like a chipmunk with his swollen jaw,
introduced himself as Rocky Dennis (the featured character in the
movie ``Mas''k) at news conference between the first and second
periods Saturday. He said being unable to help his teammates play
for the Cup hurts as much as his jaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was going to be five games or more,'' he said.
``It's unfortunate any of this has to happen, but in this day and
age, it's the way the game is. Everybody is going to have their own
opinion, and everybody knows my opinion, I can't play. I have to
root for Dallas to be eliminated in the first round so he can't
play, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hard game, like I said. Derian is a rugged player, as
am I. It's still no reason to throw elbows into people's faces. I
don't hold grudges. I play hard, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Roenick was asked whether Hatcher has called him to apologize.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, and I don't expect him to,'' he said. ``These things
happen in hockey all the time. I accept it. That's why I love
playing this game. It's a great game. You have to take the good
with the bad. It makes for just a little longer off-season for me,
that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Coach Ken Hitchcock said if there had to be a suspension,
the one assessed was ample.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you get suspended in the playoffs it's almost a
2-to-1, or 3-to-1 ratio,'' he said. ``In the regular season, this
is probably 12 to 15 games. It's severe. Both teams suffer, missing
key players going into very important playoff runs. Derian has to
accept responsibility for what he did. A lot of people have to take
responsibility.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
