<HEADLINE>
`CIVIL WAR` HEATS UP WITH STARS, COYOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a hockey game that made the Bill Clinton-Kenneth Starr battle
look like a mere tuneup, the most combative guy on the ice in
Saturday's Coyotes-Dallas Stars war was an unlikely choice.
</P>
<P>
   That would be Dallas goalie  &UR; Eddie Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour, excitable by nature, received 14 minutes of penalties,
including a 10-minute misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   He was first whistled at 9:01 of the first period when he skated
up ice during a timeout and slew-footed Phoenix captain  &UR; Keith
Tkachuk with a sweep of his right leg, drawing the misconduct and a
two-minute tripping penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Then at 11:00 of the second period, he cross-checked Tkachuk
twice in the back, and Tkachuk wheeled and landed three quick blows
before Stars defenseman  &UR; Darryl Sydor came to Belfour's aid and was
promptly pummelled by Tkachuk.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game that featured 31 penalties and 119 minutes in
penalties, yet Coyotes Coach  &UR; Jim Schoenfeld was critical of only
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing in the game that I thought was cheap was the
slew-foot on Keith,'' he said, referring to Belfour's trip of
Tkachuk. ``He was in uncharted waters up the ice. It's one of those
hitting-from-behind things that can be very dangerous, where you
can sprain a knee going down or, a worst-case scenario, smack the
back of your head.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's a member of his team, and when things get nasty and
everybody pulls together, he probably figured it was his best
chance to be physical.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes &UR; Rick Tocchet said, ``A guy can get hurt doing something
like that. Slew-footing a guy is something you can get suspended
for. I've never seen a goalie do that before, but he gets combative
and pretty intense.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Belfour vs. Tkachuk and  &UR; Derian Hatcher vs.  &UR; Jeremy
 &UR; Roenick is likely just the tip of the iceberg, according to Stars
defenseman  &UR; Mike Keane and Coach  &UR; Ken Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing has gone above a rivalry,'' Keane said, shaking his
head. ``It's a civil war. It's good to have a rivalry in the
playoffs. It makes you play a step above normal. Today's game was
pretty much what everybody expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he thought Saturday's game put all the ill
feelings to rest, Hitchcock said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will go on for years. I expect it to, and I know
our players expect it to. There is a rivalry, a hate,'' Hitchcock
said. ``That's what builds a rivalry. I don't imagine it will be
anything different. I don't imagine Derian will come in and play
any less physical, and as this series moves along in years to come,
I'm sure Roenick will be a big part of it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``These issues stay with you for a long period of time and build
the level of play, and if you want to go along for the ride, it's a
pretty good series. Unfortunately, there's a lot of responsibility
that has to be taken along the way. A lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes goalie  &UR; Nikolai Khabibulin, who set a franchise record
with his eighth shutout, was asked how much he wants a second-round
match-up with the Stars:
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I want to play them bad,'' he said. ``That means we get
out the first round.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
