r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     04-18 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS QUICKLY GO WITH BEST AVAILABLE ATHLETE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Invoking a tired but time-honored disclaimer,
the Cowboys surveyed the NFL's first-round offerings yesterday and
opted to draft the _ fanfare, please _ ``best available athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   What a concept.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, this is a significant departure from seasons past, when
the Cowboys were prone to select the draft's best available Shante
or one of a series of Jay Novacek-alikes.
</P>
<P>
   But 6-foot-3, 281-pound Ebenezer Ekuban was different, in that
the Cowboys claimed that at the time he was selected _
midafternoon, 20 picks into the first round _ he was the ``last
first-round defensive player left on our board.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, they didn't reach. Nor did they bow to the
pleadings of an assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, coach Chan Gailey and Owner Jones drafted a solid
citizen with an engaging upside who, provided he can perform as
billed, will find his way onto the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   Again, such a concept.
</P>
<P>
   But just as Owner Jones cannot have enough TV sound bites, the
Cowboys' defensive system cannot have too many linemen. A
procession of fresh bodies is desired, especially in the dog days
of a Texas Stadium autumn.
</P>
<P>
   From that angle, the drafting of Ebenezer Ekuban makes canny
sense. Ekuban is quick and reportedly can rush the passer. The
Cowboys covet both attributes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense has always been built on speed,'' coordinator Dave
Campo said. ``This young man brings a speed factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard nothing from the media but that we can't rush the
passer. Well, we're going to give ourselves a chance to rush the
passer.''
</P>
<P>
   The theory is bold and intriguing. Imagine _ a Cowboys
first-round draft choice who actually plays. Contributes, even.
</P>
<P>
   We'll believe it when we see it. But until then, Owner Jones and
his war-room comrades are to be commended for doing something the
patient, old-fashioned way. Drafting the ``best available athlete''
is a ploy they can live and grow with.
</P>
<P>
   The young player may do nothing for three seasons. But at least
he'll look good doing it.
</P>
<P>
   In the seasons since Jimmy Johnson left, the Cowboys have
exhibited a fatal propensity to make draft-day mistakes and then
nurture them. It was the natural offshoot of letting assistant
coaches have too much say in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   With no Jimmy, Owner Jones turned to the whims of the assistant
coaches and their accompanying opinions. Line coach Hudson Houck
took a liking to 345-pound Shane Hannah. Oops. Former defensive
coordinator Butch Davis took his turn in the first round in 1994
and selected Shante Carver. Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts are scouts. They tend to remain unbiased. But assistant
coaches are tempted to view draft picks as works in progress,
awaiting only the assistant coach's guiding hand to be transformed
into the next Montana, the next Singletary.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, the assistant coach is always the last to let
go. The once-prospect lingers well past his shelf life.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys no longer draft that way, thank goodness. And thus,
it was interesting yesterday that they drafted in the first round
for shelf life and speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speed factor is the biggest thing,'' Campo said. ``That's
something you can't coach. Either a guy can run or he can't.''
</P>
<P>
   In Ekuban, newly signed linebacker Quentin Coryatt and the shift
of Randall Godfrey to inside linebacker, replacing the ineffective
Fred Strickland, Campo's defense should have a sleek, new look.
</P>
<P>
   But a key part of that prognosis, however, remains Leon Lett.
The owner and the defensive coordinator both rambled on yesterday,
acting as if they expected Leon to return to the fold at some point
this season. ``I believe he'll really be here,'' Campo said.
</P>
<P>
   Campo is no trained parrot, speaking for the owner. The feeling
here is that he and other coaches have been given assurances _ from
Jones, presumably _ that Leon's alleged transgressions won't be
deemed as serious as the ones that previously rendered him a year's
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Owner Jones isn't one to spoil a good draft party.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Cowboys been able to select defensive tackle Anthony
``Booger'' McFarland, they could have achieved that rare match of
talent and need. But McFarland went early.
</P>
<P>
   It speaks volumes that the Cowboys didn't reach or try to
conjure another McFarland _ a Booger Lite, if you will.
</P>
<P>
   Fanfare, please. This time, instead, they say they took the best
athlete left on the board.
</P>
<P>
   It's a cliche, but one that works. Especially when that cliche
can rush a quarterback.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
