<HEADLINE>
RODMAN'S LATE SHOW MAY BE DONE FOR GOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Great One is gone from the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   The Late One is gone from the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Inexplicably frustrated by his consistent tardiness, the Lakers
waived Dennis Rodman on Thursday night, leaving their title run and
his basketball future in serious jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Signing Rodman wasn't LA's mistake. Expecting him to act like a
normal human being was. The Lakers trusted a person with rainbow
hair, multiple body piercings, graffiti skin and a history of
chaos, and then acted aghast when he didn't conform to their rules
_ specifically showing up on time for practice and going into games
when coach Kurt Rambis asked him nicely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just couldn't keep making special accommodations for him,''
said Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, who traded away big body Elden Campbell in part
because of Rodman's presence, are now left with only J.R. Reid and
Robert Horry to play power forward in the Western Conference
playoffs, where they could run into the likes of David Robinson,
Karl Malone and Brian Grant. As cancerous as Rodman seemed,
Shaquille O'Neal just lost his bodyguard.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were 17-6 with Rodman, 8-9 without him.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry Buss, it seems, was the only one in the organization
willing to put up with Rodman's antics, which included refusing to
go back into games four times in his 23-game stint and missing four
games for personal reasons. He was also late to five practices,
including Thursday, when he slowly shuffled in search of shoes and
socks until a fuming Rambis ordered him home.
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't have shocked the Lakers, it came with the
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing the release of Rodman was a possibility, Lakers vice
president Jerry West should have covered himself by keeping
Campbell around. The Lakers' frontcourt will now be exposed as
soft, and their front office as suckers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rodzilla who sits out games, head-butts referees and takes
gambling jaunts to Vegas has played his last NBA game. No longer
able physically to shut down opponents in the low post or able
mentally to keep focused on basketball for more than three days,
Dennis the Menace must revamp his approach at age 38 or _ as he did
after his release _ simply ride his Harley into the sunset.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure we can sign him,'' joked Jazz coach Jerry Sloan. ``And he
can coach, too. Because if he's here, I won't be.''
</P>
<P>
   Added former Rodman coach and longtime admirer Chuck Daly,
``Dennis has a great act, one of the best ever. But he's got to
tone it down and do things like show up for practice if he ever
wants to play again.''
</P>
<P>
   That's doubtful at best. Because he wouldn't be eligible for a
team's playoff roster, Rodman is done this season. And in all
likelihood, the Worm has turned the last page in his peculiar book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm the fall guy for the Lakers,'' Rodman said.
``They're being cowards for not taking some of the blame. But
that's OK, I'm used to it. It's always Dennis' fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Rest in peace, Late One. And, by the way, enjoy sleeping in.
SPOTLIGHT ON ... Kevin Garnett
</P>
<P>
   With the departures of Tom Gugliotta and Stephon Marbury, the
Timberwolves' lone remaining star literally collapsed last week
trying to carry Minnesota on his $126 million shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Garnett, the team's leading scorer, rebounder and
shot-blocker, spent Monday night and Tuesday in a Twin Cities
hospital being treated for dehydration and flu-like symptoms, while
the team lost in San Antonio and Dallas without him. Garnett had
been logging heavy minutes as the Wolves played five games in six
nights, winding up with an IV in his arm in the training room after
a 95-90 loss to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked on trying to get some rest, but it's hard when you
have three games in a row and your team counts on you,'' Garnett
said. ``I learned a lesson. I've got to get some rest. Pushing
myself too far put me in the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota is 0-7 without Garnett in the lineup the past three
seasons.
QUICK HITS AROUND THE EAST
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls are out of the playoffs for the first time in 14
years. Their scoring differential has plummeted 15.9 points this
season. ... Atlanta is on pace to be one of the worst offensive
teams to ever qualify for the postseason. Currently with the No. 4
seed, the Hawks scored 79, 71, 78 and 77 last week and average just
85 on 40-percent shooting. ... New Nets guard Stephon Marbury took
a shot at the Knicks' point guard tandem of Charlie Ward-Chris
Childs after they held him to eight points and eight turnovers in a
93-78 Knicks rout. ``They still need a point guard,'' he said.
``They'll never win no championship with them two guys. They'll
never, ever win. You can put that on your back page if you want to.
It's just not gonna happen. They're just not the guys you need to
win a championship. They might not even make the playoffs.'' ...
Michael Jordan met again with Hornets owner George Shinn last week
to discuss his possible purchase of control of the team. The lone
remaining issue appears to be final say on basketball decisions,
which Jordan is demanding.
AROUND THE WEST
</P>
<P>
   Portland, which last week became the last team to lose two
consecutive games, is giving more crunch-time minutes to Jim
Jackson over Isaiah Rider. With Rider on the court the Blazers are
plus-62; with Jackson plus-211. ... Suns center Luc Longley, who
suffered a hyperxtended knee in Utah, ripped into Karl Malone for
what he says was an intentional ploy to injure him. ``It looked
pretty bloody flagrant to me,'' Longley said. ``There's a fine line
between trying to draw a foul and going straight for someone's leg.
It looked like he went for my knee, and that's weak, as far as I'm
concerned. I don't know why he would do that, especially for a guy
who projects himself as a class act.'' ... TCU's Lee Nailon was one
of the standouts at the Nike Desert Classic predraft scouting camp
last week. Unlike last year in the camp, scouts said the 6-8,
225-pounder got to the basket with his dribble and finished drives
with an array of layups and dunks. He is considered a top-10 pick.
</P>
<P>
   NUMBERS GAME
</P>
<P>
   0: Number of NBA teams averaging 100 points per game. Ten years
ago, 24 of the 25 teams averaged at least 100.
</P>
<P>
   37: Times Michael Jordan scored 50 points or more in a game for
the Bulls, who last week set an all-time mark with 49 against the
Heat. \Nsubheds:Quote to note ``It's tax season. They're all
nervous about the IRS.'' _ Houston's Charles Barkley, explaining
the poor quality of officiating recently.
Best and Worst
</P>
<P>
   Best microcosm of ugly season: In what should be the enduring
highlight from this irregular season, the Warriors' Chris Mills
grabbed the tip off a jump ball near his defensive basket and
inexplicably went up for a dunk. Even more ridiculous, however, was
the Mavericks' Samaki Walker, who tried to block the shot and
fouled Mills, thereby preventing Mills from scoring two points for
the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   Worst consistency: And Sonics fans thought George Karl's wacky
tactics were a little unstable. Under Paul Westphal the last 10
days, Seattle defeated the Rockets, Trail Blazers and Lakers and
lost to the Grizzlies. ``If you can figure this team out,''
Westphal said, ``let me know. We're a Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde
team.'' The Sonics grabbed an NBA-record low 19 rebounds in a home
loss to the Suns last Wednesday.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
