<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-JAZZ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS: BEATEN BUT UPBEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Is it stubborn confidence, sunny optimism or
just plain false bravado? Or are the Los Angeles Lakers simply so
dizzy with defeats they can no longer discern between their hopeful
self-image and the painful reality?
</P>
<P>
   Another disjointed performance netted another double-digit loss
Saturday, but after being dismantled 109-93 by the Utah Jazz, the
Lakers somehow found silver linings where no one without
astigmatism could have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of the guys today. They showed a lot of effort and a
lot of heart,'' Shaquille O'Neal said. ``Good times are ahead,
hopefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Kurt Rambis' face screamed frustration, but his carefully
chosen _ albeit strained _ words indicated otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a lot of good things out there,'' he said. ``It's not
gonna turn around overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Or even seven nights. The Lakers lost their third straight game,
all to playoff teams, the same ones they might see next month. A
crucial stretch run has netted them four losses in their last six
games.
</P>
<P>
   The deadline for creating a viable playoff team is now nine
games away.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Lakers have their first three-game losing streak since
late February, and that slide got a coach fired. But as if
desperately holding onto their prized self-esteem, the Lakers
spurned any talk of frustration or low morale.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can always dig yourself out,'' Kobe Bryant said. ``It's a
no-brainer, we're gonna get better.''
</P>
<P>
   In their first game of the post-Dennis Rodman era, the Lakers
outrebounded the Jazz by one, but their defense was spotty and the
offense inconsistent. Utah shot 50.7 percent for the game and
outscored the Lakers 57-36 in the second and third quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers shot a respectable 48.1 percent but scored 24 fewer
points from the foul line as the Jazz made 35 of 41 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, Utah led by a dozen. By midway through the third it
was a 19-point lead, and the Lakers seemed almost uninterested in
making a run. Despite a 24-point second half from Rick Fox, a late
surge from Bryant and a 29-point night from O'Neal, the game was
over 16 minutes shy of the final buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by 15 points with 4:17 to play in the third, the Lakers
watched the Jazz score seven straight, capped by a Greg Foster
3-pointer. Nothing like a wide-open 3 from a journeyman center to
suck the air out of a team.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the fourth that the Lakers got within 20 again.
They did outscore the Jazz reserves 33-27 in the final quarter to
make it semi-respectable, but the garbage-time effort couldn't
overshadow 36 minutes of uninspired play.
</P>
<P>
   Frustration was evident, from Fox's third-quarter flagrant foul
on Karl Malone to technical fouls on Fox and Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   And nothing irritates a losing team more than an unbalanced
final tally in the fouls column. Utah went to the free-throw line
41 times, making 35. The Lakers took only 18 foul shots, converting
11.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the stats sheet and they make almost twice as many
free throws as we attempt. That's something that's hard for me to
believe in a big ballgame like this,'' Rambis said. Added O'Neal,
``There's not much you can do when a team like that goes to the
line 41 times.''
</P>
<P>
   Or when Malone scores 27 points and Jeff Hornacek scores 20 and
Bryon Russell scores 14 in methodical fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Consecutive losses to Seattle, Portland and Utah have the Lakers
looking primed for no better than a second-round exit. But they're
clinging to a new, three-word affirmation.
</P>
<P>
   There's still time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got nine games to go, we've got plenty of time to turn
things around,'' Derek Fisher said. ``We didn't lay down today.
They beat us. And we played a lot better than we had.''
</P>
<P>
   So with optimism as their guiding force, and a winnable date
with Vancouver on Monday, the Lakers will eschew the negative as
best they can.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to stay positive,'' Fisher said. ``As soon as you
start to doubt your ability as a team and start to have negative
thoughts, there's no sense going out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
