<HEADLINE>
CHIRPING AL READY STARTING FOR ORIOLES  
 UNHAPPY WITH MANAGER, PITCHING COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most splintered club in all of baseball is at it again, and
this is a situation that has all the markings to get uglier before
it gets better.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Orioles, the worst club money can buy, are sniping
at each other and their manager,  &UR; Ray Miller, whose time as the
head bird seems tenuous at best. And the season is just two weeks
old.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Eric Davis' just released book, ``Born to Play _ The Eric Davis
Story,'' has revealed a batch of problems afflicting the Orioles,
whose $84 million payroll this season is the highest in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Davis suggests in the book that several Orioles question the
leadership capabilities of Miller and pointed to a closed-door
meeting last Aug. 27 in Chicago, when Miller and then-second
baseman  &UR; Roberto
 &UR; Alomar were in each other's face.
</P>
<P>
   Miller then pulled his coaching staff out of the clubhouse and
told the players to straighten out the situation any way they
wanted, even by fighting each other if they cared to, according to
Davis' book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like we're supposed to fight,'' Davis writes. ``We're looking
at each other in confusion. Even Cal Jr. is scratching his head. We
were a couple of pitches away from the World Series (in 1997).
</P>
<P>
   . . . Somebody said, `We ought to kick Ray's (butt) . . . for
not realizing his inexperience is part of the problem. . . . That
meeting killed the will of a team struggling to get back into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis goes on to write about an on-field exchange between  &UR; Cal
Ripken
 &UR; Jr., and an American League umpire in which Ripken supposedly said,
``Why don't you throw this (manager) out of here, so we'll have a
chance to win this game?''
</P>
<P>
   Davis did not say who the manager was, but considering he only
played for  &UR; Davey Johnson and Miller while in Baltimore, the finger
was clearly pointing toward Miller. Should Miller be fired, the
list of candidates to replace him is headed by  &UR; Eddie Murray, a
favorite of owner  &UR; Peter Angelos.
</P>
<P>
   Others on a potential short-list include former Milwaukee
Manager  &UR; Tom
 &UR; Trebelhorn, who currently works for the Orioles, Atlanta hitting
coach
 &UR; Don Baylor and Brewers Manager  &UR; Phil Garner, who is in the final
year of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   But before the Orioles make any managerial moves, there are
still rumblings from the pitching staff over how first-year
pitching coach
 &UR; Bruce Kison used them during spring training. Starter  &UR; Scott
Erickson, who is 0-2 with a 10.13 ERA after two starts, is implying
Kison did not give the staff enough spring innings. Entering the
weekend, the club was 3-0 in games  &UR; Mike Mussina started and 0-7
with anyone else starting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's still part of guys getting where they need to be
with fewer times to go out there,'' Erickson said. ``We have to get
ready to play. . . . We've got a ways to go, I guess you could
say.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was asked if it was normal for pitchers to still be
preparing for the season once it has begun, Erickson said, ``I
don't know, but there are a lot of other teams playing pretty good
right now.'' &QL; 
Trivial question &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta outfielder  &UR; Otis Nixon needs three stolen bases to
become the 16th player ever to reach 600 steals. From the group of
15, seven have come since the end of World War II. Who are the
seven to steal 600 bases since 1945? &QL; 
Mickey takes on Bart &QL; 
Disney Chairman  &UR; Michael Eisner, whose empire includes the Anaheim
Angels, is apparently ready to put on the boxing gloves when it
comes to taking on Southern California's other power outlet, the
Fox-owned Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner was in no mood to pull his punches or bow to the mighty
Dodgers, who have basically owned the Los Angeles area for 40 years
when it comes to baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in competition with Fox everywhere,'' Eisner said in a
recent ``Los Angeles Times'' story. ``Luckily, their baseball team
doesn't compare to our baseball team. So in that area, we don't
have to worry about the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have been in nine World Series since moving from
Brooklyn in 1958. The Angels have been in none since their
inception in 1961. But this is 1999, and the Dodgers have not won a
postseason game since Game 5 of the 1988 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the quality of players, and the quality of how we're
going to win,'' Eisner said. ``They're the lesser team in the
market. They're just going to have to deal with that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels did distinguish themselves over the winter when they
guaranteed $80 million to first baseman  &UR; Mo Vaughn, easily the
largest contract this organization has ever given any player. In a
way, the Angels finally began playing big-league ball with the
Dodgers last winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Angels are the one thing in our series of assets that does
not turn a profit and that I don't think has the potential to turn
a profit,'' Eisner said of Disney's vast holdings. ``That's
discouraging. But that's OK.'' &QL; 
Nudging Pudge &QL; 
Texas Manager  &UR; Johnny Oates may have to implement a little-known
bit of motivation his buddy  &UR; Jim Leyland used a few years back on
 &UR; Barry &UR; Bonds while the two were in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers catcher  &UR; Ivan Rodriguez does not like to run out every
ball he hits. So Oates came to a compromise similar to the one
Leyland had with Bonds: When he hits a ground ball run it out to
first base. On fly balls, it's OK to sometimes jog since so few are
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can live with that,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, Rodriguez barely made it to first base when Anaheim
left fielder  &UR; Orlando Palmeiro dropped a fly ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pudge will catch a lot of innings and run out a lot of balls
for us,'' said Oates, carefully choosing his words. &QL; 
The crawling stage &QL; 
St. Louis' rookie phenom,  &UR; J.D. Drew was sent to the bench to
ponder his first 10 days in the majors last week after going 2 for
18 in his first games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to the starting lineup a full day later, Drew
was 1 for 5 with three strikeouts and mis-played a ball in the
outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's taking baby steps,'' said Cardinals Manager  &UR; Tony La
Russa. ``This is a tough league.'' &QL; 
Helping hand &QL; 
San Francisco outfielder  &UR; Stan Javier, one of the best all-around
people in the game, is crediting new Hall of Famer  &UR; Orlando Cepeda
with helping improve his hitting from the right side.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants switch-hitter already has three home runs while
batting right-handed, amazing considering he went all of last
season without one from that side of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me I had to make some adjustments,'' Javier said.
``I'm hitting more straight up now. I used to be more bent over. I
feel better right-handed now, more free to swing.'' &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL; 
The group is headed by the career stolen base king,  &UR; Rickey
Henderson. Next among those who played in the Baby Boomer age with
at least 600 steals are:  &UR; Lou Brock,  &UR; Tim Raines,  &UR; Vince Coleman,
 &UR; Joe Morgan,  &UR; Willie &UR; Wilson and  &UR; Bert Campaneris.  &UR; Maury Wills fell
14 stolen bases short of reaching the 600 plateau. &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL; 
 &UR; TOP OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. ClevelandWould it be bad form to start setting the postseason
rotation?  &QL; 
2. NY Yankees &UR; Roger Clemens got rocked Thursday and still no signs
of worrying.  &QL; 
3. BostonThe Sox's 6-1 start was the best Beantown had seen in 44
years.  &QL; 
4. NY MetsHow long until Manager  &UR; Bobby Valentine needs a larger
cap?  &QL; 
5. San FranciscoUh-oh,  &UR; Barry Bonds is off to one of his best
starts ever.  &QL; 
6. AtlantaIn the midst of a 15-day trip that will crisscross the
country.  &QL; 
7. Los AngelesAs long as the Dodgers are winning, everything
remains cohesive.  &QL; 
8. St. LouisThe supposed weak link, the starters, have been
impressive so far.  &QL; 
9. HoustonAstros were 5-0 with catcher  &UR; Tony Eusebio behind the
plate, entering weekend. &UR; BOTTOM OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
30. DetroitLearned last year how disheartening April losses can be.
Now repeating?  &QL; 
29. FloridaStarter  &UR; Alex Fernandez is back on the DL because of a
sore shoulder.  &QL; 
28. MontrealYou get what you pay for. In this case, it's not much.
 &QL; 
27. Kansas CityJust 29-51 at home last season and started 0-3 at
Kauffman this year.  &QL; 
26. SeattleFirst A-Rod, now  &UR; Carlos Guillen; The signs are not
good.  &QL; 
25. Chicago CubsFinally, a  &UR; Sammy Sosa sighting on Friday.  &QL; 
24. CincinnatiTogetherness? Six Reds went to a ``Jerry Springer''
``Show'' last week.  &QL; 
23. BaltimoreThe in-fighting began in earnest last week.  &QL; 
22. Tampa BayWay too many problems for this tiny of space. ON THE
RISE &QL; 
 &UR; Diamondbacks: The disastrous first week of the season is little
more than a long-ago memory these days. Arizona is benefiting from
what it paid most for during the off-season, starting pitching.
Starters  &UR; Randy Johnson,  &UR; Todd Stottlemyre and  &UR; Armando Reynoso _
all signed as free agents over the winter _ have looked impressive
most often. Take away Johnson's one bad outing last Thursday and
this trio is looking like they will make a solid return on all the
millions the club is paying them. &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL; 
 &UR; Colorado Rockies: Once again, it's pitching and defense that has
prevented this club from winning more games during the first two
weeks of the season. The Rockies face the very real stigma of
playing home games a mile above sea level. Whatever that means to a
baseball or a pitcher's psyche is not a figment. But playing at
Coors Field was always a plus for the Rockies. Last year it was not
and this year who knows? &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL; 
Former Chicago Bears Coach  &UR; Mike Ditka, who remains a Chicago icon,
sang the seventh-inning staple ``Take Me Out To The Ballpark,''
last week during a Cubs game. After badly butchering the song last
year when he rushed through it, this time he was far more
deliberate. ``I'm terrible. What did you expect, Pavarotti? I said
it was going to be slower, not better.'' &QL; 
OUT OF LEFT FIELD &QL; 
Kansas City rookie center fielder  &UR; Carlos Beltran earned all the
praise during spring training from just about every preseason
publication that exists. So far, he's showing why. Beltran, the
Royals' leadoff hitter, entered the weekend batting .314 while
playing well in center field. He had a little trouble retrieving
his first home run last weekend after White Sox center fielder
 &UR; McKay Christensen tossed the ball into the stands after a fan
threw it back from the seats. The ball was eventually tracked down
for Beltran. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE HIT LIST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Latest punch lines for a joke about a stadium: Tropicana Field,
home of the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, was home to a pair of moments
that add to its laughable resume when a bank of lights refused to
go on and lingering smoke from pre-game fireworks prevented a fly
from being caught by Devil Rays center fielder  &UR; Randy Winn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Z factor hard at work: The Texas Rangers have three players
( &UR; Gregg Zaun,  &UR; Todd Zeile and  &UR; Jeff Zimmerman) whose last name
begins with the letter ``Z.'' The only other club to make such a
boast was the 1916 Chicago Cubs. They had  &UR; Rollie Zeider,  &UR; Heine
 &UR; Zimmerman (no relation to Jeff) and  &UR; Dutch Zwilling.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Mike Aldrete.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; One-third of Mark McGwire? I don't think so: Pitcher
 &UR; Eric Ludwick was designated for assignment by Toronto. So what?
Ludwick and pitchers  &UR; T.J. Mathews and  &UR; Blake Stein were the three
players Oakland received in exchange for baseball's one-man circus.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; If this is a precursor, it should be a great NL West
 &UR; race: Seven games against each other and very little separates the
Diamondbacks and Los Angeles. The Dodgers lead in games, 4-3, and
runs scored, 39-38. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jose Offerman, the subject of so much consternation during the
winter, had six straight multihit games for Boston to start the
season. In his previous stints with the Dodgers and Royals,
Offerman had never accomplished the feat. Teammate  &UR; Nomar
Garciaparra's longest such streak is four games.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher  &UR; Mike Morgan of the Texas Rangers earned a victory over
the Seattle Mariners last week and earned a distinction that could
remain for a long while. Morgan's last victory over the Mariners
was 20 years earlier, surpassing the 18 years  &UR; Cal McLish took
between wins over Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The Montreal Expos actually had a larger crowd for their home
opener (43,917) than the Toronto Blue Jays (37,160). The next
night, though, it was back to the usual, when only 5,589 showed up,
the smallest Olympic Stadium crowd in nine seasons.
</P>
<P>
   If  &UR; Terry Mulholland, the Rock of Gibraltar for the Cubs'
pitching staff, had his way he'd start every four days and relieve
in between, just like in the old days. Because of  &UR; Kevin
 &UR; Tapani's sore shoulder, Mulholland has moved into the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City outfielder  &UR; Johnny Damon had played 169 consecutive
games entering the weekend. His streak, however, was in jeopardy of
being snapped since his wife is due to deliver twins any day.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh broadcaster  &UR; Steve Blass, poster child for what is
currently afflicting  &UR; Mark Wohlers, left the then-Braves reliever a
note last year wishing him luck. Wohlers, who is attempting to be
the first to overcome a sudden loss of the strike zone, never
returned the message. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees may have had their fill of pitcher  &UR; Hideki
 &UR; Irabu, who gave up five runs in just one-third of an inning last
week. The club was seeking either to trade him or send him to
Triple-A Columbus (Ohio), the more likely scenario.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers General Manager  &UR; Kevin Malone and  &UR; Steve Kim, uncle and
agent for  &UR; Chan Ho Park, are scheduled to meet this week to resume
negotiations on a multiyear contract extension. Park wants a deal
between four and six years that will pay him around $10 million per
season.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh's  &UR; Rich Loiselle has apparently lost his closer's
role even though he never was presented with a save opportunity. He
gave up one run in a tie score against Montreal and now is watching
 &UR; Jason Christiansen and  &UR; Mike Williams as co-closers.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is very close to finalizing a contract extension that
will keep  &UR; Jamie Moyer, whose .726 (45-17) winning percentage is
the best in the majors the past three years, with the Mariners for
at least two years and an option for a third season. If Moyer
reaches all three years, he will be paid between $14-$16 million.
</P>
<P>
   Former Atlanta Braves second baseman  &UR; Mark Lemke, 33, has been
working out since January and feels no ill effects from the
post-concussion syndrome that sidelined him most of last season.
Lemke is working out with the hopes a club will call on him.
</P>
<P>
   Boston right-hander  &UR; Ramon Martinez, former ace of the Dodgers,
may be ready to begin his rehabilitation assignment within a month.
If all goes well, Martinez, brother of Boston ace
 &UR; Pedro Martinez, will need about six weeks before he is ready to
join the Red Sox's rotation. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at (602) 444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
