<HEADLINE>
BARTLETT LAKE, MARINA HIDDEN PLEASURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Bryan Church believes he's winning the battle but not
as quickly as he'd like.
</P>
<P>
   Church owns the marina at Bartlett Lake. Even getting it built
was a struggle. Financing was a problem, and it took him a while to
get more backers. He has built the marina into a first-class
facility, but again nature isn't serving him well.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the extremely dry winter and spring, Bartlett fell
into 20s in percentage of fullness. The boat ramps were useless,
and anglers are still forced to launch from a point beside the
ramps.
</P>
<P>
   That's a shame. Bartlett has been the most consistently good
bass and crappie fishing lake in the state since fall. It'd drop
off sometimes but not for long.
</P>
<P>
   But, naturally, low water hurt Church's business. Now, he
believes, that's almost over.
</P>
<P>
   ``My business was hurt, but it was more of a perception of the
lake,'' Church said. ``People believe it's in bad shape. They see a
dirt ring on the water and think it's a mudhole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 1,300 surface acres, and boating is just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the lake is rising at 32 percent of capacity and is
going to come up eight to 10 feet.
</P>
<P>
   He said he's been told by Salt River Project, which controls the
lake, that it is going to buy Central Arizona Project water this
year to try to keep the lake stable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public ramp is almost usable now,'' Church said.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints have reached me through readers that the marina has
built so much fence that reaching the shoreline to fish is next to
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Church said shoreline anglers are welcome to fish inside the
fence as long as they park in the upper parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``People with disabilities are more than welcome to fish down
there,'' said Church, who is confined to a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that the U.S. Forest Service has concurred that
anglers either on shoreline or in boats should fish at least 50
feet from his docks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marina members are allowed to fish by their boat,'' Church
said. ``Others need to stay 50 feet away. The most important reason
for that is that lures are stuck in a lot of boat covers. We have a
$150,000 Sea Ray (boat) here that had lures stuck all over the
cover. I can't sanction that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, the lures also break off on the cables that hold the
marina. When divers go down, they get pricked by the lures.''
</P>
<P>
   Church has been confident enough to purchase a new fleet of
rental boats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've purchased a large number of 14-foot pontoon boats,'' he
said. ``They rent for $70 for half a day and are good for fishing.
A small aluminum fishing boat rents for $40 for half a day, and a
20-foot pontoon that rents for $220 for a full day.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the lake low, the lake ``is plenty boatable,'' Church
said. ``The Arizona Game and Fish Department has been great at
marking hazards.'' He also believes the marina is in excellent
shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only problem is we still don't have food service,'' Church
said. ``But we do have a store on the water now.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the year, when water started dropping, things were
grim in October and February.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a terrible hit in those two months,'' he said. ``We
spent two to three weeks just keeping the marina wet. You have to
make decisions on the fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he regret getting into the marina business?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd do it again,'' Church said. ``It's been fun. But I'm sick
of old problems. I want some new ones.'' He also said that fishing
guide Don Roughan has joined the marina staff. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at (602) 444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
