<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOTTLEMYRE EXPECTS NO SUS PENSION  
 SAYS HE DIDN'T DO ANYTHING IN HAYES INCIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Diamondbacks pitcher  &UR; Todd Stottlemyre said he doesn't
expect the league to suspend him for Friday's sixth-inning
altercation with San Francisco Giants third baseman  &UR; Charlie Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do anything _ unless you're suspended for ducking,''
the right-hander said.
</P>
<P>
   After rounding second on  &UR; Brent Maynes' single, Hayes ran toward
the mound, swung at Stottlemyre and missed. The Diamondbacks' &UR; Matt
 &UR; Williams tackled Hayes, and Stottlemyre was pulled away.
</P>
<P>
   The benches and bullpens emptied, but no other punches were
thrown.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes and Stottlemyre were ejected.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks first baseman  &UR; Travis Lee said that Hayes had been
upset about how Stottlemyre was getting calls on outside pitches
and was ``freaking out'' when he reached first. Stottlemyre heard
Hayes' remarks and had a few of his own once Hayes reached second,
triggering Hayes' action.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes refused to talk and was greeted by a chorus of boos by
fans Saturday. He told reporters Friday night that the Diamondbacks
were going to be in a lot of fights because of Stottlemyre and that
Stottlemyre's teammates didn't like him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't even want to comment on that (expletive), because
it shows you how (expletive) stupid he is,'' Stottlemyre said.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder &UR; Dante Powell, who was with the Giants last year,
said, ``It was just an angry comment by Charlie. That's the
farthest thing from the truth. Everyone in this clubhouse respects
(Stottlemyre).''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, who served a suspension in 1993 for brushing an
umpire after disputing a play, was surprised he even got tossed
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he (the umpire) made the decision, I wasn't trying to
change his mind,'' Stottlemyre said. ``I was just asking, `What are
you supposed to do to try to stay in the game? What actions are you
supposed to choose?'
</P>
<P>
   ``He just said, `Go take a shower.' '' &QL; 
First save &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander &UR; Brian Anderson, who moved to the bullpen this year,
was the last pitcher expecting to pick up the Diamondbacks' first
save of the '99 season.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who got a save in the '97 World Series for the
Cleveland Indians, worked 3 innings in Friday's 10-4 victory. He
came in with the bases loaded in the sixth and got  &UR; Ramon Martinez
to ground out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do it, but I'll never learn to like it,'' Anderson said
about being a reliever. ``I'm going to take pride in it, but it
will never overtake starting pitching.'' &QL; 
Loading up &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter loaded his lineup with mostly
right-handed hitters Saturday against left-hander  &UR; Kirk Rueter, who
came in with a 14.85 earned-run average after his first two starts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Greg Colbrunn played first and batted third,  &UR; Bernard Gilkey
played left field and &UR; Dante Powell started in center.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early season, we'd like to get these guys as many
opportunities as we can,'' Showalter said.
</P>
<P>
   Colbrunn hit his first home run as a Diamondback. Powell had a
double, and Gilkey singled in three at bats.
</P>
</TEXT>
