A3088 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-NOTEBOOK-AZ     04-18 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER BECOMES EXPENDABLE  
 CARDS FIND POTENTIAL REPLACEMENT IN RUTLEDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. -  &UR; Jamir Miller's future with the Cardinals was
placed into even greater question Saturday when they selected a
linebacker in the second round of the NFL draft and a pass-rushing
specialist in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably makes it less likely that he'll be back,''  &UR; Bill
Bidwill
 &UR; Jr., Cardinals vice president, said of Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, an unrestricted free agent who led the Cardinals in
tackles last season, rejected a two-year, $6 million offer last
month. Then, after firing agent  &UR; Steve Baker and hiring  &UR; Leigh
Steinberg, Miller expressed renewed interest in staying with the
team that drafted him in the first round in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   It is believed Miller wants a one-year offer so he can try his
luck on the open market again next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have said they want Miller back and that the door
remains open, but by drafting linebacker  &UR; Johnny Rutledge of
Florida 51st overall, and defensive end  &UR; Tom Burke of Wisconsin
83rd, the door would appear to be slamming shut.
</P>
<P>
   At 6 feet 2, 246 pounds, Rutledge can play inside or outside, a
bigger version of his new teammate,  &UR; Ron McKinnon. Rutledge is a
run stopper, something that right outside linebackers  &UR; Tony McCombs
and
 &UR; Patrick Sapp didn't always do.
</P>
<P>
   Rutledge was an All-Southeastern Conference pick and among 10
finalists for the Butkus Award after making 106 tackles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm basically in tears right now because it's a dream come
true for me,'' Rutledge said. ``I'm just happy to be a Cardinal
now. Hopefully, I can come in and play. I'm a player that plays
with speed. I'm very smart, physical, and I think I can add a lot
to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes pass coverage, Rutledge said. That is the weakest
part of Miller's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coverage has always been part of my game,'' Rutledge said. ``I
always played corner in little league so I think covering is pretty
natural.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke (6-2, 243), a first-team All-American, played defensive
end for the Badgers but also could swing to linebacker. He
undoubtedly will be a prominent member of the special teams. He set
Big Ten records with 22 sacks for 130 lost yards and with 31 other
tackles for loss, 151 yards worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``These last two picks, we had them graded higher than where
they were when it came our turn to pick, so it was hard to pass
them up,'' Coach Vince Tobin said. ``We would have drafted a
linebacker even if we had Jamir signed. Linebacker is the core of
the team. They can do a lot of things for you, especially on
special teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller was a strong run stopper and complained that he wasn't
used more as a pass rusher, which he considers one of his strongest
skills. &QL; 
Staying put &QL; 
The future of running back  &UR; Adrian Murrell in the desert became
more secure when Indianapolis unexpectedly selected Miami back
 &UR; Edgerrin &UR; James with the fourth pick. That set up Washington to
make a monumental trade with New Orleans that allowed the Saints to
take Heisman Trophy winner  &UR; Ricky Williams at No. 5.
</P>
<P>
   It was somewhat surprising that Murrell's status was ever in
question, considering that he came in last season and rushed for
more than 1,000 yards behind a mediocre line as the Cardinals
posted a winning season (9-7) and won a playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   And according to the Cardinals, there never was a question about
it.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, sources close to the Cardinals and New England
Patriots, a team desperately seeking a back, said the teams had
agreed to a trade of Murrell for the Patriots' third-round pick if
the Cardinals drafted James at No. 8 after New England's attempts
to move higher and draft either Williams or James were
unsuccessful. Tobin denied the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never ever said that we would even consider that,'' Tobin
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stephen Hayes, Murrell's agent, said he believes Tobin, but
would have understood why the Cardinals might have done it had
Williams or James been on the board when they selected at No. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adrian has no problem with what happened,'' Hayes said. ``He's
absolutely fine. He knows (with Cardinals first-round pick  &UR; David
 &UR; Boston, a wide receiver from Ohio State), they're looking at a lot
of three wides with one back, which could mean a lot of running
room for Adrian.'' &QL; 
And furthermore . . .  &QL; 
The selection of Boston marked the first time during the Vince
Tobin- &UR; Bob Ferguson era that the team has drafted a player it had
brought to Tempe for a pre-draft interview.
</P>
<P>
   In using both first-round picks on offensive players after
drafting defensive players first for three straight years, Ferguson
said, ``We need an explosive offense to run this engine.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, Ferguson said the Cardinals now can ``line up as well
as Minnesota,'' which set an NFL scoring record last season.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's father,  &UR; Byron, is an NFL official, prompting Ferguson
to crack, ``That's a consideration in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   By league rules, Byron Boston can officiate one preseason game
this season in which his son plays, but no regular-season games. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
