<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3090 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLICE-KILLING-AZR &LR;      04-18 1556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-KILLING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLAIN OFFICER CHOSE TO GO FIRST INTO APARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM WALSH  
 JUDI VILLA AND LAURA TRUJILLO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was typical that when Chandler police needed a point man in a
stand-off with a gunman, James Snedigar volunteered to be the first
one inside Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The four-year veteran officer had volunteered for the SWAT team
and as a former Army paratrooper, was always ready to help. So it
surprised no one when the 38-year-old third-generation cop stepped
through the broken arcadia door of a Chandler apartment complex
after throwing stun grenades into the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   But Snedigar apparently never had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   He stepped into an ambush, police say.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Sergio Hernandez Martinez, 26 _ suspected of
robbing a jewelry store _ stood armed with an assault rifle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was ready. I think he was planning. It was very
premeditated,'' said Tempe police Sgt. Dave Lind, whose department
is taking over the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   And the two men saw their worlds collide.
</P>
<P>
   Snedigar wore his protective vest. Martinez wore body armor
under his clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Snedigar, police say, didn't get a chance to fire.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, police and Martinez fired at least 15 times.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez died there in the apartment, a gunshot wound to the
head. And Snedigar, also shot in the head, died at Chandler
Regional Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``In combat, there's always a point man who makes the first
contact with the enemy,'' Chandler Police Chief Bobby Joe Haris
said. ``As the result of that, many times, he is the first to die.
He gives his life so others can survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, police booked Martinez's friends, Leroy Campbell, 24,
and Arthur Lucero, 24, both of Phoenix, on two counts of
first-degree murder, armed robbery and burglary, according to their
booking slips. Both have previous records. They were transfered to
the Madison Street Jail Saturday afternoon and held on $4.5 million
bond.
</P>
<P>
   Police released no information about Martinez, of Phoenix, who
was indicted in 1992 for fleeing from police, according to Superior
Court records.
</P>
<P>
   Snedigar was the first Chandler officer to die in the line of
duty.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the statistics tell a story that worries Valley
police officers. He was the second Valley police officer slain the
past three weeks and the fifth officer shot in the past month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the hazards of our job that things of this sort are going
to occur,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's shooting started with a typical smash and grab robbery.
The following is the police account.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before noon, two men walked into Crescent Jewelers in a
strip mall near Priest and Elliot, smashing a display case with a
hammer. They grabbed handfuls of gold chains and necklaces and ran
outside, disappearing in a stolen Ford Mustang.
</P>
<P>
   Police say a third man drove the car as police followed it on a
two-mile chase, winding through residential and busy streets.
Officers lost sight of the car, then discovered it inside the
Sierra Palms Apartments _ doors open, engine running, the suspected
robbers _ Martinez, Lucero and Campbell _ nowhere near it.
</P>
<P>
   Police simply followed a trail of gold chains and jewelry from
the car to apartment 1086. The arcadia door was broken. So was the
door of 1055. Martinez hid inside 1055.
</P>
<P>
   Lucero and Campbell busted into No. 1086 through a sliding glass
door.
</P>
<P>
   SWAT officers fanned out throughout the two-story complex,
spotting the broken door at 1055. Police tossed stun grenades into
the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   And Snedigar volunteered to lead the four men team into the
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The officers weren't carrying protective ballistic shields and
didn't have helmet shields, police said, adding that SWAT team
members don't use them in every entry.
</P>
<P>
   During the shooting, Lucero and Campbell apparently tried to
change their appearances, dressing in clothes found in the
apartment they broke into, police said.
</P>
<P>
   About an hour later, as police and apartment managers forced
residents to stay inside their apartments, fearful of their safety,
Lucero and Campbell simply tried to walk away, police said.
</P>
<P>
   They almost made it, but a police officer patrolling the
perimeter of the gated complex noticed the two men, thinking they
resembled the suspected robbers. Neither carried stolen jewelry or
guns.
</P>
<P>
   At first, police held the two men on unrelated traffic warrants.
</P>
<P>
   As police led Lucero from the Chandler jail Saturday afternoon,
he proclaimed: ``I'm innocent.'' Campbell didn't say anyth &UR; ing and
tried to hide his face from reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Saturday, residents brought flowers to a makeshift
memorial for Snedigar that sprouted up in front of the Chandler
Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Even before it was revealed that Snedigar led the charge into
the apartment, his uncle predicted it. ``He probably offered. It
wouldn't surprize me,'' said Robert Snedigar, 72, of Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   James Snedigar dreamed of becoming a cop since he was a child,
friends say. He watched his father, also James Snedigar, serve for
the Department of Public Safety. And his grandfather, Stanley
Snedigar, worked the beat as a deputy sheriff in San Bernadino,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, he was all business, ``Yes sir and Ma'am,''
remembers his uncle.
</P>
<P>
   '`He worked hard, when you gave him a job, it didn't matter how
rough, how tough, he did it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Snedigar worked on his uncle's farm as a child, building
corrals, driving a tractor, anything.
</P>
<P>
   Classmates remember the Marcos de Niza high school graduate as
the hard-working football player, always ready to help a friend.
He'd drive to the desert if a friend's car broke down.
</P>
<P>
   That work ethic carried him through graduation in 1978 and later
as he worked on his father's calf ranch in Chandler. Later, friends
say, he battled to get into the Army because of a hearing problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``He overcame that,'' said Joe Waters, 39, a friend of
Snedigar's since high school. ``If you look at Jim, he was what
America is meant to be. He looked to serve people.''
</P>
<P>
   When he got out of the Army, he applied for a job on the police
force at age 35. Snedigar obtained a waiver for his hearing
problems and wore hearing aids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admired him because he was willing to deal with his
problem,'' Harris said. ``You have favorite people in the
department, people you think more highly of than others, and Jim
was one of those.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends say he also was fiercely dedicated to his family, his
wife, Dawn, 7-year-old son and daughters, ages 18 and 6, and a
year-old grandson.
</P>
<P>
   He looked after his mother, Lorna, after his father died a year
ago from a heart attack, Robert Snedigar said. ``Whatever she
needed, he was there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Robert Snedigar said, the family is trying to cope with the
loss. ``They're taking it hard,'' he said, ``it's a real shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Snedigar's son, Rupert, biked outside the family house as people
stopped by throughout the morning. Neighbors signed a sympathy card
and collected about $200 to buy dinners.
</P>
<P>
   Like many neighbors, Elaine Rackley described Snedigar as always
polite but a man of few words. She and her husband used to see
Snedigar working out in his garage early in the morning or
tinkering with the boat in his driveway. They would wave, and he
would wave back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed like a really nice guy,'' Rackley said. ``They
seemed like such a nice family. It's very sad.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The father of suspect Lucero said Saturday that his son tried
to keep out of trouble after getting out of jail two years ago. He
had been in jail six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed,'' Gene Lucero said Saturday from his
South Phoenix home where he raised Arthur and four other children.
</P>
<P>
   Lucero said his son and Campbell left their home around 10:30
a.m. Friday, not saying where they were headed. Lucero next saw his
son on television, being led away in handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   Lucero worked at a warehouse, his father said. At night he was
home, to keep in terms of his probation from an assault conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's family said he had been in some trouble and been in
the juvenile detention center and jail, said his grandfather, Billy
Ortiz, 66.
</P>
<P>
   A family friend, Hubert Jones said Campbell works on and off in
construction. Campbell also has a court record.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Cruz Ortiz, could barely speak Saturday. ``I feel
awful, especially for the police,'' she said. ``My heart goes out
to the family.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Harris said, Snedigar paid the ``ultimate
sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   But he defended the police's decision to enter the apartment and
arrest the gunman, though authorities wouldn't discuss the tactics
used.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would have happened if we hadn't caught them? They may
have killed civilians on the streets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At a briefing session Saturday afternoon, Sgt. Jim Halstad
encouraged officers to talk to friends about the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't you rip your heart out of your chest,'' Halstad told
a reporter. ``That's how it feels.''
</P>
<P>
   The other officers involved in the shooting will be placed on
administrative leave, a standard-procedure after a shooting. The
240 other officers will return to their beats.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Republic reporters Richard Ruelas and Janelle Cowgill
contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
