<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-SHARKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS TIE SHARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ It should have been a sleepy game between two teams
locked in their playoff positions and meeting as a mere formality
to complete their schedules, with a couple of Anaheim Mighty Ducks
trying to reach personal milestones.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kariya succeeded, reaching the 100-point mark for the
second time in his career. Teemu Selanne came up short, finishing
stuck on 47 goals, still enough to win the initial Maurice
``Rocket'' Richard Award as the NHL's goal-scoring champion.
</P>
<P>
   But the 3-3 tie Saturday between the Mighty Ducks (35-34-13) and
the San Jose Sharks (31-33-18) before a San Jose Arena sellout
crowd of 17,483 proved to be anything but mellow.
</P>
<P>
   An ugly incident in the final seconds of the second period took
care of that.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the play, Sharks defenseman Andrei Zyuzin slashed Ducks
enforcer Jim McKenzie who was headed in the other direction.
McKenzie turned, and both players slashed at each other _ each
connecting. Unfortunately for McKenzie, whereas his slash caught
Zyuzin on the leg, Zyuzin's caught him on the neck.
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie dropped to the ice in pain, and referee Dan Marouelli
assessed him a two-minute minor and Zyuzin a five-minute major and
a game misconduct. McKenzie did not return for the third period.
</P>
<P>
   The third period was marked by plenty of nasty stickwork by both
teams. The Sharks also managed to tie the score with an early goal
by Owen Nolan
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the Ducks _ preparing for a first-round playoff series
against the Detroit Red Wings, expected to begin Wednesday _ had
bolted to a 3-0 lead on first-period goals by McKenzie and Kariya,
and a second-period score by Tomas Sandstrom. The Sharks, who will
meet the Colorado Avalanche in the first round, rallied on goals by
Alexander Korolyuk and Joe Murphy, closing the deficit to one
entering the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry Suter: More than a year later, injured San Jose defenseman
Gary Suter said he still regrets the hit that injured Kariya last
season, and said he never intended to cause the Ducks' star such
harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question it was a bad hit,'' Suter said Saturday morning.
``I feel bad I put him out for the rest of the year. People who say
I did it intentionally are totally wrong. Take a look at my career.
I'm not some derelict who goes around cross-checking people in the
face.''
</P>
<P>
   Suter has missed all but one game this season with an elbow
injury. He said there is no chance he will return to the lineup for
the playoffs, but he expects to be ready for next season.
</P>
<P>
   It was last Feb. 1 that Suter (then a Chicago Blackhawk)
cross-checked Kariya, who was sidelined the rest of the year with
post-concussion syndrome. The play by Suter (an American) knocked
Kariya (a Canadian) out of the Winter Olympics. Suter said he
received threats from angry Canadian fans after the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say that during the Olympics, I wasn't walking around
with my name on my back,'' Suter said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he is relieved Kariya has returned from the injury
to have a strong season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept hoping for him to come back last year and he never
did,'' Suter said. ``I'm glad he's back on top of his game and
maybe better than ever. The game needs players like him, especially
with (Wayne) Gretzky retiring.''
</P>
<P>
   Rucchin back: Until Thursday, when he played against the Kings,
it had been expected that a groin injury would sideline center
Steve Rucchin until the playoffs. Rucchin had missed seven
consecutive games before Thursday, but he played in a 4-3 overtime
loss to the Kings and he played again against the Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to get a little game time in before the
playoffs,'' Rucchin said. ``Some is better than none to get back
into the flow of things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
