<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW LONG WILL GRIFFEY REMAIN WITH MARINERS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Ken Griffey Jr. was answering questions in the
visitors' clubhouse at Edison Field on Saturday afternoon when a
small, glistening object whistled past the reporter's notebook and
struck the Seattle Mariners' center fielder in the chest.
</P>
<P>
   Being a nine-time Gold Glove winner, he caught it.
</P>
<P>
   It was an emerald and gold Oakland A's World Series ring from
1989. Griffey looked up and, across the room, saw the gap-toothed
grin of the memento's owner, outfielder-turned-broadcaster Dave
Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just trying to dog you, man,'' Hendu said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants you to see one of those,'' one of Griffey's teammates
chimed in.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey laughed and tossed the ring back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just got All-Star rings. And a wedding ring,'' Griffey
said. ``I bought a state high school football ring.''
</P>
<P>
   But a World Series ring? Dave Henderson has one. Ken Griffey Sr.
has one. Hundreds of perfectly ordinary ballplayers have one. Ken
Griffey Jr. does not have one.
</P>
<P>
   He has done almost everything in baseball except play in a World
Series. When should that injustice begin to bother him as much as
it bothers us, his fans?
</P>
<P>
   When he turns 30, as he will this fall?
</P>
<P>
   When he marks 10 years in the major leagues, as he did last
season?
</P>
<P>
   When he cracks the top 50 on the all-time home-runs list, as he
did last week when he hit his 352nd?
</P>
<P>
   The milestones pile up. Not a precious gem among 'em.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to play baseball,'' said Griffey, who hit his third
home run of the season in the Mariners' 4-3 victory over the Angels
Saturday night. ``I just haven't been one of the fortunate ones to
get to the World Series yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to make it. But I'm not complaining. I love going out
there on the grass _ and (artificial) turf _ and competing.''
</P>
<P>
   He isn't often asked about it either, about the passing years
and the frustration of missing the playoffs in eight of his 10
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't realize how old I am,'' said the man who
goes by Junior. ``They say, `You've got, what, six years in?' ''
</P>
<P>
   People are going to start asking about it soon enough. Griffey
can become a free agent when his four-year, $34 million contract
runs out after the 2000 season. Just in case money is no object,
teams' championship potential certainly will be. Assume that
Griffey won't stay in Seattle unless he sees more from Mariners
management.
</P>
<P>
   The club ended '98 third in the American League West and needing
to improve the top of the starting rotation, the bullpen, the
defense and the leadoff hitter. It's not certain general manager
Woody Woodward improved any of those, working within the same $52
million payroll as last year.
</P>
<P>
   The opening-day starter, Jeff Fassero, was a big step down from
'98's Randy Johnson, traded away in July.
</P>
<P>
   The majors' worst bullpen added 32-year-old Jose Mesa, coming
off a one-save season, after letting Mike Timlin become a free
agent. The Mariners' relievers began Saturday's game with a 7.07
ERA.
</P>
<P>
   The defense's big reason for optimism was third baseman Russ (35
errors) Davis' offseason footwork lessons.
</P>
<P>
   And the big plans at the top of the batting order went pfffft
when rookie second baseman Carlos Guillen _ acquired in the Johnson
trade _ suffered a season-ending knee injury last week. David
(.200) Bell led off Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Before his injury, Guillen had been switched to shortstop to
fill in for 40-home run, .310 hitter Alex Rodriguez, who'll miss
the first four to six weeks with his own knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't look like the Mariners' year, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all a team. We win or lose together,'' said Griffey,
who's hitting in the .370s but is behind his league-leading
56-homer pace of the past two seasons. That is to say: This is not
Griffey vs. His Teammates.
</P>
<P>
   As for Griffey vs. the Front Office: He points out that those
negotiations are more than year away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't even thought about (the future),'' Griffey said,
referring to himself and his wife Melissa, who have a 5-year-old
son and a 3-year-old daughter. ``We have to take care of '99 first.
The important thing is, are you happy and comfortable in the
situation you're in? Is your family happy and comfortable?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I feel the team is competitive ... (the Mariners have a
chance to re-sign him).''
</P>
<P>
   He said he won't judge them by their payroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no guarantee. You can have an $80 million payroll and
still lose,'' Griffey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have young guys on this team who need to go out and pitch.
We had a young second baseman who had an untimely injury. Some of
these guys might be making $200,000, but there can be guys making
$2 million who give us as much as they will.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody wears optimism as well as Griffey, bearer of the most
convincing smile in baseball, the perpetual Kid in the backward
cap.
</P>
<P>
   But how long can that last? The Kid turns 30 on Nov. 21 _ a
month after he watches another World Series on TV.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
