<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT PADRES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Devon White's road trip began with Tony Womack
robbing him of a homer in Arizona. Going hitless in seven at-bats
during a 16-inning loss one night later didn't help matters.
</P>
<P>
   It's why Los Angeles Dodgers manager Davey Johnson decided to
give White the night off Saturday. It's a good thing, because it
made him available for pinch-hitting duty in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his career White came off the bench and
homered. His three-run shot broke a tie game and lifted the Dodgers
to a 7-3 victory over the Padres in front of 56,568 at Qualcomm
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield homered twice and had three
RBI. He hit a two-run homer off starter Sterling Hitchcock in the
second inning and added a solo homer in the seventh. But it was
White who delivered at the most opportune time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Devo's a veteran, a big RBI guy so when guys are on base, you
know he's going to come through,'' said Sheffield, who leads the
Dodgers with five homers. ``I know that in '97 (with Florida) he
did that and he's continued that here.''
</P>
<P>
   White hit .440 during the Dodgers' season-opening homestand. But
before connecting for the three-run homer off Padres reliever
Carlos Reyes, he was 1 for 19 on the trip that began Monday. His
only other base hit was an RBI double off Arizona's Randy Johnson
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The little chances I've had to pinch-hit, I'm looking to get a
pitch to drive,'' White said. ``You can't think about two or three
games. You really can't harp on things, going 0 for 12 or 0 for 20,
because it's early in the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers right-hander Chan Ho Park (1-1) recorded his first win
of the season. He allowed three runs on eight hits in five innings,
walking two and striking out six. Park got help from three
relievers.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes (0-1) pitched one inning but took the loss.
</P>
<P>
   In White's place, Brumfield got the start and was in the middle
of both the Padres' game-tying rally and the Dodgers' winning
rally.
</P>
<P>
   He mis-timed his jump on Tony Gwynn's double to the
right-center-field wall that was part of the Padres' three-run
fifth inning, which tied the score 3-3. In the top of the sixth,
Brumfield got some retribution when his one-out single moved Adrian
Beltre to third. Brumfield went to second on the throw.
</P>
<P>
   It brought catcher Paul LoDuca to the plate, with Park due up
next. But when LoDuca, hitless in 11 at-bats this season, fell
behind in the count, White appeared in the on-deck circle.
</P>
<P>
   LoDuca struck out, but White didn't miss Reyes' 2-1 fastball
over the plate. He hit it 406 feet to give the Dodgers a 6-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being honest with you, I thought it was a 50-50 chance maybe
they'd pitch to him,'' Johnson said. ``I figure if I went with my
best pinch-hitter (Dave Hansen) they probably would have put him
on, so I went with White.''
</P>
<P>
   With Park no longer available, Johnson went to his revamped
bullpen to chew away some innings. Antonio Osuna, activated from
the disabled list Friday, made his first appearance of the season,
though not without incident. Before he threw his first pitch he was
met at the mound by trainer Charlie Strasser and Johnson. Osuna had
developed a blister on the middle finger of his pitching hand and
had to have it cut off.
</P>
<P>
   If affected Osuna so much he retired the Padres in order. Pedro
Borbon and Jeff Shaw also pitched scoreless relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to throw only five innings, but I wanted to
throw nine innings because that's what I always want to do,'' Park
said. ``I feel really bad. I have to follow what the manager is
thinking and doing, and today he did good.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Park's pitching problems had more to do with his
attitude than his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chan Ho was really breezing along and then I think he got
defensive,'' Johnson said. ``He quit going after them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
