<HEADLINE>
GILL'S OT GOAL MOVES BRUINS UP A NOTCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins have maintained all along that they didn't
care whom they played in the first round of the playoffs. The
battle cry has been, ``Bring 'em on, whoever they are!''
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday, coach Pat Burns amended that after his team's
impressive 2-1 overtime victory over the Buffalo Sabres, an
opponent they hadn't been able to take a point from in four tries.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have won three in a row and seven of their last eight
as they head into their regular-season finale Sunday against the
Flyers in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's victory means Boston can finish no worse than sixth
in the Eastern Conference and, depending on what happens in
Sunday's games, will face either third seed Carolina or fourth seed
Toronto. The Bruins are tied for fifth with the Flyers but have the
edge in the first tiebreaker (39 wins to 36), so a win or tie
Sunday would guarantee Boston fifth place.
</P>
<P>
   Burns said he is thrilled to avoid New Jersey and Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we were trying to do, stay away from eighth,''
said the coach. ``Jersey is a team that is going to have to be
reckoned with in the playoffs. Ottawa is still a good team.
Carolina is an excellent team, too. Toronto is a highly skilled,
offensive team, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The preference is, if you could bypass the first round, that'd
be probably the best. But that's impossible. The first round is the
toughest round to get through.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's matinee at the FleetCenter, which was Fan
Appreciation Day, had all the drama and excitement of a playoff
game. It was the hockey equivalent of a pitchers' duel, with
Dominik Hasek and Byron Dafoe going head to head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, there was a little extra incentive for me just
because it was Dominik,'' said Dafoe, who made 22 saves on the way
to his 32d win of the season. ``I'm sure he didn't feel any
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a moral victory in itself for the whole team. Everyone
had extra motivation because we hadn't beaten them all year.''
</P>
<P>
   It was especially sweet for defenseman Hal Gill. Buffalo's tying
goal in the second period, credited to Miroslav Satan, had gone in
off the stick of Gill. He felt as if he redeemed himself when he
scored the winner from the point with 13.1 seconds left in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Gill said he expected Ray Bourque to take the shot. Bourque's
initial shot was blocked, and when he got the puck back, he dished
it to Gill. When told that Gill said he didn't expect it, Bourque
laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was yelling his head off,'' said Bourque. ``I heard him. I
was just hoping the puck wouldn't bounce over his stick or
something like that. He really took charge on that. He was yelling,
he knew he was wide open and I heard him, looked up, gave him the
puck and he made a great shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill said he thought Bourque giving him the puck completely
fooled the Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave me all the time in the world to let it rip,'' said
Gill.
</P>
<P>
   Gill was relieved because he would've felt badly to have the
Satan goal cost the Bruins a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's awesome,'' he said of what he felt was poetic justice.
``To have something like that happen, obviously I don't want to be
the goat. To get that back was really nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Right wing Landon Wilson had given Boston the lead briefly at
13:11 of the second period. Left wing Sergei Samsonov dished a pass
to Wilson, but Wilson lost the puck to Buffalo right wing Dixon
Ward. Samsonov stole it back and fed Wilson in front. Wilson beat
Hasek with a backhand shot.
</P>
<P>
   Only 1:42 later, Satan tied it. After center Michael Peca dumped
the puck into the Boston zone in the right corner, the puck came
out. Gill tried to get control of it, but Satan poked at it, Dafoe
was caught off guard and it sailed through the goalie's legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him not to worry about it,'' joked Dafoe. ``It was both
of our faults. It was a fluky goal. I kind of assumed Hal had it,
but I should've been following it more. I learned a little lesson
going into the playoffs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
