<HEADER>
A3103 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     04-18 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIER AND COMPANY GOT THEIR MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Good business and good football business
blended Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   When the Patriots were unable to trade up high enough in the
draft to grab either Ricky Williams or Edgerrin James, they did not
sit at Nos. 20 and 28 in the first round and hope to get what they
wanted. Instead they made a move so they could make some moves.
</P>
<P>
   Director of personnel Bobby Grier knew all along what he wanted
to do if one of the two top running backs were not available, and
when it appeared he might be stymied with his secondary plan, he
reacted quickly, swapping his 20th pick plus a third and sixth to
Seattle to move up to 17 and grab Boston College center Damien
Woody.
</P>
<P>
   Grier feared the one team that might foil his plan to draft
Woody was the Giants, who picked 19th and have 33-year-old Brian
Williams starting at center. Williams is coming off two years of
injuries and is the kind of question the Giants might well have
chosen to answer with Woody, who was not only the highest-rated
center in the draft but the first in years to be projected as a
possible immediate starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Woody is a unique athlete who comes along once in a while,''
Patriots coach Pete Carroll said. ``We had enough information that
something could happen with the Giants. We knew what we wanted and
went and got it. We're counting on Damien Woody at center.''
</P>
<P>
   That trade did far more than provide a likely starter. It also
allowed New England to unload two picks it didn't really need but
would have cost it money. More important, it could create a series
of offensive line shifts that could not only strengthen New England
on the field but shore up a dire salary cap situation.
</P>
<P>
   If Woody can step in and play immediately, as Carroll expects,
it would allow New England to shift Heath Irwin back to right
guard, his more natural spot, and move guard Max Lane to right
tackle. Irwin then would battle Todd Rucci and Damon Denson at
guard, while Lane would replace aging and overpaid Zefross Moss at
tackle.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well, New England opens the season with Woody at
center, Irwin and the winner of Denson-Rucci at the guards, and
Bruce Armstrong and Lane at the tackles, releasing Moss to save
$200,000 on this year's cap and $1.2 million next year, when they
will need all the cap room they can muster to try and keep their
secondary in tact.
</P>
<P>
   Relieved of Moss's 2000 salary of $1.2 million and having taken
a $900,000 salary cap hit on the remaining portion of his bonus
this year, the Patriots would be roughly $1.65 million to the good
overall, a sum they could use in the next offseason when, as things
stand, their entire secondary is scheduled to become free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Woody will also be a salary cap bargain compared with the man he
replaces, Dave Wohlabaugh. Wohlabaugh signed a seven-year, $26.25
million contract with the Browns in the offseason that guarantees
his salary cap number will likely be three to four times higher
than Woody's by the end of the BC center's first contract and
likely at least $1 million higher even this season because
Cleveland front-loaded many of its free agent deals to make them
all but unmatchable by other teams.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Terry Fair of the Lions was the 20th pick in the
first round and received a five-year contract with a $2.875 million
signing bonus and base salaries of $266,000, $420,000, $511,000,
$596,000, and $682,000, giving him a salary cap figure of
$1,001,300 last year. Figuring an 8-10 percent inflation rate,
Woody is likely to end up with a cap number around $1.1 million in
1999. In the short term, that is unimportant because the rookie
pool money must all be spent by every team, but as the years move
on, Wohlabaugh's cap figure will skyrocket while Woody's, like most
rookies', will stay at around the same mark. That would make Woody
a huge bargain if he turns into a serviceable NFL center or better
as Carroll and Grier expect.
</P>
<P>
   As for the selection of Ohio State linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer
with the 28th pick, he will come in and do exactly what Woody will
and what both Grier and Carroll knew their selections this year had
to do _ play immediately. He will step into Steve Sidwell's
defensive scheme as the weakside linebacker, the spot previously
manned by departed free agent Todd Collins, and thus take the
burden off undersized Tedy Bruschi.
</P>
<P>
   Bruschi had been penciled into that position, but there were
serious concerns within the organization whether he could hold up
full-time. With Katzenmoyer's arrival, that is another problem
solved if he is anywhere near the player most scouts feel he can
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Katzenmoyer loves to play football,'' Carroll said. ``He has
all kind of measureables and may have been the fastest linebacker
in the draft. We can put him next to Ted Johnson to give us a
couple of linebackers at the inside position who can run and hit.
We can put him at the weakside spot and that would allow us to use
Tedy in the way we have in the past, in nickel and third-down
defenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Grier and his scouts are right, his first-round moves
Saturday provided the Patriots with two things they desperately
needed out of this draft _ immediate starters on the field and
salary cap relief off it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
