<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS BEAT ANGELS IN 10TH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Ken Griffey Jr. didn't beat the Anaheim
Angels. He helped of course, but the 430-foot home run off Angels
reliever Troy Percival in the 10th belonged to David Segui, who
gave Seattle a 4-3 victory over the Angels on Saturday in front of
43,752 _ the largest crowd ever to watch a game at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Percival (0-1), who had pitched only one inning this season (a
save April 6 against Cleveland), said he served up a fastball to
Segui _ and it ended up just the Mariners first baseman likes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My breaking ball wasn't really working (tonight) so I got
reduced down to my fastball,'' said Percival. ``I threw one
low-middle and to him (Segui) that's a good spot. I was trying to
go low and away and I didn't get it there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had a chance to make something happen in the bottom
of the 10th. With one out, David Erstad singled and Tim Salmon
walked to put runners on first and second with clutch hitters
Garret Anderson and Troy Glaus to follow. But Seattle closer Jose
Mesa struck out both to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels (6-6) moved into a three-way tie for first in the AL
West with Oakland and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Paniaguea (1-1) picked up the victory for Seattle (5-7)
after pitching the ninth. He followed a good start from the
Mariners Freddy Garcia, who pitched eight innings and allowed three
runs.
</P>
<P>
   The loss spoiled a fine outing from Angels starter Ken Hill, who
has had his share of problems prior to Saturday's contest. Hill
said he hasn't struggled because of the his surgically-repaired
right elbow. In fact, the elbow's fine.
</P>
<P>
   After walking seven his last time out and watching his
earned-run average jump to 7.56, he acknowledged that an adjustment
to his delivery (to relieve the stress from his elbow) had caused
him comfort problems.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Terry Collins said before the game that Hill had
been progressing steadily since his last start and it would only
take a short time for him to adjust to his new delivery.
</P>
<P>
   After a shaky start and the pitch to Griffey he'd like to have
back, Hill had an effective night. He allowed only three runs on
five hits in seven innings of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really settled down and that's the Kenny Hill we know,''
said Collins. ``I was real, real happy. That's back-to-back games
by two guys (Tim Belcher on Friday) that we're counting on big
things from. That's two good performances so we're gonna be just
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle spotted Hill an early 1-0 lead in the second inning.
With one out, Anderson struck out but reached first on a passed
ball. Glaus continued his hot hitting, sending a liner to
left-center to advance Anderson to second. Todd Greene struck out,
but Matt Walbeck's single scored Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   That lead lasted all of 10 minutes. With two outs in the third
and David Bell at first for the Mariners, Griffey strolled up, then
smacked a 390-foot homer (his third of the season) into the
right-field bleachers to give Seattle a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hill struggled a bit in the fourth, giving up a hard single to
Butch Huskey, who advanced to second on a wild pitch. After Russ
Davis struck out, Dan Wilson sent a curling drive to right, eluding
Tim Salmon for a triple that scored Huskey for a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Greene, who had homered in his two previous games for the
Angels, extended his hitting streak to eight games in the fourth
inning with a two-out, two-run homer to left to tie the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
