<HEADLINE>
GORDON HURTS ELBOW AS RED SOX ROMP 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-DEVIL RAYS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There should have been smiles all around. Nomar
Garciaparra was back, singling in the day's first run and scoring
the second, and so was the Red Sox' offense, which had 11 hits and
took advantage of 10 Tampa Bay walks, two wild pitches and a hit
batsman in an 8-5 win over the Devil Rays Saturday at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the expression that stuck with the Red Sox Saturday was
the pain on closer Tom Gordon's face after he hurt his right elbow,
a look that caused catcher Jason Varitek to sprint to the mound in
the ninth inning, followed almost immediately by manager Jimy
Williams, pitching coach Joe Kerrigan, and trainer Jim Rowe.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just grimaced,'' Varitek said. ``It was a bad look on the
mound. I saw it happen once before in Double A, to a kid named
Geronimo Newton. He threw another pitch, and there went the elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't wish anybody that face, especially when it's good
people like Flash.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who had struck out one batter, Bobby Smith, and was
ahead, no balls and two strikes, on Dave Martinez when the pinch
hitter fouled back a fastball, was not allowed to throw another
pitch by Williams. Jim Corsi finished, albeit clumsily, finally
retiring pinch hitter Wade Boggs on a force play with two runners
on to end it.
</P>
<P>
   The condition of Gordon's right elbow, which troubled him in
spring training and has flared up again in the last 10 days,
according to Kerrigan, remains uncertain. At the moment, it is
still being called a strain. Gordon, who underwent X-rays in spring
training, is hurting in the same inner part of the elbow that
bothered him in camp, Kerrigan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same thing, in the same place and the same feeling as
spring training,'' Kerrigan said.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was examined immediately after the game by Dr. Bill
Morgan, who was on call Saturday in the absence of team physician
Arthur Pappas, and though Gordon remained in seclusion after the
game, he almost certainly will undergo tests in the next 48 hours
to determine the severity of the injury.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who hadn't pitched in a week and was bidding for his
major league record 47th consecutive save, is not likely to be
pitching soon and would appear to be a strong candidate for the
disabled list. Derek Lowe probably would serve as the interim
closer, though Williams will be forced to improvise Sunday with a
shorthanded bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe has pitched the last two days, including two innings
Saturday in relief of starter Mark Portugal, a winner in his Fenway
Park debut despite giving up a 469-foot home run to Jose Canseco,
the second in two games by the Tampa Bay DH, whose first-inning
single off the Monster would have been a home run anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Corsi has pitched in two of the last three games and labored
both times, while lefthander Mark Guthrie has worked each of the
last two games. A complete game out of No. 5 starter Pat Rapp would
be ideal, but he lasted just 3 2/3 innings last Sunday against the
Devil Rays and has gone the distance just twice in 93 starts in the
last three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to wait and see what's going on with the injury,
then proceed,'' Williams said. ``Let's come back out here tomorrow
and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan said Gordon first grabbed at his elbow on his third
strike to Smith, a 94-mile-an-hour fastball, then hurt himself
again on what Kerrigan said was a 93-mile-an-hour fastball to
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox have had a run of elbow injuries this spring.
Catcher Scott Hatteberg went on the disabled list Thursday night
with an inflamed elbow _ he said Saturday he was awaiting results
of an MRI _ and Garciaparra had been shelved this spring by a
strained flexor muscle and tendinitis in his elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Garciaparra returned to the starting lineup after
being limited to just one pinch-hit appearance in seven games. Sox
killer Danny Clyburn made a diving catch in right field of
Garciaparra's bid for extra bases in the first inning and converted
it into a rally-killing double play.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, Mike Stanley saw reason to be encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times as a team we work on emotion,'' Stanley said.
``He gets announced to a standing ovation, the crowd's into it,
they see he's back. He hits a rocket, and they get a double play,
but the crowd's still in it. The place was upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I feed off it. I enjoyed watching it, seeing how people
reacted to his being back.''
</P>
<P>
   In comes Garciaparra. Out goes Gordon. One vigil ends, another
begins. And it's only April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
