<HEADLINE>
DUCKS TIE SHARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ It should have been a sleepy game between two
teams locked in their playoff positions and meeting as a mere
formality to complete their schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the night ended with the most unlikely combatants, the
Anaheim Mighty Ducks' Teemu Selanne and Paul Kariya, squaring off
against San Jose's Owen Nolan and Alexander Korolyuk in overtime of
a season-ending 3-3 tie Saturday before a sellout crowd of 17,483
at the San Jose Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a little Muhammad Ali tape going before the game,''
joked Kariya, who received a roughing penalty and has never been in
a fight in his NHL career.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put him out there to score,'' Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg
said of Kariya, ``but he wanted to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a spirited tune-up for the playoffs, which the Ducks
(35-34-13) expect to open Wednesday in Detroit against the two-time
defending Stanley Cup champion Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   It became ugly, too, when San Jose's Andrei Zyuzin slashed Jim
McKenzie late in the second period. Zyuzin, who recently rejoined
the Sharks (31-33-18) after a puzzling exile, received a major
penalty and game misconduct. McKenzie left the game with a swollen
jaw.
</P>
<P>
   Before his bout with Korolyuk, Kariya succeeded in reaching the
100-point mark for the second time in his career. Selanne, however,
came up short in his bid for 50 goals, but 47 will be enough for
him to win the initial Maurice ``Rocket'' Richard Award as the
NHL's goal-scoring champion.
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie, Kariya and Tomas Sandstrom gave the Ducks a 3-0 lead
early in the second period, but Korolyuk, Joe Murphy and Owen Nolan
evened the score for the Sharks, who face a first-round series
against the Colorado Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   Of the ugly nature of what might have been a quiet game,
Hartsburg said, ``There's some spark there, that's for sure. It was
like a playoff game. But it's over, and the season is over. Now,
the real fun starts.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry Suter: More than a year later, injured San Jose defenseman
Gary Suter said he still regrets the hit that injured Kariya last
season, and said he never intended to cause the Ducks' star such
harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question it was a bad hit,'' Suter said Saturday morning.
``I feel bad I put him out for the rest of the year. People who say
I did it intentionally are totally wrong. Take a look at my career.
I'm not some derelict who goes around cross-checking people in the
face.''
</P>
<P>
   Suter has missed all but one game this season with an elbow
injury. He said there is no chance he will return to the lineup for
the playoffs, but he expects to be ready for next season.
</P>
<P>
   It was last Feb. 1 that Suter (then a Chicago Blackhawk)
cross-checked Kariya, who was sidelined the rest of the year with
post-concussion syndrome. The play by Suter (an American) knocked
Kariya (a Canadian) out of the Winter Olympics. Suter said he
received threats from angry Canadian fans after the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say that during the Olympics, I wasn't walking around
with my name on my back,'' Suter said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he is relieved Kariya has returned from the injury
to have a strong season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept hoping for him to come back last year and he never
did,'' Suter said. ``I'm glad he's back on top of his game and
maybe better than ever. The game needs players like him, especially
with (Wayne) Gretzky retiring.''
</P>
<P>
   Rucchin back: Until Thursday, when he played against the Kings,
it had been expected that a groin injury would sideline center
Steve Rucchin until the playoffs. Rucchin had missed seven
consecutive games before Thursday, but he played in a 4-3 overtime
loss to the Kings and he played again against the Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to get a little game time in before the
playoffs,'' Rucchin said. ``Some is better than none to get back
into the flow of things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
