<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WIN FOR THE HOME TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANDRADE, FAXON PAIR UP TO BRING CVS CLASSIC TO R.I.  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When the PGA Tour ended its long run at Pleasant Valley
last year, few took it as personally as Brad Faxon and Billy
Andrade. As native New Englanders who are always on the road, the
event in Sutton was a chance to get back home and play in front of
family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Faxon, who won at PV in 1992, and Andrade knew the Tour's
decision was beyond their control. But they also feel a
responsibility to keep as much of a PGA Tour presence in New
England as possible. There is the annual Greater Hartford Open, but
they felt there could be more, so they moved into action. To those
who know Faxon and Andrade, it's no surprise that their efforts
have met with great success: The $1 million CVS Charity Classic
will feature a field of 20 PGA Tour players and be held Aug. 1-3 at
Rhode Island Country Club in Barrington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy,'' said Faxon. ``It's a big purse, a great
title sponsor, and a great field. We want it to mirror the Fred
Meyer Challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fred Meyer is a wildly successful charity event held
annually in Portland, Ore., and the force behind it, Peter
Jacobsen, is one of those on board for the CVS Charity Classic.
</P>
<P>
   The title sponsor made sense since CVS had been out in front for
the last three PGA Tour stops at Pleasant Valley. Tom Ryan, chief
executive officer of CVS, had a desire to stay involved in golf and
went out to the Fred Meyer Challenge with Faxon and Andrade last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   As for the site, that, too, holds a special meaning to these
Rhode Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our home course,'' said Faxon. ``We caddied there and as
kids that's where we both started playing.''
</P>
<P>
   It also happens to be one of the great courses in New England, a
Donald Ross creation that opened in 1911. It has played host to the
US Women's Amateur and will be the site of the NCAA Eastern
Regional Championship next month.
</P>
<P>
   The first day of the event, which overlaps with the final round
of the Greater Hartford Open, will be a Sunday pro-am. Then, on
Monday and Tuesday, 10 two-man teams will compete in a medal play
best-ball format. While it isn't a regular Tour event, it will,
said Andrade, offer spectators a more casual look at the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just happy to have the opportunity to keep pro golf in
New England,'' said Andrade. ``It was unfortunate to lose PV, but
this will be great for the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Faxon and Andrade were recently honored by the Golf Writers
Association for their annual efforts on behalf of charity, and this
event is separate from a private tournament they also put on in
July. They began that one in 1992, and the Brad Faxon and Billy
Andrade Children's Charities will benefit from a portion of the
proceeds at the CVS Charity Classic.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Faxon, Andrade, and Jacobsen, players committed
to the event include fellow Rhode Islanders Dana Quigley, Brett
Quigley, and P.H. Horgan. Also: Mark Calcavecchia, John Cook, Jim
Furyk, Jay Haas, Tim Herron, Lee Janzen, Tom Kite, Davis Love,
Scott McCarron, Jay Sigel, Jeff Sluman, and Curtis Strange. Ben
Crenshaw, Ernie Els, Tom Lehman, Justin Leonard, Phil Mickelson,
and Payne Stewart are among those who have been extended
invitations to round out the field.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets will be $40 per day, and children under 12 will be
admitted free when accompanied by a ticketed adult. A three-day
ticket that includes clubhouse privileges will be $100. For
information, call 401-842-0138.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gary Player has fond memories of PGA National's Champions Course
in Palm Beach Gardens, Fla., site of this week's PGA Seniors
Championship. After all, he's won this major three times. So it
sounds strange to hear him add his voice to those pushing to move
the event. For some reason, the oldest major championship in senior
golf has not drawn well, a perplexing quandary for PGA of America
officials, since six Senior PGA Tour stops in Florida annually draw
strong crowds. ``We think we need to move to different venues and
different markets to expose the tournament to a new crowd,'' said
PGA of America CEO Jim Awtrey. It has been held here for 17
straight years and 26 of the last 36. ``I think we should take golf
to the people,'' said Player . . . Doug Sanders was on the putting
green in his purple golf boots, purple pants, purple shirt, and
purple sweater to kick off the week for the PGA Seniors. The next
day on the range he had toned down a bit, just red boots and red
pants to go with a white shirt. ``Bubba,'' said Lee Trevino, ``you
look like a lollipop.'' . . . Joe Carr's anger turned into
embarrassment Thursday when he was disqualified for signing an
incorrect scorecard. ``It's the first time I've ever done that,''
said the 60-year-old who is part-owner and operator of Bedrock GC
in Rutland, Mass. After shooting 84, Carr headed to the practice
range, ``determined to shoot par'' on Friday, but he thought he
misplaced his glasses, so he went to check the scorer's trailer.
That's when he got the bad news: He had caught a scoring mistake on
his card, but had not changed the numbers on the strip he turned
in. ``Stupid. My fault,'' said Carr . . . Arnold Palmer was 1 under
through 10 holes in the Seniors, but in the next four holes he went
double-bogey, par, quadruple-bogey, bogey, a stretch that cost him
a chance at making the cut . . . Though he failed again to make the
cut at the Masters, Palmer's trip to Augusta, Ga., was a big hit.
At a local bookstore, he agreed to sign copies of his new
autobiography ``A Golfer's Life,'' for one hour. He ended up
staying a half-hour longer than that, but the line reportedly still
had 800 people when he had to leave. No word on whether
Calcavecchia was one of them. Calcavecchia, of course, expressed
his opinion that Palmer should stop playing at the Masters because
he was so noncompetitive. Hopefully Calcavecchia said this before
checking the latest balance on his bank account, which is no doubt
healthy thanks to everything Palmer has done for the game and its
players, though too many of them are too selfish to realize it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the news broke that Mark O'Meara had fired his caddie,
Jerry Higginbotham, the jokes and snide remarks flew. It was too
easy. After all, O'Meara's best friend on Tour, Tiger Woods, fired
his caddie, Mike ``Fluff'' Cowan, not too long ago. ``Must be
something in the water at Isleworth,'' Cowan reportedly said to
Higginbotham, a reference to the neighborhood in which the golfers
live. It's easy to point to Woods and O'Meara and blame them, but
talk to caddies and they tell you one thing: ``There must be a good
reason.'' Such as bad yardage, which one caddie said Cowan was
giving at last summer's British Open, which Woods had a great
chance at winning . . . Woods and Cowan still should come in
contact a lot, since Jim Furyk has hired the Maine native. Woods is
usually in contention, as is Furyk (his nickname is ``T-4''), and
both players figure to be in Brookline for September's Ryder Cup .
. . Woods's father, Earl, has been diagnosed with prostate cancer
and will start radiation treatment . . . Jack Nicklaus keeps
talking about a quicker recovery than expected, still targeting his
Memorial event June 3-6. But Dr. Benjamin Bierbaum was a bit more
cautious, leaning more toward the six-month estimate, which would
keep Nicklaus out of competition until sometime in July (the hip
replacement was in late January). ``Playing tournament golf two,
three, or four days is a different story,'' said Bierbaum, who will
get a visit from Nicklaus sometime next month . . . Christy
O'Connor, who turned 50 last August and is playing in the PGA
Seniors Championship on a special invitation, had kind words for
Nicklaus. ``He's a lovely man. He wrote some lovely letters to me
during our problem,'' said O'Connor, referring to the death of his
son last fall . . . Bernard Gallacher, the former European Ryder
Cup captain who is making his senior debut in this week's stop, was
asked about his game and cited the usual culprit: putting. ``But
you are one of the best putters,'' said a member of the British
press. ``I am a good putter,'' said Gallacher. ``Until Thursday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
