<HEADLINE>
LAKERS BEHIND RAMBIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
by HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Los Angeles Lakers management backed coach Kurt
Rambis on his decision to fire Dennis Rodman, and management is
equally supportive of the job Rambis has done, despite the team's
struggles this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done a wonderful job through very trying circumstances,''
general manager Mitch Kupchak said. ``We're not performing as we'd
like to perform at this time, but we feel with the number of games
left in the season we can turn this around.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have lost three straight, dropping Rambis' record as
coach to 18-10 since succeeding Del Harris. But Rambis has also had
to endure the whirlwind that was Rodman, a trade that debilitated
the Lakers' defense and disrupted its rhythm and seemingly a lineup
change per day.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly the ideal way to start a coaching career.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shortened season, the coaching change, a major trade,
major free-agent signing _ it just wasn't practical for us to
assume we could play our best basketball so quickly,'' Kupchak
said. ``It just doesn't happen that quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Although speculation continues to center on former Bulls coach
Phil Jackson as the Lakers' coach of the future, Kupchak said
Rambis is ``absolutely'' a strong candidate to win the permanent
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think Kurt's done a great job and we support all his moves
to the degree you can support anything,'' Kupchak said. ``We're not
sure there's anything anybody else could have done differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis offers that he's made his share of mistakes but overall
feels good about his performance in the face of endless chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been easy. It's been a daily thing,'' he said. ``All
of the changes and disruptions throughout the season, those are all
things that have been difficult to deal with. And no practices on
top of that has made it doubly difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think I've done a good job in handling all this. Did I
make mistakes? Yeah. Is everything perfect? No. But I did the best
I could. I thought I made the right decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Still mad: Shaquille O'Neal avoided reporters Friday after
Rodman was waived, and he avoided the questions Saturday once he
decided to speak at all. But there's no question he's upset with
the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't got nothing to say,'' he said of Rodman's dismissal.
Because he disagreed? ``What do you think? Write what you think.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, yes.
</P>
<P>
   Stockton to Malone: John Stockton, the NBA's career assists
leader, registered his 13,000th on a bucket by longtime running
mate Karl Malone in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Derek Harper, replaced by Derek Fisher as the
starting point guard, in part to conserve him for the playoffs, sat
out Saturday's game because of a sore right foot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
