<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-CREW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION SHOT DOWN AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution's 100th regular-season MLS
game produced highlight saves from Walter Zenga, some sideline
histrionics, but no goals Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. They tied the Columbus
Crew, 0-0, in regulation time, then lost in the post-match shootout
to remain in fourth place in the Eastern Conference with 3 points
in four games.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga made three saves within a minute to keep the Revolution in
contention in the first half, as the Crew's striking combination of
Stern John and Brian McBride took control of the penalty area. And
the Revolution rejuvenated themselves in the second half, partly
due to some creative play by Edwin Gorter, who then contentiously
confronted assistant coach Giuseppe Galderisi.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Revolution had little midfield possession, and were
off balance in the first half, they retained some compactness in
the second half and emerged with some confidence intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``One game could be better or worse than another, and this was
the worst game for our forwards,'' Zenga said. ``Sometimes you can
play bad. It isn't any one reason or another.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the Revolution would certainly have collapsed in a
contest like this. But the reorganized defensive scheme and Zenga's
inspiring play are keeping them in contention. They have fallen
behind in one game, for 16 minutes, a marked improvement over last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We held them to zero, and with a little luck we could have
won,'' midfielder Ivan McKinley said. ``When we get Giovanni
Savarese back we will have a good goal scorer. It feels better this
year, and we have more hope. In a European system, we would be near
the top of the standings.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the Revolution's sixth shutout in 10 games and their
second scoreless result in the last five games, including the
season-ender last year, under Zenga's direction. The team has great
room for tactical improvement, but at least it has defense as a
point of reference.
</P>
<P>
   Crew coach Tom Fitzgerald went to a physical lineup to combat
the Revolution's hard-charging prediliction, with Matt Kmosko
replacing Andy Williams, one of the league's most dynamic young
players, in midfield. The alignment functioned well, as Brian West
found space on the right side and nearly converted twice in the
opening three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy has been playing well, but Matt is our New Jersey street
fighter and he and Todd Yeagley allow Brian Maisonneuve to go
forward a little more,'' Fitzgerald said. ``We played a great first
half, and any kind of win is a win, especially on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution's best first-half chances were a bicycle kick off
the top of the crossbar by Tony Kuhn in the 24th minute and a
Joe-Max Moore free kick that went wide three minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   But more typical of the Revolution's first half was the
defensive play by Jair, who saved a certain goal by catching Kmosko
from behind near the goal area with the net open. Zenga then
kick-saved on McBride in the 36th minute, smothered John's
point-blank shot from the edge of the goal area, and blocked John's
left-footed volley from 15 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second half, Gorter soon made one of the best moves
of the match, showing the ball to Mike Clark, then pulling it away
as Clark slid past in the penalty area. Gorter penetrated along the
end line, then pulled the ball back for Johnny Torres, who wasted
the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, however, Gorter was replaced by Brian
Dunseth, as the Revolution went into even more of a defensive mode.
Yet, within minutes of the change of alignment, Moore nearly broke
the deadlock, running onto a pass from Kuhn.
</P>
<P>
   In the shootout, Zenga fouled Jason Farrell on the final shot,
surrendering a penalty kick which Farrell converted to clinch the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter kept us in it in the first half,'' defender Dan
Calichman said. ``We are still not scoring, but that's not just
because of the offense. Maybe we are not holding the ball enough.
We have to be smarter. But that will come with time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
