<HEADER>
A3111 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBANOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      04-18 1909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITINO PUSHING IT WITH WORKOUT PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Celtics have a new workout facility and it's a
beauty. It's got every bell and whistle, and Rick Pitino has
already ironed out a summer schedule for his players to use it.
</P>
<P>
   He's blocked out two days in May and more time in June, July,
and September for what he says are ``voluntary'' sessions. Just a
couple of hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds innocuous and, in truth, it is. The players probably
are going to work out anyway _ most of them should _ and those who
stick around will likely use the facility on their own. It's all
part of Pitino's plan to have his players in top shape for the
1999-2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a voluntary thing,'' Pitino said. ``If people want to
get better, we will work with them. Just playing basketball is a
detriment.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino went on, ``This is for people who want to work with us.''
Asked if the players would be paid, the coach said, ``No. Nor
should they.''
</P>
<P>
   Oops. Boston, we have a problem. The NBA Players Association
isn't thrilled with Pitino's ``voluntary'' summer plan _ without
remuneration _ and, in fact, says it's against the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have a problem with it,'' said union attorney Ron
Klempner, who plans to discuss the matter with Billy Hunter, the
union's executive director. ``We bargained for a season that ends
in the spring and begins in the fall. If a team wishes to have
skills and workout sessions in the summer, there must be
individually negotiated bonuses for those who attend.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino ran afoul of the union in his first summer because some
of Boston's contracts contained language that actually docked
players who did not attend workout sessions. He apparently has done
so again; prohibitions against such policies are spelled out in the
not-so-fine print in the just-completed Collective Bargaining
Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The league, too, has kept an eye on the coach's ``voluntary''
summer sessions. Two summers ago, it warned him that it viewed such
gatherings as unfair because it gave his team a competitive
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino has a history of envelope pushing, and this is just the
latest example. He's got the right idea; getting the players in
shape is important. The union just feels it might be a good idea if
he and his people checked the rules first.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There were a lot of familiar names on rosters at the
just-concluded Nike Desert Classic in Phoenix. One of the more
intriguing is that of Lari Ketner, the Massachusetts big man who
alternately fascinates and puzzles NBA scouts. The early returns on
Ketner, courtesy of Celtics general manager Chris Wallace, were
encouraging. ``He's looked a lot better than he did in college.
He's more alert, more active,'' Wallace said. ``He's slowly
crawling out of the hole that he dug for himself. I don't know how
far he still has to crawl or where that puts him in the draft, but
he's taken the first step at coming back from the dead.'' Ketner
measured only 6 feet 8 1/2 inches (in socks) and weighed a svelte
282 pounds at Phoenix, a predraft showcase for seniors, although
the top ones rarely participate. Ketner said he felt he had a lot
to prove. ``I have to start playing the way I played when the
scouts were first attracted to me,'' he said. ``That's what I'm
trying to do. I had a bad season, I know that. I know there are a
lot of guys who know what I can do, but question whether I can do
it on a consistent basis. I've got a lot to improve on and I'm
going to make the most of it.'' Wallace said there were seven or
eight others who showed well in the early games. James Posey of
Xavier probably made the biggest impression and now might be the
fourth senior taken after Wally Szczerbiak, Andre Miller, and Jason
Terry. Wayne Turner also is there. ``Wayne is still Wayne,''
Wallace said, referring to Turner's reputation as a point guard who
cannot shoot. ``He can defend. He can push it. The big question is
always going to be if he can develop into a shooter.'' . . . One
more interesting name at Phoenix: Menk Bateer. He's a 6-10,
270-pound Chinese version of Vitaly Potapenko. He's also a free
agent, which means he could go anywhere anytime. He has played for
both the Chinese National Team and the Beijing Ducks. He was the
second-leading rebounder in China this past season, but Wallace
says he doesn't anticipate anyone rushing to sign the kid. ``Then
again,'' Wallace said, ``he's one of the few big men who's free as
we speak.'' . . . A lot of NBA teams, mainly those in the East, are
on the losing end in revenues because of Michael Jordan's
retirement. The reason? The Bulls aren't filling up buildings
anymore. Through Thursday, the Bulls, who sold out everywhere last
season, were drawing an average of 15,191 on the road. That's the
second-lowest mark in the NBA, beating only the Golden State
Warriors (15,065). Even the Clippers (16,258) and Grizzlies
(15,584) are outdrawing the Bulls. Last year, Chicago averaged
21,970 on the road (there were a couple dome games to inflate
that), so the dropoff is slightly more than 30 percent. Leaguewide,
attendance is down about 600 fans a game, or slightly more than 3
percent. The top road draws are the Lakers, Knicks, and, amazingly,
the Cavaliers (the only three teams drawing more than 18,000),
while Chicago remains the top home draw (22,389), though we're not
sure why . . . Keep an eye on the Milwaukee Bucks. They beat Miami
and Atlanta this week and have seven of their last 10 at home.
``They hammered the hell out of us,'' Heat coach Pat Riley said.
``They shoot the ball better than anyone in the NBA. What George
(Karl) has brought to them is a sense of excitement and chance and
hope. He's been there. He's changed their style to up-tempo,
pressure, trapping, a fast-paced game that is conducive to their
talent.'' . . . Landing On Your Feet Dept.: Wayne Lebeaux, the
former director of team and travel services for the Celtics, has
lined up a nice temporary gig. He's working behind the scenes for
Bruce Springsteen, now touring Europe with the E Street Band.
Lebeaux was one of several longtime Celtics employees who were
given walking papers when Pitino came to town.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the better comeback stories of the season is taking place
in Miami with the return of Voshon Lenard. He underwent surgery
Feb. 12 to repair a stress fracture in his left tibia. He has
recovered, and rejoined the Heat this past week. Lenard was told
that it would be up to nine weeks before he could return. That
period is up. ``I never lost hope,'' he said. ``I just wanted to
get it taken care of right away so that I wouldn't have the same
problem again. I've got a rod in my leg now and all I have to do is
work on getting my rhythm back and getting into game condition.''
The Heat now have all their people in place for the stretch run.
``As much as people talk about Miami, Indiana, and Orlando, because
we have the best records, we've also shown that on any given week,
all three of us can lose four in row. So you really gotta stay on
it,'' Riley said. More of those four-hour practices, Pat? ``There's
never a four-hour practice,'' he said. ``Just a four-hour window. I
may have them for four hours, but we might meet for 3 hours and
only practice 15 minutes.'' Riley even called off Thursday's
practice in Boston in favor of a team bonding session. ``I do have
a little mercy left in me,'' Riley said. ``Not much, just a little.
There's no time. I don't complain, but there's no time to really
plan. We always plan things on a two-week basis with a time block
allotted for practice and other things. We don't have that anymore.
Basically, when there's a day off now, the guys are so mentally
drained that it's not very productive anyhow. The playoffs will be
normal. But (the league) wanted to get in 50 games and they did.
It's taken a toll.'' . . . Antoine Walker is right about one thing:
If the Celtics keep adding five and six players every year, they're
going to spin their wheels forever. Last year, Pitino's first, we
saw too many new people to track. This year, we've got Paul Pierce,
Potapenko, Tony Battie, Eric Riley, Dwayne Schintzius, Marlon
Garnett, and, for their first full years, Kenny Anderson and Popeye
Jones. Next year, there are bound to be more. The only free agent
of any note the Celtics have is Bruce Bowen, and don't be surprised
if they let him go. First, they tried to trade him to the Clippers.
Second, the play of Greg Minor is making Bowen expendable. Minor
may not be as good as Bowen on defense, but he's much better on
offense. And he's locked up for two more years, and how many teams
would want that salary even if they wanted the player? The Celtics,
by the way, have about $43 million-$44 million committed in
salaries next season, including a freshly minted $2.5 million for
Walter McCarty (why they moved so fast on him is still a mystery)
and $1.5 million for Schintzius, although less than half is
guaranteed. The salary cap is $34 million . . . The NBA and the
Players Association are waiting for the NCAA to decide how it will
handle the proposal to deter high schoolers and college freshmen
from turning pro. Union officials met Thursday with NCAA honcho
Cedric Dempsey in an informal setting. The NBA/union proposal is to
add another year to the rookie scale for players who come from high
school or leave college after just one year. (So the Duke
sophomores would not have been affected.) But the union wants to
make sure the kids are compensated in some way and the NCAA is
looking into loan programs that might make it happen. Don't hold
your breath . . . Lest we overstate the value of veteran players,
we hark to the words of P.J. Carlesimo, coach of the Golden State
Warriors. He has his heretofore hapless, hopeless team actually
thinking about making the playoffs. Reason 1: more talent. Reason
2: more veterans. ``You can't imagine how important they've been to
us,'' he said of graybeards Terry Cummings and John Starks. ``These
are guys who know what it takes. They work hard every day and the
young guys see that and say, `Oh, so that's how it's supposed to
be.' '' Carlesimo has fallen in love with Cummings, who has been
critical to the team's turnaround on and off the court. He's got 13
years of playoff experience. Starks has been in the playoffs the
last nine years, and Chris Mills has missed only one year out of
five. Carlesimo points out those three basically came for nothing
(Latrell Sprewell) because the Warriors didn't have Sprewell but
for 14 games last year. Along with the blossoming of Antawn Jamison
(``he'd be further along if we started him out of the box,'') the
Warriors are _ gasp _ within sight of the playoffs after an 0-5
start . . . News Item: The Lakers waive Dennis Rodman. This wasn't
exactly the basketball equivalent of ``Waiting for Godot.'' The
Lakers have problems that run deeper than Rodman; namely, defense.
Kobe Bryant is having trouble defending shooting guards. Glen Rice,
as we all know, doesn't defend, period. Shaquille O'Neal does if
the spirit moves him. In the six games before Saturday's contest in
Utah, the Lakers' opponents shot 48.1 percent. While that might not
sound bad, this year it's stupefying. The league average is 43.5,
and the worst team in the league in that category, the Clippers,
hold foes to 47.2 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
