<HEADLINE>
LAST ROUNDUP BEFORE PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
 LEAGUE NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY VAN HANDLE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With the regular season concluding Sunday and the
playoffs on the doorstep, it's time to check out a few matters of
minor (league) import:
</P>
<P>
   --They've clobbered just about every opponent, recorded
glittering statistics, and dominated the American Hockey League
All-Star team, so it's no wonder that the Providence Bruins are the
favorites to win the Calder Cup when the playoffs get under way
Friday. But no matter what happens in the postseason, the Bruins'
accomplishments during the regular season have been nothing short
of astonishing. Providence has registered the biggest single-season
improvements in victories (37) and points (69), and can set an AHL
record for wins (58). The Baby B's have already established 22 team
and 13 individual records, and AHL Most Valuable Player Randy
Robitaille (101 points) became Providence's first 100-point scorer.
</P>
<P>
   --The four-on-four overtime experiment seems to be achieving the
desired result _ determining a winner. Some 60 percent of overtime
games have been decided, as opposed to 33 percent prior to the
change.
</P>
<P>
   --The International Hockey League has its own version of
Providence in the Houston Aeros, who have only one fewer
regulation-time loss than the Bruins (the IHL employs a shootout to
decide ties), thanks to a dominant defense (2.56 goals-against per
game) and league-leading offense. Two former Bruins, Greg Hawgood
(17-56_73, the I's top-scoring defenseman) and Cam Stewart
(36-25_61), are among Houston's top scorers. Maine's Jeff Tory
(19-35_54) was an All-Star choice on the blue line.
</P>
<P>
   --Patrik Stefan, projected as one of the top picks in the NHL
entry draft, was sidelined for the rest of the season and playoffs
after suffering his second concussion this year on March 31. The
18-year-old center played less than half the IHL season with Long
Beach, sitting out three months earlier with postconcussion
syndrome and a bruised spine. Though still a highly touted
prospect, Stefan's future has been clouded a bit, at least
according to Jacques Demers, whose Tampa Bay team owns the No. 1
choice. ``He's maybe the one kid who could come in and play right
away,'' said Demers. ``But once you start talking about
concussions, you really got to be careful.''
</P>
<P>
   --Boston College products Dave Hymovitz and David Littman are
putting the finishing touches on stellar IHL seasons. Hymovitz is
third on the league's goal list with 45, and also ranks among the
I's top 10 scorers with 75 points for Indianapolis. At the age of
31, Littman is having a career year for Orlando with 31 wins, a
2.90 GAA, and a league-best 54 appearances.
</P>
<P>
   --A 5-foot-11-inch New Hampshire star goes undrafted, puts in a
terrific senior season, and has his choice of signing with any NHL
organization. Hobey Baker winner Jason Krog is in the same
situation as Mark Mowers was last spring; now Mowers is one of the
IHL's most promising rookies and a 26-game veteran of the NHL.
Mowers, UNH's 1998 Hobey Baker finalist who signed last summer with
Nashville, spent most of the season in Milwaukee and posted totals
of 14-21_35 in 50 games.
</P>
<P>
   --Portland may not have made the AHL playoffs, but the Pirates
became a popular team for college players to break in with. With
seven players either called up to Washington or reassigned to other
teams, Portland needed bodies and found four from the collegiate
ranks. Mike Omicioli, the former Providence sparkplug, made his
presence felt quickly with two goals in his first three games,
including a game-winner. Anthony Cappelletti scored his first pro
goal against Lowell at Paul Tsongas Arena, where Cappelletti had
played his home games while with UMass-Lowell. Dean Stork
(UMass-Amherst) and Alain St. Hilaire (RPI) also propped up the
Pirates, who used an AHL record-tying 62 players this season.
</P>
<P>
   --The St. Louis Blues sent Jim Carey to Cincinnati (IHL) in the
hope that he could find his game again and work his way back to the
NHL. Instead, Carey found himself on the sideline after two games,
the victim of a concussion after he was kicked in the helmet during
a goalmouth scramble. The Cyclones are hoping he'll be back for
this week's playoff opener. Former UMass-Amherst goalie Brian Regan
is acting as Cincinnati's backup goalie on his off-days from his
job as Dayton's No. 1 goalie in the East Coast Hockey League
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   --The ECHL had its HoustonProvidence equivalent in Pee Dee. The
team with the curious name (actually a region of South Carolina
named after a river) chalked up 51 victories, impressive in any
league but especially one with a 70-game schedule. Players with
local ties played a major role in the Pride's success, which
included a league-record 29 home wins. Goalie Mark Richards, a
minor league vet who played collegiately at the University of
Lowell, was 29-4-3 with a 2.82 goals-against average. Three former
Salem State players _ Kurt Mallett, Tom Field, and Mike Payne _
along with Providence's Rick Bennett and Lowell's Brendan Flynn,
helped form the winning nucleus for coach Jack Capuano, the former
Maine defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was another record-setting year at the gate in the minors;
each of the three top leagues set records while, not
coincidentally, announcing plans to expand. The AHL, which has
broken attendance records every year since 1992, is on pace to draw
more than 4.1 million spectators. Not surprisingly, Providence is
among the leaders with an average of 7,159 per game, and Worcester
is close behind at 6,097. The Fredericton franchise, Montreal's
affiliate, is moving to Quebec City next year, and Wilkes-Barre,
Pa., will be joining, bringing the AHL to a total of 20 franchises
. . . The IHL, based almost exclusively in big cities, drew an
average crowd of almost 7,000 and will total more than 5 million
fans. But more salient is its philosophical change in trying to woo
NHL affiliations. The I has consisted almost exclusively of
independent teams, but owners began to question the wisdom of
trying to go it alone after several teams folded. Milwaukee and
Nashville were affiliated this season, and expansion Columbus has
hooked up with Orlando for next year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How could anyone think that Adirondack would miss the playoffs,
especially when it has some Majic on its side? Xavier Majic joined
the Red Wings midway through the year from the ECHL, and he
contributed to Adirondack's drive to the postseason. If the
presence of Satan (Miroslav) hasn't hurt Buffalo, a Majic touch
could only be a plus . . . It's common to see hats, caps, octupi,
and even fish tossed onto the ice in the spirit of celebration, but
a bride's bouquet? Well, a marriage was held at center ice before a
Long Beach game this season, and the bride's bouquet hit the
playing surface during the game. Obviously spoken for, the players
declined to pick it up . . . Logo of the week: It appears that a
relative of the ``Elvis'' Patriot has been located in Milwaukee.
The Admirals' logo features this fellow with a jaunty hat. But if
you compare him with the Patriots' guy, it looks as though the
Admiral could be his uncle. Maybe the teams should switch faces _
the Admiral sure looks meaner than Elvis, and isn't that what the
Patriots really need?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
