<SLUG> BC-CAR-LONG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANAAN IS BEST BET AT LONG BEACH
</HEADLINE>
 BEACH-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ On Friday, Tony Kanaan won a couple of
wristwatches after betting his race engineers he could turn a lap
quicker than 62.500 seconds during the first qualifying run for
CART FedEx Championship cars at the Toyota Grand Prix of Long
Beach. Kanaan ended up with a best lap of 62.332 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Kanaan upped the ante.
</P>
<P>
   Kanaan turned his gambling ways toward his mechanics before
directing the No. 44 McDonald's Drive Thru Reynard-Honda onto the
streets in the final qualifying session for today's 25th running of
the Long Beach Grand Prix. And, once again, the wager included
watches.
</P>
<P>
   ``(I told the mechanics) I make a bet with all you guys,'' said
Kanaan, who, if you haven't figured it out, is a watch collector.
``I said if I make the pole, I want all of your watches. They said,
`OK, if you don't make the pole, what do we get?' I said `I'll buy
you dinner.'''
</P>
<P>
   So how did it go?
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody want to buy a Rolex '95?,'' Kanaan asked.
</P>
<P>
   Kanaan was the proud owner of a handful of watches that were
previously the property of the Drive Thru crew members. More
importantly, the personable 24-year-old Brazilian is the proud
owner of his first pole position as a CART driver.
</P>
<P>
   He accomplished the racing milestone by turning a quick lap of
61.109 seconds at an average speed of 107.454 miles per hour to
finish in front of street-course specialist and provisional pole
sitter Dario Franchitti (107.412 mph), last year's Long Beach pole
sitter Bryan Herta (107.154), Herta's Team Rahal teammate Max Papis
(107.044), Target/Chip Ganassi rookie Juan Montoya (106.966) and
Patrick Racing's Adrian Fernandez (105.173).
</P>
<P>
   Kanaan, last year's CART Rookie of the Year, turned the fast
time 20 minutes into the second of two 30-minute sessions on the
11-turn, 1.824-mile street circuit and then held his breath. No
other driver was able to better his effort before the session
ended. There was four minutes remaining on the clock when Christian
Fittipaldi's engine stopped in the middle of the hairpin turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We changed from the primary (car) to the spare in the morning
practice and immediately went quicker,'' said Kanaan, who had a
gearbox problem in the primary car in the morning. ``We talked
about it at length and about 10 minutes before qualifying decided
to switch to the backup.''
</P>
<P>
   The switch meant that Kanaan's Friday qualify times were
disallowed and he was starting from scratch. But that didn't
concern him; the cars running in Saturday's first session were
blazing around the track.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Gil de Ferran, 15th after Friday, moved all the way to
first after the first session by turning a top-average time of
106.568 mph. De Ferran hoped the time would stand up to give him
his third Long Beach pole, but he had to settle for seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw what Gil was doing and saw the times improving,'' Kanaan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kanaan wasn't the only guy who went out in the second session
with a backup car. Franchitti did the same, but for a very
different reason. He lost his primary Team Kool Green Reynard-Honda
on the second lap of the morning practice session when he made
contact with the wall at Turn 2. The collision caused extensive
damage to the nose and left front suspension and moved Franchitti
into his backup car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brushed the wall (at turn 1) with the left side of the
car,'' Franchitti said, ``and that must've damaged the steering,
because the car wouldn't turn for the next corner and I went into
the barriers. It wasn't even a quick lap and I end up brushing the
wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Herta and Papis will follow Kanaan and Franchitti into the first
turn in today's 85-lap, 115.04-mile race. It is a good starting
position for Team Rahal, but not as good last year when Herta began
on the pole and Bobby Rahal was by his side.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get where we wanted with the car but we were
close,'' Herta said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, starting on the pole doesn't guarantee victory. The last
driver to win the race after beginning on the pole at Long Beach
was Al Unser Jr. in 1990, and its only happened five times in the
15 years the CART cars have run here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The race isn't won on the first lap,'' Franchitti said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
