<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RED </SLUG>
 SOX-MINOR LEAGUES-BOS  
 McCOY STADIUM DRAMATICALLY TRANSFORMED  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There are ways not to pay the highest average prices in
baseball and still savor New England ballparks that may not have
Fenway Park's tradition but make you mighty happy that you passed
through the turnstiles.
</P>
<P>
   A baseball fan planning summer weekends could do worse than
trying to visit them all, especially if she's thinking of taking
the family and would rather not blow the mortgage on an excursion
to Yawkey Way.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in Cape Cod League baseball, a showcase of some of the
best college talent in the country, and the competitive New England
Collegiate League, whose president is former major league
commissioner Fay Vincent, and there are plenty of satisfying
alternatives to big-league ball.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, start with red-brick New Britain Stadium, the
three-year-old home of the Rock Cats, the Twins' Double A team. In
Norwich, there's four-year-old Senator Thomas Dodd Stadium, home of
the Navigators, the Yankees' Double A affiliate. Blue-collar
Bridgeport has the independent Bluefish, who play in The Ballpark
at Harbor Yard, its new palace.
</P>
<P>
   There is the year-old Edward LeLacheur Park in Lowell, home of
the Single A Spinners, the Red Sox' affiliate, and in Nashua, N.H.,
the independent Pride play in Holman Stadium. There are people who
swear you can't do better than Portland's Hadlock Field, where
historian Doris Kearns Goodwin threw out the first ball on Opening
Day for the Sea Dogs, Double A affiliate of the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a new contender for a midsummer night's baseball
dream: venerable McCoy Stadium in Pawtucket, which turns 57 in July
but has undergone a $16 million facelift that dramatically has
transformed the home of the Triple A PawSox, with increased seating
capacity to 10,031, left-field berm, party tents down the
right-field line, new entry tower, expanded concourse, new playing
surface, and revamped outfield dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   The PawSox drew an overflow crowd of 10,586 to their Wednesday
night opener, a 3-2 win over Rochester that featured a
game-deciding two-run homer by Dernell Stenson, the organization's
top hitting prospect, and 10 strikeouts from Juan Pena, the
righthander who threw a no-hitter last season and pitched to
favorable reviews in big-league camp this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The PawSox' first homestand ends Sunday afternoon, with a chance
for fans to check on the progress of Brian Rose, who is attempting
to return to the majors after being sidelined most of last season
because of a bone spur in his elbow. Rose struck out six and
allowed one run in five innings in his first start in Buffalo and
afterward said he felt as good as he did in 1997, when he went 17-5
for the PawSox and was named the International League Pitcher of
the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Game time Sunday is 1:05, and while ticket prices went up a
buck, the top price remains $7, with kids and senior citizens
tickets selling for just $4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adam Everett, 1998's top draft pick who last season played for
short-season Lowell, has skipped full-season A ball and is playing
for Double A Trenton. In his first five games, Everett was batting
.273 with one error . . . Shea Hillenbrand, who led the
organization in hitting last season with a .349 average at Single A
Michigan, is off to a hot start for Trenton, batting .375 with a
home run and 9 RBIs . . . The Thunder, unbeaten in their first
seven games, have had no hitter hotter than ex-Expo farmhand Israel
Alcantara, who had five home runs and 15 RBIs . . . To make room
for Creighton Gubanich on the 40-man roster, the Red Sox placed
Pawtucket lefthander Brian Barkley on the 60-day disabled list with
what was described as inflammation of his left shoulder . . .
Justin Duchscherer, the 21-year-old righthander who last season was
7-12 for Michigan, allowed just four hits in 14 scoreless innings
in his first two starts for the Augusta Greenjackets and was named
South Atlantic League pitcher of the week. The Sox ended their
affiliation with Michigan in the Midwest League and hooked up with
Augusta . . . Outfielder Jess Graham, signed as a nondrafted free
agent out of Ohio University two years ago, had a remarkable first
week for Butch Hobson's Single A Sarasota team. In a 13-1 win over
Clearwater April 8, Graham singled in a run in the first, hit a
three-run double in the second, and followed with a three-run home
run in the third. He finished 3 for 4 with a walk and 7 RBIs. He
had three hits and an RBI in a Sarasota loss in his second game, 3
for 6 with a game-winning RBI in the 11th the next day, then 4 for
5 with a home run and two RBIs in his fourth game. It took Yankee
pitcher Andy Pettitte, working on a rehab assignment, to slow him
down, but Graham still had a double off the lefthander.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
