</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-KATZENMOYER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KATZENMOYER GETS THE CALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Patriots stepped out of their prim and
proper mode Saturday and drafted Ohio State linebacker Andy
Katzenmoyer, an individual who may have a Dick Butkus mentality _ a
little crazy, a little reckless.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer, who had a problem with alcohol in the past and who
needed to take seven summer courses to keep up with his slipping
academics at Ohio State, fell to the 28th pick after being
projected as high as the top 15.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-hitting linebacker, one of the most colorful players in
the draft, said he was not disappointed he slipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' he said. ``I came in having no clue or
premonition of where I'd end up. It doesn't matter to me. I just
want to come in and contribute the best I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer, who played in the middle for the Buckeyes, will
likely be plugged into the weakside linebacker position vacated by
Todd Collins. He will compete with Tedy Bruschi for playing time at
that spot and may also see time inside protecting Ted Johnson, who
has had three arm/shoulder operations the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of Johnson, Bruschi, and Katzenmoyer should put
the Patriots among the hardest-hitting group of linebackers in the
league, which should also complement the pass-rushing skills of
Chris Slade.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt Katzenmoyer was Pete Carroll's choice. The
coach convinced war room head Bobby Grier as well as owner Robert
Kraft that Katzenmoyer would be an impact player. Some in the draft
room wanted the Patriots to take LSU running back Kevin Faulk, but
Carroll made a case for Katzenmoyer, who was rated 14th on the
Patriots' board.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew what we wanted and we went ahead and did it,'' said
Carroll. ``When we started talking about someone who is a little
crazy and a little wild, Andy is someone who isn't that fired up
about school. This guy is nuts about football. He's really excited
about the fact that now he can concentrate all his efforts on
football. He did not do a great job in school. This guy is a
football player. Everybody has something they have to deal with. He
might have a few things he needs to straighten out.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer, the final Bill Parcells compensation pick, called
his poor academics ``a lack of discipline on my part. I was a
little lost and I let my classes slip. That's basically it.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerning alcohol, ``That was an incident that happened a long
time ago. It's a non-issue with me and my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer has spent no time as an outside linebacker, but said
he will adapt. The Patriots really don't employ a true outside
linebacker on that side, so Katzenmoyer should fit the role as a
read-and-react type, more like his role as a freshman at Ohio
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Ohio State) attacked so much that they had him blitzing so
much and attacking the line,'' Carroll said. ``Early in his career
he was more of a reader. We think that hurt his production but the
style they played with him grew with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer, a 6-foot-3-inch, 245-pounder, has 4.5 speed in the
40. His college coach, John Cooper, said Katzenmoyer could even
bulk up to ``280 pounds and be a down lineman.'' Cooper said
Katzenmoyer's role really didn't change much over the years but
teams later double- and triple-teamed him.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the fans' reaction at the draft party Saturday, he
will likely be a popular player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy to start it off with fan support,'' said
Katzenmoyer. ``I've never been to Boston and I don't know much
about the Patriots except that Bob Kraft has built a great
organization. I'm really looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer didn't speak to the media his senior season at Ohio
State. He has admitted that probably wasn't the smartest thing to
do. He fancies himself a Mike Singletary-type linebacker but when
asked by New Orleans coach Mike Ditka which linebacker he most
enjoyed watching, he answered Brian Bosworth, the former
first-round bust.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer was also Mo Vaughn's favorite college player. So
enamored was Vaughn with Katzenmoyer that the former Red Sox star
began exchanging uniforms and other items with him over the past
two years.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn is gone but Katzenmoyer hopes his stay in New England
lasts longer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-99 0322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
