<DOCNO> NYT19990418.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 03:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3118 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      04-18 2115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO LOOKING BACK FOR GRETZKY 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Wayne Gretzky will wave goodbye to the game he loves
Sunday, uncertain of his future, but convinced that by Sunday night
he will be perfectly comfortable with his status as ex-icon, former
shaper of the game, a legend designated for assignment.
</P>
<P>
   He'll go on being the Great One, only now at his leisure and his
pace, far from the cacophony of everyday celebrity and fame. He
won't have to live anymore by an 82-game schematic. He is 38 years
old and has spent more than half his life working the boards of
fame and fortune and he is ready for a rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was going to take something real special three weeks ago to
start changing my mind,'' Gretzky said Friday at his farewell news
conference, dating his decision to call it quits back to about when
the Rangers were eliminated from the playoffs. ``And I never
wavered off of that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   We live in a time of wiggle room, of course. When someone stands
before us and says, ``So long,'' especially a superstar with some
legs left, we look at our watches, check the calendar, and begin to
wonder when rumors of a return will begin. But don't go making book
that Gretzky will pull a Gordie Howe or a Michael Jordan and come
clattering back down the track. Not based on how he sounded Friday.
If he were to return, he first would have to be presented an
Academy Award for his convincing performance at the Paramount Room
in Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, someone may call and ask if he'd consider it,'' said
longtime agent Mike Barnett. ``But he's made it so absolutely clear
_ and his word is always his bond. There is zero likelihood of his
coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, with Gretzky gone, what of the league?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in solid shape,'' Gretzky said Friday. ``There's not one
guy in there that's bigger than the game. Gordie Howe taught me
that when I was 18 years old. I teach that to everybody that comes
to the game. We have great players, from (Jaromir) Jagr to (Teemu)
Selanne. The game is better than it was 20 years ago, and it will
be better than it is today.''
</P>
<P>
   In two decades, the game has taken two major growth spurts: (1)
in numbers of teams; (2) in player salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Growth and health, however, are separate issues.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL soon will be 30 teams wide and the average salary per
man is nosing toward $1.5 million. More people, especially
Americans, care far more about the NHL than they did in '79, and
Gretzky's skill and success are the root cause for much of that. If
not for his grace and greatness, his skill and appeal, it might
still be only Canada's game and not the growing American
Wal-Mart-like enterprise it has become. He, more than anyone,
helped it become a Big Box product.
</P>
<P>
   When Gretzky bids farewell Sunday afternoon, the game itself
will not suffer in his absence. If he had pulled out, Koufax-like,
at age 28, in his prime and before mega-expansion, then the game's
direction might have been altered dramatically. But not now. His
game has been in decline for a couple of years and the latter part
of this decade has seen some brilliant, identifiable stars emerge _
including the likes of Eric Lindros and Paul Kariya, Dominik Hasek
and Peter Forsberg, Jagr and Selanne. The game is not hurting for
interest or eyeballs.
</P>
<P>
   Star quality aside, however, the game has a significant
financial problem that Gretzky, if he soon hitches on somewhere as
a part-owner (a point Barnett hinted at in Saturday's Globe),
quickly will understand.
</P>
<P>
   NHL superstars now are making $10 million a year at the top end
(twice what Gretzky earned this season). Average salary has
increased tenfold in his playing career and, given the recent
inflation rate, is on course to bump up another 100 percent in 4-5
years. If ticket prices move in lockstep _ and what else can they
do without huge TV revenue? _ that $70 lower-bowl seat at the Vault
will be $140 by about the 2004-05 season. The cheapest (relative
term) seat in the house will run upwards of $50. The most
blue-collar sport of them all will be watched exclusively by a
white-collar crowd. Goodbye to big hair and Neely shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to what Gretzky may think, or say, that is not great
shape.
</P>
<P>
   Quality of play is another dicey, discouraging issue. Atlanta
comes aboard this October, followed by Minnesota and Columbus in
the fall of 2000. There just aren't enough players to stock 30 NHL
rosters. When there were shortages in the old days, the '60s and
'70s, the league's ``have-nots'' resorted to thuggery to keep the
masses entertained. Brawling now gone by the wayside _ for good
reason _ the league's many ``have-nots'' must ply their traps and
dumbing-down defenses to compete with the ``haves.'' Result: a lot
of bad games with a lot of bad players.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday afternoon, we have one sweet glimpse remaining of the
game's greatest offensive performer. No one will touch his
almost-obscene scoring records. And if they do, the bet here is
that this scribe won't be around for you to shove this yellowed and
tattered newspaper clipping in his nose.
</P>
<P>
   When he was at his best, when he was the Great One, Gretzky used
his speed and vision in a way that magically turned him into a
computer cursor. He was that tiny arrow that, in a click, could
change the screen's dimension, make the game whatever he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Click: suddenly the defenseman, closing in so fast, just
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Click: the goalie hugging the right post now was on the left
post.
</P>
<P>
   Click: Jari Kurri, not even on the screen a split-second ago,
now was stuffing the puck in an open net off a Gretzky feed out
from behind.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky was not power and might. He was megabyte and RAM, and
for five or six years, in the stretch when he led the Oilers to
four Stanley Cups, he made everyone else look like Hockey for
Dummies.
</P>
<P>
   All the greats of all the sports eventually say, ``So long.''
Hockey was great before Gretzky arrived and he made it better in a
way that Bobby Orr made it better when he was here in the Hub, the
way Howe did in Detroit and Rocket Richard did in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky did it more profoundly, with all the numbers to prove
it. He stood apart. He had his own way, his own number.
</P>
<P>
   As a farewell Sunday, the league should lift high his No. 99 in
Madison Square Garden and call for it to be similarly retired in
every NHL rink for the start of next season. In that sense, the
league won't have to go forward without him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OK, now what for the Rangers? They've missed the playoffs for a
second year running and there's no reason to believe they'll make
it back to the dance next season _ which would be their worst
drought since the mid '60s. The one trade they might be able to
build on would mean moving goalie Mike Richter (three years, $16
million-plus remaining on his deal), but that would mean handing
the job to the still-unproven Dan Cloutier. The only other viable
scenario could be firing general manager Neil Smith and/or
jettisoning coach John Muckler (one year remaining at about $1
million). Makes one wonder whether Gretzky might have opted against
retirement if the Blueshirts had landed Theo Fleury from the Flames
or Mark Recchi from the Canadiens . . . How about Recchi's plight?
He recently suffered his second concussion in 23 days and he's
actually thinking about playing more this season. The blows must
have left him addle-brained. Remember, he is an unrestricted free
agent, and should sign for at least $7 million a year somewhere.
But if he doesn't come back for the playoffs, will a team risk
investing big money in someone whose future could be affected by
the recent blows to his head? All of which might explain why he
wants back in the lineup . . . Derian Hatcher lines up Jeremy
Roenick, sends him to Palookaville while cracking his jaw in three
places, and then offers, ``I guess it's unfortunate that his jaw
ended up being broken . . . His head was in a bad place . . . I got
pushed from behind.'' Head in a bad place? Please. Coyotes captain
Keith Tkachuk responded with a profanity-laced tirade that got a
lot of air time around the Original 27, and a challenge to league
disciplinarian Colin Campbell to suspend Hatcher for the playoffs,
given that Roenick is done for the season. Neither a bad nor novel
concept. Campbell Saturday tagged Hatcher with seven games _ the
final two in the regular season and five in the playoffs.
Typically, the league has steered clear of suspending players for
the postseason. The Stars will have to handle the Oilers in Round 1
essentially without Hatcher _ that shouldn't be a problem _ but the
Coyotes are all but finished without Roenick . . . Former Bruin Joe
Juneau appears to be done for the season in Buffalo after suffering
a concussion, compliments of a heavy hit by the Flyers' Dan
McGillis, ex- of Northeastern . . . One for Bruins fans to
fantasize over: Penguins forward Alexei Kovalev will be an
unrestricted free agent come July 1. He looked like a sure-shot
superstar in the '92 Olympics at Albertville, but never has put it
together in his time with the Rangers and Penguins. His skill level
is undeniable. ``Some guys come from Europe and have no problem
making the switch,'' said one NHL assistant coach. ``Then there are
guys like Kovalev who just don't get the idea that the ice surface
is smaller and they have to use their linemates.'' Makes you
wonder: perhaps with Pat Burns as his coach, and Dmitri Khristich
and Sergei Samsonov around for support, Kovalev could be one
outstanding acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With a 4-1 victory at Nashville Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, the Devils set
the league record for road victories with 28. They won their 27th
last week, tying the mark set by Montreal in back-to-back seasons
(1976-78). Just one more reason why no one in the East wants to
face the Devils in the postseason . . . Word around Montreal is
that the Habs, out of the playoffs this season, will lose upwards
of $5 million when the accounting is finished . . . The Oilers lost
their leading scorer, ex-Boston College Eagle Bill Guerin, with a
leg injury last week and he won't suit up against the Stars. To
help fill the void, the Oilers called up Joe Hulbig, the former St.
Sebastian's star who was a first-round pick (13th overall) in '92.
He'll be an unrestricted free agent in July and rumors around
Edmonton have him signing a two-way deal with Boston in the
offseason . . . Michael Peca, the Sabres' lean-but-mean hitter, was
the No. 40 pick in that '92 draft. The Bruins owned that pick
originally, but swapped it to Vancouver, and the Canucks eventually
shoveled Peca to the Sabres in the Alexander Mogilny trade . . .
The deal Peter Forsberg signed in Colorado last week will bring him
salaries of $8 million, $9 million, and $9.5 million the next three
years and a signing bonus of $3.5 million spread over the same
stretch. Where does that put a guy like Byron Dafoe? The Bruins'
sensational netminder wouldn't be out of line asking for annual pay
in the $4 million-$6 million range for two or three years. The
Bruins would be in a far bigger pickle without Dafoe than the
Avalanche would be sans Forsberg . . . Doctors say Eric Lindros,
who lost half his blood supply a couple of weeks ago when he
suffered a collapsed lung, already has recovered nearly all of
those three liters. Lindros hasn't granted interviews since his
release from a Nashville hospital, but there is no way he'll be
back for the first round. It's highly improbable that he'd be back
for anything but a final round _ and it's even more improbable that
the Flyers still will be hanging around by then . . . The
Hurricanes aren't likely to have their top power forward, Keith
Primeau, back at full strength for the playoffs. He's been nursing
a lower back strain that had him back in Ontario late last week
consulting a specialist. They're also down defenseman Sean Hill,
who suffered multiple fractures when he was hit in the face by a
slapper in Washington Wednesday night. He won't be back this year .
. . Former Bruin Bill Ranford couldn't stop a beach ball in
Washington or Tampa, but last week he ran his record to 3-0-1 since
getting swapped to the Red Wings. Remind anyone of Larry Murphy? He
was booed unmercifully in Toronto a couple of years ago and then
came to Detroit, where he now has two Cup rings to soothe whatever
wounds those boos caused him . . . I have this image: Gretzky
loosening up for 18 holes on some exotic golf course, with Steve
Kasper bolting out from behind a palm tree and knocking the club
out of his hands on the first tee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
