<HEADLINE>
BC'S CLOUD, BRZEZINSKI JOIN THE FUN 
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-BOSTON COLLEGE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ They spent the day separated by one time
zone and thousands of miles, but Mike Cloud and his Boston College
teammate Doug Brzezinski were linked by an overwhelming sense of
relief after both were finally selected in Saturday's NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   After the Patriots made BC center Damien Woody their initial
first-round draft choice with the 17th pick overall, Cloud, a
5-foot-10-inch, 202-pound All-American from Portsmouth, R.I., was
the second Eagle taken when Kansas City picked him in the second
round (54th overall) after swapping picks with Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Then Brzezinski, a 6-4, 300-pounder from Livonia, Mich., who was
rated by some as the top guard in the draft, was taken by
Philadelphia in the third round (64th overall).
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, it ended an excruciatingly long wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stayed home and watched the first two rounds at home until 7
o'clock,'' said Cloud Saturday &UR;  &LR; night from his home. ``When they
switched it to ESPN2, we had to go and find a place to watch it,
because we didn't have it here at my house.''
</P>
<P>
   So Cloud hopped into a car with his girlfriend Julie Van Dorn,
his brother Kevin, and their good friend Jeff Macumber and drove
across the Rhode Island border to Fall River, Mass., to find a
restaurant that was showing the draft on ESPN2. Problem was, the
cell phone Cloud was using to remain in contact with NFL teams had
gone dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost the signal for about 10 minutes and I started to get
nervous, because it was the number I'd given out to all the
teams,'' Cloud said. ``But once we crossed over into Mass., I
switched on the phone and it started ringing.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Chiefs calling. The car pulled into an Applebee's in
Fall River, where Cloud remained on hold, waiting to be patched
into the Chiefs war room for a conference call with general manager
Carl Peterson and new coach Gunther Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out in the parking lot, standing in the cold, when they
told me that they were going to draft me,'' Cloud said. ``It's a
great opportunity. As my agent told me, it's not where you get
drafted but the position you're put in as far as the depth chart is
concerned, and I think Kansas City will give me the opportunity to
get my feet wet early.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloud, who ranked as the Big East's leading rusher and No. 3 in
the nation last season after carrying 308 times for 1,726 yards and
14 TDs, said he will likely face some opposition from incumbents
Bam Morris, whose career has been plagued by off-field problems;
Donnell Bennett, a fifth-year pro from Miami; Jesse Haynes, a
product of Northwest Missouri State who signed as free agent two
years ago; and Rashaan Shehee, a 1998 third-round pick from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin's really happy for me,'' Cloud said, referring to his
brother, whose own dreams of a pro football career were shattered
by a serious neck injury in his junior year at Portsmouth High.
``He knew in the back of his mind that KC was where I'd wind up.
But he's really excited because KC are his initials.''
</P>
<P>
   In yet another interesting twist, Brzezinski, like former BC
teammate Mike Mamula, went from being an Eagle in college to being
an Eagle in the pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had it planned out that way,'' Brzezinski deadpanned. ``I'm
just glad that I finally got picked. I thought the Eagles was the
team I'd wind up with because they had flown me down for an
interview.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Eagles waited until the third round to select
Brzezinski.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were calling the house, but they were calling for my
brother Nick,'' said Brzezinski, whose brother will be an freshman
tight end at Duke next season. ``I was about to throw the phone
right through the wall, to tell the truth. I thought I was screwed.
I didn't think I'd get picked. It just took so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Brzezinski, who will likely battle George Hegamin and Melvin
Thomas for time at right guard, speculated the reason he went from
one of the draft's top prospects at guard to a third-rounder ``was
maybe because of some perceived lack of athleticism. I think that
hurt me a little bit. But it's no big deal. I'll just try and go in
and prove myself and do the best job I can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
