u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-FAULK-BO     04-18 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-FAULK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS FIND SOLUTION IN FAULK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ They waited nearly seven hours. They
attempted to make deals, hoping to move up in the draft to get a
``franchise'' running back like Texas's Ricky Williams or Miami's
Edgerrin James.
</P>
<P>
   None of it worked. Patriots coach Pete Carroll came out of the
``war room'' after two first-round selections yielded center Damien
Woody and linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer and said they were going to
``attack it'' in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a tremendous effort (to trade up),'' said Carroll, who
was hampered by the Patriots' low standing (20th and 28th) in the
first round. ``We were in on every one of the options that were
there for us. We had been workng on it continuously. But it just
kept on coming back that the teams just didn't want to go that far
down to lose that spot that they held.''
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, the Patriots would get what they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   In selecting Louisiana State running back Kevin Faulk in the
second round, the Patriots came up with what they hope is a
solution to a running attack crippled by the possible career-ending
injury to Robert Edwards and the lack of production from any other
back on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Along with former Indianapolis running back Lamont Warren, whom
the Patriots signed as a free agent Saturday, the team now has a
pair of third down-type backs who will battle it out for the
featured role.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like competition,'' said Carroll, ``we'll see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   As Carroll stated earlier in the day, the Patriots had to go on
the offensive to get the 5-foot-8-inch, 205-pound all-purpose back
by making a deal with Tennessee, trading their second-round (52d)
and fourth-round pick (117th) to get the 46th overall pick and
select Faulk.
</P>
<P>
   As was the case with all of the running backs in this draft
other than Williams and James, Faulk brings some questions such as
size and durability. With his dimension, Faulk is not someone who
can carry an offense. But with Drew Bledsoe around, the Patriots do
not expect Faulk to do so.
</P>
<P>
   When Faulk came to LSU out of Carenco (La.) High School as a
quarterback, he came with potential All-America and Heisman Trophy
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   His role at LSU was a little simpler. He led the Tigers in
rushing, caught a few passes, and returned a few kicks. Nothing
changed the next two years, although a series of nagging injuries
brought the question of durability into focus.
</P>
<P>
   His responsibilities increased not only as a student, but as the
father of two children, Tanasha and Kevin.
</P>
<P>
   But Faulk stayed the course. He passed up what could have been
first-round money a year ago by staying at LSU as he went after his
degree as well as a future in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the fall from the first round was hard to accept
since he left LSU as the career leader in rushing (4,557 yards) and
touchdowns (46). He ranks second in school history with 856 carries
and is the only player to rush for over 1,000 yards three times in
his career.
</P>
<P>
   He closed out his career in Baton Rouge with an All America
season, gaining 1,279 yards on 229 carries for a 5.6-yard average.
</P>
<P>
   All of which begs a question. How did a running back with
impressive stats and 4.57 speed in the 40 drop to a mid-second
rounder?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in life, you look for the little button that makes you
go that extra mile,'' Faulk said by conference call
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. ``(Not getting picked in the first round) is the
one thing that's going to make my motor go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots made it clear early they were focused on Faulk.
Along with the Baltimore Ravens and the New York Giants, the
Patriots spent the most time evaluating Faulk.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came down and spent the day with me, watching me work
out,'' said Faulk, who spent the early part of Saturday playing
basketball rather than sitting in his apartment, waiting for the
phone to ring. ``I felt I had a good relationship with the running
back coach (Kirby Wilson).''
</P>
<P>
   ``We liked this kid a lot,'' said Carroll, who said the Patriots
considered selecting Faulk with their second pick in the first
round. ``What put him over the top (against BC running back Mike
Cloud, whom they also had rated high) was his return ability.
That's an area where he can contribute immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Faulk's role with the Patriots will be as a running back/special
teams player. But he also likes to come out of the backfield and
catch passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up I loved playing wide receiver,'' said Faulk, who
said he patterned himself after Walter Payton.
</P>
<P>
   But the Patriots will settle for Kevin Faulk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
