<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA'S GEORGE SEEN AS SAFETY VALVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ He played cornerback last season at the
Univeristy of Florida, but that's not his natural position. Ask
Tony George what he likes about playing defensive back and he will
look you in the eye, smile, and talk about the contact.
</P>
<P>
   Not so much knocking down passes, but knocking down people.
After a long day and part of the night waiting to see what would
happen in Saturday's NFL draft, the 5-foot-10-inch, 198-pound
George learned he will be coming to New England.
</P>
<P>
   All of that became official when the Patriots used their
third-round pick (91st overall) to select George and add depth to a
secondary that already has some guys who like to get physical.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, George was diagnosed with diabetes. He didn't miss a
step as he accepted his condition and continued playing through
high school and into college, where he was a star for the Gators.
</P>
<P>
   George played cornerback last year because of injuries. Although
his speed may be a notch below average, he did fine with the Gators
because of an instinctive ability to sense where the ball was going
and a willingness to sacrifice his body.
</P>
<P>
   George's NFL career will no doubt mirror the early stages of his
time at Florida, when he arrived from Cincinnati and established
himself as a special teams performer, playing in every game and
leading the special teams unit with 34 tackles (22 solo).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to play him as a safety,'' said Patriots coach
Pete Carroll. ``And he can cover the third wide receiver at
times.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said he liked George's competitiveness and leadership
qualities. ``He played against top level competition and he's just
a tremendous kid,'' said Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his diabetes, George shrugged it off. ``It
really hasn't affected me,'' he said. ``I just go out and perform
the best I can.''
</P>
<P>
   George conceded he had some trepidation as Saturday wore on and
he had not been selected. ``I'm happy to be drafted at all,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   As for where he plays in New England, that doesn't matter to
George either. ``I look at the position as defensive back,'' he
said. ``It doesn't matter whether you play safety or cornerback.
Just as long as you do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   He also will play special teams as he did at Florida. But the
important thing for George is he will be playing football.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
