<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KONRAD REWARDED FOR BEING PATIENT 
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-KONRAD-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Bob Konrad said the wait was the worst part,
but it was worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Konrad likened it to giving birth all over again.
</P>
<P>
   As for Rob Konrad? By 5 p.m., when the NFL draft had lapsed into
the second round, the Syracuse fullback decided to retreat to his
bedroom upstairs, away from the party at his North Andover home.
</P>
<P>
   A sudden chill descended upon the warm celebration when the
Miami Dolphins, who made overtures about drafting Konrad, instead
traded their first-round pick (24th overall) to San Francisco and
wound up picking Mississippi State running back James Johnson with
the 39th pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a curious move,'' said Bob Konrad, disappointed the
Dolphins didn't draft his son with their first-round pick. ``Who
knows what works in minds of those mastermind football braintrusts,
but we're just happy that it's all over.''
</P>
<P>
   An hour and a half later, Konrad's long and excruciating wait
finally came to an end when, in the solace of his bedroom, he took
a call from Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson. Downstairs, the
partygoers fell silent when Miami traded its 54th pick in the
second round for Kansas City's 43d.
</P>
<P>
   Back upstairs, Johnson was telling Konrad he was going to be
Miami's next pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once it was announced on TV,'' Konrad said, ``about 70 people
here were jumping for joy.''
</P>
<P>
   Including Konrad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a little warmer, huh?'' Konrad said,
referring to his move from Syracuse to Miami's tropical clime. ``It
was gettting a little heated there for a while. Waiting isn't too
much fun. Patience is one virtue that I don't have very much of. I
was a little concerned when they traded down, then picked a running
back with their first pick of the draft, but then they called and
said they were going to trade up and pick me.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom and dad are excited. My mom's excited about hitting the
beach and my dad's excited about me playing for Jimmy Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, after all, has had some experience coaching fullbacks
from Syracuse after working with Daryl Johnston at Dallas, where he
was a featured element in the Cowboys' offense.
</P>
<P>
   With the numerous running backs now crowding Miami's backfield,
a question did arise about how Konrad would be utilized. Asked if
he was aware of Miami plans to use him at H-back or at tight end,
Konrad said, ``Not that I know of, but I won't be surprised if I'm
asked to do a couple of different things. I'll be happy to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim O'Leary, Konrad's coach at St. John's Prep, was one of the
celebrants at the Konrad household. ``It's the first time since
I've been coaching that we've had a kid going in the draft,'' he
said. ``When I had Rob, he was our horse and we rode his back for a
number of years. When he went to Syracuse, I thought he'd be a
better football player. The thing that people didn't understand
about Rob is that he can catch the ball, and now he's going to a
team with a Hall of Fame quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Konrad was the sixth Big East player taken in the draft (43d
overall) and third player from his school after quarterback Donovan
McNabb (Philadelphia, 2d overall) and wide receiver Kevin Johnson
(Cleveland, 32d).
</P>
<P>
   Konrad said he was surprised by the reaction Philadelphia fans
had when McNabb was selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why they wouldn't want him,'' Konrad said. ``The
kid is spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand where they're coming from, but I don't think
it was directed at Donovan, it was more at the team for who they
didn't pick.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
