<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDYLIGHTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIAFFONE EARNS POLE IN INDY LIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ The past five seasons have been fruitless
for Felipe Giaffone, as far as finding pole positions. Don't be
misled. The 24-year-old Brazilian has been a solid professional
driver, but his last pole position was in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   That was until Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Giaffone found Long Beach fruitful and took the pole position in
the Indy Lights Championship in the Toyota Grand Prix of Long
Beach. Giaffone's best lap was 1:07.668 at an average speed of
97.038.
</P>
<P>
   So Giaffone finished first for the second consecutive day in the
racing series considering the final steppingstone to the CART FedEx
Championship. This finish by Giaffone may have been more impressive
than Friday's because each of the 19 drivers in Indy Lights
improved his best-lap time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that I had to improve my car because everybody was
trying to,'' Giaffone said. ``But I knew at the same time I had a
really good car, so I didn't have to make any big changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Giaffone fell out of the pole position twice, but reclaimed the
position both times. First, with about 24 minutes remaining in the
30-minute qualifying session, Guy Smith took first, but three
minutes later Giaffone reclaimed it.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with 18 minutes left, Jonny Kane took first, but Giaffone
reclaimed the position with 13 minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Giaffone is the driver to beat in today's Indy Lights Race,
which starts at 10:20 a.m. If Giaffone wins, he would become the
third consecutive Brazilian to take the checkered flag in Indy
Lights at Long Beach. Cristiano da Matta won last year and Helio
Castro-Neves won the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   In last year's Indy Lights Race, Didier Andre claimed the pole
position. On Saturday, Andre showed the biggest improvements of any
racer and finished third with a best lap of 1:08.025 at 96.529 mph.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's practice session, Andre finished 14th. He finished
seventh in Friday's qualifier and fifth and third in Saturday's
practice round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that means I'll be first (today),'' Andre said.
</P>
<P>
   Andre had a few new strategies Saturday. His crew put on new
tires Friday, and he used only a half tank of gas to improve speed.
That tactic worked, but he ran out of gas and exited the race with
about five minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did my best lap, then ran out of fuel,'' Andre said. ``My
car started to go `putt, putt' at the end of the straight, and that
was it.''
</P>
<P>
   That actually was good timing for Andre as the qualifier ended
prematurely when its only incident forced the conclusion. With 3:23
left, a red flag went up when Geoff Boss hit a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Jonny Kane finished the highest of any rookie. This is in
contrast of the first Indy Lights event last month in Homestead,
Fla., in which two rookies finished first and third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-99 0329EDT &QL; 
