<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAT SQUIRMING AT LOUDON 
</HEADLINE>
 RACING NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bob Bahre, the 72-year-old owner of New Hampshire
International Speedway in Loudon, would prefer to go about his
business in a neighborly fashion. And, for the most part, he has
done just that, establishing a good rapport with community leaders
and state officials while bringing in a new source of revenue to
the Granite State with his 83,000-seat mile oval.
</P>
<P>
   In three weeks, Bahre will swing the gates open when NHIS hosts
a season-opening doubleheader, a 200-lap NASCAR Busch Series event
and a 100-lap Busch North race. But plans to expand the track's
capacity by 9,000 seats have been put on hold, as Bahre has been
hit with a lawsuit from a group of citizens in the neighboring town
of Canterbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put up 1,200 of 9,000 and stopped when they brought the
lawsuit,'' said Bahre, who has retained the Boston firm of Hale and
Dorr to fight the suit. ``So we actually want to put up 7,800 more.
We got the permits from the state and from the town of Loudon, but
there were, oh, about 10-12 people over in Canterbury who brought
the suit. They just don't like traffic. They don't like noise.
Those kinds of things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, we get along fairly well with the neighbors. We
always get somebody that complains a little bit, but these people
in Canterbury and Shakerville, they really just don't like racing
and they don't like race fans. There's been racing here since 1963
and they're complaining about the noise during the week from
practice and tryouts. We've done tests and it isn't that bad. We've
gone up to Shaker Village and you can't hardly hear it at times.
Sometimes you can when the wind blows just right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just continue to go into court and, eventually, we'll
make it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time since he opened the track in 1990 that
expansion has been impeded by a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in a while you'll get somebody on a planning board who
will go and (complain),'' said Bahre, whose track was wildly
received by fans, sanctioning officials, and competitors when he
staged a successful inaugural NASCAR Winston Cup race in 1993.
``Most of the people are for it and they know it's good for the
economy and everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these people, they're all wealthy people and they don't
care about anybody else and that's just the way it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong, I hate fights and that kind of stuff, but
we're going to stay right in there and fight with them. It's a lot
nicer if you can do things without having to fight and everything.
It doesn't get me down, but I sure don't like it. You would just
like to go forward and do things, and be friendly people and have
things work right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever there's a bunch of hard feelings, I mean, who the
hell wants those? We don't need it. All this lawsuit stuff, nobody
enjoys it and it's one of those deals where nobody really wins.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he felt about not having to stage an Indy Racing
League event, Bahre seemed to express immense relief when he sighed
and said, ``Thank God.''
</P>
<P>
   Bahre was among the first track owners to defect from
Championship Auto Racing Teams and join the fledgling racing series
founded by Indianapolis Motor Speedway president Tony George.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, citing dwindling crowds and mounting losses,
Bahre parted ways with the IRL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since we went with the IRL, we lost money every year,''
said Bahre, who estimated his total losses from IRL events to be
$1.6 million-$1.7 million. ``But when we went in with Tony, we told
Tony that we'd stick with him for three years, and we had to do
what we said we would do. In fact, we budgeted to lose $500,000
(last year) and we couldn't even stay in budget; we lost
$700,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Bahre made one startling admission: ``I'll admit that we made a
mistake when we didn't stay with CART. CART is not perfect, but I
know we would've done a little better with CART than we did with
this one. But they've got to get together someday.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IRL driver Greg Ray, who put an underfunded car on the front row
in last year's Indianapolis 500, looks to be a strong contender for
the pole position this year after he topped the speed chart during
an open test session last weekend at the Brickyard with a fast lap
of 227.072 miles per hour. ``We ran two different cars and three
different suspensions, and we did pretty good,'' said Ray, now a
driver for Team Menard. ``We still have not put the car anywhere
near qualifying trim. The conditions were just really good. When
you go out and scrub tires at 225, you know the conditions are
great.'' . . . Adrian Fernandez, who won last week's CART FedEx
series race at Motegi, Japan, will switch formulas when he trades
his proven Reynard for a Swift chassis in Sunday's Toyota Grand
Prix of Long Beach on a reconfigured 1.85-mile street circuit. ``We
don't know much about the Swift with the new configuration on road
courses, so I am going to have to get used to how this car
reacts,'' said Fernandez, who qualified among the top four drivers
in each of the season's first two races in his Tecate/Quaker
State-sponsored Reynard. ``We are on a roll right now and I am
confident that the team will make the maximum effort to make the
car as competitive as possible. I just have to go out and drive the
car to the best of my abilities. Hopefully, with the new
improvements to the car, we can produce a good result.'' . . .
Winston Cup driver Rusty Wallace debuted a new car in stunning
fashion when he dominated last weekend's Food City 500 at Bristol,
Tenn., leading 425 of 500 laps from the pole position. It was his
first victory of the season and 49th of his career and moved him
into eighth in the point standings, which Jeff Burton continues to
lead with 1,064 headed into Sunday's Goody's 500 at Martinsville,
Va. ``That was a pretty cool deal for our team at Bristol,'' said
Wallace, who'll debut another new car at Martinsville. ``When you
stop and think about it, it was pretty incredible that we were able
to take a brand new car _ a car that had never seen a lap on a
racetrack until last Friday _ win the pole, and then kick butt like
we did there on Sunday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-99 0331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
