u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXINGNOTEBOOK-BO     04-18 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AYALA STARTS OVER 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Tony Ayala comes home this week.
</P>
<P>
   After 16 years of incarceration, one of the most talented boxers
of the 1980s will be released from Bayside State Prison in
Leesburg, N.J., Tuesday, and two days later he will begin what may
prove to be a quixotic quest for a return to boxing glory when he
meets the media at the home of his former prison psychologist and
present fight manager, Brian Raditz.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala has served hard time for a long time on a 1983 rape
conviction, for a crime he once tried to deny he committed but now
sadly admits he did. During his long years away, Ayala searched his
soul and his psyche, became a new man after finally telling Raditz
that he had been sexually abused as a child and silently carried
the shame inside him fearing his family's reaction if they ever
learned the truth. Slowly, he turned himself not only into a model
citizen but also into a prison counselor.
</P>
<P>
   Once Ayala was a fighter filled with so much hate and fire that
he spit on one fallen opponent and destroyed many. He was widely
expected to be a sure thing to annihilate World Boxing Association
junior middleweight champion Davey Moore, but he was arrested a
month before that scheduled fight and his life was forever altered.
</P>
<P>
   Now Ayala hopes to somehow get his boxing life back despite the
long layoff and the years of working through the internal problems
that had made him a madman in and out of the ring. Many wonder
whether Ayala will be the same destructive machine he once was.
</P>
<P>
   Among his advisers is veteran promoter Don Elbaum, who
acknowledges that no one can predict what will happen when Ayala
steps back into the ring, but he hopes to find out by July in
Ayala's native San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony would do 25,000-30,000 (people) if he fought me,'' Elbaum
said. ``In fact, the way some people talk about me, he might do
more if he fights me. The way the boxing market is today, you get
two or three wins and, like it or not, you'll be on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see him have a couple of fights off TV if that's
possible just to get his confidence back and get him comfortable,
and then maybe you put him in with a Hector Camacho or Roberto
Duran, and if he wins you go for the big payday.''
</P>
<P>
   To Elbaum, to Ayala, to everybody really, that payday is
obvious. It is a Hispanic confrontation with Oscar De La Hoya. It
is The Golden Boy against the Bull, El Muchacho de Oro vs. El
Torito. If there is a bigger fight in boxing in the next year or
two, Elbaum can't see it.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala said in a Sport magazine interview this month that he
dreams of standing bloody and battered over De La Hoya after
knocking him out. Certainly the fighter he once was would have been
capable of that. But that was 16 years ago, a time when De La Hoya
was 9 years old.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, only makes such a confrontation all the more
theatric and all the more saleable, as Elbaum knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of some heavyweight fight, absolutely the biggest
fight in 2000 would be Tony Ayala vs. Oscar De La Hoya,'' Elbaum
said. ``When he was young he was the most exciting kid I ever saw.
It would be a huge fight. It would do awesome numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely it would if Ayala can get himself a half-dozen wins,
especially if several are of the spectacular knockout variety he
was once so famous for.
</P>
<P>
   But could he beat someone with De La Hoya's youth, speed, and
power after 16 years locked away from a ring?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony's been taking care of himself,'' Elbaum said. ``He's
about 170 and says he can make 154. When he didn't get out about
eight months ago when he thought he would, he had a bout with
depression; but he's over that. He's been working out inside, and
he believes he can do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Belief is half the battle in boxing, but the calendar is often
the other half and few fighters have ever beaten that for long.
Maybe a 36-year-old Tony Ayala will be one of the few.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HBO finally got the front end of its June 19 show worked out by
cutting Michael Grant's pay by $500,000 to convince Lou Saverese to
fight him for $1.05 million while Grant gets $950,000, but then the
semi-main event fell apart when Ike Ibeabuchi decided $500,000
wasn't enough to match punches with Jeremy Williams. No wonder HBO
Sports senior vice president for sports programming Lou DiBella has
a perpetual headache . . . Speaking of Ibeabuchi, veteran trainer
Teddy Atlas wonders whether the boxing world has made too much of
the undefeated Ibeabuchi's knockout of Chris Byrd March 20. ``My
instinct says we're getting carried away with it,'' said Atlas, who
trains heavyweight prospect Kirk Johnson. ``Byrd was a small
heavyweight who couldn't punch enough to keep the guy off him.
There were always doubts about how Chris would handle a big
heavyweight that could hit him. Give Ibeabuchi credit. He caught
Byrd on the ropes, which is difficult to do, and took him out, but
we'll see what Ibeabuchi does when he gets in with some big
heavyweights. And you shouldn't forget, he's a nut outside the
ring. We'll see if the things that have been a problem before for
him'' _ manic depression, according to some _ ``become a problem
again.'' . . . Although Ibeabuchi would have been favored, he
wasn't in Williams's mind. ``I'm going to beat Ike every minute of
every round,'' Williams said before Ibeabuchi rejected the $500,000
payday. ``He can't beat me. He's a nut job. He can't adapt in the
ring. His mind is all over the place.'' . . . By the way,
Ibebuchi's promoter, Cedric Kushner, continues to insist that
Ibeabuchi will agree to the fight but has refused to pay for
insurance to cover the promoters and HBO if he doesn't show up . .
. Bob Arum plans to bring De La Hoya into the not-yet-completed
Staples Center in Los Angeles in December for a major pay-per-view
show. The building will not be ready until October, but Arum
already has a deal in place for De La Hoya to become the building's
first fight. He is hoping to put on a rematch with Ike Quartey or
Pernell Whitaker, assuming a mega-fight with International Boxing
Federation welterweight champion Felix Trinidad cannot be worked
out . . . Everyone has a point of view when it comes to World
Boxing Organization featherweight champion Naseem Hamed, but
perhaps no one has one like heavyweight champion George Foreman's.
While Foreman was watching Hamed stop Paul Ingle in 11 rounds in
Manchester, England, last week, he said, ``I like what he did right
there. He did something stupid, and that's what he does best.'' . .
. In case you missed it (and I hope you did), on the Hamed-Ingle
undercard, 40-year-old Thomas Hearns won the little-known IBO
cruiserweight title with a unanimous decision over 35-year-old Nate
Miller, who agreed to come out of retirement to be Hearns's dance
partner. Miller clearly did not come to fight and, frankly, neither
man really could anymore. But Hearns's appearance was still a treat
for British boxing fans. It was his first in England. ``I'll be
back,'' said Hearns (59-4-1). You have to hope not if you remember
him when he was still The Hit Man . . . IBF junior featherweight
champion Vuyani Bungu is ready to vacate his title because of
weight problems and move up to the 126-pound class. He, like every
featherweight, would like to pursue Hamed. It is expected that
Benedict Ledwaba and John Johnson will box off for the vacant
122-pound title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
