<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYMPIC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKATER'S CASE ISN'T ROUTINE 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The sexual misconduct grievance filed last week against
skating coach Richard Callaghan is a hot potato nobody wants to
handle.
</P>
<P>
   The US Figure Skating Association, which already knew about
allegations that Callaghan had an inappropriate relationship with a
teenage male pupil two decades ago, is expected to decide that it
has no jurisdiction because Callaghan wasn't a member at the time.
The Detroit Skating Club, where Callaghan and accuser Craig Maurizi
were coaching partners, says that the incidents occurred before the
men worked there. Which leaves the Professional Skaters
Association, which could expel Callaghan if it deems him guilty.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that it's a nasty ``he says-he says'' case with
no apparent witnesses and with Callaghan vehemently denying
everything. It's complicated by the fact that Maurizi waited more
than 20 years to come forward and did so only after he and
Callaghan had a bitter professional split over Tara Lipinski last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If there is still skepticism about how seriously the
International Olympic Committee is about reforming itself, it may
be because president Juan Antonio Samaranch is dragging his feet
naming the special commission that is supposed to recommend
dramatic across-the-board changes. A month after the special IOC
session in Lausanne and less than two months before the next
session in Seoul where the 2006 winter site will be chosen,
Samaranch has appointed only half a dozen of the 24 members and
four of them are Americans _ IOC vice president Anita DeFrantz, US
Olympic Committee president William Hybl, former Los Angeles
Olympics chief Peter Ueberroth, and former US Secretary of State
Henry Kissinger. That's why some critics believe that the Lords
will merely spin their wheels until the world loses interest. ``I
think we'll see a great flurry of activity, with some discussion of
how they may change slightly how people are chosen and maybe some
term limits,'' says John Hancock president David D'Alessandro.
``Then Samaranch will declare victory and exit. That looks like the
plan here. I don't think you're going to see a great culture
change.'' Stickiest issue among the proposed reforms is how new
members will be chosen. The Lords aren't wild about having
international federations or national Olympic committees doing the
picking and they're aghast at the idea of governments having a say.
``The independence we've had has allowed us to survive,'' insists
vice president Richard Pound of Canada. ``I voted against the
Moscow boycott in spite of the fact that my government wanted that
to happen. If I had been appointed by the Canadian government, I'd
have been toast in a nanosecond.'' . . . While camera-ready US
senators are pounding the IOC on Capitol Hill, there's a tiff
brewing at home between the USOC and the Salt Lake organizers that
could affect the athletes. With sponsors slow to sign on in the
wake of the payoff scandal and SLOC facing a $300 million budget
shortfall, new chief Mitt Romney has drawn up an $84 million chop
list that includes $5 million that was supposed to help fund
operations at the Utah Winter Sports Park where American bobbers,
lugers, and jumpers were counting on training for the 2002 Games.
The park, built with public money and run by a state authority, was
supposed to be turned over to SLOC last week but the transfer was
put on hold for 90 days while options are weighed. Meanwhile,
there's behind-the-scenes wrangling over whether SLOC, whose
original bid officials were responsible for the worst scandal in
Olympic history, should have to ante up toward the $9 million the
USOC is spending to restore its image and make structural changes.
``Everything can't be laid at Salt Lake's feet to solve,'' says
Romney.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect to see synchronized (i.e. precision) skating in the
Olympics until the International Skating Union figures it's ready
for prime time. ``They have to improve,'' says ISU president
Ottavio Cinquanta. ``It is not a criticism, it is an assessment.
They are not at the level the ISU expects, but they will be soon.''
Nor will the ISU stage figure and synchronized skating at the same
championships, as some have suggested. ``If you sell two products
once, you get money for one product,'' Cinquanta says. ``If you
sell them twice, you get more money.'' . . . Despite their
last-place group finish last year, the US men's ice hockey team got
a decent draw for next month's world championships in Norway.
They'll face the Japanese and Austrians before meeting the Czechs,
the defending bronze medalists. If the international federation
moves future events to February, it could be the last time the
Yanks have NHLers or collegians on the team . . . Dramatically
improved showing by the US curlers at the recent world
championships in New Brunswick. The women, eighth last year, won
the silver medal and the men moved up from sixth to fourth. The
Swedes took the women's crown for the third time in five years. The
Scots, who hadn't won the men's title since 1991, knocked off the
Canadians, who'd taken five of the last six . . . Though some folks
advised her to stick to skating and delay college, Michelle Kwan
says she'll take a full course load at UCLA this fall and still
prepare for the 2002 Olympics. ``I can't put skating on hold, nor
do I want to be a 26-year-old freshman,'' says Kwan, who'll be 19
in July. ``The key part is, when I'm skating I can't think about
school and when I'm in school I can't think about skating.'' . . .
Look for Todd Eldredge to bypass the Olympic-eligible circuit again
next winter, but return in 2001 to prepare for a possible third
Winter Games. ``Maybe I'll come back full force and do the whole
deal and be re-energized to make a run at it again,'' says the
five-time US champion. The X factor will be how high the technical
bar will have been raised by then (i.e. how many quadruple jumps
will be necessary). ``I would come back if I felt I could be
competitive and be able to do what I needed to do,'' says Eldredge,
who'll be 29 in 2001. ``If I didn't feel I could do that . . .''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No, Mark McGwire didn't get his Olympic baseball number (41)
retired for what he did at the 1984 Games in Los Angeles. McGwire,
who won a silver medal along with teammates such as Will Clark,
Barry Larkin, B.J. Surhoff, and Billy Swift, batted only .190 (4
for 21 in five games) and hit no homers . . . Terrific new book
(``Awaken the Olympian Within'') by 1976 swimming gold medalist
John Naber, who collected motivational stories from more than two
dozen Olympians ranging from Dan Jansen to Valerie Brisco-Hooks and
including local athletes Mike Eruzione, Eric Flaim, and Tim
Daggett.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
