<HEADLINE>
OAKLAWN ABUZZ WITH SUSPICION 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Was 30-1 shot Valhol hit with a ``buzzer'' on the way
to winning the $500,000 Arkansas Derby at Oaklawn Park April 10?
</P>
<P>
   The Arkansas State Racing Commission has begun an investigation,
with the probe centering on whether Valhol's rider, Billy Patin,
used an electrical device during the race. Valhol, who is trained
by Dallas Keen, had started only twice and had not won. He captured
the Arkansas Derby with ease, dominating the stretch run to score
by 4 1/2 lengths and return $68.
</P>
<P>
   Commission chairman Cecil Alexander confirmed that an Oaklawn
employee had found a battery on the track after the race, but he
declined to explain why Patin was the focus of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a most serious offense, so I'd rather not say anything
until the inquiry goes forward,'' said Alexander, who held a
meeting on the matter Thursday. ``If we did not feel there was
evidence, we would not be having this meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   To call Patin ``obscure,'' would be a compliment. Going into the
Arkansas Derby, he had nine wins from 120 mounts this year. A
regular on the Louisiana circuit, Patin was 34-673 last year. Patin
was scheduled to ride one horse at Lone Star Park in Texas Thursday
night, but he took off the mount.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has the right to redistribute the purse. If the
$300,000 Valhol won in the Arkansas Derby is taken away, it is
possible that he would not qualify to run in the Kentucky Derby at
Churchill Downs May 1. The Kentucky Derby is limited to 20
starters, based on earnings in graded stakes races, and Valhol had
only $38,400 in graded earnings entering the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly hope to have this resolved before the Kentucky
Derby because it is so important to racing,'' said Alexander. ``We
feel we are part of the Triple Crown and we are pleased to have
Kentucky Derby nominees go through Arkansas.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wondertross, second in the Florida Derby at Gulfstream March 13
but sixth in the Blue Grass at Keeneland April 10, will not run in
the Kentucky Derby. Wondertross was found to be suffering from
colic following the Blue Grass and was sent to the Hagyard Equine
Hospital to be treated. Trainer Nick Zito, who conditions the son
of Chief's Crown for co-owners William Condren and George
Steinbrenner, got Wondertross back to his Keeneland barn Thursday
but decided there was not enough time left to train him properly
for the Derby. ``Unless the colt is 100 percent, none of us want to
run him,'' said Condren. Zito indicated that the Preakness at
Pimlico May 15 remains a possibility . . . Desert Hero, winner of
the San Rafael Feb. 28 (in only the second start of his career) but
third in the Santa Anita Derby April 3, was not entered in Sunday's
Lexington Stakes at Keeneland, but instead will be trained up to
the Derby. ``I was thinking I wanted to get another prep into him,
but we decided it would be best to train up to the Derby like I was
thinking after the Santa Anita Derby,'' said Richard Mandella, who
conditions the son of Sea Hero for The Thoroughbred Corp. ``We
thought we could get him a little more experience with another prep
race, but we want him to go to the Kentucky Derby sound and
healthy.'' . . . Zito won't have Wondertross in the Derby, but he
has a decent chance with Stephen Got Even. The son of A.P. Indy is
being trained up to the Derby after winning the Gallery Furniture
at Turfway March 27, and he went 5 furlongs in 1:02 2/5 at
Churchill Thursday. ``I think he went really well,'' said assistant
trainer Frank Allen. ``The exercise rider said he did it really
easy, and that he liked the track. I know he came out of it real
good, knock on wood.'' The chances of Stephen Got Even were
enhanced considerably by the recent announcement that he will be
ridden by Chris McCarron in the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet, winner of the Kentucky Derby last year, will make
his second start of 1999 Sunday in the Texas Mile at Lone Star.
Real Quiet was held out of the Oaklawn Handicap because his
trainer, Bob Baffert, did not like the weights. ``Every time I've
been to Lone Star, they've given me money,'' said Mike Pegram, who
owns Real Quiet. ``I've run there three times, and hit the board
every time.'' Real Quiet will go from Lone Star, near Dallas, to
Baltimore for the Pimlico Special May 8. ``The Texas Mile will set
him up perfectly for the Pimlico Special,'' said Baffert. At
Pimlico, Real Quiet will face Santa Anita Handicap winner Free
House, currently the top-ranked thoroughbred in the country. Free
House, who is training at Hollywood Park, went 5 furlongs in 1:01
last Monday . . . Pegram also owns Silverbulletday, trained by
Baffert and considered the top 3-year-old filly in the nation. It
has not yet been decided whether she will run in the Kentucky Oaks
April 30 or the Derby. On Monday, she worked a half in :48 2/5 at
Churchill under Robbie Albarado, one of the leading riders in
Kentucky. ``I thought it was an awesome work,'' said Albarado.
``They wanted to go easy with her. She gets over the track great;
she loves it here.'' . . . One filly who will definitely run in the
Derby is Three Ring, who was dominant at Gulfstream this winter and
captured the Bonnie Miss Stakes. Owner Barry Schwartz confirmed
recently that the Oaks was out and the Derby was in for Three Ring,
who will be ridden by John Velazquez. ``John rode her in her last
two starts, both impressive victories, so naturally we are excited
about the decision,'' said Schwartz. Velazquez chose Three Ring
over Lemon Drop Kid, whom he rode to a fifth-place finish in the
Blue Grass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
