<SLUG> BC-AROUND-THEWORLD19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bill and Alicia's excellent adventure
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Shannon Donnelly
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Imagine a seven-year honeymoon in an
exceedingly cramped space.
</P>
<P>
   Too much togetherness for just about anybody, you say? Not Bill
and Alicia Blodgett.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm Beach couple spent seven years sailing around the world
on their 62-foot Pegaso, stopping at far-flung ports with names
such as Hiva Oa, Rangiroa, Vanuatu, Gove and Komodo.
</P>
<P>
   They survived storms, pirates, the temporary loss of their boat
(it drifted away while they were playing bridge aboard another
boat) and even a battering by an amorous whale.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't kill each other. They didn't get divorced. Alicia
has even written a book about their adventures, called ``Just the
Two Of Us,'' which started out as a sort of personal diary.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the trip, I'd keep notes and every six months or so
send a newsletter back to our friends,'' Alicia said. ``When we
came back, a lot of our friends said I should write a book. Finally
Bill urged me to do it, so I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill and Alicia's relationship has been unusual from the
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   He proposed the day after their first date. They married just a
few weeks later in Akron, Ohio, where Bill built a trucking
business that became so successful, he was able to retire at age
48. He wanted to realize his life's dream of sailing around the
world and Alicia, an inexperienced sailor, agreed to go.
</P>
<P>
   So, after saying goodbye to her children from her first marriage
_ her youngest was by then 19 and a college student _ she set off
with Bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried for months,'' Alicia said about leaving her youngest.
``I felt so guilty about leaving my baby. I'd try to hold it in,
and Bill would ask me what's wrong and I'd say 'nothing' and then
start to sob.'' But Alicia eventually got over her separation
trauma and turned her attention to the rigors of circumnavigation.
</P>
<P>
   It was, she says, the trip of a lifetime. Her favorite places
were New Zealand (where they ended up staying six months) and Fiji.
Both places have breathtaking topography, but Alicia said that
wasn't the attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the people. The Fijians and the New Zealanders are the
warmest, friendliest people you can imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   She is less enthusiastic about Egypt, where they sailed through
the Suez Canal into the Mediterranean. ``The Egyptian men treated
me very disrespectfully,'' she said, refusing to elaborate. ``I'll
never go there again.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip was full of adventures. A glandular whale off the
Australian coast mistook the hull of the Pegaso for a female and
bumped it repeatedly, lifting it completely out of the water on his
final pass. (Alicia slept through that.) Off Sri Lanka, Pegaso was
pressed into a search-and-rescue mission for another
around-the-world sailor, a woman who'd had enough of her husband
and jumped overboard five miles off the Sri Lankan coast. (She was
later rescued by a fishing boat.) A volcano erupted as they were
sailing away from Bali, leaving Bill, Alicia and Pegaso coated in
ash. Leaving Australia, they took fourth place in the
Darwin-to-Ambon race. In Fiji, Bill shared a sacred kava ceremony
with a tribal chief. (No women allowed.)
</P>
<P>
   The trip turned Alicia into an enthusiastic and accomplished
sailor. Still, seven years at sea was enough.
</P>
<P>
   Bill and Alicia still have Pegaso. It's docked at the Rybovich
Marina, where they ended their circumnavigation on Mothers' Day,
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the two years since we returned, we sailed it twice _ down
to Fort Lauderdale to get it painted blue, and then back from Fort
Lauderdale after it was painted blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, it's for sale. ``It'll always be a friend,'' Alicia said.
``But it's too big to take out for a day sail and too deep to take
to the Bahamas. It's a boat for someone who wants to sail around
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the Two Of Us'' is available at bookstores and
amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, Alicia used a philosopher's words to sum up the
adventure. ``We all die,'' she wrote. ``But only some of us live.''
</P>
<P>
   All proceeds from the sale of the book go to charity. ``I've
been so blessed,'' Alicia said. ``I couldn't possibly want another
thing. I am a walking, living Cinderella.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
