<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COTTAGE-HIDEAWAY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Historic `hideaway' renovated
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Robert Janjigian
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When writer-actress T.J. Fisher bought the
little house on historic Root Trail in Palm Beach, she planned to
spruce the place up on a two-month schedule. Her intent was to
clean the cottage up for use as a pied a terre, as she and her
husband were contemplating a move from their rented quarters on the
island to a farm property a good distance away. It was to be a
place to spend the night in town when a long drive wasn't
convenient.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen months later, the 600-square-foot, four-room cottage
was ready for occupancy, having undergone a complete restoration
and transformation beyond what Fisher originally expected _ or
budgeted. The couple scrapped their plans to establish a primary
residence outside Palm Beach proper. They purchased a more
substantial residence located _ conveniently _ just over the back
fence from the cottage.
</P>
<P>
   By building a simple gated walkway connecting the two
properties, the small cottage became an extraordinary guest house.
For Fisher, it's also a ``hideaway'' retreat, but one that
represents an authentic chapter in Palm Beach's architectural story
that's quite different from the usual Flagler-Mizner account.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher worked with Jane Day, the town's historical consultant,
to get the details right. Wooden sheathing replaced vinyl sliding.
Vinyl shutters were removed. A new shingled roof was put in place.
When contractors suggested she use lower-maintenance plastic and
composite elements, Fisher refused.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, it was a matter of stripping down to the bare essentials
before proceeding. Linoleum covered the floors. ``I knew there was
something lurking under there,'' said Fisher, who eventually had to
put in old-style new oak flooring, as well as a new foundation,
during the renovation process. Walls throughout the four-room house
are paneled in period-style wainscoting. To finish off the
interiors, Fisher sought out historic-style fixtures, including all
lighting elements, a replica of a vintage stove, and a clawfoot tub
and 1920s-style commode she found for the bathroom. ``I've avoided
modern-looking things as much as possible,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The bedroom at the rear of the house came with 36 electrical
outlets. ``The thought is that it was a telegraph office,'' Fisher
explained. In her preliminary research into the history of the
house, she said that the structure first showed up in town records
in 1917 as a print shop, though it may have been built circa 1910.
``There's a bit of mystery about it, but it definitely was one of
the first commercial buildings in Palm Beach,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In walking through the house, one cannot help but notice the
preponderance of African animal-theme works of art and
leopard-print fabrics in the decorating scheme of the cottage.
Fisher, who's made a name for herself locally by posting the reward
to find the killer of some of the island's feral feline population,
is, ironically, allergic to cats. And though she and her husband
plan to go on a tent safari someday, she's never been to Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Her affinity for the jungle look, which includes a couple of
animal paintings she created as a teen-ager and whose impact is
somewhat toned down by the warm wicker furniture and interior
treatments, is innate to her personality. She said: ``I find the
leopard prints primitive, but somewhat relaxing. They give the
rooms a more casual atmosphere, as well as a kind of island
flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
