<HEADER>
A3176 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DESIGNER-DEBT19-COX     04-18 2468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESIGNER-DEBT19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deal with designer dashes American dream
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Michele Gelormine
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Hoping for better opportunities and a
brighter future, Anna and Michael Veksler and their 6-year-old son,
Robert, left the former Soviet Union in 1978 to come to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   They came with $300 in their pockets and six suitcases full of
clothes. The Soviet government would allow them to take only $100
per person out of the country. All other valuables had to be left
behind. For Anna Veksler, the most painful loss was her books. The
Vekslers had a library full of classical literature.
</P>
<P>
   The family settled outside Washington, D.C., in Gaithersburg,
Md. Michael Veksler worked as a plumber and Anna Veksler worked in
accounting. Two years later _ after saving some money and borrowing
from relatives _ they bought a tiny restaurant and named it the
Village Cafe. In the early days, it was a mom-and-pop operation.
The couple worked 14-hour days to build up the business. Still
owned and run by the Vekslers, the restaurant has expanded and
serves breakfast, lunch and dinner with full bar service.
</P>
<P>
   Hard work paid off for the Ukrainian immigrants. In December
1997, the Vekslers saved enough money to buy a home in Palm Beach
that they planned to use for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   But Anna Veksler said her American Dream turned into a nightmare
shortly after she entered into a partnership with Worth Avenue
businessman Louis DiCarlo. The partnership has turned into a raging
dispute. Each is suing the other to dissolve the partnership.
</P>
<P>
   And Veksler filed a complaint earlier this month with the Palm
Beach Police, claiming DiCarlo threatened her by telephone.
According to the complaint, DiCarlo said to Veksler, ``This time
I'm going to strike, and if I strike, I strike hard. So watch your
back.''
</P>
<P>
   DiCarlo said he is outraged by her claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two things I want to protect,'' DiCarlo said. ``No.
1, my product, and No. 2 is the fact that I've never threatened
anyone. That is a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Anna Veksler, 54, and her 64-year-old husband wanted ultimately
to sell the restaurant and retire to Palm Beach. Anna Veksler said
she did not see herself staying home and toyed with the plan of
opening a small business.
</P>
<P>
   Her plan accelerated after a March 1998 trip to buy jeans in
DiCarlo's store.
</P>
<P>
   Veksler said DiCarlo, claiming to be ``a world-renowned
international designer,'' started a conversation with Veksler and
her friend as they shopped. DiCarlo told them of his plan to open
stores selling couture jeans and accessories throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a nice portfolio about his big projections _ millions _
and what would be done in Palm Beach,'' Veksler said.
</P>
<P>
   Promises of profit
</P>
<P>
   With promises of huge profits within a year, DiCarlo convinced
Veksler to form a partnership and open a store in a larger
location, Louis DiCarlo Couture Jeans. What Veksler did not know
was that DiCarlo had stopped paying rent for the space, according
to property manager Santo Lumia. In addition, landlord Burton
Handelsman evicted DiCarlo from his office at nearby for nonpayment
of rent. DiCarlo said he was going through bankruptcy and could not
pay the rent at the store. DiCarlo said he stopped paying
Handelsman because the landlord refused to fix the roof and the
leaky roof damaged his merchandise. Handelsman called DiCarlo's
allegations ``baloney. It was because of returned checks and
nonpayment.''
</P>
<P>
   Veksler said she had no idea DiCarlo had more than $1 million in
debts _ including more than $300,000 in income tax and $150,000 in
credit card debts _ and she did not know of a 1992 bank fraud
indictment by the federal government. Veksler said DiCarlo told her
of the bankruptcy but led her to believe he had paid back his
debts.
</P>
<P>
   DiCarlo filed for bankruptcy in February 1997. Craig Kelley, his
attorney, advised DiCarlo to convert his Chapter 11 bankruptcy to a
Chapter 7, which would have liquidated his debts. But DiCarlo chose
instead to voluntarily dismiss his bankruptcy claim, leaving him
still owing 100 percent of his debts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to pay my creditors,'' DiCarlo said. ``If I had gone
Chapter 7, I would have had a fresh start. I chose not to. I wanted
to pay my bills.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley said, ``He went right back into the hornet's nest by
doing that. He may have needed a fresh start, but as long as he is
carrying around the debt, he has a lot to overcome. Most of my
clients are dodging bullets, and they've got life jackets with
holes in them.''
</P>
<P>
   William Bader, owner of B&AMP;B Graphics in West Palm Beach, is one
of the creditors listed on DiCarlo's bankruptcy filing. DiCarlo
owes him $1,000 for printing T-shirts to give away at a 1996 Dreher
Park Zoo benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has not paid,'' Bader said. ``I keep getting letters from
his attorney saying he intends to pay his debts. Yeah, 'the check's
in the mail.'''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Halley is a Miami attorney representing the New
Jersey-based shipping company Panalpina Inc. in a lawsuit against
DiCarlo. According to court documents, DiCarlo failed to pay
$43,000 in shipping costs in 1997. The company obtained a judgment
for $35,000, and Halley said DiCarlo still owes about $25,000.
``He's making an effort to pay,'' Halley said.
</P>
<P>
   'Guilt by association'
</P>
<P>
   Another chapter in DiCarlo's past is his problems with the
federal government. In September 1992, DiCarlo pleaded guilty to
charges of bank fraud in federal court in Cleveland. He was
sentenced to three years of probation, four months of house arrest
and a $10,000 fine. The indictment came after a Cleveland-based
telemarketing scam was linked to DiCarlo's now-defunct Southcoast
Financial Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't steal any money from anybody,'' DiCarlo said. ``I
lost $1.2 million. It was guilt by association.''
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks of forming their business partnership, Veksler
said, she found herself in debt and questioning DiCarlo about the
purchases he was making with her money. At that point, Veksler
estimated, she had poured nearly $100,000 into the new store. She
mortgaged both houses and, eventually, maxed-out her credit cards.
Veksler said she has poured $300,000 into the business _ which
included meeting his demands for an elaborate $10,000 grand
opening, $10,000 in commercials and print advertising, and $90,000
in store remodeling. Veksler said she questioned his purchases and
would have preferred putting more money into inventory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would say, `If you don't pay for this, I won't open the
store and you'll lose money,''' Veksler said. ``I couldn't get out.
That's what he does. He's like a spider. He puts you in his web and
you can't get out.''
</P>
<P>
   DiCarlo said he brought all his furniture and $92,800 worth of
jeans and accessories from his previous stores to the business.
Veksler just laughed. DiCarlo did contribute the furniture, she
said, but the inventory that he brought is worth closer to $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   DiCarlo said Veksler knew of his money problems. His function
was to lend his name and fashion expertise to the business _ Louis
DiCarlo Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get a partner, it is to pay the bills, or else I would do
business by myself,'' he said. ``I make a wonderful product. The
fact that I have financial difficulties does not make me a bad
person.''
</P>
<P>
   A diverse reputation
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, DiCarlo has managed to drive expensive cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Bentley, Mercedes, Jaguar ... All my cars were blue,''
DiCarlo said.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Bruce, owner of the Donald Bruce gift store, remembered
DiCarlo always driving around in ``very fancy'' cars, including a
royal-blue, custom Jaguar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how they allow him back on Worth Avenue,'' Bruce
said. ``He's stiffed everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin Schwalberg, president of the Worth Avenue Association,
said he has never met DiCarlo, who is not a member of the
association. But Schwalberg has heard about him.
</P>
<P>
   ``His reputation has spread up and down the avenue,'' Schwalberg
said. ``A lot of people are aware of his relationship with
landlords. I've read in the newspaper and I've heard his reputation
is not up to snuff. It's something that property owners should be
careful of when leasing property to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees. John Baughman owns the clothing store
Dazzle, specializing in women's couture and designer clothes.
Baughman said he has been in the clothing business for 29 years and
has been at the Palm Beach location for 18 months. He has known
DiCarlo for three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a good product, and I know a lot of people who have his
products,'' Baughman said. ``He's a hell of a nice guy. I have not
heard complaints. I haven't had anybody say anything bad about
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in his business relationship with Veksler, DiCarlo went to
New York on business. Veksler said he called from New York and told
her to give her credit card number to a hotel to pay for his
lodging. He stayed three nights at $365 per night, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He calls me from the Essex (House) Hotel,'' Veksler said. ``I
gave my charge card number. He wanted to stay an extra week, but I
told him I couldn't pay for it. He always needs to have the best
and finds a fool to pay his expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   DiCarlo said he paid for his airplane ticket for the New York
trip and other business trips. Veksler still owes him more than
$5,000 in travel expenses, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Veksler said DiCarlo went on a buying spree for store inventory
at a Las Vegas fashion show with her money. When she tried to ask
DiCarlo about the purchases, Veksler said, he told her not to
interfere and it was not her business. Now, Veksler said, she has
oversized sweaters and $17,000 worth of red-and-green jeans she
cannot sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I'm the one with the knowledge,'' DiCarlo said.
``She comes from the restaurant business. I'm the one to do the
ordering.''
</P>
<P>
   According to their written business agreement, Veksler owns 70
percent and DiCarlo owns 30 percent of Louis DiCarlo Inc. Anna
Veksler is the president and only officer. According to the
agreement, DiCarlo was supposed to work in the store from 2 to 6
p.m. five days a week. Veksler agreed to pay as much as $30,000 to
renovate the store, and DiCarlo agreed to pay anything in addition
to that. But the agreement was later amended: Any construction
costs in excess of $30,000 would be deducted from DiCarlo's $60,000
initial investment, which was in inventory, not in cash. Veksler
said DiCarlo has not put any money into the business and has not
worked in the store at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``She threw me out of the store and changed the locks two days
after we opened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Veksler responded, ``I changed the locks because he started
giving away clothes to people he owed money to. It was impossible
to have him in the store.''
</P>
<P>
   Slater Construction Inc., the company that performed the
renovations, is suing both of them, alleging they ordered $45,000
in extras without paying. Veksler paid $43,000 on the original
renovation contract. She said DiCarlo ordered the $45,000 in extras
without her consent, and Slater Construction did not get her
written approval for the work. The following week, DiCarlo sued
Veksler to dissolve their partnership. She countersued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we could resolve the differences,'' Veksler said.
``I was not going to sue anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Since filing bankruptcy, DiCarlo has new debtors banging on his
door. Even though DiCarlo admits ordering advertising and other
business items, he said Veksler is responsible for paying the
bills.
</P>
<P>
   Robert C. Kirschner owns Passport Publications &AMP; Media,
publishers of Palm Beach Polo annual magazine. DiCarlo came to
Kirschner in August about taking out a full-page advertisement for
the 1999 polo season. Because the publisher had heard about
DiCarlo's reputation for nonpayment, Kirschner requested a $1,000
deposit on a $2,500 bill. DiCarlo agreed to pay the balance by
October, but as yet, the account remains unpaid, Kirschner said.
The bill has been turned over to Dunn and Bradstreet for
collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we had heard of his reputation, we don't write
people off, we treat everyone with the same amount of respect as an
individual,'' Kirschner said.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Carpenter of Dixie Printing in West Palm Beach is not so
charitable. She said she plans to sue DiCarlo in small claims
court. Carpenter has never met Veksler. The only person she dealt
with was DiCarlo, and as far as she is concerned, he is the one
responsible for the debt. DiCarlo owes her $1,500 for invitations,
letterhead and business cards for his November grand opening.
Because another client referred DiCarlo, Carpenter did not require
a deposit. Carpenter said DiCarlo ordered top-of-the-line paper
with gold-embossed emblems and needed a rush order. Her March bill
statement was returned and marked ``moved, left no address.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I bent over backward for him,'' she said. ``It was high-priced
items, and I had a lot of out-of-pocket costs.''
</P>
<P>
   DiCarlo said he goes back and forth between a New York office
and an office he still occupies in Palm Beach. He also has an
apartment there, for which he owes the town $725 in unpaid alarm
system fees.
</P>
<P>
   DiCarlo's nonpayment came before the town's Code Enforcement
Board on Thursday. Chief Code Compliance Officer Brian House said
the town has sent numerous bills to DiCarlo since April 1998. All
have been ignored, House said. If the bill is not paid within 15
days, House said, he will begin assessing daily fines. DiCarlo said
he did not receive any notices and did not know about the fines.
House said the town sent a notice of Thursday's meeting to DiCarlo
with return receipt requested.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of everything, DiCarlo said, he will open a new store
in Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Veksler wants to dissolve the partnership and get out from under
the Louis DiCarlo name. By the same token, DiCarlo said, he wants
an emergency court hearing to take his ``trademark'' away from
Veksler as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   DiCarlo said he has never had one complaint about his clothing
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the bankruptcy, the bad press and everything, I'm still
holding my head high,'' DiCarlo said. ``I keep fighting for what I
believe. If you have faith and a good product, you will survive.''
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal has split the Veksler family geographically. Michael
Veksler must stay in Maryland and run the restaurant; while Anna
Veksler works six days a week in the store because she cannot
afford to hire help. It is not exactly what she had in mind when
she entered the partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all the hard work in the restaurant business, I thought
this would be a breeze,'' Anna Veksler said. ``It turned out to be
a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
