<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANNING-DEPRESSION19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Psychologist chases depression into print
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Michele Gelormine
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Martha Manning was a clinical psychologist,
counseling patients by day and teetering on the brink of suicide at
night.
</P>
<P>
   Her preoccupation with suicide became so intense, there was only
one recourse _ Electroconvulsive Therapy, commonly known as
electric shock treatment. Although such treatment has come a long
way from its early days, Manning knew one of the greatest risks she
would face was memory loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to take a major risk,'' she said. ``It was very
frightening, because I had to commit myself to living and went into
the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning, author of ``Undercurrents,'' will speak at a luncheon
for the The Mental Health Association of Palm Beach County on
Thursday, April 29. ``Undercurrents'' is Manning's daily journal,
chronicling her slide into depression, her decision to undergo ECT
and her fight to regain herself afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   Manning, of Arlington, Va., will give a psychologist's view of
depression ``from the inside out.'' Manning said her family history
of depression, two difficult miscarriages, and her drive for
perfection and overachievement combined to push her deeper into
depression in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't outrun it and you can't fake it anymore,'' she said.
``Whatever my achievements were, they were not proof I wasn't
depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1990, she turned to a psychotherapist for help, while still
treating her own patients and teaching college classes in
psychology.
</P>
<P>
   ``My psychologist said, `You're depressed.' I said, `I'm just
stressed because I'm doing this, this and this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Her book documents her interaction with her husband, a
therapist, and her then-12-year-old daughter during the depths of
her disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having two therapists in the family is actually a liability,''
she said. ``You're so helpful in the office, only to come home and
be wretchedly inadequate. He thought he could pull me out of it if
he said the right things. It just shows the nature of the beast.
Depression is so insidious.''
</P>
<P>
   Medication and therapy failed to treat her depression. When
Manning thought she was literally one day away from suicide, she
opted to undergo ECT. She had six treatments over a two- to
three-week period, while under hospitalization. Manning said she
experienced ``a spotty memory'' for events that happened two to
three weeks before she went into the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Manning relapsed and had another series of ECT
treatments, this time as an outpatient. She lives on a combination
of anti-depressants, mood stabilizers and occasional psychotherapy
tune-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of being OK _ I'm OK,'' she said. ``As far as
overcoming depression, I don't feel like I've overcome it. I live
with it and have given it a room in the basement.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning kept a journal throughout her ordeal, but could not look
at her writing for a year after being discharged from the hospital.
When she picked up her journal again, Manning decided to write a
piece for The Networker, a magazine for mental health
professionals. The editor suggested that Manning write a book.
HarperCollins bought the rights and published ``Undercurrents'' in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Manning published her second book, ``Chasing Grace,''
about her experiences growing up in an Irish-Catholic family. After
her second book deal, Manning quit her psychology practice to
become a full-time writer and lecturer. She is working on a third
book, this one about mothers and daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Manning said that when she looks back on her suicidal days, she
cannot conjure up those feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, you are out of your mind, because it's someone
else's mind thinking those things.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
