<HEADER>
A3178 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN19-COX     04-18 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Elected leaders fail to see moral dimension of
crisis
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ I couldn't ignore the obscenity tattooed on his arm as
the young man behind me in the grocery line peered over my shoulder
at the newspaper I was reading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that a photo of the tornado damage?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I answered,'' it's Kosovar Albanians _ killed, maybe, by
our own NATO bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get that guy,'' he said, shaking his head over a
small grocery basket of beer and cigarettes. ``He's just killing
people because they're not like him, ain't he?''
</P>
<P>
   I nodded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about like me killing you because of them shoes you're
wearing,'' he said, pointing to my black sandals.
</P>
<P>
   We exchanged a few more comments about how America can't sit it
out in the face of such awful human rights violations. It seemed
clear my grocery line acquaintance couldn't come up with Slobodan
Milosevic's name _ but that was the least important thing to me.
</P>
<P>
   I thought later about how universal were the principles we
shared _ just strangers in the grocery store with seemingly little
in common.
</P>
<P>
   When I returned to the office, news releases on Kosovo from some
members of Georgia's congressional delegation were still on my
desk. How dissimilar were the pronouncements to the honest
reactions of an ordinary guy.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Mack Collins said we should support Milosevic's
Serbian opposition _ a silly statement since there is no viable
opposition. Rep. Saxby Chambliss said he's worried about an exit
strategy. U.S. Sen. Paul Coverdell applied the ``I told you so''
rationale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I voted against the resolution,'' he said in a press
statement, ``because I did not share the president's view that it
would slow Milosevic, but rather believed that Milosevic would use
the bombing to consolidate the Serbian people and accelerate the
removal of the Kosovars.''
</P>
<P>
   All of the Republicans in the Georgia delegation voted against
the resolution to support NATO action except U.S. Rep. John Linder,
who was justly critical of the president's lack of a long term
strategy, but still felt it necessary for the United States to
support the action.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's two House Democrats were split: U.S. Rep. John Lewis
supported the resolution; U.S. Rep. Cynthia McKinney opposed it.
Ironically, McKinney also showed the poor judgment to support Congo
president Laurent Kabila even after his troops carried out a
massacre and many atrocities against opponents.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Max Cleland, who lost three limbs in Vietnam,
supported the air campaign, but opposes ground troops. In a
telephone interview, Cleland said he meets regularly with fellow
veterans in the Senate in both parties. ``We test our reactions
with each other to make sure we're applying our personal
experiences constructively.'' Cleland said they were all aware
their war experiences could both cloud their judgment and give them
special insight. Cleland thinks NATO needs to establish clear
criteria for when human rights abuses, such as those in Kosovo,
demand intervention.
</P>
<P>
   What is curious is the failure of so many of our elected
representatives in Congress to see a moral dimension in the crisis.
Nobody, for example, has talked more about America's moral
responsibilities than U.S. Rep. Bob Barr. But he and others see no
connection between the moral principles this nation has always
stood for, and our role in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Thank heavens for average folks all over America who do.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
