<HEADER>
A3179 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN19-COX     04-18 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: One candidate's plight epitomizes sacrifices of many
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ People running for city offices commonly want to
do something about crime when they come to meet with the Trib
editorial board. In recent years I've have the urge to take one or
two of them up on that and have them arrested for impersonating
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   It would have made the streets safer.
</P>
<P>
   But hope springs eternal, and I feel pretty good this spring
having talked to several local candidates and incumbents in city
and school races. As a body, they are as informed, specific and
pure-of-heart as many I've encountered.
</P>
<P>
   I really shouldn't speak ill of those who are pretenders, who
know little about the issues, who have a petty grudge to settle or
only one issue grating on them. Even they serve a purpose. They
force the legitimate candidates and incumbents to go out and
demonstrate their legitimacy by talking to the people.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone should welcome the sight of the yard signs around town.
They are signs of life and commitment. As much as an editorial
writer might jump on elected officials _ they have their job, I
have mine _ you have to give credit to anyone who lays it on the
line, even when those making civic sacrifices end up getting
slapped in the face.
</P>
<P>
   Take Ruben Hinguanzo Sr. He bought 60 yard signs for his run for
mayor of Lacy-Lakeview. After placing the signs on yards around
town, someone pulled 50 or so out of the yards. Even the sign on
Hinguanzo's own yard was snatched.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not versed on where Hinguanzo stands on issues. I sure don't
want to be seen as boosting his candidacy since I haven't
interviewed Dennis Cogliati and Dennis Ard, who also are running
for the office. I remark on Hinguanzo's bad break only because it
epitomizes the sacrifices local candidates make.
</P>
<P>
   All three of the Lacy-Lakeview mayor candidates have devoted a
lot of time to their community. Cogliati is seeking his second term
as mayor. Hinguanzo has been mayor pro tem. Ard came on the board
as a representative of newly annexed Northcrest, where he was on
the council.
</P>
<P>
   It's encouraging to see three candidates with experience run for
such a seat.
</P>
<P>
   In Beverly Hills, voters will be adjusting to the first mayor's
race in 12 years without incumbent Betty Gibbs on the ballot. Gibbs
has plunged a lot of her life into the little city. Grief? Oh,
yeah, and this for one who's had personal grief, the death of a
daughter, to face. But she kept breathing deep and coming back. She
even found the time to head up Compassionate Friends, an
organization for people who've lost next of kin.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Hills voters have a choice of three candidates to
succeed Gibbs: councilman James Stolsworth, former concilman David
Gonzales and Henry Wright.
</P>
<P>
   What if they gave an election and nobody came? It won't happen
this year because we can still get people to make sacrifices like
these.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail:
jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
