<DOCNO> NYT19990418.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3186 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMDEX19-COX     04-18 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMDEX19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WILL MICROSOFT MAKE WINDOWS CODE PUBLIC?
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ As two computer pioneers offer rival views here
Monday, users will be watching to see if they are moving toward
adopting a common strategy for developing their products.
</P>
<P>
   Windows creator Bill Gates and Linux creator Linus Torvalds will
deliver separate keynote speeches at the spring Comdex/Windows
World conference. While both Windows and Linux are operating
systems, the neural engine of personal computers, Windows holds an
overwhelming edge in market share.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, 43, chairman and co-founder of Microsoft Corp., hopes to
build on his company's vast lead. His talk will focus on Windows
2000, a next-generation industrial-strength operating system, which
Microsoft plans to ship in October.
</P>
<P>
   The Finnish-born Torvalds, 29, wrote the basic Linux code eight
years ago while a student at Helsinki University. He is a prime
advocate of ``open source'' programming, an approach under which
tens of thousands of people around the world collaborate to improve
Linux _ itself a flavor of UNIX, an operating system widely used on
mainframe computers.
</P>
<P>
   At a computer conclave in Houston last week, Gates called the
impact of Linux ``fairly limited,'' playing down its commercial
potential to average consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Gates's appearance here comes at a time when Microsoft finds
itself under a strong attack in federal court by the Justice
Department and 19 states for allegedly seeking to use its Windows
muscle power to dominate cyberspace and software markets.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to settle the court case in Washington in mid-trial have
sparked an internal debate at Microsoft's Redmond, Wash.,
headquarters on whether the software giant should adopt a
Linux-style open source model for Windows. Microsoft could find
that to be a necessary price for the government to drop its illegal
monopoly charges.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Steve Ballmer, Gates's second in command,
said Microsoft ``is thinking with great interest'' about opening
Windows' source code. Ballmer, the company's president, said
Microsoft was ``trying to understand this whole notion of open
source.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Raikes, Microsoft's group vice president of sales and
support, noted that the firm already licenses its Windows source
code at no charge to some university research labs, such as the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   While Raikes suggested that the program could be expanded, he
added: ``I don't think you'd ever see us do the same thing as
Linux, but I do think you'll find us looking at some aspects.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Jim Allchin, senior vice president of Microsoft's
business and enterprise division and consumer Windows division,
said he was not all sure whether Microsoft should respond to the
growing open-source wave. While ``more eyes on the (Windows) code
is actually a good thing, fragmentation of the code is its death,''
he argued.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Microsoft insiders believe, this is an issue that
Gates must decide.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape Communications Corp., Microsoft's rival in the Internet
browser wars, has struggled with its own open source project,
dubbed Mozilla. Although some 100 Netscape software engineers are
committed to the Mozilla effort, it has yet to dent usage of
Microsoft's Internet Explorer browser, which was recently upgraded
to work more seamlessly with music, video and animation.
</P>
<P>
   Torvalds, who claims he does not profit from his creation, said:
``I'd be very interested to talk to Bill Gates to see what he's
like. But we don't have that much in common. First and foremost,
he's a businessman.''
</P>
<P>
   The business aspects of the four-day Comdex meeting, which is
expected to draw a record 80,000 attendees, clearly will dominate
the scene here.
</P>
<P>
   According to Microsoft officials, more than 20 hardware
companies _ including Compaq, Data General, Dell, Hewlett-Packard,
IBM, Micron, and Unisys _ will soon launch programs to sell
personal computers, notebooks, and servers carrying the latest
``beta,'' or test, release of Windows 2000. Some of them will also
provide technical support services when the ``Beta 3'' version
ships at the end of April, Microsoft officials noted.
</P>
<P>
   The company will also launch a Web site devoted to information
about the new release and provide free phone support _ the first
time it has done so for a beta product, said Jonathan Perera, lead
product manager for Windows 2000 server applications.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
