   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-BILLBOARDS (Undated) _ By midnight on Thursday, every
cigarette billboard in the nation must come down as part of the
$206-billion lawsuit settlement agreement reached last year between
tobacco producrs and 46 states. For anti-smoking groups, the end
of the cigarette billboard stands as a major victory, a choking-off
of an advertising medium that tobacco producers dominated for
nearly 20 years. But it also marks another change, one in this
country's visual landscape. For decades, outdoor tobacco signs were
the canvas used by some of the advertising industry's most-talented
designers and photographers. And the work they produced, ranging
from the quaint to the ingenious to the garish, have served not
only as urban meeting places and reference points for lost
motorists but also as cultural touchstones. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   PARKINSON-EXPERIMENT (Washington) _ In the 14 years since he
discovered he has Parkinson's disease, Steve Ashworth has slowly
lost control of his muscles. Two years ago, with simple tasks like
brushing his teeth becoming next to impossible, he eagerly signed
up for a chance to stave off his slide into immobility: the first
government-financed study of brain cell transplants using tissue
from aborted fetuses. But the use of fetal cells was not all that
made the experiment controversial. Like all 40 people who enrolled,
Ashworth, a 53-year-old labor negotiator for General Motors, would
have to undergo brain surgery: four tiny holes drilled into the
skull through the wrinkle lines above his eyebrows. Yet only half
the participants would get the tissue. The other half would get
nothing. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   AGRI-BIOTECH (Lubbock, Texas) _ A look at the controversy over
new technology that would make the seed produced by crops sterile
and therefore unusable the following year. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   DNA-FREEDOM (Ada, Okla.) _ A talk with the two men who were
freed from prison after more than a decade when DNA evidence showed
that they could not have committed the murder they had been
convicted of.
</P>
<P>
   ACADEMIA-LABOR (New Haven, Conn.) _ Yale and Harvard have long
competed over which has the best students, best football team and
best law school, but this weekend they engaged in a different sort
of competition, vying to attract people to conferences aimed at
building academia's bonds with the labor movement. By Steven
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-FIRES (Dateline TK) _ An update on the wildfire situation in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-DISABILITIES (Washington) _ The Supreme Court begins an
unusually wide ranging review of the Americans With Disabilities
Act with four cases over the next 10 days. The first case pits a
group of states against the federal government over the question of
whether the law entitles people with severe disabilities to
treatment in community settings rather than in big state
institutions. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
