<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3242 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMOUS-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     04-18 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMOUS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FAMOUS AFTER DEATH': THIN, LOVED, FAMOUS: HOW NICE IT WOULD BE
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his first two novels, ``The Plagiarist'' and ``The
Partisan,'' Benjamin Cheever made touching comedies out of his
struggle to escape the shadow of his famous father, the writer John
Cheever. In his funny new book, ``Famous After Death,'' his alter
ego, Noel (No) Hammersmith, seems to be mostly out from under the
weight of his father but finding the landscape of liberty
remarkably bleak.
</P>
<P>
   Far into a psychotherapy intended to cure a condition of memory
lapses Noel has been suffering, his doctor, Cleo Santarelli, learns
that his parents had been killed in a bombing incident in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could you hide this?'' she asks. ``The trauma might have
led directly to your memory lapses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're wrong,'' says Noel. ``I'm very very sorry that my
parents died. But I don't actually think it's all that
significant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is important then?'' Santarelli asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to find a girlfriend, get down to my ideal weight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to get right to the core of your despair,'' the
therapist asks, ``what would you say it was about?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about weighing too much. It's also about powerlessness.
It's catching a glimpse of this pitiful monster in the mirror.
Having that red ring around my waist when I undress at night. ...
I'm in a trap, with one way out: thinness. You know what fatness
says? It says I'm self-indulgent, it says I'm weak. It says I'm
sexually ambiguous. Make me thin, or make me famous.''
</P>
<P>
   Noel's solution to his fatness is to undertake the program
suggested by one of the diet books he has edited for the publisher
he works for, Acropolis Inc. This prescribes one butterscotch
sundae a day, the rationale of which Noel describes as follows:
``We eat to satisfy the inner child. The ice cream fills the mouth,
in the way a mother's breast might do. The burned or scotched
butter represents the disappointments of adult life. That's the
theory.''
</P>
<P>
   As for fame, Noel is outraged by the way Americans laud
scoundrels for achieving notoriety. ``Kids learn as much about Lee
Harvey Oswald as they do about George Washington,'' he reflects.
``All you need, all you really need for immortality nowadays is a
cold eye and a mail-order rifle.''
</P>
<P>
   Or all you need is death. ``Look at Emily Dickinson,'' he writes
a friend. ``Because she wouldn't stop for death, he kindly stopped
for her. Nobody else ever did. Alive she couldn't get arrested.
Dead she's the belle of Amherst.''
</P>
<P>
   Noel appears to have arrived at fame by the route of notoriety.
At the start of ``Famous After Death,'' he is locked up in prison,
being interviewed by Barbara Walters for presumably having killed
people over the issue of ``quality control.'' As the subsequent
flashback reveals through Noel's letters and journal entries, his
life has been a series of disappointments and betrayals. Not only
do women let him down, but also manufactured products keep failing
him. In retaliation, he may possibly have become ``the Wordsworth
Bomber,'' a mysterious figure who has killed some 34 people while
blowing up commercial establishments like Crazy Eddie's and Brooks
Brothers. He is called the Wordsworth Bomber because one of his
mail bombs arrived with a fragment of a Wordsworth poem, perhaps
``Getting and spending we lay waste our powers,'' or so one guesses
from its being quoted in another context.
</P>
<P>
   Now the satirical spirit at work here is not exactly a
light-handed one. That even notoriety counts for so much in
contemporary America has been said many times before, and not
always as obviously as Cheever has done. Countless lampoons of the
publishing industry have argued that the woods are full of editors
who consider books to be only marginally less ephemeral than potato
chips, as Cheever somewhat tiresomely puts it.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the laboriousness of the novel's ending is not really
justified by its point, which simply isn't sharp enough to do any
serious damage.
</P>
<P>
   All the same, from line to line ``Famous After Death'' offers
considerable amusement. Cheever is particularly good at detailing
the tiny inconveniences that complicate life in a ``getting and
spending'' society, like the tendency of the scissors on Swiss Army
knives not to work because ``the small band of metal used to make
the blades pop apart after you've cut something has snapped off.''
</P>
<P>
   For Noel the world just isn't what it used to be. As he writes
to a distributor of Swiss Army knives: ``When my father,'' an
Episcopalian priest, ``was a young man, and growing up outside of
Boston, he once bought a box of Cracker Jacks in which there was no
prize. He wrote a letter to the president of the Cracker Jacks
company, and got back an apology in return, a note so finely worded
that it was framed, and hung on the wall behind his desk in the
rectory. With the note the president of the company _ not a public
relations officer, but the president himself _ had enclosed an
entire box of prizes, one of every prize they made. The best of
these was a tiny pair of metal scissors so sharp that they actually
cut through paper.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just that the gently comic disappointment captured here
doesn't justify the bitterness of the plot's satire. The two forms
of humor don't quite blend, and this failure mars ``Famous After
Death.'' Not fatally but enough to make you flinch.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FAMOUS AFTER DEATH'
</P>
<P>
   By Benjamin Cheever
</P>
<P>
   211 pages. Crown Publishers. $23.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
