<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: JAZZ IN NEW ORLEANS; A BIRTHDAY PARTY FOR
SHAKESPEARE IN LONDON; A FESTIVAL OF NEW PLAYS IN NEW YORK; A
SLOVENIAN PIANIST GOES SOLO AT ALICE TULLY HALL   
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., R.I., Great Britain)   By   LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   All that jazz looks as if it will be converging all at once on
New Orleans, where the 30th annual New Orleans Jazz and Heritage
Festival opens on Friday with a first-day lineup that includes
Willie Nelson, Dave Brubeck, Santana, George Wein and the Newport
All-stars, Nelson Riddle's salute to Frank Sinatra and more.
Through May 2, jazz will be pouring off a dozen stages
simultaneously from about 11 a.m. to 7 p.m. on the Fairgrounds
Racecourse while bands strut through the crowds. Around the city,
evening concerts abound, principally at the Municipal Auditorium.
Information: (504) 522-4786 or www.nojazzfest.com.
</P>
<P>
   Virtues Trumpeted
</P>
<P>
   For those in love with Shakespeare after seeing ``Shakespeare in
Love,'' perhaps the place to be this weekend is London, where the
playwright's 435th birthday on Friday will be celebrated. One of
the most ambitious observances is Shakespeare Day at the British
Library on Saturday. There will be a reading of all 154 sonnets by
students, scholars and lovers of poetry, an Elizabethan menu (thick
pea pottage, braised chicken with gooseberries, poached herring, et
al.) in the cafe and restaurant and ``Music of Shakespeare's Time''
performed on instruments like the sackbut, shawm and dulcian.
Lectures on ``Shakespeare the Man'' and ``Romantic Shakespeare''
also beckon, and all ends well with a showing at 5 p.m. of the
Oscar-winning ``Shakespeare in Love.'' Information:
011-44-1-71-412-7332.
</P>
<P>
   In the Beginning
</P>
<P>
   The creations of Tony Kushner, Suzan Lori-Parks, Robert O'Hara
and others share the spotlight in ``New Work Now,'' the sixth
annual festival of new play readings, which begins at 7 Monday
night at the Anspacher Theater of the Joseph Papp Public Theater.
The play Monday night is Jose Rivera's ``References to Salvador
Dali Make Me Hot,'' a poetic drama that pays homage both to Dali
and Federico Garcia Lorca. The series ends on May 3 with a reading
of Kushner's ``Caroline, or Change,'' which explores personal and
political engagement through two families, one black, one Jewish,
in Louisiana at the time of President Kennedy's assassination.
Information: (212) 260-2400.
</P>
<P>
   Hello Again
</P>
<P>
   Her recital at Carnegie Hall in 1954 when she was 14 earned the
Slovenian pianist Dubravka Tomsic the accolade ``amazing.'' Monday
night, still greatly admired as an exemplar of the golden age of
pianism, she will play her first New York solo recital in 45 years
at Alice Tully Hall. Ms. Tomsic (pronounced TOM-shitch), a protege
of Artur Rubinstein who was rediscovered by American audiences in
1989 at the Newport Music Festival, will perform works by
Beethoven, Debussy, and Brahms. Information: (212) 875-5050.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
