<HEADER>
A3246 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-ARNETT-990(2TAKES     04-18 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-ARNETT-990(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETER ARNETT IS MISSING IN ACTION AT CNN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When bombs fell on Baghdad in 1991, he was there, live,
describing the action in what became the defining achievement for
CNN; but when the bombs began falling on Belgrade last month, Peter
Arnett, the most recognizable correspondent in the history of the
all-news network, was nowhere to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is he likely to be seen again on CNN. The network is
planning to exercise an exit clause in Arnett's contract in July,
Arnett said, effectively dismissing him with two years left on his
five-year agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Two CNN executives, speaking on the condition of anonymity, also
said Arnett's contract would be terminated. Other CNN executives
refused to discuss any aspect of Arnett's status. Tom Johnson, the
chairman and chief executive of CNN, did not return phone calls
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett, who has hired a lawyer to try to work out a settlement,
said: ``I don't want to fight with CNN. I've worked there for 18
years. I love the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   The love is apparently no longer mutual. The decision to
terminate Arnett's contract ends the CNN career of probably the
best-known foreign correspondent in recent television history. The
move comes nine months after Arnett played a prominent role in what
became an embarrassing debacle for CNN, when a much publicized
investigative report for the inaugural edition of CNN's prime-time
news magazine ``CNN Newsstand,'' blew up in the network's face.
</P>
<P>
   The report, entitled ``Tailwind,'' charged that a U.S. military
operation in the Vietnam War included the use of the lethal nerve
gas sarin.
</P>
<P>
   After an internal examination, CNN declared the conclusions of
the report to be unsupported by the evidence. The network issued a
public retraction and apology. Arnett was the correspondent for the
report. He was also listed as the co-author of an accompanying
magazine article that ran in Time.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the retraction, CNN dismissed both producers who
put the report together, Jack Smith and April Oliver. Pam Hill, the
senior executive producer in charge of ``Newsstand,'' resigned.
Even Johnson offered to resign, an offer that was refused by Gerald
M. Levin, the chairman of CNN's parent company, Time Warner, and
Ted Turner, the founder of CNN, who is now vice chairman of Time
Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett, who won a Pulitzer Prize in 1966 as a correspondent for
The Associated Press for his Vietnam coverage, came under the gun
for his role in the Tailwind affair. He argued with his CNN bosses
that he should not be let go because he had made minimal
contributions, conducting only three interviews and making no
decisions about the validity of the accusations. He received only a
reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   But the situation left Arnett in limbo at CNN. Two CNN
co-workers said that Eason Jordan, the president of global news
gathering for CNN, was so angry with Arnett after the Tailwind
incident that he felt he could not use him any more. Jordan was one
of the CNN executives who declined to return phone calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Since July, Arnett has been seen on CNN only once. That was in
December, when he filed a report from Algeria. Even then, CNN used
only one of five reports he filed from that country, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett said in a telephone interview that he had asked to cover
the war in Yugoslavia, ``but CNN has not seen fit to send me
there.''
</P>
<P>
   On at least two occasions recently, CNN executives, when asked
why Arnett was not a presence in Yugoslavia, said the reason was
that Arnett's specialty was the Mideast, and thus he was not
especially qualified to cover the war in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   But Arnett pointed out that he covered the Serbian side of the
war in Bosnia in 1994, that he had been in the city of Pale when it
was bombed in 1995 and that he had covered demonstrations in
Belgrade in December 1996 and January 1997. ``I got to know many of
the players there,'' Arnett said. ``I had great access to that side
of this conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN declined to explain why it had first tried to explain
Arnett's absence from Kosovo by saying his expertise was in the
Middle East. When asked for confirmation that Arnett was being let
go in July, a spokeswoman, Maggie Simpson, said, ``We have no
comment.'' When asked why Arnett had not been sent to cover the war
in Yugoslavia, she said, ``I don't know.'' When asked when Arnett
last appeared on the air, she said, ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tailwind report appeared on June 7, and CNN's retraction
came on July 2. Arnett defended himself in subsequent examinations
of what happened in the Tailwind story by saying that he had been
an insignificant contributor. In one statement, he said he had
added ``not one comma'' to the report.
</P>
<P>
   That comment received widespread criticism both inside and
outside CNN, especially from other reporters who did not want to be
associated with any implication that correspondents only serve as
mouthpieces for reports controlled by news producers. Christiane
Amanpour, CNN's chief international correspondent _ and currently
its star reporter in its war coverage from Yugoslavia _ scathingly
criticized Arnett, saying, ``I object to the new image of
correspondent as nincompoop.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of Arnett's associates at CNN said his job had been
saved only by the intervention of Turner, who asked that Arnett be
retained out of loyalty to his long service to CNN. Indeed, CNN had
found Arnett a highly useful spokesman for the network, dispatching
him to dozens of places around the world in the years after Iraq to
give speeches and lobby for the establishment of CNN bureaus.
Arnett said he had made ``thousands of appearances'' on CNN's
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett first said that the word that CNN was seeking to end his
contract ``caught me completely by surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I had no hint that it was coming. If they're going
to fire me, they should let me know why.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But he later acknowledged that he was virtually cut off from CNN
since July. ``They gave me a beeper, and they said, `Sit by the
beeper.' But it hasn't beeped.''
</P>
<P>
   He repeated that he had specifically asked to cover the war,
``but I've been given no clear reason why I can't cover Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The connection to his role in Tailwind might seem to be obvious,
given how his assignments dried up. But Arnett said, ``It can't be
Tailwind.'' He cited statements made by Johnson after the
dismissals in July that CNN would take no further action as a
result of its examination of the Tailwind report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that has been written since has confirmed that my
role was minimal,'' Arnett said. ``I know they were concerned about
Tailwind. I'm embarrassed by it. But I did argue the point that I
did not feel I should be fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the argument has shifted. Arnett said he wanted to know why
CNN was trying to sever his contract, and refusing to make his
status clear to those who asked about it. ``My reputation is taking
a heavy beating, because I'm not on the air at all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett said he had asked his lawyer to try to find some more
amicable way to end his association with CNN. ``If they want to
make an arrangement with me, fine,'' he said. ``My five-year
contract is up in July 2001. I don't think a journalist with my
reputation should be in limbo like this. CNN is an adult company.
They're making a lot of money. They're part of Time Warner.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-99 1651EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
