<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990418.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3248 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NEWS-CORRESPONDENT     04-18 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEWS-CORRESPONDENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS BARRIERS ERODE, REPORTERS CONTRIBUTE TO SEVERAL SHOWS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an earlier time of broadcast news, marked by far-flung
correspondents and high-roller budgets, individual news programs
fought for turf, for talent and for money. A correspondent for the
NBC ``Nightly News'' would not be assigned to do a report for, say,
a news magazine, nor would a CBS News domestic reporter be sent to
cover a war.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, no one would have dreamed of asking Diane
Sawyer to combine her prestigious work as a prime-time news
magazine anchor on ABC's ``20/20'' with a five-day-a-week stint in
the folksy world of breakfast-show television. But there she is
now, the co-anchor of ``Good Morning America'' with Charles Gibson
_ and, by all accounts, happy to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The hierarchies and fiefs of television news are breaking down a
bit, driven by the networks' needs to cut costs and by new
management philosophies that see a need for broadcast news reports
to distinguish themselves from the reporting found on 24-hour cable
news networks, radio and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, correspondents are contributing reports to several
programs, not just the one to which they are assigned. Programs are
becoming less territorial about stories and staff.
</P>
<P>
   The war in Yugoslavia is providing many examples.
</P>
<P>
   ABC News assembled a team to report on the Kosovar refugees,
including a senior foreign correspondent from London (Jim Wooten),
a Los Angeles-based domestic reporter (Jane Clayson), a ``20/20''
correspondent (John Quinones) and Gibson, co-anchor of ``Good
Morning America.'' The result was an hour report for ``20/20,'' the
prime-time news magazine, and reports for the Walt Disney Co.-owned
network's other programs.
</P>
<P>
   The NBC foreign correspondents Ron Allen and Jim Maceda, who
have been in Yugoslavia since the war began, have reported for
``Nightly News,'' the morning program ``Today,'' the prime-time
magazine ``Dateline,'' the CNBC business-news cable network and the
MSNBC all-news cable network and World Wide Web site, which are
jointly owned by NBC's parent, the General Electric Co., and the
Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Thalia Assuras, a reporter for ``CBS This Morning,'' that
network's breakfast-hour news program, began reporting from Tirana,
Albania, last week on the refugee crisis, and filed a report for
the ``CBS Evening News'' as well.
</P>
<P>
   Even Dan Rather, the ``Evening News'' anchor who traveled to
Belgrade last week, has contributed reports since then to his own
6:30 ``Evening News,'' ``CBS This Morning,'' the magazine program
``48 Hours'' and the CBS News Web site as well as six to eight
reports daily for the CBS Radio network.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's economic world,'' said Andrew Heyward, president of
CBS News, ``we've made it very clear to our correspondents that,
with the possible exception of prime-time correspondents, we're
asking all our hard news correspondents to contribute to all of our
broadcasts and to radio.''
</P>
<P>
   Although economics may have kicked off this trend, other reasons
played a role.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not just 24-hour cable news, but Internet news, local
news, radio news, pager news and everything else,'' said David
Westin, president of ABC News. ``In that world, giving people raw
data is no longer a way of competing. We need to focus on
explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   That means pooling the fact-gathering resources of ABC News with
the expertise of producers and correspondents, he said, then
directing the results to whichever programs may best serve viewers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Quinones of ``20/20'' and Chris Bury, one of two
``Nightline'' correspondents, are reporting separate pieces for
``World News Tonight,'' something that would have been unthinkable
a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working toward a situation where ABC News reports the
news, rather than an individual program reports the news,'' Westin
said. ``Does it have cost effects? Of course. But sometimes
economic pressures cause us to do what we should be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC News, for example, decided the audience for the early
morning ``Today'' show was news-savvy enough that the network's two
White House correspondents, David Bloom and Claire Shipman, were
divided equally between that program and the ``NBC Nightly News.''
They alternate weeks of reporting for each.
</P>
<P>
   NBC News paved the way in this new multitasking world three
years ago with the creation of the MSNBC cable network and Web
site. Since then, NBC News correspondents and producers have
contributed to all programs on all those outlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viewers benefit from this in getting Tom Brokaw or Brian
Williams on the little cable network,'' said Andrew Kohut, director
of the Pew Research Center for People and the Press in Washington.
``It's good when the resources of the premier news shows can be
brought to bear on smaller shows or on cable.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Kohut cautioned, ``working journalists aren't as sanguine
about this as the executives are,'' partly because some feel they
are being stretched too thin.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence K. Grossman, a former president of NBC News who is now
a media consultant and a columnist for the Columbia Journalism
Review, said there are fewer specialists in network news, which
``isn't the end of the world, but it has changed what's reported.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Basic news gathering is farmed out to news agencies, stringers
and freelancers,'' he said, a major event like the war in
Yugoslavia being an exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a major story develops, the networks will parachute in one
of their mainstream correspondents from a bureau,'' who will do a
professional but less expert job, he contended.
</P>
<P>
   But such methods do save money. Last year all three broadcast
news divisions had to shrink their costs.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS Corporation gave pink slips to about 120 people in the
fall, about 7 percent of the CBS News staff, though none of those
dismissed were correspondents. ABC News and NBC News made similar
reductions, without setting percentage quotas or publicizing
precise layoff figures.
</P>
<P>
   ABC News achieved some savings last year by not renewing
contracts of five correspondents, though it has also hired two new
correspondents this year.
</P>
<P>
   For example, ABC News told George Strait, a longtime medical
correspondent for ``World News Tonight,'' that his contract would
not be renewed. In part, this was because Dr. Tim Johnson and Dr.
Nancy Snyderman were contributing reports to all programs, enough
that news executives felt that beat was adequately covered without
Strait.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, ABC News did not renew the contract of Tim O'Brien,
who has covered the Supreme Court for ``World News Tonight'' for 22
years, choosing to rely on its recently formed law and justice
unit, whose correspondents are John Miller and Terry Moran,
formerly of Court TV.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-99 1656EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
