<DOCNO> NYT19990418.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3249 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-18 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL'S CHAIRMAN TELLS NEWSPAPER PUBLISHERS TO SUPPLY MORE INSIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Me., Md., Okla., Wis., Colo., Ala., Wash.)  (nk) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The gloom-and-doom predictions were nothing new
to the members of the American Society of Newspapers Editors, but
there was still something arresting about hearing the chairman of
the Intel Corp. saying that the newspaper business had three years
to live. Their eyes may have rolled in ``not-this-again'' circles
when Andrew S. Grove offered his jeremiad, but editors do know a
good sound bite when they hear one.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are where Intel was three years before the roof fell in on
us,'' said Grove, referring to his company's near-death experience
in the late 1980s, when its original product, memory chips, became
unprofitable. A switch to microprocessors later propelled Intel to
the top ranks of American industry. As far as newspapers are
concerned, ``to use today's Internet terminology, you get my
eyeballs with the news coverage and you sell me commercials, sell
me advertising,'' Grove said. ``You're under attack at both ends.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider the way Grove gets his news. He told his audience on
Wednesday that he gets both breaking news from the Reuters news
service and news of the high-technology industry online. And in the
evening, he looks at the paper versions of The San Jose Mercury and
The Wall Street Journal, seeking background and interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody's already stolen a third to a half of my eyeball time
away from you,'' Grove said.
</P>
<P>
   His solution: write and edit newspapers that play to the
medium's competitive advantage, its ability to bring perspective to
the tumbling cascade of news events. And convince publishers that
the end is nigh, so that they invest in expensive and unique news
gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Grove knew his audience. The group might have already heard that
the Internet marauders were going to plunder newspapers'
high-margin classifieds and to carry off the audience. But telling
editors their publishers need to spend more on news gathering is
not a bad gambit.
</P>
<P>
   What Grove did not mention, however, was one particular
investment that the editors of the smallest of the country's 1,500
newspapers are pining for: an increase in reporters' salaries,
which now start at $16,000 in some small communities.
</P>
<P>
   Small newspapers are having trouble finding reporters and
editors.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it is the lure of online journalism, as Terri Fleming,
the editor of The Gazette of Colorado Springs (circulation 99,500)
believes, or simply the need to find a better salary to meet
college-loan payments, as Rex Rhoades, of The Sun Journal in
Lewiston, Me., believes, more editors of papers with circulations
of 50,000 or less are scrambling to find anyone to cover the school
committee and the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Edward D. Casey, editor of The Capital in Annapolis, Md.,
circulation 46,750, has in the last nine months paid $1,000 signing
bonuses to two new reporters. ``With graduation coming up, we would
normally have 40 resumes in by this time,'' he said. ``We probably
have five, maybe 10.''
</P>
<P>
   The Capital's starting salary, just raised to $25,000, is $4,000
more than that of The Sun Journal in Lewiston. With a circulation
of 38,500, ``we have two openings we can't fill,'' said Rhoades,
the paper's editor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time someone leaves, it's a crisis,'' said Don
Huebscher, of The Leader Telegraph of Eau Claire, Wis., circulation
29,700. ``We used to get 70 or 80 people for each job opening. Now
we get two or three.''
</P>
<P>
   Without surveys, there are only anecdotes, whose larger message
is disputed by other editors. Editors of some larger papers, like
Joe Worley of The Tulsa World, circulation about 160,000, say they
have no problem _ the journalism departments at Oklahoma State and
the University of Oklahoma fill his needs.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, H. Brandt Ayers, the publisher of The Anniston Star in
northern Alabama, circulation 27,500, said he had 100 applicants
just for summer internships.
</P>
<P>
   But if many neophytes are going directly to larger markets, the
result is having more untried journalists making their inevitable
mistakes before a larger audience. That's something that should
scare the big papers, said Rick L. Doyle, editor of The Walla Walla
Union-Bulletin, a small newspaper in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   When Grove spoke, he made the crowd-pleasing exhortation that
newspapers' future required investment now. ``From a publisher's
standpoint, there's going to be a huge push and pull,'' he said,
``This requires more money at a time when margins are going to be
under attack.''
</P>
<P>
   In small newspapers, with a small advertising base, there may be
very little to invest. But if something is not done to make young
people aspire to be reporters, the editors, too, will have to look
for another line of work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
