   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are considering
for Page 1, Monday, April 19. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Sam Weiss; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TARGETS (Washington) _ As part of NATO's strategy, the
bombing in Yugoslavia is targeting Slobodan Milosevic's economic
assets. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ Developments concerning NATO.
By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-POLITICS (New Delhi) _ A day after the
Hindu-nationalist-led government fell, leaders of the opposition
Congress Party began trying to patch together a new coalition to
govern the nation of 980 million people. By Celia S. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-BILLBOARDS (Undated) _ By midnight on Thursday, every
cigarette billboard in the nation must come down as part of the
$206-billion lawsuit settlement agreement reached last year between
tobacco producers and 46 states. For anti-smoking groups, the end
of the cigarette billboard stands as a major victory, a choking-off
of an advertising medium that tobacco producers dominated for
nearly 20 years. But it also marks another change, one in this
country's visual landscape. For decades, outdoor tobacco signs were
the canvas used by some of the advertising industry's most-talented
designers and photographers. And the work they produced, ranging
from the quaint to the ingenious to the garish, have served not
only as urban meeting places and reference points for lost
motorists but also as cultural touchstones. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   AGRI-BIOTECH (Lubbock, Texas) _ A look at the controversy over
new technology that would make the seed produced by crops sterile
and therefore unusable the following year. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-DISABILITIES (Washington) _ The Supreme Court begins an
unusually wide ranging review of the Americans With Disabilities
Act with four cases over the next 10 days. The first case pits a
group of states against the federal government over the question of
whether the law entitles people with severe disabilities to
treatment in community settings rather than in big state
institutions. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-TV (Undated) _ In the last three years, children's
television has undergone an explosive growth spurt, with new cable
channels, new program blocks on broadcast channels and scores of
new shows, many instructive if not downright instructional. And at
a time when adult television is spilling over with crude humor and
vulgarity, children are spending less time watching adult
television than ever before and more time watching their own shows.
By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   HKN-RANGERS-PENGUINS (New York) _ Rangers vs. Pittsburgh. By Joe
Lapointe.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-DUBAI-PRINCE (Dubai, Saudi Arabia) _ The crown prince of
Dubai, Sheik Muhammed, has jumped into horse racing, acquiring two
of the top 3-year-olds in the world, Worldly Manner and Aljabar. He
intends to enter at least one in the Kentucky Derby, but has taken
the unconventional approach of preparing them by racing them only
in private at his facilities in the desert, steering clear of the
traditional prep races that are held in the United States.
Whichever horse he enters will be facing the rest of the 3-year-old
field for the first time. By William Orme.
</P>
