<HEADER>
A3255 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT &LR;      04-18 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA TALK: AWKWARD MOMENT FOR THE WHITE HOUSE?; STATISTICS ARE
MIXED ON MINORITY HIRING; CONDE NAST `OUTSERTS' SEEK NEW
ADVERTISERS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Bill Clinton stands on stage at the White House
Correspondents Dinner in the Washington Hilton on May 1, he is
scheduled to shake hands and stand for photographs with the three
journalists who have won awards for their coverage of the White
House this year.
</P>
<P>
   But what to do if you're the president and one of the award
winners almost cost you your job?
</P>
<P>
   This year, Clinton will find himself in the somewhat awkward
position of honoring Michael Isikoff, the Newsweek correspondent
who broke the story that led to his impeachment and who refers to
Clinton in his current best-selling book, ``Uncovering Clinton: A
Reporter's Story,'' as ``a far more psychologically disturbed
individual than the public ever imagined.''
</P>
<P>
   The award recipients have not yet been publicly announced, but
according to the partially updated Web site of the White House
Correspondents Association, Isikoff will receive the Edgar A. Poe
award for reporting over the last year that offered ``nuanced,
detailed and often exclusive information in a story that dominated
the year's headlines.''
</P>
<P>
   The award for Isikoff comes at an interesting time. Several
years of eyebrow-raising dinner guests _ Paula Jones, Anne Heche,
Ellen DeGeneres _ have turned the once-quiet dinner into an antic
opera bouffe of media, celebrity and politics. And this year, John
F. Kennedy Jr. has invited Hustler publisher Larry Flynt, actress
Claire Danes and conservative multimillionaire Richard Mellon
Scaife to the dinner as the guests of George magazine. All have
accepted, said a George spokeswoman, Lisa Dallos.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Oreskes, Washington bureau chief of The New York Times,
has expressed his concerns over the direction of the dinner and
said that the newspaper will not purchase a table at the dinner
this year.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to restore some dignity to the proceedings,
however, the president of the White House Correspondents
Association, Stewart M. Powell, said he had made choices that
reflect the dinner's original intent, which he said was to honor
the president of the United States and to present awards and
scholarships. For one thing, Aretha Franklin will perform this
year, not one of the usual comedians, who have in the past thrown
jibes the President's way.
</P>
<P>
   By Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics Are Mixed On Minority Hiring
</P>
<P>
   One of the most contentious issues at the annual convention of
the American Society of Newspaper Editors last year _ the degree to
which the newspaper business is trying to hire journalists from
underrepresented groups, particularly members of minorities and
women _ was less of a sore point this year at the society's
convention in San Francisco. Still, amid a strong push for more
hiring of members of minorities _ including job fairs and increased
proselytizing about the newspaper business _ the percentage of
minorities remained little changed.
</P>
<P>
   The annual data the industry compiled showed a slight increase
in minority representation among the 55,100 journalists working in
the nation's newsrooms.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 6,365 Asian, black, American Indian and Hispanic
journalists _ up from 6,270 _ now make up 11.6 percent of the
newsroom work force. Women, who were counted this year for the
first time after some initial resistance, make up 36.9 percent of
newspaper journalists. Of these 20,325 women, 14 percent are
members of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who want to see a greater level of diversity in
newsrooms, there were unsettling trends buried in the larger
statistics. The percentage of members of minorities among
first-time hires for full-time jobs dropped to 18.7 percent from 21
percent last year. In the wake of court rulings against racial
preferences in minority hiring, the percentage of members of
minorities among interns hired in 1998 dropped to 31.3 percent from
a peak of 39.6 percent in 1991 and 33.3 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Among individual newspapers, the two larger papers with the
highest percentage of minorities were The Oakland Tribune, with
47.8 percent, and The Miami Herald, with 46.8 percent. Among the
larger papers with the lowest percentages were The Minneapolis
Star-Tribune, 11.5 percent; The Boston Herald, 8.5 percent, and The
St. Louis Post-Dispatch, 7.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the New York area, the paper with the greatest diversity was
The Jersey Journal in Jersey City, N.J.; more than 30 percent of
its newsroom staff are members of minorities. Newsday is next with
21.4 percent. The Wall Street Journal reported a minority staff
percentage of 17.6; The New York Times, 15.6; the Daily News, 13.9;
and the New York Post, 12.6.
</P>
<P>
   By Felicity Barringer
</P>
<P>
   Conde Nast `Outserts' Seek New Advertisers
</P>
<P>
   In a shift aimed at bringing new advertisers to the pages of its
magazines, Conde Nast has begun churning out special issues with
targeted audiences that attract new advertisers to Conde Nast, a
unit of Advance Publications.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the one-time supplement ``Currency'' attracted
financial advertisers who had never before advertised with the
company. This fall, ``Persona'' _ a title for women over 40, with
an array of advertisers from Prudential Securities to General
Motors _ will be produced as an ``outsert,'' an additional magazine
that is packed into a polyurethane bag with an already existing
magazine. (The practice known as ``poly-bagging.'') In the case of
Persona, the issue will be ``poly-bagged'' with 14 of the Conde
Nast titles. The frequency of Persona's publication has not been
determined.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Viscardi Johnston, a Conde Nast executive
vice-president said that these issues begin as ``marketing
opportunities.'' Persona appealed to her because it ``creates
opportunities for advertisers, with an attractive editorial
surround.''
</P>
<P>
   And what advertiser doesn't crave good editorial ``surround''?
Now, Mademoiselle is going after advertisers in the computer and
software market. Elizabeth Crow, the editor in chief of the Conde
Nast title Mademoiselle, said that the monthly magazine will
introduce an outsert this October, separately titled Click Here,
which will address the issues of computers and the Internet in
young women's lives.
</P>
<P>
   She said that the magazine will include ``a lot of first-person
stuff, like `I Was an On-Line Shopaholic.'''
</P>
<P>
   David Verklin, chief executive of Carat North America, said that
Conde Nast's program of ``outserts'' like Persona and Click Here,
reflects a growing trend in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Publishers are going after marketing programs, not just ad
pages,'' he said. ``These one-time issues bring in new advertisers,
and Conde Nast can say to those advertisers: `Buy a page here, but
you have to buy two pages in Persona.'''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``The down side is that these are often one-time
issues, so you're not having an ongoing dialogue with readers that
we at one time paid so much attention to.''
</P>
<P>
   By Alex Kuczynski
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
