<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3263 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CARTOONS-COLUMN-NY     04-18 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CARTOONS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARTOON CHARACTERS IMITATE, EVEN TRANSCEND THE LIVE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARGO JEFFERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is really a shame that the entertainment industry continues
to believe that if a good thing works once it will work even better
twice, thrice and then as many times as ratings and profits allow
before going bad.
</P>
<P>
   It is a shame because it means that every advance contains the
seeds of its own decay. So we have every reason to fear the success
of all those smart, saucy television cartoon series made for
viewers somewhere between the legal voting age and senior
citizenship. I mean, of course, shows like ``The Simpsons,'' ``King
of the Hill,'' ``The PJs,'' ``Futurama'' and ``South Park'' that
relish satire as well as farce. They can even find room for
tenderness that is on the wry side, not in the maudlin middle.
</P>
<P>
   If greed and knockoff imitation run true to form, we will soon
be heading into a glut of highly touted second- and third-rate
shows. (``Family Guy'' suggests we're on our way.) Too bad for us.
But too bad for television also. It is the perfect medium for
innovative animation, not the lowly second choice.
</P>
<P>
   Movies don't do any of this better, and they don't do most of it
as well, when you consider content as well as form. Their animation
epics (insect epics, Bible epics, history and folklore epics) are
loaded with showoff effects or faux-human sincerity and music that
goes back and forth between treacly and perky.
</P>
<P>
   No, it is the condensed, focused television cartoons that are
advancing the form. I think this is because their creators, apart
from being clever and talented, know television history: not just
the history of cartoons like ``The Flintstones'' or Rocky and
Bullwinkle, but the history of the half-hour sitcom and melodrama.
We know what is nonnaturalistic about sitcoms, but just think about
those old thrillers. What is more cartoonish than a convention that
requires a crisis to be laid out, exploited and resolved in less
than 30 minutes, making room for the total ruptures in attention
that commercials impose?
</P>
<P>
   The classic television sitcom was and is family fare, whether
centered in the home or in the kind of workplace that creates a
facsimile family. Track the progression from the innocent emotional
pratfalls of ``I Love Lucy,'' ``Father Knows Best'' and ``Our Miss
Brooks'' to shows like ``The Mary Tyler Moore Show,'' ``All in the
Family,'' ``The Jeffersons'' ``Cheers'' and ``Roseanne,'' where
hostility and confusion are right there beside the old-time laughs,
supplying the most intense comic charge.
</P>
<P>
   Then go a few steps further. Cartoon humans like Homer and Marge
Simpson and the rest of their circle are as grotesque and
ineffectual as we fear (or know) ourselves to be on occasion. The
little boys of ``South Park'' _ four white egg figures bouncing
along on flat feet _ are as belligerent and uninhibited as we would
like to have been (and were when we could get away with it) in
those precious early childhood years. And the big-eyed, big-headed
PJs, more like puppets than cartoon figures, look as ready to pop
out of the television screen as their real-life counterparts are to
bust out of their lousy neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Week after week ``The Simpsons'' manages to show that the words
``nuclear waste'' can be applied as easily to a family as to a
chemical plant. ``The PJs'' proves that the mocking humor of black
minstrelsy can extend outward to a nonblack audience, not just
inward to self-hatred. ``South Park'' shows that there is such a
thing as white minstrelsy, which can make fun of its own opinions
and conventions, not just those considered alien or politically
correct.
</P>
<P>
   I have seen only two episodes of ``Futurama,'' the new show from
Matt Groening, the creator of ``The Simpsons.'' But the year-3000
look of ``Futurama'' is great fun: all the technology we know,
hyperextended and activated; all the cultural artifacts we live
with, relocated (Earth theme parks on the Moon); and our
biochemical systems inverted (the robot that lives on alcohol and
gets the D.T.'s when dead sober).
</P>
<P>
   Every one of these shows mixes cheerfully shallow comic gags
with parody (affectionate but pointed gibes at everything from
consumer fads to psychological theories) and satire, that angrier
critic of the status quo (the greed of the rich and the powerful,
the chasms separating what children think and want from what their
parents and teachers think and want for them and the pure everyday
shallowness and selfishness that the ordinary well-meaning human
being manages to get mired in).
</P>
<P>
   It is this mixture of tone, motive and genre that makes these
cartoons so right for television. Television brings us the banal,
the arcane, the extreme, the violent and the pastoral, uplift and
degradation, all within seconds, if we wish. It supplies
entertainment that is both disposable and indispensable. It
specializes in giving us that delicious mix of the valuable and the
throwaway.
</P>
<P>
   Here is an insight side by side with the platitude, a scene that
demands all our attention, followed by a commercial that demands
none (or that demands as much as the scene did). Television gives
us quick, easy pleasures and hidden messages. (We look for them
constantly in reruns or in the tapes we play over and over.)
</P>
<P>
   Like cartoons, television sets themselves are some of the most
abnormal vehicles of entertainment ever to have entered our
ostensibly normal lives and homes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-99 1743EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
