<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MAIN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THOUSANDS OF EXPECTED KOSOVO REFUGEES FAIL TO APPEAR
 &HT;    890&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ The refugee pipeline from Kosovo inexplicably
closed again Sunday after nearly 6,000 refugees passed the gnarled
wreckage of a car that hit a mine in the border no man's land,
killing five members of an escaping family.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the deepening refugee crisis, NATO officials said they had
evidence that Yugoslav Serbs were forcing ``chain gangs'' of
Kosovars to dig graves for their countrymen killed in a campaign of
ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   NATO also said the alliance's heaviest day yet of bombing
sorties caused heavy damage inside Yugoslavia on Sunday, the 25th
day of the air campaign. Officials insisted that the bombing was
weakening President Slobodan Milosevic and there were no plans to
introduce ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion that killed the five refugees in neutral territory
between the Yugoslav and Albanian borders came after the car
apparently strayed from the channel of safe passage into an area
known to be mined.
</P>
<P>
   Another refugee, Nysret Gerguri, said in a hospital interview
that he had been walking about four yards behind the white car when
it veered off the road and then blew up. He said the explosion
clearly came from below the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbian border guards told us to move on quickly,'' said
Gerguri. ``They told us the Albanians did this.''
</P>
<P>
   He was not permitted to help the injured survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Gerguri identified the dead man as Ibush Barisha, and his wife
as Hajrije Barisha. He said he lived near the family in a town in
central Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies of three children killed in the 3 a.m. blast were
retrieved by Yugoslav authorities and remained on that side of the
border, according to Doran Vienneau, a field officer of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), which
was investigating the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Three adults and an 11-year-old son groped their way from the
conflagration and were helped to safety by medics from the Albanian
side of the border, Vienneau said. However, the grandmother of the
family, age 65, and the 35-year-old mother died after arriving in
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Vienneau described the incident as probably ``a tragic
accident'' rather than an intentional assault by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously the (Yugoslav) authorities want as many refugees to
leave Yugoslavia as possible,'' he said. ``They have land mines in
that area probably as a defensive position.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Sunday, the refugee flow into Albania abruptly halted.
After 1:30 p.m., only a single ailing man literally crawled from
the Yugoslav side into the border crossing area, where he was
retrieved by medics with a stretcher.
</P>
<P>
   While 24,000 refugees crossed into Albania on Saturday, slightly
under 6,000 had been counted by late Sunday night. At border points
in neighboring Macedonia, fewer than 1,000 new refugees arrived
Sunday, compared to a total of 12,000 on Friday and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   With reports of 40,000 to 90,000 Kosovars en route to exile in
Albania, the diminished flow troubled workers and families awaiting
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pattern has been that there's no pattern,'' said Owen
O'Sullivan, director of the Kukes field office of the OSCE. He said
the uneven flow of refugees apparently has been manipulated by
Yugoslav authorities.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, NATO briefers said that film taken from allied
aircraft supported refugees' accounts that Serb forces had pressed
Kosovo Albanians into ``chain gangs'' to dig graves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand they are being used by President Milosevic to
dig graves for their countrymen killed by Serbian ethnic
cleansing,'' said Brig. Gen. Giuseppe Marani.
</P>
<P>
   Marani said the film showed ``neat rows of individual graves
pointing to the southeast, toward Mecca.'' He said that was a sign
the mostly Muslim ethnic Albanians were trying to ``bury the
victims of Milosevic with respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen said NATO jets had flown more than 500 missions in the
24-hour period ending Sunday afternoon, the highest daily total
yet.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea called it ``a highly successful day of
air operations'' focusing on army and police targets.
</P>
<P>
   Correspondents in the Yugoslav capital of Belgrade reported that
choking black smoke rose from an oil storage depot and nitrogen
fertilizer plant in Pancevo, six miles northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Other targets reportedly included an oil refinery in
Yugoslavia's second-largest city, Novi Sad, military jets and
vehicles on the ground, and several bridges.
</P>
<P>
   The official news agency Tanjug reported a 3-year-old girl was
killed when a bomb hit a school in Batajnica, northwest of
Belgrade, where a military airfield is located.
</P>
<P>
   Although a shipment of U.S. Army ground-to-ground missiles were
delivered to an air base in Albania, NATO Secretary General Javier
Solana insisted there were still no plans for ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   That assertion was echoed by Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about ground troops on ABC-TV's ``This Week,'' Albright
said, ``the president has said that he has no intention and that
the air campaign is inflicting a great deal of damage and weakening
(Yugoslavia's) military.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether U.S. ground troops were training for a Balkan
mission, Albright answered, ``I have been told that there is no
training specifically going on for this kind of operation.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Here in Albania, miserable weather and apparently tougher Serb
tactics within Kosovo were taking a toll on those who did cross.
Relief agencies reported more refugees arriving dehydrated and
suffering malnutrition, and also bearing bullet wounds and other
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our projection is that there are a large number of refugees
still to come,'' said Daniel Endres, coordinator for the UN High
Commissioner for Refugees here. ``It looks as if entire cities are
being emptied. It really is unprecedented.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Sunday morning that the line of refugees waiting to
cross in cars, tractor-hauled carts and on foot had been estimated
at 10 miles in length, though other estimates have been put at
double that. What happened to all those people was not known.
</P>
<P>
   In Macedonia, authorities allowed about 500 refugees who had
been stranded for more than a day at the Jazince border crossing to
enter the country from Yugoslavia after appeals from the U.N.
refugee agency.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia's government has said it can host no more than 20,000
refugees because of the strain on its poor economy and delicate
ethnic balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not build new camps any more. It is possible to expand
existing camps, but new refugees definitely must go to third
countries,'' Defense Minister Nikola Kljusev said in remarks
published in Macedonian newspapers over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers speculated that refugee arrivals dropped because
ethnic Albanians still in Kosovo may believe that Macedonia has
closed its borders and thus are attempting to make it to the
Albanian border.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 18,000 refugees have been airlifted to European host
countries, but Macedonian officials claim that tens of thousands
more must leave.
</P>
<P>
   (Charles Holmes contributed to this story from Skopje,
Macedonia.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
