<HEADLINE>
KNIGHT RIDDER MAKES APPOINTMENTS IN NEWS DIVISION  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A corporate reshuffling in the top ranks of Knight Ridder's news
division is bringing an old Washington hand back to head the
newspaper chain's Washington bureau, while the executive editor of
The San Jose Mercury News in California is taking over as Knight
Ridder's vice president for news.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper chain's new Washington editor, Clark Hoyt, shared
a Pulitzer Prize for articles disclosing that Sen. Thomas Eagleton
of Missouri, the man George McGovern, the Democratic nominee for
president in 1972, initially selected as his running mate, had
received electric shock treatments for depression. The disclosure
prompted Eagleton to withdraw from the race.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyt will supervise the Washington bureau and the company's wire
service, which carries its national and international coverage.
Direct management of the bureau will be handled by Katherine
Carroll, the former deputy bureau chief, who was named Washington
bureau chief. The former bureau chief, Gary Blonston, died this
month of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington bureau's coverage is being reorganized around
thematic beats like health in the wake of a company survey that
showed that some editors of its member newspapers had less appetite
for traditional daily coverage of federal agencies like the Health
and Human Services department.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome M. Ceppos led the newsroom at The Mercury News for four
years, presiding over a broad expansion of technology coverage in
an effort to make Silicon Valley's home newspaper a leader in
explaining the industry. He also presided over a controversial
series contending that the CIA played a role in Central American
drug trafficking, a contention that the paper later reinvestigated
and recanted.
</P>
<P>
   David M. Yarnold, now managing editor at The Mercury News, will
succeed Ceppos as editor.
</P>
</TEXT>
