<DOCNO> NYT19990418.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3273 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-BILLBOARDS-AR     04-18 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-BILLBOARDS-ART-780(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BILLBOARDS, IT'S SUNSET IN MARLBORO COUNTRY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: W.Va., Fla., Minn., Miss, Texas, Calif., Md.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unhitched by riggers, the vinyl billboard in Times Square
advertising Kool Natural cigarettes slid down like a curtain last
week and was quickly carted away.
</P>
<P>
   By midnight Thursday, every cigarette billboard in the country
must come down as part of the $206 billion agreement reached last
year between tobacco producers and 46 states to resolve all state
claims over health costs related to smoking. Over the last month,
cigarette makers and outdoor advertising companies have been
scrambling to meet the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   For anti-smoking groups, the end of the cigarette billboard
stands as a major victory, a choking-off of an advertising medium
that tobacco producers have dominated for nearly 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   But the absence of the billboards is also significant for the
change it will produce in this country's visual landscape. For
decades, tobacco signs were the canvas used by some of the
advertising industry's most talented designers and photographers.
And the works they produced, ranging from the quaint to the
ingenious to the garish, have served not only as urban meeting
places and reference points for lost motorists but as cultural
touchstones.
</P>
<P>
   ``For better or for worse, they were an integral part of the
American landscape,'' said James Fraser, the library director at
Fairleigh Dickinson University in Madison, N.J., and the author of
``The American Billboard: 100 Years'' (Harry N. Abrams, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   For 25 years, a Camel billboard in Times Square, which may rank
as the most famous billboard ever built, sent out huge smoke rings.
Until his recent enforced retirement, a 64-foot-high cutout of the
Marlboro Man loomed for more than a decade over the Sunset Strip in
Los Angeles. There were glowing neon billboards like the Newport
brand sign not far from Yankee Stadium. Horses stampeded out from
three-dimensional billboards. And when things got psychedelic, so
did outdoor signs, splashing the tobacco products with black light.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the signs disappear, some people have rallied to defend
historic outdoor tobacco advertisements like the work of Harley
Warrick, who spent four decades painting advertisements for Mail
Pouch chewing tobacco on the sides of barns. Recently, regulators
in West Virginia had to decide whether Warrick's barn signs fell
under the settlement. The barns won a reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Venturi, the postmodern architect, said that while he was
sympathetic with opposition to smoking, tobacco billboards could
also be objects of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a time when they will be hanging in craft
museums on the wall next to patchwork quilts so that we can
understand their beauty as a craft,'' said Venturi, who has
celebrated outdoor advertising in books and articles about design.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the agreement by cigarette makers to do away with
billboard promotions is a replay of a strategy that led producers
to dominate the outdoor landscape in the first place. In early
1970s, the tobacco industry voluntarily dropped television and
radio advertising in the face of a looming government ban.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those advertising dollars were soon poured into
billboards. By the 1980s, one in every three billboards carried a
tobacco ad, advertising industry executives said.
</P>
<P>
   But the tobacco industry's dominance of the medium has declined
in recent years. According to the Outdoor Advertising Association
of America, a trade group, cigarette makers last year accounted for
only about 9 percent of the industry's revenue,
</P>
<P>
   Some of the factors behind the drop included efforts by many
municipalities to end outdoor tobacco advertisements. Before
November's $206 billion deal with 46 states, the tobacco industry
agreed to end billboard and transit promotions as part of
settlements with four other states _ Florida, Minnesota,
Mississippi and Texas _ to resolve lawsuits brought to recover
smoking-related health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   Some outdoor advertising companies said they had to yet to find
new advertisers for all the billboards that were becoming
available. Steve Bryant, the president of Capital Outdoor Inc. in
Raleigh, N.C., said that his company had removed 50 tobacco
advertisements from billboards it owned in the Carolinas.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen of those billboards as well as scores of others
nationwide will carry anti-smoking messages until rents paid by
tobacco companies run out, typically by year's end. Bryant said
that of his company's 50 tobacco billboards he had found new
advertisers for 35 but hoped to pick up others soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will open up billboards to a whole new spectrum of
advertisers,'' Bryant said. ``But I doubt that we are going to see
anything that had the impact of cigarettes.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Anti-smoking groups have long charged that cigarette makers
carefully positioned outdoor advertisements near schools and
playgrounds and concentrated on minority neighborhoods because
those areas had high smoking rates.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Pollay, a professor of marketing at the University of
British Columbia in Vancouver, said that the billboard blitz
launched by cigarette producers had a purpose: By making tobacco
images commonplace in the visual landscape, they conveyed the
impression that a deadly product was harmless.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more we see something the more we see it as benign,'' said
Pollay, who has testified as an expert witness for municipalities
seeking to ban cigarette billboards. ``It creates a familiarity
effect, and billboards are wonderful for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Outdoor advertisements were a part of the tobacco industry from
its beginning. Before the turn of the century, large, colorful wall
paintings advertising Bull Durham tobacco appeared. And as
cigarette smoking grew more popular, tobacco producers quickly
began to erect dramatic signs advertising their wares throughout
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Around 1911, for example, R.J. Reynolds Co. erected a mammoth
blinking electric sign near the Flatiron building in Manhattan that
depicted a man with a giant glow at his feet and the words ``Prince
Albert.'' The sign read ``The Nation's Joy Smoke, R.J. Reynolds
Tobacco Company,'' according to a history of the tobacco producer
written by Nannie Tilley.
</P>
<P>
   As cars began to crowd the nation's highways in the 1920s,
tobacco signs bearing slogans like ``Lucky Strike Means Fine
Tobacco'' became regular roadside attractions.
</P>
<P>
   But as a crowd stopper, few billboards have rivaled the smoking
Camel sign that began a 25-year run in Times Square starting in
1941.
</P>
<P>
   The large billboard bore the brand's slogan ``I'd Walk a Mile
for a Camel'' and showed a figure like a serviceman who had a round
hole for a mouth. Behind the hole was a steel chamber with a rubber
backing that acted like a diaphragm. As steam filled the chamber,
the rubber was pulled tight by a gear. When a second gear turned,
the diaphragm relaxed, forcing the steam out of the chamber with a
whooshing sound and sending it, like a smoke ring, wafting over
Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   With the advent of television after World War II, tobacco
companies cut back on billboard advertisements in favor of the new
medium, Pollay, the marketing professor, said. But in the early
1970s, tobacco companies faced not only the prospect of a
legislative ban on television ads but the likelihood that
broadcasters would offer equal time to anti-smoking messages, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, cigarette producers voluntarily dropped both
television and radio advertising and returned to outdoor
promotions, which did not face the same regulations. At that time,
Marlboro cigarettes, made by the Philip Morris Cos., were also
quickly becoming the country's most popular brand, and soon
billboards featuring cowboys and Western themes became imprinted on
the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   One huge Marlboro Man cowboy sign was erected in 1983 above the
Sunset Strip in Los Angeles and soon became a reference point for
tourists and lost motorists. But it was the construction of a giant
billboard in Times Square in 1989 with Joe Camel that may have
tolled the beginning of the end for tobacco billboards.
</P>
<P>
   The 72-foot-high sign, featuring an advertising campaign based
on a cartoon-style camel, used 2,600 light bulbs and more than 1.5
miles of computer-controlled neon to create an animated display,
according to R.J. Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few years, anti-smoking groups were pointing to Joe
Camel as well as the Marlboro Man as major culprits behind a steady
rise in smoking by teen-agers. And soon some municipalities, like
Baltimore, moved to ban tobacco billboards. Outdoor advertisers and
tobacco companies squared off in court against such cities and
asserted First Amendment protections for billboards.
</P>
<P>
   Though the agreement by the tobacco industry ends the billboard
debate, some advertising by cigarette makers outside stores can
continue. Under the recent settlement, those signs can not exceed
two by seven feet. (The typical billboard is 48 times bigger.)
</P>
<P>
   Getting the billboards down has not always gone smoothly.
Workers removing a Marlboro sign last year outside Texas Stadium in
Irvine discovered a family of red hawks, with two chicks, nesting
there. The birds, which are protected by federal law, could not be
disturbed, so authorities waited for months until the chicks could
fly before using horns to roust them so removal work could proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Some tobacco signs will last even longer. For four decades,
Warrick, a sign painter from Belmont, Ohio, traveled through the
Midwest and Southeast painting the slogan ``Chew Mail Pouch
Tobacco'' on the sides of thousands of barns. Hundreds of the signs
still remain and have been celebrated as folk art. Some people,
including Ted Koppel, the host of the ABC television news program
``Nightline,'' have even hired Warrick to paint Mail Pouch signs on
barns they own.
</P>
<P>
   Signs painted by Warrick before 1970 are federally protected
landmarks. But because Mail Pouch chewing tobacco is still sold,
West Virginia officials, for one, recently grappled with the issue
of what to do about the barn signs painted by Warrick after that
date.
</P>
<P>
   Will Steele, a managing deputy attorney general in West
Virginia, said regulators determined that the settlement's language
on billboards did not cover Warrick's barn signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to push that issue,'' said Steele, ``While no
one has said this, we still believe they are a part of Americana.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
