<HEADER>
A3277 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-VOLUNTEERS-ART     04-18 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-VOLUNTEERS-ART-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE A PASSION FOR THE NET, MANY ONLINE VOLUNTEERS WANT PAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Wis.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By LISA NAPOLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Mann has played piano and written arrangements for Frank
Sinatra, serenaded President Truman on his yacht and written
popular music like the song ``In the Wee Small Hours of the
Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, from his home in Kinnelon, N.J., he sits at a
different keyboard, talking about classical music with the members
of a chat room on America Online. By his estimate, he puts in at
least five hours a week as a volunteer, moderating a weekly chat
session, answering e-mail and filling out an online report about
his duties.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, he and more than 10,000 other people who perform
similar tasks for the online service get a free account and the
designation ``community leader.'' What they do not get is a
paycheck, which is fine with Mann.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not too concerned with being remunerated, since my
purpose was to fulfill an obligation to my art _ my Muse, as it
were. I merely believe that I owe it to the cause of good music to
steer less knowledgeable people in the right direction,'' said
Mann, 82, in an e-mail interview. ``I deem it not only an
obligation for me to do so, but a privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   While Mann considers his role a privilege, some former
volunteers for America Online view it as work and have filed
complaints with the Labor Department. They say volunteers at the
company are treated like employees and perform functions that are
integral to the online service's mission and should be paid.
</P>
<P>
   In asking the Labor Department to investigate their claims, they
have raised two decidedly Internet-age questions: When does taking
part in and enjoying a community transcend hobby status and become
work? And what does an Internet company owe to the people who give
it life, not to mention high valuations on the stock market?
</P>
<P>
   While the Labor Department will not comment on the complaints
against America Online or any action it is taking, the industry and
the volunteers themselves are looking on with interest. If the
department does find America Online in violation of laws like the
Federal Fair Labor Standards Act, it could change the online
landscape, since America Online is not the only company that relies
on the passions and goodwill of people like Mann.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of other Internet businesses, including Prodigy
Communications, iVillage and Geocities, are built on the foundation
of a virtual community, where volunteer participants establish,
lead and police discussion areas. In turn, the businesses proudly
boast about the number of members who take part in their
communities, and trade on those numbers to attract advertisers and
make multimillion-dollar business deals. Without their
contributions, company executives acknowledge that their services
would be virtual ghost towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the core foundation of our business,'' said Bruce
Zanca, a spokesman for Geocities, a Web community where he says 4
million people have built free home pages. Zanca said 1,800
volunteers contributed their time to the management of the online
community, hosting chat rooms and enforcing community standards,
among other tasks. In exchange, they get Geo-Points they can use to
buy products and services on Geocities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The monetary exchange probably wouldn't be an inducement,''
Zanca said. ``These people are the cyber equivalent of scout
leaders and PTA members and the Rotary and Kiwanis Clubs. Why do
people participate in these programs? It's the same reason I coach
Little League on Saturday mornings. It's something people do for
their own personal reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   The local Little League is a different proposition, however,
than Geocities, a publicly traded company with 300 paid employees
that was bought in January by Yahoo in a stock deal worth about
$3.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of volunteering for a for-profit corporation is an
unusual one, so there is little precedent by which to judge these
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   But one question the Labor Department might be asking as it
looks into the complaints about America Online is whether the
volunteer force is providing a service that the company would have
to pay for if volunteers did not exist, said Jeffrey Chamberlain,
an employment lawyer based in Albany, N.Y..
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the difference between volunteering at IBM to assemble
computers and volunteering at the IBM soup kitchen,'' Chamberlain
said. ``The difference between doing good and making computers is
relatively conceptually easy to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   In the digital age, the lines between volunteering and working
without pay are less clear. Many of the people who volunteer online
say they do the work for personal reasons _ not for the
corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Bass spends, by her estimation, 20 to 30 hours a week in
her home in Middleton, Wis., as a supervisor in the pet care forum
on America Online.
</P>
<P>
   She says she loves her virtual, unpaid job: hosting chat
sessions, checking bulletin boards for inappropriate comments,
responding to e-mail from those who visit the area. Sure, she said,
she would like to be paid. ``Who wouldn't love that?'' she said.
But even without financial compensation, she derives great
satisfaction from her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a close-knit family here,'' she said. ``Most of my best
friends are here.''
</P>
<P>
   It may seem peculiar to the uninitiated that so many people
would give so much time, without financial compensation, to a
company with $2.6 billion in revenue last year and a stock market
valuation of $130 billion. Perhaps even more peculiar is the notion
that volunteers would be so personally invested in the work they
do. But it is a phenomenon that is part of an online tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like sex, it looks funny from the outside,'' said Howard
Rheingold, author of the book ``The Virtual Community''
(Addison-Wesley, 1993). ``Any virtual community that works, works
because people put in some time.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But in exchange, he said, what the members of virtual
communities need and want is respect. Many Internet businesses, in
the frenzied rush to capitalize on industry buzzwords, have used
the word ``community'' in their marketing, but not necessarily in
deed.
</P>
<P>
   Rheingold said he suspected this was the case with the
management at America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Kurnit, founder of Mining Company, a guide to the
Internet, chose a different strategy to compensate the people who
manage various topics within the company's directory, like
``pregnancy'' or ``Southern food.'' Kurnit said he knew when he
started the company that he would need a large group of guides to
fulfill his promise of a ``human-powered'' search engine, but that
the economics of hiring a large staff were unrealistic for a
start-up operation. Instead, he pays the guides a combination of a
monthly stipend and a cut of the net revenues generated by
advertising on their sections. Kurnit says the guides, who now
number 692, earn between $500 and $11,000 a month, depending on the
popularity of the section.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, he issued 200,000 shares of stock to the
guides, which is now worth a total of about $10 million. (The
company went public last month, making Kurnit, on paper, worth more
than $50 million.)
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the guides sign over the rights to the sites they
create, and agree not to work for other online services in a
similar capacity.
</P>
<P>
   While for guides who have less trafficked sites, the
compensation might not equal a living wage, Kurnit feels his
program offers a fair reward, and that the company benefits more
than it would if he relied on volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view is entrepreneurs are the best workers _ they work
tirelessly,'' Kurnit said. ``Volunteers are unreliable, and have an
expectation that you owe them something.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Zanca of Geocities disagrees that the quality of work
he gets from his volunteers is less than if he were to pay them. He
also said he was not concerned that the Labor Department inquiry
might affect the way his company is structured.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the Net has a new dynamic,'' he said, ``and in new
dynamics, laws and regulations need to be re-evaluated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-99 1817EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990418.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3279 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-BUSINESS-2TAKE     04-18 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-BUSINESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NET'S REAL BUSINESS HAPPENS .COM TO .COM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Conn., Mass., Calif.)   By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each month, Patricia Ruszkay, a purchasing agent for BOC Gases,
distributor of industrial gases with American headquarters in
Murray Hill, N.J., pulls a chair up to a computer, logs on to the
Internet, and looks for a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the bargain involves not only the price of the
product, but an entire cost-saving process set in motion when the
on-screen ``order'' button is clicked.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 7,000 miles away from New Jersey, in a Japanese gas
processing plant, a BOC supplier receives the million-dollar order
for tungsten hexafluoride, a highly toxic gas used in semiconductor
manufacturing, among other purposes. Within minutes, some 2,500
miles miles from Murray Hill, a BOC distribution center in San
Diego receives electronic notice from Japan that the shipment is on
the way.
</P>
<P>
   No multilingual phone calls or faxes required. No written
purchase orders, invoices or shipping notices to lose. Because the
entire process takes place on the World Wide Web, there are no
extra charges for handling the order over a special long-distance
data network _ which until a few years ago would have been the only
way to conduct business electronically.
</P>
<P>
   BOC makes some $20 million worth of purchases from the Japanese
supplier a year, and BOC officials say the Internet will save the
company several hundred thousand dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
   There may be more headlines about retailers selling books and
compact disks on line, or consumers Web-auctioning the contents of
their attics to one another. But in terms of dollars and impact,
the real electronic-commerce action these days is the
business-to-business transactions quietly taking place among
companies like BOC and its suppliers and customers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, American companies had $43 billion worth of sales to
one another over the Internet, five times the consumer retail
total, according to Forrester Research, a market research firm in
Cambridge, Mass. Within four years, Forrester says
business-to-business sales on line will reach $1.3 trillion, or 9.4
percent of corporate America's purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Another research firm, the Aberdeen Group, is even more
exuberant in its calculations of business-to-business E-commerce,
estimating that the market may now be 10 or more times larger than
the online consumer arena, and hold at that level.
</P>
<P>
   Word early this year of strong online Christmas sales ``put
visions of sugar plum fairies into people's heads,'' said David
Alschuler, a vice president at Aberdeen, which is based in Boston.
``But the fact is, business on the Internet is cutting significant
costs out of the supply chain, with better procurement and resource
planning,'' Alschuler said. In the long run, ``that will have a far
bigger impact than what you buy from Amazon.com,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   While computer companies like Cisco Systems and Dell Computer
have been the notable leaders in business-to-business E-commerce
organizations in other lines of business have also joined the
parade.
</P>
<P>
   Harley-Davidson, Mobil Oil and Los Angeles County are among the
disparate cases cited by Alyse Terhune, an analyst with the Gartner
Group, a research firm in Stamford, Conn., as evidence that
business-to-business E-commerce ``is absolutely proliferating
beyond the high-tech companies now, into just about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobil, for instance, recently implemented an Internet ordering
system for its roughly 300 lubricant distributors, saving the
company $100,000 a year in ordering costs, and cutting the error
rate for such orders from 30 percent to virtually none, Ms. Terhune
said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, E-commerce has brought fundamental change to
businesses like BOC Gases. Its British parent, the BOC Group, has
been pushing for online supplier and customer transactions
throughout its multinational operations, which include a wide
variety of warehousing, distribution and cargo-handling services.
And the benefits transcend mere back-office efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Cahill, a BOC purchasing manager in Murray Hill, cites the
example of tungsten hexafluoride. The company sells the gas in
six-foot steel cylinders that are worth $10,000 each when filled,
making for an unwieldy, expensive inventory.
</P>
<P>
   ``In previous years, our stock has been bloated to accommodate
for miscommunication, upturn in demand, returns or problems with
quality,'' Cahill said. ``So it was typical to have three months of
inventory in the system _ which could be between 50 and 60
cylinders, with a bunch en route.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary reason for such ``blind stocking,'' as Cahill put
it, was the inefficiency of the order fulfillment process. ``We
have quite a lot of people interested in each purchase order,'' he
said. ``All that communication was handled through faxes, e-mails
or the phone, one on one _ which is great until someone goes on
vacation or sick leave, or they leave the office for a few hours,
or transcribe something incorrectly.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the system, which the San Diego site put in place in March
1998, BOC negotiates a bulk purchase with suppliers for a year's
worth of gas, and posts the information on a restricted-access Web
site. This site, or ``extranet,'' is accessible only to select BOC
suppliers and customers, and to BOC employees like Ms. Ruszkay who
place orders by choosing from an online catalog of gases that has
been screened for price and selection, based on the bulk purchase
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   As the order progresses through delivery, both the supplier and
BOC will update the Internet order page, noting the shipping dates,
quantity, and shipping method. This gives key personnel instant
access to the order's status, which cuts down the need for
correspondence, slashes the amount of time spent processing
purchase orders and greatly reduces the opportunities for human
error.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more significantly, Cahill said the system's precision
had enabled the company to reduce substantially the number of
filled cylinders it keeps in stock, saving his division ``several
hundred thousand'' dollars in annual inventory costs.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton Wilcox, BOC's director of technical business development,
conceded that the estimated $60 million worth of business the
company transacted last year on the Internet represents but a tiny
portion of BOC's annual revenue of $1.2 billion. Because the buyers
using the system tend to be the biggest and most valued of BOC
Gases' customers, dollar volumes tell only part of the story, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we had the hard numbers of exactly how much in sales
we do on the Internet,'' Wilcox said, ``it's still chump change
compared to what it's doing to deepen the customer relationship and
reduce the overall cost of ownership.'' He was referring to the
costs a customer incurs not only in buying gas from BOC, but in
storing and tracking it.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be the case with the military contractor Raytheon
Systems, one of BOC's key customers. In 1997 BOC approached what
was then the Hughes Aircraft Company (Raytheon merged with Hughes
later that year) and offered to put its catalog of gases on an
extranet and let the company order around the clock, if necessary.
The customer accepted, and now orders as many as 30 cylinders of
gases each week for its El Segundo, Calif., plant, for use in
research and development.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Despite such headway, there are speed limits on the growth of
corporate E-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   While the overall size of the business-to-business market dwarfs
the consumer market, the rate of E-commerce adoption among
corporations has been _ and will continue to be _ much slower, says
Chris Davis, a vice president CSC Inc., an information technology
consulting concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business-to-business space is just a lot more complex,''
Davis said. ``And organizations don't always behave like
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   With layers of bureaucracy to navigate, and with procurement and
sales methods ingrained in the corporate culture, he said, those
who champion E-commerce within corporations must be prepared to
move slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sun and the moon and the stars have to line up to make
this work,'' said Wilcox, of BOC. ``We're so intertwined with a
customer and their processes, we can't just do things suddenly
without re-engineering the whole process. That's why
business-to-business E-commerce will have a more organic growth
than the flash growth on the retail side.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike consumer-oriented E-commerce, there are no ready-made
software programs sophisticated enough to quickly apply to most
business situations. Analysts and industry executives note that the
requisite business-to-business software tends to be expensive _
often more than $1 million for the initial software license, from
vendors like Ariba Technologies Inc. and Spaceworks Inc. Making the
system fit the specific needs of a particular company, not to
mention keeping it in tune, typically requires an internal support
staff as well as continued consultation with the software vendor.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every dollar that businesses will spend on the packaged
application, they'll spend $5 to $50 on system development and
integration,'' said Ms. Terhune, the Gartner Group analyst.
</P>
<P>
   BOC was pulled into E-commerce by a longtime customer, the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, which has been buying gases
from the company since 1989 for use in science experiments and
other purposes. Four years ago, seeing the Internet's potential for
more efficient business practices, MIT persuaded BOC and another of
the university's big vendors, Office Depot, to offer their products
for sale in virtual catalogs. Like BOC, Office Depot gave it a try,
liked what it saw and has since become an E-commerce evangelist.
</P>
<P>
   BOC hired IBM in early 1996 to custom-design its extranet. But
the system also includes a large amount of software written by
BOC's own engineers, which helped keep the initial outlay below $1
million, according to Wilcox, who said annual maintenance now ran
around $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond money, though, companies embarking on E-commerce must
also become accustomed to doling out ample portions of trust. BOC,
for example, gives its suppliers unprecedented access to its own
inventory data, in order to keep its stockpiles replenished. BOC
customers like MIT give BOC access to their cost accounting
systems, to avoid having to re-enter data as an order works its way
through the process.
</P>
<P>
   Such trust is a departure from traditional business practices,
Wilcox conceded. ``But somebody's got to be willing to do something
a little differently for this to work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
