<HEADER>
A3281 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBANIA-SHELLING19-CO     04-18 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-SHELLING19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    YUGOSLAV SHELLING OF ALBANIA BORDER TOWNS ACCELERATES
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MAIN.
 &HT;    With photos.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KRUME, Albania _ Accelerated shellings and explosions aimed by
Yugoslavia's military at this craggy border region are raising
fears for the safety of Kosovo refugees, aid workers and local
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   The blasts have killed 17 Kosovo guerrilla fighters and forced
the evacuation of an entire village. They also are interfering with
humanitarian aid deliveries for thousands of refugees crammed into
a tent camp and the homes of local Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   The series of cross-border attacks appears to be directed at
training camps of the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``One shell landed right there up on the hill,'' said Avni Dita,
a plainclothes police investigator, pointing to a spot overlooking
this town.
</P>
<P>
   He said shells or mortars buffeted a village not 15 miles to the
west, and the nearly 1,000 residents all were evacuated. Local
television reported that a Yugoslav military unit then crossed over
the border and looted the village, which held a KLA headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Another explosion in the Krume area, this one of unknown origin,
forced the UN World Food Programme(cq) to halt helicopter
deliveries of food and other aid, according to agency spokesperson
Angela Walker. She said food now travels here by truck from Kukes,
near the main refugee border crossing about 18 miles southeast of
Krume.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't afford helicopter accidents,'' Walker said in an
interview in Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA set up camps throughout this border area to continue
their fight for Kosovo's independence from Yugoslavia.
International negotiations failed when the Serb-led Yugoslav
government refused to agree to a settlement accepted by the KLA,
leading to the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Serbs intensified their campaign to end
the independence movement and drive out most if not all of the 1.8
million ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   So far the Serb aggression has not convinced Kosovar Albanian
refugees here or elsewhere along the border to move further south,
much to the consternation of relief agencies. They are trying to
relocate these concentrations of people for their own safety and to
make room for the huge new influx of refugees arriving daily at
border crossings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to stay here,'' said Shahe Dallaveri, 47, who has
lived in the tent camp on Krume's outskirts for two weeks. ``I can
think only of the hospital where I have my wounded children. We
just want to get back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dallaveri family left three children across the border in
Kosovo. They said two were wounded when Serbs opened fire on their
refugee convoy trying to exit the country. A third, who is 20 years
old, stayed behind to care for her wounded siblings in a hospital,
according to the mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they (Serbian Yugoslavs) are trying to get revenge
against Albanians because they are helping us,'' said Ramadan
Dallaveri, 61, the husband of Shahe.
</P>
<P>
   Humanitarian workers have expressed concern that the local
populace will grow impatient with this refugee presence and the
stress they are bringing to the area, including the Serbian
shelling campaign. That is another reason they are urging refugees
to disperse to southern regions where they would be less
concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   At least some Albanian residents of Krume showed no qualms about
keeping the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult, but we feel it's a duty because they are our
brothers,'' said Mane Musa, 36, who runs a vegetable stand at the
Krume central square. She has 20 ethnic Albanian refugees from
Kosovo staying in her three-room house, Musa said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not the problem. We never think they are the cause of
the bombing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
