<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3287 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-AUCTIONS-720     04-18 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-AUCTIONS-720(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-COMMERCE REPORT: INTERNET ESCROW SERVICES ARE CATCHING ON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.) (js) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Internet auctions are promoted for their ability to rid the
world of middlemen and let buyers and sellers strike deals in
free-market harmony. But as auction sites look to cash in on the
trend by selling more costly goods, this Internet utopia is coming
under threat. Higher prices can mean lower levels of trust.
</P>
<P>
   That is why, in recent months, Internet escrow services have
gained a following in person-to-person selling circles. These
services, in which a third party holds the money until both buyer
and seller are satisfied with the transaction, can reduce the risk
of fraud, bounced checks or goods that fall short of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Internet executives and analysts say a vast majority of business
is still conducted without such services, but that could change
quickly, as Beanie Babies and baseball cards are eclipsed on the
auction block by Bordeaux and BMWs.
</P>
<P>
   The services work as their offline counterparts do: The parties
strike an agreement, the buyer pays the sale price _ plus a fee,
which is typically 5 percent _ to the escrow service, and when the
buyer accepts the item, the escrow service transfers the money to
the seller. Though some online auction companies, such as Auction
Universe and Edeal, provide their own escrow services for
customers, others, like Amazon.com, Ebay and Yahoo Auctions, offer
the services of third-party escrow providers, often in exchange for
a percentage of the escrow fee.
</P>
<P>
   Notably, the escrow services collect the fee even when a
transaction falls through, as was the case with Heather Krolak, a
24-year-old photographer and artist from Brooklyn, who entered into
an agreement to buy a Patrick Nagel painting on Ebay in early
February for $1,500. ``I was skeptical,'' Ms. Krolak said, noting
that works by Nagel, a nationally known artist in the 1970s and
'80s, typically command much higher prices. ``It seemed like a
little too good of a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the seller was in Spring Valley, Calif., Ms. Krolak
asked him to conduct the transaction through I-Escrow, one of the
two leading online escrow providers. (Tradesafe, I-Escrow's chief
competitor, is also available on Ebay. Both sites are also
available on Amazon's auction channel.) Ms. Krolak and the seller
clicked onto I-Escrow's site and registered, creating a secure page
in which they could further negotiate the length of the inspection
period and other terms of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Krolak argued for a one-week inspection period, while the
seller wanted to allow only one day. The seller also informed Ms.
Krolak that the artist's signature was slightly off, but that he
had a letter from the artist's brother verifying the painting's
authenticity. ``I thought that was a little odd,'' Ms. Krolak said,
``so I stuck to the one-week inspection period.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon receiving the painting, Ms. Krolak had it inspected by two
experts, who declared that it was not a Nagel. She sent it back,
forfeiting the $120 escrow fee. ``I was disappointed, and I lost
the fee,'' she said. ``But it was worth it because I would have
lost a lot more if I hadn't used it.''
</P>
<P>
   Would she bid on expensive artwork again? ``You have to be
careful _ especially with art,'' she said. ``But sure I would.''
</P>
<P>
   This is just the kind of testimonial that Internet auction sites
are hoping for, since Web auctioneers are intent on pushing the
average sale price for an item beyond the current $45 level so they
can collect fatter commissions.
</P>
<P>
   That means that consumers can expect to see more so-called
special event auctions, like a recent Ansel Adams auction on
Auction Universe, and more specialized auction sites where rare
items are offered. (Auction Universe is a division of Classified
Ventures.com, which is partly owned by The New York Times Co.)
</P>
<P>
   ``With more auction sites that are specific to collectors, we
could see an enormous growth in the need for escrow services,''
said Sue Rothberg, a senior analyst with Gomez Advisers, an
electronic commerce research firm in Concord, Mass. ``When you're
talking about things like antique Shaker furniture, those people
are serious shoppers who don't want to mess around.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rothberg said that in a recent survey, she found that just
four of the top 15 Internet auction sites offered some form of
escrow service. ``But that will blossom, I'm certain,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   According to Ken Pereira, Tradesafe's chief executive, less than
1 percent of auction transactions use escrow, although he expects
such use to exceed 4 percent by year's end. In the future, Pereira
said, ``we don't see it going much beyond 10 percent,'' because he
expects that most auctioned goods will still have relatively low
prices.
</P>
<P>
   But operators of escrow services see ample opportunity to
profit. Edeal, a Toronto-based auctioneer that offers customers an
escrow option, is one such example. ``If we start doing large
volumes of deals, there's constant cash in trust for us. It's not
our money, obviously, but you could have a period of a week where
there's $10 million in trust. We could invest it in an extremely
secure Treasury bill, for example, and roll it over at, say, 5
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is ``still figuring out the legalities of it,'' said
Leon Kuperman, chief technology officer for Edeal. ``But we know
there's some potential there.''
</P>
<P>
   But some other auction sites avoid this approach. ``We're
licensed in California, so we have to put the money in a
non-interest-bearing trust,'' said Sanjay Bajaj, vice president for
marketing and business development at I-Escrow. ``But we make our
money on fees. We don't want any incentive to delay payment to
sellers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bajaj said the number of registered I-Escrow users had grown to
50,000 from 5,000 in the last five months, but ``you'd be surprised
at how many people still don't know about these services.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason, perhaps, is that escrow services generally do not
receive prominent placement on auction sites. On Ebay, for
instance, information about the service's escrow providers is
located two pages within sections titled Safe Harbor and After the
Auction.
</P>
<P>
   Escrow information may gain prominence as the value of auctioned
goods rises, though _ and in response to mounting concerns about
auction-related fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the National Consumers League had seen a 600 percent
increase in online fraud reports since 1997, Zona Research warned
in a recent report that ``if the online auction community does not
take steps to limit fraud then it could face serious problems,
including government intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   Given a choice between government intervention and a free-market
solution, auction providers may quickly see the virtue of promoting
escrow services front and center on the user's screen _
representing one small victory for Internet middlemen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
