<SLUG> BC-IBM-NEW-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NOTEBOOK CHOICE FROM IBM: SVELTE OR BULKIER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pity the poor notebook computer designer. Everyone complains his
notebook is too heavy. But when manufacturers try to make more
svelte machines, users say the screens are too small and the floppy
disks and CD-ROM drives are missing.
</P>
<P>
   That is why many notebooks today come with an array of flaps,
bays and compartments into which disk drives and batteries can be
added or removed. Other machines start small, but wind up looking
like snake pits as all manner of devices are plugged in from the
outside.
</P>
<P>
   IBM Corp. is trying to appease the schizophrenic notebook user
with a new model scheduled for introduction Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Thinkpad 570, the new machine is the replacement for
its 560 model, a leader in the four-pound ultraportable category.
IBM calls the machine a transformer, after the cartoon series about
robots that morph into different shapes.
</P>
<P>
   In one incarnation, the 570 appears to be a somewhat bulky
traditional notebook of the kitchen-sink variety. Two inches thick
and weighing 6.8 pounds, the machine has a floppy drive, a CD-ROM
or DVD drive and room for two batteries. But push a button on the
front and a four-pound, one-inch-thick laptop emerges, leaving all
those drives behind in a single base unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want a desktop replacement, but they also want the
flexibility to take off when they need,'' said Adalio Sanchez, the
general manager of IBM Mobile Computing.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Reynolds, a research fellow at Dataquest, says that the
570 is part of a series of well-designed products that has helped
IBM regain momentum in the notebook market after losing ground
earlier this year. Still, he said, Dell Computer has burst forward
to take the lead in notebooks for the first time this year, with
Toshiba losing the greatest amount of market share.
</P>
<P>
   The transformer concept represents ``some breakthrough
thinking,'' Reynolds said. ``But I still would be inclined to bet
that it's not going to be a barn-burner. The market has not liked
ultraportable machines alone. And in its big version, it's bigger
than other full-featured notebooks.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM has set the price of the 570 higher than the smaller but
more-pared-down Sony Vaio 505 and at about the same price as the
similar Portege line from Toshiba. The cheapest of IBM's 570
configurations is $2,699, for the notebook machine only, with a
300-megahertz Pentium II processor and a 12.1-inch screen. The
high-end version has a 13.3-inch screen and a 366-megahertz
processor for $3,599.
</P>
<P>
   But to get the full transformer effect, customers will also have
to buy an ``ultrabase'' unit for $119, and a CD-ROM drive for $135.
(Watching movies on the laptop will require a DVD drive for $335
and an extra battery for $209.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
