<HEADER>
A3290 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GRETZKY-IMPACT-TE     04-18 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETZKY-IMPACT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE INCREDIBLE GREATNESS OF GRETZKY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MITCHELL KRUGEL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunday, Wayne Gretzky will set up behind the opponent's net one
last time, and send one last blind pass into the slot. Network
television will show him. Fans in San Jose, Phoenix, Nashville,
Tampa and Miami will stop to watch him.
</P>
<P>
   And this chain of events will encompass the Gretzky legend, his
legacy of offensive ingenuity, his passing fancy, his spreading and
selling the game to markets that rarely have weather below
freezing. When Wayne Gretzky plays the final game of his 20-year
career today against the Pittsburgh Penguins at Madison Square
Garden, the NHL will say farewell to the man who is bigger in his
game and his world than even Michael Jordan was in his.
</P>
<P>
   ``Muhammed Ali may be the closest person who sold a sport as
much as Gretzky,'' said Daryl Reaugh, the Stars' radio and
television analyst who was a teammate of Gretzky's with the
Edmonton Oilers from 1985-88. ``He sold the game in the United
States, pure and simple. And in Canada, he's bigger than Jordan or
Babe Ruth. We don't have royalty in Canada. He's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky's global impact even spreads to Fort Worth. Andy Moog,
president of the Fort Worth Brahmas, was a goalie on the Edmonton
Stanley Cup champions of 1984, '85, '87 and '88. And Mike
Krushelnyski, the coach of the recently departed Fort Worth Fire,
was also an Edmonton teammate who was traded with Gretzky to the
Los Angeles Kings in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Moog contends that the trade to Los Angeles paved the way for
the NHL to expand to warm-weather climates. Since that trade, the
NHL has had teamsfind homes in Anaheim, San Jose, Phoenix, Dallas,
Nashville, Tampa and Miami. Atlanta will rejoin the NHL next
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was also responsible for the escalation of salaries,''
Krushelnyski said. ``And he always had time for everybody off the
ice. He always signed autographs, visited children in hospitals,
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember one time we were leaving town at like six in the
morning, and there were all these people waiting for him in front
of the hotel. He signed autographs for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   What he did on the ice, of course, created the off-the-ice
impact. Gretzky's point totals are enough for any three superstars
to accumulate in a career. His NHL-record 2,856 points (894 goals
and 1,962 assists) going into today's game is more than 1,000 ahead
of the next-highest scorer. There are NHL players who go their
career without scoring the 215 points Gretzky did in the 1985-86
season, one of his four 200-plus seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The way Gretzky scored is also part of the legacy. He is widely
renowned as the first player ever to set up from behind the
opponent's net to initiate offense. He created passing lanes from
that vantage point, invented the wrap-around shot from behind the
net, and, as Reaugh said, ``changed the geometry of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   In leading the NHL in scoring 10 times, Gretzky was the master
passer, who Krushelnyski said saw the game three or four moves
ahead. Some of the plays he made elicited the old
eyes-in-the-back-of-the head cliche.
</P>
<P>
   Reaugh thought he had them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were playing a game at the Montreal Forum in 1987, and they
had just installed the new Plexiglass, the kind that didn't scratch
so fans could actually see through it,'' Reaugh remembered. ``He
had the puck at the blue line and the defense was closing in on
him. He dropped a pass to Jari Kurri, and there was no way he could
have known Jari was there. He never looked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jari scored, and I asked Wayne after the game how he knew Jari
was there for the pass. He said he saw his reflection in the
glass.''
</P>
<P>
   Moog, Krushelnyski, Reaugh and many others appreciatively call
Gretzky's love of the game his greatest gift. There were times,
Reaugh remembered, when he would come off the ice, get some oxygen
they always kept behind the bench for him, and go back out on the
ice and keep going and going and going.
</P>
<P>
   ``He changed the game, like Bobby Orr changed the way defensemen
played and Dominik Hasek plays goalie,'' Reaugh added. ``His
physical skills were equal to his mental skills, which were equal
to his competitive skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jordan was a great player. Wayne was amazing.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
