<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN LAKERS COME TO OWN DEFENSE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If the Lakers have a tough time defending their
recent lousy play, it shouldn't be a surprise. They can't defend
much of anything lately.
</P>
<P>
   Over their last 10 games, the Lakers have given up an average of
102.9 points _ worst in the NBA during that span. In the same
10-game stretch, Lakers opponents are shooting 46.8 percent, the
26th-worst figure among the 29 teams in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, they went 5-5 during that run. They have lost
three straight and four of six heading into tonight's home game
against Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Blame the defense, the only element of the game a player can
control every night with simple hustle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively, it doesn't matter how you're shooting the
basketball. Each game mentally you can come out and play defense,''
Derek Fisher said. ``Physically you can do that. We can't continue
to be at the bottom of the league defensively and expect to be at
the top of the league standings. We have to be able to stop teams
from scoring a lot of points, and right now we aren't doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not at all. The Lakers have given up 100 points or more in five
of their last seven games and are 5-12 overall this season when
they do. Only three teams have allowed opponents to score 100-plus
more often _ the Clippers, Denver and Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   No one's pointing fingers around the locker room, but maybe it's
because two of the main culprits for the defensive slide now play
in Charlotte. Eddie Jones was the Lakers' best all-around defender
and one of the best in the league among guards, and Elden Campbell
was their best power forward to defend against the league's bigger
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   It's no coincidence both were present when the Lakers last beat
the Utah Jazz _ in Salt Lake City no less _ on March 7, just days
before they were traded for Glen Rice and J.R. Reid.
</P>
<P>
   And without Dennis Rodman, the Lakers are now weaker defensively
at three positions than they were before the trade _ shooting
guard, where Kobe Bryant replaced Jones; small forward, where Rice
replaced Bryant; and power forward, where Reid and Travis Knight
are sharing time.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the once-feeble Hornets have won seven straight
and are 14-8 since the trade. The Lakers are 10-10.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' season totals are reflective of a long, bad
defensive trend: 25th in the league in points allowed (95.8), worst
among playoff teams; 17th in opponents' field-goal percentage
(43.8) and 24th in opponents' turnovers (13.9 per game).
</P>
<P>
   Despite the defensive slide, coach Kurt Rambis said he saw
progress in Saturday's loss at Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense wasn't as good as it could be, but we did a much
better job doing the things that I was asking the team to do,'' he
said. ``I could see the effort, I could see them trying to do the
things we worked on, but we did have breakdowns which got us into
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working on it, and we will get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: After missing nearly a week with a case of
tonsillitis, Glen Rice played 31 minutes Saturday and showed no
effects of the illness, hitting 4 of 10 shots for 11 points, with
two rebounds, three assists and a blocked shot. But he scored only
four points after a seven-point first quarter, taking only four
shots the rest of the game as the offense disintegrated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
