<HEADER>
A3295 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ATROCITIES-960     04-18 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ATROCITIES-960&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO ESTIMATE OF ALBANIANS KILLED CALLED `VERY LOW' BY
ADMINISTRATION OFFICIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.) (rk) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The number of ethnic Albanians killed by Serbs in
Kosovo may be far higher than the few thousand cited by NATO
officials in recent days, the Clinton administration's top official
assembling evidence of war crimes said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   David Scheffer, the U.S. ambassador at large for war crimes,
said NATO's estimate that 3,200 civilians have been killed in the
Serbs' rampage through Kosovo was ``very low.'' He suggested that
tens of thousands more civilians were at risk or had already
perished, because _ he said _ the fate of 100,000 ethnic Albanian
men is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster his case, he cited surveillance pictures that he said
supported reports by refugees of atrocities and of men being
separated from women by armed Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, Jamie Shea, the NATO spokesman, said that the Serb
police have forced ethnic Albanian men into ``grave-digging chain
gangs'' to bury the victims of their purges in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, NATO has begun releasing surveillance
photographs showing what officials said look like mass graves.
Scheffer, speaking on the Fox television network Sunday, said one
of these photographs was ``corroborated by refugee reports and
other sources of information'' that he did not disclose.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs came in, torched the town, and then proceeded with
massacres of individual groups of Kosovars,'' he said, without
giving further details.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said that refugees reported being dressed in red jackets to
dig the graves, and that NATO had photographic evidence to support
their stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``These sites are neat rows of individual graves, pointing to
the southeast, toward Mecca,'' he said. The Albanians are typically
Muslim, who unlike the Serbs would bury their dead in this fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The new details appeared to be intended to bolster the so far
unproven claims by American and European politicians about how
widespread the killing has been in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco on Thursday, President Clinton said that the
Serbs had displaced ``over a million Kosovars'' and had killed and
raped ``thousands upon thousands of them.''
</P>
<P>
   From the interviews that journalists and relief workers have
conducted with scores of refugees from Kosovo, there is no reason
to doubt him.
</P>
<P>
   But at this point it is also impossible to prove that he is
correct.
</P>
<P>
   If the U.S. government and its NATO allies have systematically
compiled records of the atrocities, they are not disclosing the
information. Nor is there a clearinghouse or database for the
material gathered by the journalists and representatives of private
organizations who are talking to the refugees at the borders.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, all there has been _ at least until now _ is a
compelling repetition of anecdotal information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting little flash bulb pictures, and that's all,''
said Fred Abrahams, the Kosovo researcher for Human Rights Watch, a
private group investigating potential war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   John D. Fox, Washington director of Open Society, the foundation
created by financier George Soros to promote democracy in former
communist countries, had a different image.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no supermarket for this information in the government
or elsewhere,'' he said. ``It's like a county fair where you've got
to go stall to stall.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, State Department Spokesman James P. Rubin said
Friday that more than 400 cities, towns and villages in Kosovo had
been destroyed by Serb forces. In recent days, the State Department
released a list of more than 100 places, ranging alphabetically
from Acareva to Zym, where ``war crimes or violations of
international humanitarian law'' had been reported.
</P>
<P>
   And Shea reported Sunday that ``numerous refugee reports have
reached us'' of ethnic Albanian men and boys being forced to dig
coal from local mines to feed the power plant in Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   But government officials concede that in most of these cases the
evidence of specific crimes is inconclusive and that in many of
them it is quite sketchy _ a report from one newspaper, for
example, or the word of one refugee. Concrete evidence is hard to
come by without investigators on the ground in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The most reliable statistics on the number of refugees come from
the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, which publishes a daily
count. Through Sunday, the organization reported, 564,700 refugees
had registered at border crossings, 359,000 of them in Albania and
the rest in Montenegro, Macedonia and Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the United States have estimated that 700,000 or
more ethnic Albanians have been routed from their homes but have
not left Kosovo. That figure is less reliable than the U.N. count
of refugees who have crossed into another country.
</P>
<P>
   Professional human rights advocates have been struck by the
extent to which the government is making accusations of war crimes
in Kosovo without offering firm evidence to back them up. The
advocates contrast this with the early days of the war in Bosnia in
1992 and 1993, when the government discounted authoritative reports
of atrocities from Western correspondents and aid agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the Bush and Clinton administrations feared that public
outrage in the United States might require a stronger response than
the government wanted to make. Now, the crimes committed against
the Albanian Kosovars are the main rationale for bombing Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   But some advocates of expanding the war believe the
administration is withholding from the pubic gruesome evidence that
might increase the demand for ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the individual accounts of atrocities reported by
refugees who have left Kosovo, the allies are relying on what
government spokesmen refer to as ``national technical means,'' a
euphemism for spy satellites and other photographic and electronic
intelligence.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Cameras on satellites are photographing acres and acres of
Kosovo several times a day. Low-flying pilotless Predators, one of
which was shot down in the early days of the war, are also taking
photos.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures are interpreted by a team of analysts working round
the clock for the National Imagery and Mapping Agency, an obscure
branch of the Defense Department with headquarters in Bethesda, Md.
The agency's budget is classified, and the number of its employees
is secret.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, the new evidence Rubin cited on Friday was from
aerial photographs, although he would not confirm that.
</P>
<P>
   Such photos, which give the impression of authenticity, have
become staples of the press briefings on the war here and at the
NATO headquarters in Brussels. But technological experts question
how useful they really are in uncovering evidence of atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many frames to be reviewed and so many images that
are inconclusive that solid evidence is rarely developed, the
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Schmitt, a technology specialist at the U.S. Institute of
Peace, a federally funded research center here, conducted a
conference last week on the technical means of investigating human
rights violations. In an interview afterward, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagery appears to offer the the promise of a safe, disengaged
way to monitor very dangerous situations. In fact, it doesn't
really tell you much. The process is deadly boring, time consuming,
tedious and expensive. It's not glamorous or rewarding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
