<HEADLINE>
WEATHER MAP 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, April 19, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures will approach or exceed 100 degrees on Monday
across parts of the deserts of southern California and southern
Arizona as a very warm ridge of high pressure holds steady over the
Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, showers will dampen parts of western Washington
and Oregon as a modest disturbance moves inland from the Pacific.
Showers will taper off later in the day as a pocket of dry Pacific
air arrives.
</P>
<P>
   To the east, showers will develop over parts of the northern
Rockies while isolated thunderstorms, triggered by a jet stream
disturbance, will flare over southeast Montana and eastern Wyoming.
A few storms may reach South Dakota and Nebraska by Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, a broad area of clouds dappled by a few
enclaves of sun will cover the region from the Great Lakes and Ohio
Valley to the northern and central Appalachians. As the day
progresses, the entire area will tend to fill with clouds. Showers
will develop, particularly in parts of the Ohio Valley and the
mountains in the northern Middle Atlantic and southern New England
states, as disturbances lift moist air.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the Northeast seaboard will start with some sunshine,
but clouds will increase by late morning or early afternoon.
Showers may survive the trip over the central Appalachians,
eventually dampening parts of the northern Middle Atlantic seaboard
later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated thunderstorms will affect parts of the Tennessee and
lower Mississippi Valleys as cold air arrives aloft while mild,
modestly moist air amasses near the ground.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Boston Marathon
</P>
<P>
   The weather will be favorable for runners competing in Monday's
Boston Marathon. Temperatures will range from the 50s at the start
of the race in Hopkinton to the upper 50s or low 60s at the finish
line in Boston. Humidity will be low and breezes from the northwest
averaging 7 to 15 m.p.h. will provide a tail wind.
</P>
<P>
   Dry breezes will accelerate the evaporation of perspiration,
helping to keep runners cool under a sky of variable sun and
clouds. Nonetheless, runners will need to drink fluids regularly,
given that a quart of water an hour can be lost through sweat
during strenuous exercise. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
