<HEADLINE>
AT AGE 51, RODGERS HAS ANOTHER BOSTON MARATHON MILESTONE IN MIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bill Rodgers always loved running a marathon. He did
not mind the routine aches. He dismissed the late-race pain that
wracked his glucose-starved body. But in 1992, tired of a new
injury every other day, he ran (he said then) his last marathon.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. When the 103rd annual Boston Marathon is held Monday,
the hometown icon known as Boston Billy, now 51 years old, will run
again. He is not the all-conquering hero who won four Boston and
four New York City marathons between 1975 and 1980. Still, when he
talks about his return, he sounds as impassioned as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do a lot of marathons and it's tough,'' he said in an
interview. ``I've done 57, including 16 in Boston, and I'm not beat
up for all that. They can tear you down. Nothing major happened to
me, but I was having trouble getting to the starting line
injury-free. That's one reason I quit marathons, and by quitting
them, I'm still able to run now.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of marathons, he has been running shorter road races.
Last year, he ran 29 races from 5,000 meters to a half-marathon and
never lost in the veterans' class for men 50 and older.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he ran one marathon in the last seven years _ the
centennial Boston Marathon in 1996. But he made that a fun race,
and his time of 2 hours 53 minutes 23 seconds was far from his
career best of 2:09:27 here in 1979. His goal Monday is 2:31, which
would make him the fastest American veteran in Boston history
(50-year-old Norm Green set the record of 2:31:34 in 1983).
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers, who makes a good living from the sport with a running
shop in Boston, appearance fees and endorsements, shows few signs
of advancing years. His hair is still thick and blond. His
freshness, his charm and his boyish innocence have survived. He
even makes aging sound like fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``My training has been going well,'' he said. ``My legs are fine
and my head is OK. Mentally, I'm there, but physically, that's the
hard part after all these years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Age 51 is tricky for everyone. Sports like this _ running and
walking _ are the best way to get older. It's a blast. You just
have to back off a bit. You can't be so enthusiastic about training
because you've done this so many years. You've put in your time on
the roads. You've paid your dues big time, so in that sense this is
a hard sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard or not, it is his sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still love to run,'' he said. ``It's harder now, but in one
sense it's easier because I've got a lot of friends who run with
me. I train with some younger guys. We did 21 miles over the Boston
course and they dropped me after a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sport is so different. It can beat you up. I'm not going
to run three or four marathons a year ever again. The marathon's
not my main race anymore. My main thing now is a road race, maybe a
10-kilometer. Now I want to do what old John Kelley did, run for
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   John A. Kelley won the Boston Marathon in 1935 and 1945. He ran
the race into his 80s, always waving to the crowds and soaking up
adoration. He is Icon No. 1 of the Boston Marathon. Rodgers is Icon
No. 2, and like Kelley he is happy with life past and present. But
what if Rodgers were young again?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were younger,'' he said, ``I would have to run against
all those great Kenyans. I ran against Henry Rono of Kenya and I
ran against a lot of Ethiopians and they burned me. Now, there are
so many top competitors. But I love the competition. I would like
to see if I could run faster against these guys now.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers smiled. His eyes wandered. The young middle-aged man
wouldn't mind at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
