<HEADER>
A3306 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-GUTERSON-SPI &LR;      04-18 1976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GUTERSON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOPHOMORE JINX GIVES DAVID GUTERSON NO PAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ David Guterson Country beckons once more.
</P>
<P>
   Here again is the Northwest rendered with a painterly attention
to landscape detail. Here again is deep personal crisis isolated
for dramatic effect. And here again is a moral novel for a
semi-moral world, one that examines questions of life and death and
personal responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Guterson's ``Snow Falling on Cedars,'' one of the publishing
phenomenons of this decade with 3 million copies sold around the
world, finally has its long-awaited follow _ ``East of the
Mountains.'' (Harcourt Brace, 277 pages, $25).
</P>
<P>
   But avid Guterson readers expecting the new novel to be some
version of ``Snow II: The Story Continues'' do not know the
42-year-old Bainbridge Island, Wash., author, his full-speed-ahead
personality, his relentless commitment to developing his craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need a fresh start in all ways,'' Guterson stressed recently
in Seattle. ``I need a new landscape, a new sense of structure, a
new point-of-view. Otherwise, I won't be able to sustain the effort
needed to finish the book. If I'm repeating myself, then I'm not
interested. After `Snow,' I couldn't imagine myself writing any
more sentences about rain and forests and saltwater. I was
exhausted by that.''
</P>
<P>
   So ``East of the Mountains'' not only forsakes rain-laden Puget
Sound, it crosses the Cascades for a setting amid the bright skies,
the burnished hills and nurtured orchards in Central Washington
around Wenatchee.
</P>
<P>
   Banished from this new Guterson novel are the sort of proven
plot devices that hooked readers into ``Snow Falling on Cedars'' _
the whodunit, the courtroom drama, the forbidden romance. ``East of
the Mountains'' instead features a 73-year-old protagonist with
terminal colon cancer, a retired and widowed Seattle heart surgeon
who travels east to commit suicide where he grew up, and with plans
to make his death look like a bird-hunting accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew this book could seem morbid; it's morbid from page
one,'' Guterson conceded. ``So I had to quickly dispense with that.
I had to make it what I wanted it to be _ a contemporary adventure
story, this unfolding picaresque. I knew that was the challenge of
this book.''
</P>
<P>
   That challenge did not daunt Guterson, a supremely
self-confident writer who firmly believes the mythic journey of Dr.
Ben Givens and its many detours will ensnare readers.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does that challenge daunt Harcourt Brace, his publisher,
which is rushing a huge first printing of 475,000 copies into
bookstores on Tuesday. This is ``the biggest book in Harcourt's
history,'' emphasized Dan Farley, president and publisher. ``East
of the Mountains'' is being backed with a $500,000 promotional
budget that will send Guterson on a two-month book tour throughout
the United States and Britain.
</P>
<P>
   But Harcourt's great expectations for ``East of the Mountains''
also represent a huge gamble for both publisher and its star
writer, as Farley acknowledged last week. Printing almost a half
million copies of Guterson's novel puts this literary writer in the
big leagues with such best-selling authors as Anne Rice, Richard
Paul Evans and Richard North Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   And it also means that if Guterson sells less than his hefty
first printing _ 200,000 copies, for example, usually a significant
success for a literary writer _ then his second novel could be seen
as a failure in the marketplace and imperil his growing reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a risk if this book doesn't take off,'' conceded
Farley, ``a real high risk that people may not think of this book
as a success.''
</P>
<P>
   The publisher's gamble could have been lessened by doing a
smaller first printing and then going back to press for additional
printings, which could have created much-desired ``velocity'' of
demand behind the book. But Harcourt rejected that approach, a
decision which is looking even more risky now that initial reviews
of ``East of the Mountains'' by major publications have been
decidedly mixed, or downright brutal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew some people would take shots at this novel based on
the success enjoyed by `Snow Falling on Cedars,''' Farley said.
``But we believe readers still like the way David Guterson looks at
the world and are waiting for what he wants to tell next, even if
it's a novel with different pacing. The number of copies in the
first printing is a number we expect to increase.''
</P>
<P>
   Guterson pronounces himself resolutely above the sales fray,
concerned only with his work. He is still willing to help with
interviews and readings and photographs, the stuff of book
marketing, but firmly believes whatever happens happens.
</P>
<P>
   So the sophomore jinx for writers with huge first books gives
Guterson no pause (although some friends and family wonder how it
could not). Nor is Guterson given pause by the 475,000-book first
printing.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to write the book, and what happens after that, I
can't control,'' Guterson emphasized. ``I'm sure there are writers
out there who get excited about what happens after, but what is
exciting to me is writing the book. There's really nothing I can do
after that. My publisher can print as many copies as they want,
they can do whatever they want to do, it's out of my hands. If it
turns out to be a failure, what can I do? I wrote the best book I
could. I don't worry about things outside my control.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the hard-won lessons of someone who went almost
overnight from being a high school English teacher and aspiring
writer to a People magazine celebrity, with every aspect of his
private life suddenly exposed to public view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Snow Falling on Cedars'' consumed eight years of the writer's
life to complete and another two years to promote, as it went from
a surprise near-best seller in hardback for Harcourt in 1994 to a
No. 1 in paperback for Vintage Books in 1996; the book is now a
movie that will be released in October.
</P>
<P>
   Guterson spent so long on the road for ``Snow,'' both in this
country and abroad, that he could not stand to read it anymore. He
instead read from drafts of ``East of the Mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I discovered that `Snow' could have become my full-time job,''
Guterson recalled. ``If I didn't manage it, I would be an author,
not a writer. I gradually realized it was up to me. If I didn't
learn to say, `No' to people, I'd never write anything again.''
</P>
<P>
   These hard-won lessons were not just born with ``Snow.''
Guterson has been unusually focused on writing ever since he was at
the University of Washington, where the Seattle native received a
bachelor's and a master's. Guterson's graduate school mentor was
Charles Johnson, the National Book Award-winning writer, who
recalls him as ``one of the most committed young writers I've ever
worked with.''
</P>
<P>
   Guterson has a similar recollection of his college days: ``When
I set out in the writing life at 21, I felt confident from the
beginning about how things would go. I knew that, if I worked hard,
things would go well. I never doubted myself, never. I never had
some dark hour or crisis when I thought of turning it over and
doing something else, no matter how many rejection slips I
received. I knew I was a writer. Call that confidence, if you want,
but I just knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing a novel to follow ``Snow Falling on Cedars'' might seem
a daunting challenge to even a writer with the deepest reservoir of
self-confidence. But Guterson had begun ``East of the Mountains''
before ``Snow'' turned phenomenon, and its success did not derail
him, as he built the new novel ``in the abstract.''
</P>
<P>
   Themes to explore came to him first, then the landscape. As
Guterson related, ``I have a very powerful, poetic impulse about
landscape, which I have to rein in. The beauty of the world
inspires me with an ache.''
</P>
<P>
   Last came the characters for ``East of the Mountains,''
including Givens, inspired by Guterson's late uncle.
</P>
<P>
   The thread linking the novel's elements is the quest, a staple
of literature in classics such as ``The Odyssey'' and ``Don
Quixote,'' as well as the recent best seller, ``Cold Mountain.'' In
the quest, the traveler is focused on a destination, but is
diverted by crises that lead to greater self-awareness.
</P>
<P>
   So Ben Givens, this healer of hearts now intent on suicide, must
confront a car crash, forced marches in the wilds, the kindness and
derision of strangers, an attack by wild dogs, his first
hitchhiking in decades, a night in a migrant camp, the cancer in
his gut. He also must confront dreams of his past, youth amid the
orchards, courtship of his wife, combat service in World War II,
all these present and past dramas leading up to what used to be
called The Moment of Truth.
</P>
<P>
   As Guterson said, ``This book asks basic philosophical questions
_ What reasons do we have for going on living? For Givens, that is
a literal question, since he is dying. But we all have to discover
reasons to go on. We're all in his shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Givens' journey and where it is heading is often underscored in
``East of the Mountains'' with religious and spiritual signposts,
references to ``better alive than dead'' or ``kind of a miracle''
or ``back from the dead.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the writer as moral teacher. This notion of a novel with
a higher purpose was part of the considerable appeal of ``Snow
Falling on Cedars.'' But it is conveyed with less subtlety in the
``compressed and spare'' world of ``East of the Mountains,'' where
Guterson's intent seems more transparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my two novels end with something uplifting, that's because
that's the kind of writer I am,'' Guterson emphasized. ``I believe
in that. I don't want people to stare into the deep abyss and come
away despondent.''
</P>
<P>
   Life has changed for Guterson and his family in the wake of
``Snow Falling on Cedars.'' The parade of journalists through their
lives was interesting for a while, but now seems intrusive, even
threatening.
</P>
<P>
   Although Guterson is a rare writer who often takes his wife or
children along on his book tours, the family is now bracing for
more than the publicity glare accompanying ``East of the
Mountains.'' The movie version of ``Snow,'' reportedly brought
Guterson $1 million in film rights.
</P>
<P>
   Guterson worked closely with director Scott Hicks on the script
for the film and considers the finished movie to be ``a work of
genius.''
</P>
<P>
   Family continues to matter deeply to Guterson, as his family and
friends attest. Ralph Cheadle is a longtime friend and a former
teaching compatriot who observed, ``David's got his priorities and
his No. 1 priority is his family. He's not changed about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Guterson takes great pride in his children, but wishes ``I had
done a better job in raising them; I have not been as good a father
as mine was.''
</P>
<P>
   The view of his father, Murray Guterson, a noted Seattle
attorney, is: ``David has made such a wonderful thing with his
life, with his wife and children. I just couldn't be more proud of
him as a father or a husband. And the nicest thing about David is
that he is just as nice as he was when he was broke. ... But if he
did start to change, you can bet he would hear about it in a New
York second from me.''
</P>
<P>
   The trademark Guterson earnestness and purposefulness remains
steadfastly in place. The writer considers himself to be ``very,
very lucky'' to have attained such success, but he is wary of fame
and its distractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to get too wound up about a good or bad review _ I
do not want anything extreme, so I ignore most of it,'' Guterson
said. ``I have tried, even with the success of `Snow' to stay on
the same road. I've been happy on that road. Why fly off on a
tangent, move to Paris, buy a Mercedes? I wouldn't be happy then.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
