<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANY POET CAN DIGEST A BIT OF THIS 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If I'd misquoted Shakespeare, it's questionable whether any
readers of this column would have noticed or cared. But I
inadvertently rearranged ``The Greatest Poem Ever Written,'' and
79-year-old Billie McKenna isn't going to allow me to forget it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The least you can do is quote it correctly,'' McKenna wrote.
``I learned this poem as a child.'' And she quotes it ...
correctly, we can hope.
</P>
<P>
   Here's to Carnation
</P>
<P>
   The best in the land.
</P>
<P>
   Here I stand
</P>
<P>
   With a can in my hand
</P>
<P>
   No teats to pull
</P>
<P>
   No dung to pitch
</P>
<P>
   Just poke a hole
</P>
<P>
   In the son of a ...
</P>
<P>
   B. Hammer, another reader blessed with an excellent memory and
great poetic tastes, writes: ``Love your food quotes. My favorite
is from Richard Armour.''
</P>
<P>
   Shake, shake
</P>
<P>
   The ketchup bottle,
</P>
<P>
   None will come
</P>
<P>
   And then a'lot'll.
</P>
<P>
   To further define the great poetry of the 20th century, we place
the following in nomination:
</P>
<P>
   An epicure dining at Crewe
</P>
<P>
   Found a large mouse in his stew.
</P>
<P>
   Said the waiter, ``Don't shout
</P>
<P>
   Or wave it about,
</P>
<P>
   Or the rest will be wanting one, too.''
</P>
<P>
   That recalls this ``Epitaph on a Waiter.''
</P>
<P>
   By and by
</P>
<P>
   God caught his eye
</P>
<P>
   And there was this instructional poem for cooks.
</P>
<P>
   When in danger
</P>
<P>
   Or in doubt,
</P>
<P>
   Run in circles,
</P>
<P>
   Scream and shout
</P>
<P>
   Eaters residing south of the Mason-Dixon Line might nominate the
following for a Nobel prize in poetry.
</P>
<P>
   True grits
</P>
<P>
   More grits
</P>
<P>
   Fish, grits and collards.
</P>
<P>
   Life is good where grits are swallered.
</P>
<P>
   Like all great poets, Ogden Nash and Dorothy Parker were eager
eaters. Lamented Nash in his, ``Reflections on Hospital
Hospitality'':
</P>
<P>
   One eats no meats,
</P>
<P>
   Just Jello and beets,
</P>
<P>
   And soups,
</P>
<P>
   And schloops of Cream of Wheat
</P>
<P>
   A product of the Roaring '20s, Parker wrote:
</P>
<P>
   Eat and drink and laugh and lie,
</P>
<P>
   Love the reeling midnight through.
</P>
<P>
   For tomorrow we shall die
</P>
<P>
   (But, alas, we never do.)
</P>
<P>
   These authors desperately needed a healthy restorative, and
these recipes fill the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Morning-After Oysters
</P>
<P>
   1 pint medium oysters
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon celery salt
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup ketchup
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   Splat of Tabasco Sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sherry
</P>
<P>
   In a saucepan cook the oysters in their liquor just until they
begin to firm up. Transfer to a cutting board, cut the little
buggers in half.
</P>
<P>
   In the oyster liquor that remains in the pan, saute the paprika,
celery salt and pepper for 30 seconds. Return the oysters to the
pan.
</P>
<P>
   Combine in a bowl the ketchup, lemon juice, Worcestershire and
Tabasco and stir this mess into the pan with the oysters. Stir in
the sour cream and sherry and when hot serve the oysters over
toast. Serves two.
</P>
<P>
   Poetic Potato Soup
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half cups minced onion
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sliced carrots
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 pound baking potatoes, peeled and cut into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 pound small, red potatoes
</P>
<P>
   5 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   4 cups water
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters pound low-fat kielbasa or your favorite sausage
</P>
<P>
   8 cups shredded kale leaves (about 2 bunches, discarding stems)
</P>
<P>
   Salt, black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   In a kettle saute the garlic, onion and carrots in the olive
oil. Add the baking potatoes, the broth and four 4 cups water.
Bring to a boil and simmer until the potatoes are tender.
</P>
<P>
   In a blender or food processor, dump the potato hunks and 1 and
one half cups of the broth. Lean on the button until you have a
puree. (If you didn't put the top on the blender, what you have is
a big mess.)
</P>
<P>
   Pour the puree back into the soup pot. Add the kielbasa, cut up.
Dump in the kale and the red potatoes, cut into 1-inch pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Add salt, black pepper and cayenne pepper to taste. Cook the
soup covered until the potatoes are tender. Makes six to eight
bowls.
</P>
<P>
   This potato soup doth beat
</P>
<P>
   Several schloops of Cream of Wheat
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
