<HEADLINE>
FANS PICK BEST AND WORST OF ALL TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The most overrated fighter of all time? Muhammad
Ali?
</P>
<P>
   The Ring magazine published its extensive reader's poll in its
latest issue. Some of the results were ridiculous, such as the
notion that Ali wasn't as good as we've believed all these years.
Some were right on, that Ray Robinson was the greatest fighter of
all time, for example. All are great fodder for argument.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the results of the poll (begin ital)and(end ital) the
Daily News' take on each question:
</P>
<P>
   Best fighter pound-for-pound today: Readers _ Roy Jones Jr.
(52.5 percent of readers believe Jones is No.1). Daily News _
Jones. Just because there's no one for him to fight doesn't mean
he's not the best.
</P>
<P>
   Greatest fighter pound-for-pound of all time: Readers _ Robinson
(62.4 percent). DN _ Robinson. It should've been 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Greatest heavyweight of all time: Readers _ Ali (51.9 percent).
DN _ Joe Louis. He had (begin ital)25(end ital) title defenses from
1937 to 1948, an unparalleled championship reign, and suffered two
of his three losses only after coming out of retirement because he
needed money.
</P>
<P>
   Most entertaining fighter today: Readers _ Arturo Gatti. DN _
Gatti. The problem is he won't last long fighting with such
abandon.
</P>
<P>
   Least entertaining fighter today: Readers _ Chris Byrd (15.6
percent). DN _ Pernell Whitaker. He should be bottled as a cure for
insomnia.
</P>
<P>
   Most entertaining fighter of all time: Readers _ Ali. DN _ Ali.
It was more his personality than what he brought into the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Least entertaining fighter of all time: Readers _ Whitaker (10.7
percent). Daily News _ Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   Most underrated fighter today: Readers _ Chris Byrd (7.2
percent). DN _ Johnny Tapia. The WBA bantamweight champion is
undefeated in 47 fights for a reason: He's a great boxer.
</P>
<P>
   Most overrated fighter today: Readers _ Naseem Hamed (25.4
percent). DN _ Hamed. He should be commended for creating the
illusion that he's a great fighter. That's where his genius lies.
</P>
<P>
   Most overrated fighter of all time: Readers _ Ali (17 percent).
DN _ Mike Tyson. Those who weren't afraid of him gave him trouble.
He was a good, not great, heavyweight.
</P>
<P>
   Most underrated fighter of all time: Readers _ Ezzard Charles
(8.2 percent). DN _ Larry Holmes. He had a Louis-like lock on the
division but had the misfortune of succeeding Ali.
</P>
<P>
   Hardest puncher today: Readers _ Tyson. DN _ Tyson. Even now, no
one can end a fight more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Best jab today: Readers _ Ike Quartey (30.2 percent). Daily News
_ Quartey.
</P>
<P>
   Best left hook today: Readers _ Oscar De La Hoya (21.2 percent).
DN _ De La Hoya. He doesn't have one-punch knockout power in it,
but it destroys opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Most courageous fighter today: Readers _ Gatti (48.4 percent).
Daily News _ Gatti. He has (begin ital)too much(end ital) courage
for his own good.
</P>
<P>
   Best right hand today: Readers _ Lennox Lewis. DN _ Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Best infighter today: Readers _ Evander Holyfield (20.3
percent). DN _ Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   Best defense today: Readers _ Whitaker. DN _ Jones. Whitaker
didn't display such great defense against Felix Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   Best body puncher today: Readers _ Jones (16.3 percent). DN _
Shane Mosley. The runner-up to Jones in best pound-for-pound
fighter category has a great body of work.
</P>
<P>
   Fastest hands today: Readers _ Jones (48.9 percent). DN _ Floyd
Mayweather. If there were a way to measure it, it'd be no contest.
</P>
<P>
   Best footwork today: Readers _ Roy Jones (23.2 percent). DN _
Mosley. He's always balanced, always in position to throw power
punches.
</P>
<P>
   Best chin today: Readers _ Holyfield (14.5 percent). Daily News
_ Julio Cesar Chavez. He's not the fighter, he was but he still
can't be hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest underachiever today: Readers _ Michael Moorer (9.8
percent). DN _ Jose Luis Lopez. His reported lack of discipline
could deprive the world of a great fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest overachiever today: Holyfield (36.6 percent). DN _
Holyfield. He turned himself into one of the better heavyweights of
all time through remarkable dedication and determination.
</P>
<P>
   Best trainer today: Readers _ Emanual Steward (32.2 percent). DN
_ Steward. No one is more coveted.
</P>
<P>
   Worst trainer today: Readers _ Teddy Atlas (13.3 percent). DN _
Who trains Hamed?
</P>
<P>
   Best promoter today: Readers _ Don King (38.9 percent). DN _
King. In terms of the actual promotion, no one does it better.
</P>
<P>
   Worst promoter today: Readers _ King (66.8 percent). DN _ King.
In terms of the disastrous impact he has on the integrity of the
sport, this is a no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   Best referee today: Readers _ Mills Lane (63.4 percent). DN _
Mitch Halpern. Lane is retired.
</P>
<P>
   Worst referee today: Readers _ Richard Steele (40.9 percent). DN
_ Steele. The memories of past debacles linger.
</P>
<P>
   Best blow-by-blow commentator today: Readers _ Jim Lampley (52.9
percent). DN _ Lampley. No contest.
</P>
<P>
   Best color commentator today: Readers _ Larry Merchant (21
percent). DN_ Merchant. Former fighters know more about the game,
but no one can provide the perspective Merchant does.
</P>
<P>
   Worst color commentator today: Readers _ Merchant (21.8
percent). DN _ George Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   Best ring announcer today: Readers _ Michael Buffer (63.5
percent). DN _ Jimmy Lennon Jr. He relies on a wonderful voice and
class rather than a gimmick, Buffer's ready-to-rumble signature
phrase.
</P>
<P>
   Most enticing possible matchup: Readers _ De La Hoya-Trinidad
(41.2 percent). DN _ De La Hoya-Trinidad. Runners-up:
Mayweather-Mosley and Mayweather-Hamed (just to see Hamed lose).
</P>
<P>
   Most competitive division today: Readers _ welterweight (76.8
percent). DN _ welterweight. De La Hoya, Trinidad, Quartey, Page,
Whitaker, Lopez, Forrest. It's hard to beat.
</P>
<P>
   Fighter who should retire: Readers _ Roberto Duran (24.4
percent). DN _ Duran. Enough already.
</P>
<P>
   Who will be the top pound-for-pound fighter in five years?
Readers _ Mosley (27.1 percent). DN _ Mosley.
</P>
<P>
   Other poll results: Best venue today, Blue Horizon in
Philadelphia (34.2 percent); worst blow-by-blow commentator today,
Steve Albert and Jim Lampley (tie, 23.8 percent); worst ring
announcer today, Buffer (31.5 percent); best boxing television
today, HBO (72.6 percent); worst boxing television today, Showtime
(32.9 percent); are you in favor of women's boxing? yes (57
percent); is Butterbean good or bad for boxing? neither, 40.3
percent; are you favor of headgear for professionals? no (93.6
percent); should pros be allowed to fight in the Olympics? no (85.5
percent); are you in favor of the standing eight count? yes (67.8
percent); are you in favor of a federal boxing commission? yes
(77.3 percent); what rule changes would you most like to see?
return to 15-round title fights (21.9 percent). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
