<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3314 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-DUBAI-PRINCE-2TAK     04-18 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DUBAI-PRINCE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM DUBAI, AN AUDACIOUS AND SECRETIVE MOVE TO WIN THE KENTUCKY
DERBY 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., Fla., Ark., Calif., Pakistan, England, Ireland,
Italy)   By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBAI, United Arab Emirates _ It was a hazy early morning in
this glitzy desert kingdom, and Simon Crisford and Saeed Bin Doroor
were staring silently at the last turn of their mile-and-an-eighth
training track.
</P>
<P>
   The object of their attention soon came into view, his pulsing
chest dark with sweat: Worldly Manner, the bay brown colt by
Riverman that they hope will make racing history as the first horse
representing the Arab East to win the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Should Worldly Manner falter, they will have another runner in
the pack: Aljabr, by Storm Cat, a taut 3-year-old with even better
blood lines, who charged past next.
</P>
<P>
   Crisford, the English manager of the Dubai-based Godolphin
stables, and Bin Doroor, the Dubain trainer, said they saw what
they wanted to see: Nothing. No worrisome changes in gait, no
sudden signs of stress. The horses were ready.
</P>
<P>
   It might be the most audacious and unorthodox Derby bid ever.
The Godolphin horses have been prepared for Churchill Downs in the
strictest privacy, half a world away in the Persian Gulf, far from
the prying eyes of rivals, breeders, handicappers and racing
writers.
</P>
<P>
   At 2 a.m. Monday, Worldly Manner, Aljabr and 10 stablemates will
be led aboard a chartered plane here and flown directly to
Kentucky. After a mandatory 48 hours in quarantine, the two Derby
contenders will be seen for the first time this season just 10 days
before they run, defying the traditional route to the Derby that
includes months of punishing and revealing prep races and public
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Behind this secretive assault on the grandest of American racing
titles is the man Crisford calls the Boss _ Gen. Sheik Mohammed bin
Rashid al-Maktoum, defense minister of the United Arab Emirates,
crown prince of Dubai and the single most powerful global force in
horse racing today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every big race is a challenge, but the Kentucky Derby is a
special challenge,'' Mohammed said later in the day, his bare feet
propped on the passenger-side dashboard as his white Mercedes jeep
sped toward a lavish all-male wedding banquet for a falconer
friend. ``A year ago I decided that we should be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to win it in four years,'' he added. ``Four years. If
we fail this time, we'll try again. That's a promise.''
</P>
<P>
   Racing professionals have learned to take such promises
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammed's investment in breeding and racing is measured in the
hundreds of millions of dollars. His Dubai-based horses routinely
compete in _ and often win _ most major races in Europe and Asia.
Godolphin, a five-year-old company owned jointly with his three
brothers, including the Dubai ruler, Sheik Maktoum al-Maktoum, has
by most accounts more competitive thoroughbreds than any other
racing consortium ever assembled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unusual thing they are trying,'' said D.Wayne Lukas,
the American trainer who has started 32 horses in the Derby and won
3 times. ``But you've got to respect them because of the
connections.''
</P>
<P>
   Godolphin has never been a dominant presence in American racing,
and the Churchill Downs classic is one of the great remaining
prizes in the sheik's quest to turn this small Persian Gulf
city-state into an equine superpower. His one previous try at the
Derby came in 1992 when the highly regarded Arazi, a horse that
trained lightly in France, finished eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The stunning scale of the Godolphin operation offers a glimpse
into the Maktoums' ambitions, and pocketbook. There are now more
than a hundred thoroughbreds at their Al Quoz Racing Stable here,
most said by industry experts to be worth a million dollars or
more. They are ridden daily on their full-scale private track by a
handsomely salaried staff of 40 current and former jockeys from
Ireland, England and the United States. Tending the horses and
their stalls are some 70 grooms recruited from Pakistan _ ``the
best,'' Crisford says.
</P>
<P>
   At a once-abandoned race track outside Paris, Godolphin
maintains a kind of farm team of 120 2-year-olds. In the fall, the
most promising 50 or so will be brought south to Dubai for winter
training, and some later go north to Newmarket, the hub of the
British racing universe, to compete in the coming season. Supplying
and benefiting from this racing conglomerate is well-stocked
Maktoum family network of British, Irish and American stud farms,
the ultimate source for their thoroughbred enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   The professional talent at the top is also among the best money
can buy. Frankie Dettori, the Italian chief house jockey, has
amassed millions in lifetime earnings. The respected assistant
trainer, Tom Albertrani, a taciturn Bensonhurst native who came of
age professionally at Belmont Park, was an assistant trainer for
the legendary Cigar before joining Godolphin three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Crisford himself is one of the most driven and successful
managers in the sport. Given to Lombardi-like pronouncements about
the transcendent importance of victory _ ``failure is a word not in
the Godolphin vocabulary,'' he says _ Crisford is known for his
encyclopedic knowledge of the competition and a proven instinct for
knowing which horse to race when, and where.
</P>
<P>
   He is working with legitimate colts. Worldly Manner, for
instance, was one of the most successful 2-year-olds in America
last year before the sheik bought him from his American owners for
$5 million and brought him here.
</P>
<P>
   But from Muhammed's perspective, there is another powerful
argument for a Derby bid. The Maktoums preside over a mostly empty
expanse of seafront desert with diminishing oil reserves. The crown
prince is the driving force behind the transformation of Dubai from
an oil-rich backwater to a thriving commercial and industrial
center dependent more on trade and tourism than petroleum sales.
Getting Dubai on internationally televised sports broadcasts _ golf
and tennis, too _ is part of a public relations strategy. European
travelers are already beginning to discover Dubai's warm winter
beaches, crime-free streets, and gargantuan duty-free shopping
malls.
</P>
<P>
   Bankrolling the $4 million Dubai World Cup, the Maktoums have
put their desert kingdom on the global racing map. They are now
upping the ante, offering $15 million over three years for a new
annual ``World Series'' of nine thoroughbred competitions in eight
countries, from Ascot to Hallandale to Hong Kong, culminating in
the Dubai Cup in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transportation is getting much better, and the world is
getting much smaller,'' said Muhammed. ``I know some people in
America think it is strange, these horses coming out of nowhere,
running in our best race. They can't understand that we are
thinking globally.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Still, the sandy wastelands of Dubai's industrial outskirts can
seem a peculiar place to train Derby contenders. As the morning
heat builds and a gritty breeze blows off the low dunes surrounding
the private Godolphin track, the environs can seem better suited to
the camel races held weekly just down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the walls, however, the Godolphin compound is an oasis of
manicured green, the irrigated lawns separating impeccably
maintained walking tracks, tile-shaded paddocks, 10 airy screened
barns, and the blue streak of a 250-foot single-lane thoroughbred
swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   The compound is a sober professional enterprise, without a whiff
of aristocratic gentility, and with little idle banter. Crisford
and Bin Soroor work in immaculate white T-shirts, clutching
ever-ringing mobile phones. The almost obsessive emphasis on
security, schedules and orderliness smacks of a military software
development lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to limit visitors, because everyone here has a job to
do,'' Crisford said, sitting in his trophy-stocked office, one eye
on a satellite feed of the live racing broadcasts seen in betting
shops across the British Isles. ``And I think people should respect
the fact that Muhammed wants to keep his business private.''
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, where Maktoum horses have competed since the 1970s,
some track professionals derided the family decision five years ago
to move its horses to Dubai for the winter. They were convinced the
thoroughbreds would wilt in the desert sun.
</P>
<P>
   But the Godolphin operation silenced critics with a swift string
of victories in some of the sport's most prestigious races,
including the Irish Derby in 1994 and the English Derby in 1995. In
1996 and again in 1998, Godolphin's soaring earnings made Bin
Soroor the champion trainer in the United Kingdom, and secured
Mohammad's standing as the dominant owner in British racing.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, in what they saw as their sweetest victory yet,
Godolphin's Almutawakel triumphed at home in the Dubai World Cup.
Judged a long shot by American oddsmakers, Almutawakel beat a
dream-team field of thoroughbreds lured to Dubai by the $4 million
purse, including Silver Charm, the 1997 Kentucky Derby winner.
</P>
<P>
   In its five years, Godolphin has picked up more than $22 million
in prize money. More to the point, though, Muhammed said, is the
story of Lammtarra, winner of the 1995 English Derby, who was bred
in Maktoum family stables and sold for $30 million after
consecutive victories in major European races. If either Godolphin
horse were to win the Derby, its value as a stallion would be
tremendous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to win, yes, but there is also a commercial logic to
everything we do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While other horses headed for Churchill Downs were making their
very public way through prep races in Florida, Kentucky and
California, Worldly Manner and Aljabr were working out behind the
barbed-wire walls of the Al Quoz Racing Stable.
</P>
<P>
   Even the two trial races won by the two Derby contenders here
this month _ run counter-clockwise unlike American races _ were
private events, albeit on a royal scale. Top jockeys were flown in
from Britain and the United States. Every mount was Maktoum family
property. There were no cheering spectators in the stands, and no
outside media coverage. Even afterward, the videotape of the race
was not publicly shown, Crisford said, because the performance of
some novice horses ``might be misinterpreted.''
</P>
<P>
   Crisford insists his goal is not to be secretive for its own
sake, but to minimize the stress on horses being readied for
world-class competition. The traditional pre-Derby prep circuit
``is a punishing campaign, and it can take a toll,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some racing professionals question the wisdom of this strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the knowledge, they have the surface, and they have
the expertise to prepare a horse for the Kentucky Derby,'' said
W.Elliott Walden, a sixth-generation horseman from Kentucky who
trains Menifee, one of the favorites for the Derby. ``But the
hurdles of transportation and how it affects the horses are what
they have to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the bloom came off the Godolphin rose last Saturday,
when Prado's Landing, another of their Derby prospects who came
over early, finished last in the Blue Grass Stakes in Lexington.
Crisford acknowledges that the race was something of an
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was disappointing,'' he said. ``I'm sure Prado's Landing
might have others thinking, who are these idiots? But we don't
think like that.''
</P>
<P>
   No, they think big _ always.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like climbing Mount Everest,'' Crisford said of the
Derby. ``We're not breezing in there, saying hey guys, look at us.
We know this is a grueling race. There is no margin for error. But
we think we have as good a chance to win as anyone.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-99 1919EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
