<DOCNO> NYT19990418.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3317 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-850&AMP;ADD     04-18 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND THE LINES WITH KOSOVO'S DETERMINED GUERRILLAS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ Down a narrow back street, inside a safe
house somewhere in Macedonia, six men in their late 20s and early
30s are sitting on mattresses on the floor. They are dressed in
jeans and rough shirts, thin and fit. They are self-described
officers of the Kosovo Liberation Army, just out of Kosovo and on
their way to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Their commander, who goes by the name of Axhaika, 31, is wounded
and lies on the only bed. He has come to Macedonia for treatment.
``Just two or three days, and then I must go back to fight,'' he
said, making light of his wound. He refused to give details of when
and where he received treatment, fearing that this might enable the
Macedonian authorities, from whom he is hiding en route to Albania,
to track his whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had traveled some 100 miles on foot in five days
through southern Kosovo to reach Macedonia, over rugged mountain
terrain that is mostly controlled by the separatist rebels. As
commander of a battalion in the Pashtrik region of central Kosovo
he is firmly optimistic, cracking jokes with his men, even while he
describes the situation in Kosovo as ``hell.''
</P>
<P>
   A builder by trade, he said he joined the rebels early, on June
20, 1991. The group was organized, he and the others suggested, in
the early 1990s mostly by Albanian men, also in their 20s or early
30s, who were frustrated by the nonviolent tactics adopted by
mainstream ethnic Albanian politicians and chose instead to fight
Serbia's revocation of Kosovo's broad autonomy in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Axhaika said he was made a commander in 1992. He said he had
served eight jail sentences for what he called ``political
crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was in 1982 that he received his first jail sentence,
for three months, at the age of 14 for wearing an Albanian badge on
his jacket and refusing to remove it when ordered. He said he faced
another sentence of five years for terrorism after being tried in
absentia last year.
</P>
<P>
   Axhaika said he came from an educated family. One elder brother
is a pilot, Axhaika said, who in the 1980s flew both Yugoslav
commercial and military planes. Another is a pharmacist, and his
sister is an agronomist. He said he joined the rebels so that
Kosovo could be free of Yugoslav control. ``I want to be free, in
my land, in my house, in my home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian attacks on civilians, such as the shelling of refugee
convoys that he said he watched from the top of a hillside above
the Pagarusa valley in southwestern Kosovo, and the mass expulsion
of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo have stiffened his resolve to
fight, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must win,'' he said. ``We are in our own homes. We cannot
go to the United States or England. We are strangers there. Every
man should be in his own home.''
</P>
<P>
   Many American and European officials remain suspicious of the
leadership of the rebel army, which they characterize as
ideologically rigid, even Communist, with a questionable commitment
to democracy. Albanian officials have told the Clinton
administration that Iran was sending weapons to the Kosovo rebels,
and European officials as well as experts on international arms
have said some of the rebels' money comes from drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Axhaika bridled at such charges. ``Of our whole brigade, that is
2,000 men, only two men are supporters of Enver Hoxha,'' he said,
referring to the former Albanian Communist dictator.
</P>
<P>
   He said the rebels wanted a ``democratic, Western state'' after
the war, with NATO troops present to enforce any peace agreement
made with Yugoslavia. He said he wanted to see President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia stand trial before the United Nations' war
crimes tribunal in The Hague. ``Milosevic must go to The Hague,''
he said. ``And he knows it. It is what he fears, it is why he is
holding out.''
</P>
<P>
   Axhaika's men, all ethnic Albanian villagers from his region,
say they agree. Five of them were officers in the rebel army. All
said their desire to fight had crystallized when they were in their
late teens or early 20s _ roughly around the time that Milosevic
stripped away Kosovo's broad autonomy and began an era of
oppressive rule with Serbian control maintained by a strong police
presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 3 my parents told me who the Serbs were, and I
understood when I was 17,'' said one of them, who gave his name as
Kujtim, 31.
</P>
<P>
   Nejmeddin, 29, said the protests by ethnic Albanian students in
1981 _ who sought outright independence from Yugoslavia even when
Kosovo had broad autonomy _ had inspired his struggle.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said: ``I did not have a chance to go to
university. I was an excellent student but my family was not
Serb.'' In 1990, ethnic Albanian professors, teachers, doctors and
other state personnel either lost or quit their jobs, setting up a
parallel education and health network, largely in private homes.
</P>
<P>
   None of the men said he wanted Kosovo to become part of Albania.
``It is not important,'' said another fighter, Kujtim. ``What is
important now is to free Kosovo.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fears that an independent Kosovo would unite with Albania and
the ethnic Albanians of western Macedonia into a ``Greater
Albania'' are one reason that the outside world _ which fears
border shifts in the Balkans would set off a wider war _ has not,
until now anyway, supported independence for Kosovo. Milosevic's
media use the vision to stoke Serbian fears of the Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Axhaika expressed support for Kosovo to become some kind of
internationally protected territory, saying that Kosovo's
Albanians, an estimated 1.8 million people, did not really have the
kind of experienced leaders or established institutions necessary
for immediate independence.
</P>
<P>
   His greatest concern is how to secure more ammunition for his
battalion. At one point, he said, he had only 10 rounds in his
rifle, and his men only 60 rounds each.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such shortages, he said, rebels are still moving freely
across sizable areas of Kosovo. They cross the main roads, which
are under nominal Serbian control, at night. ``They are scared of
the night'' and do not patrol then, Axhaika said.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs, he suggested, display similar reluctance to fight the
rebels head on, shelling villages rather than deploying infantry to
take on the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They only fight with artillery, and they do not know how to
stop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of civilians remained trapped deep inside the Pashtrik
region, he said. He said that in Guncar, his uncle's village,
southwest of Pristina, every house was bursting with refugees and
people were camping in gardens, courtyards and barns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
