<HEADER>
A3319 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-LANGUAGE-SPI &LR;      04-18 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LANGUAGE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS SET AN UNCIVIL COURSE WITH BLUE STREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: This column discusses the use of coarse language
in television. It contains words that will be deemed offensive by
some readers.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how much a part of the vernacular they become, the
words ``bitch'' and ``ass'' still strike my ear as coarse and
uncivil. Dog breeders and farmers might think differently, but I
don't like to use them in normal conversation, which probably makes
me unsuitable for employment on morning radio. And I don't like to
hear others use them, which probably makes me a prig.
</P>
<P>
   They're not likely to show up in this newspaper, either, unless
used in conjunction with something about animal husbandry or in a
quotation purposely inserted for dramatic effect and importance to
the subject at hand. Just getting them into this column required
the journalistic equivalent of papal dispensation, which begs the
obvious question: What's the big !$?% &LR; &AMP;! deal? They're perfectly
good words with perfectly good dictionary definitions.
</P>
<P>
   True enough. And if someone like Drew Carey had his way, they'd
be sprinkled liberally throughout the scripts of every television
show in the land. OK, maybe not ``7th Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey can't understand TV's long-held fear of dirty words. In
his book ``Dirty Jokes and Beer: Stories of the Unrefined,'' he
writes: ``I don't know about you, but if I ever heard the f-word on
free broadcast television, I just might lose my will to live. ...
Of course, I can hear it on cable and in real life, and even read
it in a book. But on regular TV? Anarchy!''
</P>
<P>
   He's got a point. To a point.
</P>
<P>
   Why should the government (in the case of broadcast TV and
radio) or a publisher (in the case of newspapers, magazines and the
Internet) get so exercised about blue language? Isn't censorship _
self-imposed or legislated _ a snooty attempt to foist unnatural,
and perhaps unwelcome, standards on the masses?
</P>
<P>
   Sure it is. Which is why newspapers have editors and TV networks
have standards-and-practices departments. It's part of their
traditions of trying to make us better people than we're inclined
to be.
</P>
<P>
   Is that elitism? Or just good sense?
</P>
<P>
   A little of both, I suppose. One dictionary definition describes
``anarchy'' as a ``utopian society of individuals who enjoy
complete freedom without government.'' Sounds nice, but the
coarseness and incivility sweeping into broadcast television
reminds me more of the anarchy Drew Carey sarcastically alludes to,
that is, a state of unprincipled disorder.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not suggesting that just because Andy Sipowicz gets to say
``asshole'' on ``NYPD Blue'' that we're all going to hell in a
paddy wagon. ``NYPD Blue'' has established itself as a gritty,
realistic depiction of police work in New York City. I have
absolutely no problem with the blue on ``Blue.'' It is situation
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   But I have all kinds of problems with the language on shows that
seem to think coarseness is inherently funny, poignant or
appropriate to every circumstance. ``Bitch'' and ``ass'' are
suddenly all over ``The X-Files.'' I swear (not really) sitcoms use
the terms more often than ``the'' or ``and.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cosby once said that, on ``The Cosby Show,'' he would
demand a rewrite whenever a script showed up with the word ``butt''
in it. Today, ``butt'' is almost never used, but not because of
Cosby's vigilance. ``Butt'' has no shock value anymore and has been
relegated to the mothball fleet of archaic terms. ``Ass'' has the
preferred currency now, and the standards-and-practices people at
the networks, whose numbers are dwindling every year, allow a few
references to slip in so as not to appear too puritanical.
</P>
<P>
   For some TV-script writers, it has become a childish game to see
how many naughty words they can get away with. By my count, two of
comedian George Carlin's ``seven dirty words'' _ the words that he
said could not be uttered over the airwaves _ have now been used on
``mainstream'' TV. One is ``piss,'' the other is ``tits.''
</P>
<P>
   It probably won't be long before some of the other five creep
in. Two of Carlin's forbidden words refer to the penis. A tamer
euphemism not on his list (the one that's a nickname for Richard)
is already de rigueur on ``NYPD Blue.'' Recently, it showed up on
an episode of ``Felicity.'' It's only a matter of time before the
sitcoms start using it.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, Steve Allen recently told Entertainment Weekly
that he doesn't want his 7-year-old grandchild ``watching shows in
which people say, `She's got a nice ass.' It's a matter of taste
and decency.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen has lent his voice and celebrity to the Parents Television
Council, an advocacy group that would just as soon eliminate all
questionable language from our TV sets. Full-page newspaper ads, in
which Allen criticizes the networks, are badly produced and they
tend to make Allen come across as a crank. But I gotta go with
Steverino, at least as far as suggesting that TV needs to find some
balance.
</P>
<P>
   There are few prime-time shows on the networks today that I
would consider appropriate for a child under 12. ``Cosby,'' maybe.
And ``Kids Say the Darndest Things.'' Some of the others I would
dismiss because of violence and inappropriate sexual situations.
I'd even avoid the family values shows _ ``Touched by an Angel,''
etc. _ because they're so smarmy and poorly written. But most of my
avoidance would be tied to coarse language and behavior, and it
would continue as long as lazy networks pay lazy writers who find
incivility appealing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
