<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Top Executives at Compaq Quit Amid Financial Turmoil
</P>
<P>
   In a fallout from its recent financial turmoil, Compaq Computer
said that its chief executive, Eckhard Pfeiffer, and its chief
financial officer, Earl L. Mason, had resigned. The company's
chairman and two vice chairmen were named to an office of the chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq said earlier this month that its first-quarter profits
would be less than half of what analysts had expected, dragged down
by declining sales and a shift into lower-margin products.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia Talks Are Approved
</P>
<P>
   Italy and Germany gave their approval for Telecom Italia to
continue merger discussions with Deutsche Telekom. The decision is
expected to complicate the struggle for control of Telecom Italia,
which faces a $65 billion hostile bid from its major Italian rival,
Olivetti.
</P>
<P>
   Exploring Anonymity on the Web
</P>
<P>
   At a conference last week to mark the 35th anniversary of the
founding of the Laboratory for Computer Science at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology, participants took part in a
spirited discussion on a seemingly narrow subject, an anonymous
remailer, which can be used to mask the origin of a piece of e-mail
or the computer from which a person is browsing the Web. But it was
a discussion that focused on some of the broadest social and legal
issues involving the Internet: free speech, identity, privacy and
anonymity, good-naturedly underscored by one panel member who wore
a black ski mask.
</P>
<P>
   Holding Money at Online Auctions
</P>
<P>
   As auction sites on the World Wide Web have soared in
popularity, Internet escrow services have also gained a following.
These services, in which a third party holds the money until both
buyer and seller are satisfied with the transaction, can reduce the
risk of fraud, bounced checks or goods that fall short of
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates Set for Registry Work
</P>
<P>
   The first five companies to compete with Network Solutions in
the business of registering Internet addresses will be selected
this week, even though the government has not yet made final the
terms under which the company will open its data base.
</P>
<P>
   Barriers Erode for TV News Shows
</P>
<P>
   The hierarchies and fiefs of television news are breaking down a
bit, driven by the networks' needs to cut costs and by new
management philosophies that see a need for broadcast news reports
to distinguish themselves from the reporting found on 24-hour cable
news networks, radio and the Internet. Increasingly, correspondents
are contributing reports to several programs, not just the one to
which they are assigned.
</P>
<P>
   Capital One Picks Outside Agency
</P>
<P>
   Capital One Financial, which is helping to rewrite the rules of
consumer marketing with intensive data mining _ using information
to sell in unconventional ways _ is hiring its first outside
agency. The company, one of the nation's largest issuers of credit
cards, will work with D'Arcy Masius Benton &AMP; Bowles Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Intel Chief Predicts Papers' Demise
</P>
<P>
   Andrew S. Grove, the chairman of Intel, told members of the
American Society of Newspaper Editors that the newspaper business
had three years to live. ``You are where Intel was three years
before the roof fell in on us,'' said Grove, referring to his
company's near-death experience in the late 1980s, when its
original product, memory chips, became unprofitable. His suggested
solution was to write and edit newspapers that play to the medium's
competitive advantage, its ability to bring perspective to the
tumbling cascade of news events.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
