<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3333 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-NYT &LR;      04-18 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS DELAYING EXPANSION OF REFUGEE CAMPS IN MACEDONIA,
OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRAZDA, Macedonia _ The majority of refugee camps in Macedonia
are filled to capacity, and delays in getting approval for camp
expansions are resulting in severe overcrowding, aid workers said
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The problem lies not in a lack of supplies or personnel, but in
getting approval from the Macedonian government to expand the
camps, the aid workers and Western diplomats said. They said they
saw the delays as a means of using refugees as political tool.
</P>
<P>
   President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia is widely seen here
as using the more than 125,000 refugees his forces have expelled
into Macedonia to destabilize this country and punish his political
enemies.
</P>
<P>
   And Macedonia, aid workers contend, is using the situation to
press Western countries and aid agencies to keep their promise of
airlifting the majority of refugees out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonian officials have vehemently denied that they are
mistreating or manipulating the refugees. In an interview last
week, Prime Minister Ljubco Georgievski said his government had
welcomed the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But aid workers say the government, while publicly professing
cooperation, is slow to show results. Western diplomats, who are
less critical of the government, say Georgievski is under intense
pressure to keep the refugee influx under control. Ethnic
Macedonians, who make up two-thirds of this country's population
and are Georgievski's political base, fear that if the influx of
refugees continues, ethnic Albanians could become the majority
here.
</P>
<P>
   A long planned expansion of the labyrinthine refugee camp here
in Brazda was delayed on Saturday after a group of local farmers
tore down two hundred refugee tents erected just outside the camp.
The protesting farmers, who said they owned the land, complained
that they were not informed of the expansion and that they oppose
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want compensation, we want our land,'' said one
farmer, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``Let them go to
Albania or Kosovo or wherever they want.'
</P>
<P>
   The resulting overcrowding raises tensions and could cause
health problems among the refugees. Fadil Berisha, a 36-year-old
farmer, said Sunday he has spent the last three nights sleeping
outside because there were no tents left when he and his family
arrived. After spending a night outside in the rain, his wife and
four children, including his five month old daughter, were taken
into a tent by another family.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 20 people staying in that tent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, Sedad Hoxha and his family live in a 10-foot-by-10-foot
tent that holds 16 adults and five children. He said camp officials
did nothing to help him after he arrived three days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day we arrived we slept, when we could, in the open in the
rain,'' he said. ``We made an agreement with some people and were
able to move in here''
</P>
<P>
   Anna Young, a coordinator for Catholic Relief Services, the aid
agency running the camp, said aid workers were trying to find space
for new arrivals in empty tents.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonian police held 700 refugees in a no man's land between
Kosovo and Macedonia for 24 hours, ending Sunday, without food,
water or medical care, aid workers said. One woman collapsed and
was taken away in an ambulance after the group was finally allowed
to cross the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Macedonians said there was no space for them in the
camps,'' said one frustrated aid worker. ``But the reasons there is
no place to put them, is that we can't get the authorization from
them to expand the camps.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
