A3343 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITAL-ONE-AD-COL-NY     04-18 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITAL-ONE-AD-COL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD COLUMN: CAPITAL ONE PICKS ITS FIRST OUTSIDE AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Conn., Calif., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A financial-services giant that is helping to rewrite the rules
of consumer marketing with intensive data mining _ using
information to sell in unconventional ways _ is hiring its first
outside agency.
</P>
<P>
   The company is Capital One Financial Corp. in Falls Church, Va.,
one of the nation's 10-largest issuers of credit cards, with 16.7
million customers and total balances of $17.4 billion. The agency
is D'Arcy Masius Benton &AMP; Bowles Communications in New York, a unit
of MacManus Group best known for campaigns for longtime clients
like General Motors, M&AMP;M/Mars and Procter &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Capital One, which has expanded into sales of services as
disparate as cellular telecommunications, insurance and membership
in buying clubs, is hiring DMB&AMP; B and MacManus sibling shops in the
United States, Britain and France to handle so-called integrated
communications assignments: work that will include conventional
advertising, media planning and buying, interactive marketing,
sales promotion and direct marketing. Capital One estimates that
spending could total $80 million to $100 million over the next
12-18 months.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of DMB&AMP; B by Capital One, which began in 1994 as a
spinoff of operations of Signet Banking Corp., reflects the
continuing search by large marketers for large agencies that offer
lengthy lists of services in many countries. The marketers are
seeking shops that can develop ideas to infuse all aspects of the
communications between brands and their potential and current
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to put your company in the position of never having
to guess about the marketplace,'' said William J. McDonald, the
senior vice president for brand marketing at Capital One, who
recently joined the company after stints with consumer marketers
like Boston Chicken Inc. and Pepsico Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Developing `trusted brand status' is a long journey,'' he
added, ``that requires great creative strategy from a global
partner to get you there.''
</P>
<P>
   Capital One has generated its rapid revenue and profit growth by
assiduously cultivating consumers, using what McDonald described as
an ``information-based strategy'' to analyze demographic and
behavioral data bases on tens of millions of potential and current
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lots of companies claim that they compete on knowledge,'' the
magazine Fast Company wrote in a glowing article about Capital One
in its May issue. ``Capital One has enough information on consumers
to fill the hard drives of more than 200,000 personal computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the products Capital One sells through its sophisticated
information technology are so-called affinity credit cards, bearing
logos of animals, automobiles or countries; cellular calls, under
the name America One Communications; merchandise catalogs; credit
reports; insurance, and automotive loans.
</P>
<P>
   One unconventional way the company peddles its wares turns the
practice of telemarketing inside out: Rather than have employees
call consumers at home, employees try selling goods and services to
customers who call Capital One when they have questions about their
accounts or credit limits.
</P>
<P>
   Capital One's top executives ``see themselves as
`infomediaries,' '' said John Farrell, president of DMB&AMP; B North
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scale of what they do is fantastic,'' he added. ``We have
to connect with consumers in as innovative a way as they operate as
a business, bringing together all our resources and presenting them
as seamless.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the agencies Capital One will use are the London, New
York, Paris and St. Louis offices of DMB&AMP; B, for advertising;
Televest in New York, media; Blue Marble in New York, interactive;
Clarion Marketing and Communications in Greenwich, Conn., sales
promotion and direct marketing, and Highway One in San Francisco,
affinity marketing. Capital One will continue working with a unit
of Omnicom Group, Interbrand in New York, for corporate identity
and design.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agencies have always been known for adding value by looking at
clients' businesses from a customer perspective,'' said Susan
Gianinno, executive vice president and chief branding and marketing
officer at DMB&AMP; B. ``Now you have a company that's so data-rich,
whose core competency is knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Capital One began searching for an agency in December. Morgan
Anderson Consulting in New York managed the review, McDonald said,
and ``helped us steer through a minefield of competitive
conflicts.''
</P>
<P>
   Most big agencies have accounts in categories like credit cards,
telecommunications or insurance. Capital One's activity in those
fields and others was a complication.
</P>
<P>
   DMB&AMP; B, however, did not have conflicts; its last
telecommunications client, for instance, was SBC Communications,
which consolidated accounts at other agencies in July by
eliminating DMB&AMP; B in St. Louis from its roster.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald declined to identify the other agencies taking part in
the review. DMB&AMP; B ``was the best solution,'' he said, ``not just
because of conflict but because of the breadth of resources.'' He
also praised DMB&AMP; B campaigns for P&AMP; G and a new client, Ernst &AMP;
Young.
</P>
<P>
   And surely it could not have hurt that McDonald had worked
before with Ms. Gianinno, when he was at the KFC unit of Pepsico
and she was at Young &AMP; Rubicam Advertising and when he was at
Boston Chicken and she was at the J. Walter Thompson unit of WPP
Group PLC.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's following me,'' Ms. Gianinno said, laughing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
