<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Monday, April 19. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN (Undated) _ If you're interviewing the state's
best speller, you might as well ask him to perform for you. Some
might think the request a bit rude, putting him on the spot like
that. But to his credit, Abdul Kahsai showed none of the reluctance
of a doctor at a cocktail party who balks at listening to someone
drone on about an ingrown toenail. The 12-year-old seventh grader
at Taylor Junior High School, in Mesa, jumped right in and clicked
off pestiferous and diagensesis without a hitch. By BILL
GOODYKOONTZ. Story will move in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
JEROMEHOTEL (Jerome, AZ) Like a fortress atop Cleopatra Hill, this
relic mining-company hospital sat empty for 45 years before it was
brought back to life in 1996 as the Jerome Grand Hotel. But the
hotel's owners pulled the plug in January and the 1926 landmark is
back on life support, awaiting an April 30 auction that could lure
a new owner and another revival. Potential buyers will have to
consider the viability of the hotel, which was in business just 18
months. By Peter Corbett. Story will move in the A category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MAKINGLAWS (undated) Second installment in a series. The jokes have
been making the rounds all morning in the state House of
Representatives. They involve Rep. Kathleen Dunbar, R-Tucson, who
moderate legislators believe agreed to cave in to conservative
leaders on a crucial vote on the state budget. Dunbar, an animal
rights activist, has been pushing her own legislation against
animal cruelty and domestic violence. Rep. Susan Gerard, leader of
the moderate ``Mushroom Coalition,'' repeats one of the jokes to a
group of fellow legislators: ``Did you hear that leadership is
threatening Dunbar? They say they've gone to the animal shelters
and they'll be killing one animal every hour until she gives in.''
By JULIE AMPARANO. Story will move in the A category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
WORKWEEK (undated) Let's proclaim today
Try-to-Get-Some-Real-Work-Done Day. First of all, it needs to be
adopted, proclaimed or otherwise sponsored to fit in with the rest
of the week. From bringing daughters to work to honoring
secretaries, almost every day this week has been monikered for some
cause. And Thursday has two. Tuesday is Telework Greater Phoenix
Day, which means we all should be home wearing bathrobes as we type
and handle the phones. Razor stubble is mandatory for men. Makeup
is banned for women. By JONATHAN SIDENER. Story will move in the A
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BOOKS (Gila River Indian Community) One January day, journalist
Claude Jackson was in the Gila River Indian Community's only public
library and decided to look for his favorite author. A 26-year-old
Pima Indian, reporter for the Gila River Indian Newspaper and
English literature graduate from Arizona State University, Jackson
likes to read a few passages in his spare time from the Bard of
Avon. To his dismay, the Sacaton library's only William Shakespeare
offering was a copy of King Lear. Shakespeare isn't the only thing
the Ira Hayes Memorial Library is missing. It's missing most of the
1990s. That's about to change. By BETTY BEARD. Story will move in
the A category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
REMAINS (WINDOW ROCK) For almost 50 years in the late 1800s and
early 1900s, museums from across the country paid archaeologists to
excavate Southwestern Indian burial sites, collecting tens of
thousands of human remains and a huge assortment of pottery, crafts
and sacred items buried with the bodies. But while most tribes in
recent years have been working with museums to get these items
returned to their homelands, officials for the Navajo Nation have
been taking a very cautious position. They're saying that _ at
least for now _ they would just as soon allow these items to remain
in the museums. By BILL DONOVAN. Story will move in the A
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
COYOTES (PHOENIX) When Daryl Abbott got the call that a coyote was
lying near death in the shade of a paloverde, he was almost sure
what had happened. Arriving on the scene near the border of
Carefree and Cave Creek, he watched the coyote's svelte body move
slightly with each shallow breath before scooping her up. Clinging
to life, her listless body hung from Abbott's arms as he took her
to an emergency animal clinic. With veins pulsing with poison, the
coyote died just moments later. The death was one of about
seven &UR; the rehabilitation center has responded to this year in the
far north Valley to be blamed on Warfarin, a powerful rodenticide
passed to animals that consume poisoned rodents like mice and rats.
Pet also are in danger. By BRIAN ANDERSON. Story will move in the A
category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
