<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: NEW THRILLS FROM NEW ZEALAND WITH THE `FLY BY WIRE';
INSURANCE FOR TRADE SECRETS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Nev., Texas., Calif.)   By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Strung across a valley in Queenstown, New Zealand, is an
amusement park ride that makes bungee-jumping look tame. It
combines bungee features with elements of trapeze and aircraft
flight, allowing thrill-seekers to swing through the air at the end
of a tethered cable at speeds up to 120 miles an hour, piloting a
one-man craft shaped like a B-movie rocket ship in any direction
they want.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Harrap invented and built the ride he calls Fly by Wire.
Now he has won a U.S. patent for his daring toy and is scouting
locations in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Stringing it across the Las Vegas Strip, he says, would be a
good place to start.
</P>
<P>
   Harrap, a property developer in Wellington, New Zealand, got the
idea for his ride in the middle of the night a few years ago. ``I
woke up at four in the morning with the idea for a swing that would
move in figure-eights,'' he said while in New York last week. ``It
was a swing that could change directions in the air, and out of
that came the seed of an idea.''
</P>
<P>
   That seed grew into a design for a narrow, missile-shaped plane
with a cutout for a pilot and powered by a 60-horsepower aircraft
engine. A single pilot, lying on his stomach, is strapped into the
craft with a five-point harness and ankle clips. His arms extended
in front of him, and he controls steering and acceleration with his
hands.
</P>
<P>
   In New Zealand, the aircraft is suspended above ground from a
cable tethered to a line strung across a canyon. In the United
States, Harrap plans to anchor that line from towers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 1,400 feet across and 340 feet from the ground,'' he
said. ``A single wire, three-eighths of an inch in diameter, comes
down from that, and it carries the weight of the plane and pilot
and takes care of the additional G-forces generated, because it can
pull up to three times gravity during the middle of the flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's sufficient strength in the steel cable to accommodate
that,'' he continued. ``We're running the cable at 10 percent of
its load capacity. There's no single load path so there's no single
path to break and be catastrophic.''
</P>
<P>
   The craft has a conventional-shaped tail for stabilization, a
five-bladed rear-mounted propeller inside a circular drum that
looks like a giant fan, and a four-stroke aircraft engine. At the
beginning of the ride, a winch lifts the plane seven or eight feet
off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It pulls the plane backward the same way you'd pull a child
back on a swing, up to the desired height for launch,'' Harrap
said. ``At any point on the way up, the pilot can release. He can
get a little way up and think it's scary and release from there,
giving it as much acceleration as he wants. The steering is
controlled with both hands, pretty much the way you steer a bike.''
</P>
<P>
   The winch can lift a the craft clear of its launch deck and a
cautious pilot can simply ``give it a bit of gas and fly in a
circle, backward, forward or wherever he wants to go,'' Harrap
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Away he goes, all downhill and up the other side,'' said
Harrap, who has ridden his own ride. ``Lots of people go slowly at
the start, but within a minute or two they're flying as fast as
they can as they gain confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Pilots can then swish through the air in figure-eights, loops,
arcs or wild swings. Harrap is careful to point out that his ride
``doesn't fly; it's a powered swinging device.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the design, the worst that can happen if you don't
pilot it well is it will go slow,'' Harrap said. ``We believe it is
completely idiot-proof. No matter what you do, you can't hit
yourself, anyone else or any object. It's not powerful enough to go
up and strike the support cables.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrap says none of his passengers in New Zealand have ``gotten
sick, taken a fit, or passed out'' on the six-minute ride, which
costs about $70.
</P>
<P>
   He was in the United States to scout locations in Las Vegas,
Texas and California and to talk to tower construction companies.
``The first in the U.S. will be in year-round locations,'' he said.
He has a Web site at www.flybywire.co.nz featuring a short snippet
of video of the New Zealand ride. He also holds patent 5,782,699.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance For Trade Secrets
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to the growing value of intellectual property as a
business asset, the CNA Financial Corp. of Chicago has announced
that it is offering what it says is the first insurance policy to
cover financial losses from the theft of trade secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secrets must be owned by the company and be in a recorded
form, either formulas, patterns, compilations, programs, devices,
methods, techniques or processes,'' CNA said. ``The policy includes
coverage for ideas designed for commercial use, which have economic
value because they are not being generally known.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan could pay benefits up to $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
