<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO KISSES FOR THIS CLUELESS FROG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ I'd call Reggie White a fat toad, except knowing
the way he looks at things he'd probably take that to mean I want
to kiss him so I can find my prince and live happily ever after.
</P>
<P>
   But seriously, it must be nice to live in White's fairy-tale
world, where no stereotype is too gauche to mention and men of the
cloth don't have to be broad-minded as long as they're
broad-shouldered.
</P>
<P>
   White, an ordained minister who recently retired from the NFL,
ought to know he isn't the only one who talks to heaven. I rang God
just the other day and, boy, was She mad!
</P>
<P>
   I can't say I was surprised. I was feeling a little out of sorts
myself after I saw what White had to say about female
sportswriters.
</P>
<P>
   My initial reaction was that White must be talking about women
in another profession. My husband has no misgivings about me
entering the war zone known as the men's locker room, so why should
White?
</P>
<P>
   Before reading published excerpts from White's book, ``Fighting
the Good Fight,'' I had no idea anybody was ``forcing male athletes
to walk around naked in front of women who aren't their wives.''
</P>
<P>
   I've seen plenty of towels and bathrobes in locker rooms before,
but never anybody holding a gun to the head of an athlete as he
walked, dripping wet, from the showers to his dressing cubicle.
</P>
<P>
   White sees no reason why any athlete, male or female, should be
put in such a compromising position. On this White and I are of one
mind. That's why I have no problem standing outside a closed locker
room immediately after a college or pro game for a mandatory
cooling-off period that can last 20 minutes or more.
</P>
<P>
   If that's not enough time for the athletes inside to shower and
dress, well, that's what the towels and bathrobes are for.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I'd notice either way. When White says ``I've seen a
lot of female reporters and camerawomen ogling guys in the locker
room,'' I have no earthly idea who he is talking about.
</P>
<P>
   Methinks he flatters himself. Because all the female
sportswriters I know would sooner pose in a bikini next to a
``Sports Illustrated'' swimsuit model than step inside a men's
locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Not since junior-high dances have I been exposed (pardon the
pun) to anything so excruciatingly awkward. When female sports
journalists aren't talking to athletes, you'll find most of us
staring intently at some water spot on the ceiling or studying the
nameplates above the individual locker stalls.
</P>
<P>
   The bare truth is, the locker room is no place for journalists
of any gender. But until somebody comes up with a more practical
way for us to conduct interviews under tight time constraints,
it'll have to do.
</P>
<P>
   When White maligned Asians and Hispanics and Caucasians and
Native Americans under the guise of praising them last year, people
were swift to react in the sports sections and on the Op-Ed pages.
Strangely, his latest incendiary remarks have drawn a big yawn from
almost everyone save the surfer on the Internet who offered his
support of White and said, ``The next thing you know women
reporters will be allowed in men's bathrooms, too.''
</P>
<P>
   I guess the guy never has seen ``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone suggested to me that if White is being roundly ignored,
it's only because that's how villages treat their idiots.
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to believe that. I'd like to think silence, in this
case, isn't a nod of approval. But how do I explain the strains of
intolerance that play over and over on my office voice mail? The
lyrics go like this:
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)``You should stick to female basketball, female
badminton. Why don't you go away from real sports that men
play?''(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   And this:
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)``You should stick to knitting. That's where you
belong. I think you can get a job on the Home Shopping
Network.''(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   And this: (begin ital)``What the &AMP; do you know about sports,
$$?(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   As for White and all the anonymous men in his chorus, I can't
speak for their anatomies. But I can say they have awfully small
minds. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
