<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3359 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPAQ-RESIGN19-COX     04-18 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-RESIGN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Compaq chief executive resigns
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In its second industry-shaking announcement in less
than two weeks, Compaq Computer Corp. said Sunday that Chief
Executive Eckhard Pfeiffer and the company's chief financial
officer resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, the world's biggest personal computer maker and the No.
2 company behind IBM in overall computer revenue, said in a
statement Sunday that the board of directors formed a three-member
office of the executive to run the company until a replacement for
the 57-year-old Pfeiffer is named.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation came 10 days after Compaq shocked Wall Street
with the warning, in a statement issued after market closed on
April 9, that first-quarter earnings will be about half of the $530
million that investors had expected. Pressure from analysts, whose
companies advise millions of stockholders, and from pension funds,
which own millions of Compaq shares, forced the company to hold two
conference calls April 12 to shed light on the shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Compaq shares plunged about 23 percent last Monday. They
closed Friday at $23.60 on Friday, less than half their high in
January of $51.25.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer blamed Compaq's problems, in part, on industrywide
pressures. But analysts refuted that, saying Dell Computer Corp.
and other computer makers appeared to be having good quarters.
Then, on Tuesday, Intel Corp. reported healthy profit of $2 billion
for its first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Because Intel supplies the chips that run most of the world's
computers, that strongly suggested other PC companies such as Dell
Computer Corp. and Gateway Inc. were not plagued by Compaq's woes.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trying period for Compaq, its credibility became
an issue. On one front, analysts openly questioned whether it could
forecast demand for its products. At the same time, they wondered
why it took so long for the company to identify the size of the
shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got no indication from the company up till the last week of
the quarter,'' Cody Acree of Southwest Securities in Dallas said
Sunday. ``We kept hearing that February was better and March was
better than that. They probably had better indications (of
weakness) than they were letting on.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dube of Wasserstein Perella Securities in New York likened
Compaq's performance _ meeting Wall Streets expectations one
quarter and missing it the next _ to a bumper-car ride at a
carnival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's this careening ... from one wall to another,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Acree was surprised by the resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very drastic step taken in response to something
that maybe was not that serious,'' he said, adding that a rebound
by Compaq in the second quarter would have redeemed Pfeiffer.
</P>
<P>
   Ashok Kumar of Piper Jaffray, a securities company in
Minneapolis, called the move ``a step in the positive direction.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Compaq's credibility on Wall Street had been hurt too
badly for Pfeiffer to continue effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been so much bad blood spilled between management and
the street,'' Kumar said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the resignations and Chief Financial Officer Earl Mason
are sure to further rattle the company as it heads into an
important week. Compaq reports first-quarter earnings on Wednesday
and holds its annual shareholders meeting at its Houston
headquarters on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compaq has come a long way since I joined the company in
1983,'' Pfeiffer said in a statement Sunday. ``We are a world
leader in personal computing, enterprise computing and Internet
applications. ''
</P>
<P>
   The company formed a committee of three board members to take on
chief executive duties while the executive-search firm Heidrick &AMP;
Struggles, which a spokesman said Compaq retained over the weekend,
sounds out possible successors to Pfeiffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have re-energized this company before, and working
together, we will do it again,'' Compaq Chairman Ben Rosen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will prove to every customer that this is the best company
to serve their information technology needs. And we will confirm to
our investors that Compaq remains a core holding in any
portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   The German-born Pfeiffer joined Compaq in 1983, one year after
it was founded.
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming CEO in 1991, Pfeiffer guided Compaq to a position
of leadership in the PC industry. The company is still trying to
digest his most ambitious move, the 1998 acquisition of Digital
Computer Corp. That and the 1997 acquisition of Tandem Computers
Inc. were designed to lift Compaq to a higher level than a PC
maker.
</P>
<P>
   In the view of some investors, Compaq has not assimilated
Digital's divisions quickly enough.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
