<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rocker says inactivity hurt rhythm
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ A day after blowing his first save opportunity as the
Braves closer, John Rocker was still seething a bit. Part of that
is his personality. Part is the fact that he hadn't given up a run
since last Sept. 9, and there he was giving up three in one inning
to lose Saturday's game against the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker had pitched 27 consecutive scoreless outings dating to
last September against the Expos. The streak extended through six
regular-season outings, eight in the postseason, 10 in spring
training and three to start the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   With another day's perspective, Rocker conceded that having
eight days since his previous outing did come into play in the
ninth inning Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``After some consistent work, I'll get my rhythm back,'' Rocker
said. ``I'd thrown two innings in the last week and a half. When I
get back pitching every day, every two or three days, I'll be a lot
more comfortable with what I'm doing and my sharpness will come
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker also figures he was over-compensating in his first
appearance in Coors Field. Hearing that breaking balls don't bite
as much in the thin air, he was trying to put a little more break
into his slider and the results weren't good. Remlinger ready
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Mike Remlinger came off the disabled list and pitched a
scoreless inning in Sunday's game, striking out two. To make room
on the roster for the veteran left-hander, the Braves optioned
lefty Derrin Ebert to Class AAA Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   For Remlinger, it's been a tough way to start his career with
the Braves, waiting through 10 games before he'd get a chance to
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in a situation where you want to go out and prove you
can help this team win and you can't do anything,'' he said.
Remlinger also reported that the muscle in his back is healed.
</P>
<P>
   He gives the Braves another experienced arm in a relatively
young bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Patience pays off
</P>
<P>
   At one time one of the most impatient bats in the lineup, Andruw
Jones is showing patience. He drew three walks in Saturday's game
against the Rockies to bring his season total to eight in 10 games,
which leads the Braves. He's not far off Rickey Henderson's
National league-leading 13 walks.
</P>
<P>
   Jones had 40 walks all last year _ in 159 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm learning to be patient,'' Jones said. ``They're going to
have to throw three good pitches to strike me out, and that's hard
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He had five hits and six RBIs on Sunday, raising his batting
average from .156 to .263.
</P>
<P>
   But he's more interested in just being patient, learning a
lesson from a recent game in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get a hit bad. I swung at a bad pitch and got a
ground ball,'' Jones said. ``You're stupid if you keep swinging at
bad pitches. Go ahead and take your walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Klesko setback
</P>
<P>
   After taking his first swings in batting practice Saturday since
pulling his hamstring Wednesday, Ryan Klesko took a step back on
Sunday, feeling soreness in his leg. He's still not sure when he'll
be able to return.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
