<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta bid considered for Women's Final Four
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the place where the Women's Final Four emerged as a
major national sporting event six years ago, Atlanta also could
play a key role in pushing its popularity into the dome era.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the NCAA Women's Basketball Committee are in town
today and Tuesday to consider a bid by the Atlanta Sports Council
and Georgia Tech that features two possible venues for the 2003
Final Four: the Georgia Dome or the new Philips Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Omni played host to a pre-sellout Women's Final Four in
1993, when Sheryl Swoopes led Texas Tech to the title by scoring an
NCAA championship game record 47 points before a crowd of 16,141.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the event has blossomed, with a record 23,291 in
Charlotte in 1996 watching Tennessee defeat Georgia for the
championship. Last month's title game victory by Purdue over Duke
drew a 4.3 television rating, the second-highest ever for a college
basketball game on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30,000 applications for next year's Women's Final Four
at Philadelphia's First Union Center have been accepted for a
ticket lottery. In 2002, a women's national champion will be
crowned for the first time in a dome in San Antonio's Alamodome,
which will have projected minimum seating of 26,000.
</P>
<P>
   Other venues competing against Atlanta are the Charlotte
Coliseum, the Pyramid in Memphis and the Palace of Auburn Hills
near Detroit, with a decision expected in late June.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the committee decides to go big, then they've got to go
with us,'' Atlanta Sports Council President Gary Stokan said. ``If
they go small, then we've got a brand new attractive arena to play
in.''
</P>
<P>
   The only time women have competed in the Georgia Dome was during
the 1996 Olympics, when nearly 35,000 witnessed the gold medal game
won by the United States over Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Stokan said a projected Georgia Dome configuration similar to
the Alamodome is part of the bid, while the Philips Arena will hold
around 20,000 for basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bid meets two criteria that we have,'' Stokan said.
``It's a major college sporting event, and it's a mega-sporting
event in general. Women's basketball is one of the big growth
sports out there, and we want to continue to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the estimated economic impact of hosting the Women's
Final Four would be around $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
