<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Redskins clearing a spot for Bailey
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It should not take long for former Georgia star Champ
Bailey to earn the starting job at left cornerback with the
Washington Redskins. Barring an unexpected change of heart, the
Skins will release incumbent starter Cris Dishman today, clearing
the way for Bailey to line up opposite Darrell Green as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey still will have to compete for the job with four-year pro
Darryl Pounds, who also has played free safety. But the Skins
triumvirate of general manager Charley Casserly, coach Norv Turner
and defensive coordinator Mike Nolan reiterated Sunday that they
expect Bailey to make an immediate impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the best athletes to come into the league in a few
years,'' Casserly said. ``It would be a surprise to all of us if he
didn't help us right away.''
</P>
<P>
   What genius?
</P>
<P>
   The true gauge will come a few years down the road, but the
early read on Bill Walsh's first draft back with the 49ers is that
``The Genius'' had a dubious return. In the first round, Walsh
filled a huge need, trading up to snatch Florida defensive tackle
Reggie McGrew. But some scouts question how effective McGrew will
be, pointing out that his arms were amont the shortest ever
measured at the combine. In the third round, the pick was Purdue
defensive end Chike Okeafor, who tested positive for marijuana in
college. With the second choice in Round 6, San Francisco took
Michigan wide receiver Tai Streets, who could miss the entire
season because of an Achilles' injury sustained in a pickup
basketball game a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Poindexter finally taken
</P>
<P>
   Had he left school after his junior season, Virginia safety
Anthony Poindexter likely would have been a first-round pick. But
he stayed with the Cavaliers and seriously injured a knee last
October. The injury caused him to drop to the seventh round, where
he was selected by Baltimore, and might keep him out his entire
rookie season. ``Everybody plays the `what if' game,'' Poindexter
said. ``I'll just have to make up on my second contract all the
money this cost me on my first one.''
</P>
<P>
   The big reach
</P>
<P>
   San Diego general manager Bobby Beathard continued his penchant
for selecting players from small schools. Among the Chargers'
choices were tight end Steve Heiden (South Dakota State), guard
Reggie Nelson (McNeese State) and defensive back Tyrone Bell
(Northern Alabama). Beathard is fond of trading the next year's
first-round choice for a pick in the current draft. He couldn't do
that this year, because he already dealt his top pick in the 2000
draft to Tampa Bay last spring. Beathard twice refused during the
draft to deal his first pick in the 2001 draft to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Brown-out
</P>
<P>
   When the '98 college season began, Cuncho Brown of Penn State
and Georgia's Larry Brown were the top-rated tight ends in the
country. This weekend, they weren't even selected in the draft.
Other notables who went unselected: running back Devin West
(Missouri), tight end Rufus French (Mississippi), safety Gana
Joseph (Oklahoma), safety Marcus Ray (Michigan) and cornerback
Chris Cummings (LSU).
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Northeast Louisiana isn't a powerhouse, but the school had
defensive ends selected on back-to-back picks in the sixth round,
Robert Daniel to Carolina and Lionel Barnes to St. Louis. ... The
Colts took Notre Dame punter Hunter Smith in the seventh round. The
team's trainer also is named Hunter Smith, but the two are not
related. . . . Baltimore bolstered its shaky offensive line by
trading for veteran guard Everett Lindsay of Minnesota. ... Among
the players not selected was Weber State wideout John Fassell. He
is the son of New York Giants coach Jim Fassell. ... There were 26
trades during the draft
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
