<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Mayor of Eldoret' favored to continue reign
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Back home in Eldoret, in the Rift Valley of western
Kenya, Moses Tanui runs freely through the countryside. He prefers
to train solo in this land of world-class runners. They call him
the Mayor of Eldoret, and he laughs when it's mentioned,
emphasizing that it is an honorary, not elective, title.
</P>
<P>
   That he is the point man of the Kenyan contingent in town for
the 103rd running of the Boston Marathon is no laughing matter.
Tanui, one of the world's best distance runners, is a major part of
Boston history. He won the centennial celebration three years ago
and eked out another win last April. This afternoon, the favorite's
role is his again.
</P>
<P>
   The best bet of the day is that a Kenyan will be wearing the
laurel wreath at race's end. It's been that way the past eight
years.
</P>
<P>
   The dominance began in 1988, when Ibrahim Hussein of Kenya
became the first African to win Boston. Hussein wore the laurel
wreath twice more, in 1991 and 1992. Fellow Kenyan Cosmas Ndeti won
the next three. Tanui took the titles in '96 and last year.
</P>
<P>
   Until Hussein broke through, first winning the New York Marathon
in 1987, Kenyans were relative foreigners to the marathon. They won
medals for shorter races on the track, but they feared that the
marathon distance was beyond their range.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were cautious about the marathon,'' said Tanui, who smiles
frequently and speaks in a soft voice. ``People would say, `You ran
a marathon? Did you finish?' They thought the marathon was a very
difficult race.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanui's breakthrough came on the track, in the 1991 World
Championships in Tokyo, where he won the 10,000 meters ahead of
countryman Richard Chelimo and the great Moroccan, Kahlid Skah. He
later moved up to the marathon.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the 100th edition of Boston in 1996, Tanui decided
to bypass the Atlanta Olympic marathon in favor of the 10,000, but
he was slowed by an Achilles injury and failed to make the Kenyan
team.
</P>
<P>
   While Tanui races his countrymen today for a third title in four
years, Fatuma Roba _ best remembered for her unexpected victory at
the Atlanta Olympics _ will take on an even stronger field in her
bid to join Uta Pippig as winner of three Boston women's titles in
a row.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a knee injury that worsened during the race last year,
Roba persevered to finish in 2 hours, 23 minutes, 21 seconds, the
third-fastest woman in Boston history behind only Pippig (2:21:45)
and Joan Benoit Samuelson (2:22:43). Look for Roba to be challenged
by last year's runner-up, Renata Paradowska of Poland, along with
road-racing champion Colleen De Reuck of South Africa, reigning New
York City Marathon champ Franca Fiacconi of Italy and 1997 New York
winner Franziska Rochat-Moser of Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   A popular wild card in these parts is Lynn Jennings, 38, who
lives in neighboring Maine and is making her official marathon
debut. Jennings is a three-time World Cross-Country champion and
the 1992 Olympic bronze medalist in the 10,000 meters, for which
she still holds the American record.
</P>
<P>
   As a 17-year-old, Jennings ran Boston without an official
number, finishing in 2:46 _ which would have been good enough for
third place. The mystery is why she never tried again. She claims
it was her versatility and success on the track that kept her away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had done one earlier,'' Jennings said, ``perhaps I
wouldn't have accomplished all that I have.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
