<HEADER>
A3365 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXCLUSIVE-PAGER-ALLIA     04-18 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-PAGER-ALLIANCE-740&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAGING ALLIES FOCUS STRATEGY ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Texas., N.C., Canada)  (EXCLUSIVE; 10:45 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 12:01 a.m. ET
EMBARGO for electronic media.) 
(js) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Threatened by the specter of irrelevance in an era of
near-ubiquitous cellular phones and e-mail, most of the nation's
largest paging companies have formed an alliance to deploy
inexpensive hand-held computers that use a new two-way wireless
technology developed by Motorola Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The companies intend to announce the alliance Monday at the
Comdex technology conference in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   With the explosion in use of wireless telephones, the paging
business has come under intense pressure in recent years. Some 73
million people in the United States now use wireless phones,
compared with only about 56 million who use pagers.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, the increasing use of wireless phones has forced
paging companies to slash prices. It is big news in the paging
industry these days when a paging carrier makes any money.
</P>
<P>
   And as communications equipment makers begin incorporating
e-mail and in some cases rudimentary World Wide Web browsers into
wireless phones, paging companies face an even greater threat.
</P>
<P>
   The new alliance may be the paging industry's best-coordinated
and most comprehensive response. The group is in discussions with
Microsoft Corp. and 3Com Corp. about incorporating the new Motorola
technology into hand-held computers that use Microsoft's Windows CE
and 3Com's Palm operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   The paging alliance is based on a simple concept: Wireless
phones that include Web services generally do not allow people to
talk and surf at the same time. When the user is talking, the
screen is generally pressed against the person's cheek, making it
impossible to, say, negotiate a meeting time while actually looking
at one's schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The paging companies want to sell small units that are separate
from a phone but that could include a small keyboard, e-mail
access, a datebook and address book and that would have a battery
life measured in weeks instead of days or hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our vision of the future is that most people will carry two
wireless devices,'' said John D. Beletic, chairman of the new
alliance and chairman of Pagemart Wireless Inc., one of the largest
paging companies. ``One is going to be a telephone, and the
characteristics of the telephone are that they are going to get
smaller and smaller and smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``But when you use this phone maybe you wanted to set
up a lunch with me, and while you're talking to me you may be
wanting to look at your calendar. Or I'm giving you important
information and you want to enter that into a data device. And
these devices won't be optimized for voice. They will have
calendar, memos, directory, text messaging, and from a wireless
standpoint it will be optimized to penetrate into buildings and
will be optimized to work for weeks on a couple of double-A
batteries.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, such devices already exist. American Mobile Satellite
Corp. and BellSouth Corp.'s wireless data unit, which used to be
known as Ram Mobile Data, offer advanced two-way paging services
using small units made by Research in Motion Ltd. of Canada, based
partly on technology from Ericsson of Sweden. Skytel Communications
Inc., one of the paging carriers in the new alliance, already
offers two-way service using units from Motorola and Glenayre
Technologies Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we have the best performance from a network
standpoint,'' John Kampfe, a spokesman for the BellSouth wireless
data operation, said. ``The latency of messages is in seconds
rather than minutes, which allows people to chat from their
devices.''
</P>
<P>
   But the current generation of two-way pagers generally does not
offer true nationwide coverage, since most reach only big cities.
Nor do they use popular operating systems, though that will soon
change because the upcoming Palm VII organizer will use the
BellSouth network. The new paging alliance wants to offer service
everywhere in the nation and to incorporate the new Motorola
technology, known as Reflex, not only in the Windows CE and Palm
operating systems but also into devices that use Sun Microsystems
Inc.'s Java programming language.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paging has really had to in many ways redefine itself as an
extension of the desktop computer as opposed to a cheaper method of
staying in touch,'' said Jeanine M. Oburchay, a wireless analyst
for Bear, Stearns. ``The advanced networks we're seeing built out
now are the paging industry's way of redefining itself into a
remote messaging industry or remote e-mail industry.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Beletic said Pagemart, which is based in Dallas, spent about
$310 million to upgrade its network for the new devices, which
could also subscribe to data services like weather information,
sports scores or stock quotations. He wants to begin offering
advanced two-way services later this year and wants to persuade
makers of standard hand-held computers to incorporate the new
wireless technology by early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Under license from Motorola, Glenayre, of Charlotte, N.C., is
also developing chips for the new technology, which is a wireless
system based loosely on the programming language of the Internet.
The availability of Glenayre's products could help draw in
developers wary of relying on a single technology vendor, in this
case Motorola, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   The paging carriers participating in the alliance are Airtouch,
Arch Communications, Conxus, Metrocall, Mobilecomm, Pagemart,
Pagenet, Skytel and TSR Wireless. The only major paging carrier
that had not yet signed on as of Friday was Ameritech Corp.'s
paging unit.
</P>
</TEXT>
