<HEADLINE>
DOLE KNUCKLES RAPPED
</HEADLINE>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Lou Sheldon &LR; , chairman of the Traditional Values Coalition, has
written to  &UR; Bob Dole &LR;  complaining about the former presidential
candidate's Viagra ads. What's bothering Sheldon is that Dole said
the drug could be beneficial to ``millions of men and their
partners,'' rather than ``millions of men and their spouses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of the word `partner' is problematic,'' Sheldon wrote
to Dole. ``It is inconsistent with the common sense, traditional
values of Bob and  &UR; Elizabeth Dole &LR;  that Americans know.''
</P>
<P>
   sh2,10p10 Lenin Loses in Vegas
</P>
<P>
   rt,10p10 A 20-foot statue of  &UR; Vladimir Lenin &LR;  that was installed
at the Mandalay Bay resort near the Red Square vodka bar,
overlooking the slot machines, has been modified. Lenin's head has
been sawed off _ to be turned into a table base in the bar _ and
his body has been splattered with white paint that looks like bird
droppings.
</P>
<P>
   The beheading of the statue, installed as a piece of kitsch
comparable to miniature versions of the Eiffel Tower and that sort
of thing at other Las Vegas resorts, is in response to complaints
from servicemen and -women and patrons who likened it to a statue
of Hitler or Mussolini.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's any confusion about the symbolism, that now goes
away,'' said  &UR; Sarah Ralston &LR; , spokesperson for Circus Circus, which
built Mandalay Bay.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ALL KINDS OF VOICES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - A Pulitzer Prize awarded last week to Los Angeles Times
reporters  &UR; Chuck Philips &LR;  and  &UR; Michael Hiltzik &LR;  cited their expose
of MusiCares, a fund administered by the National Academy of
Recording Arts and Sciences. The formal Pulitzer citation called it
a ``charity scam,'' a term that was not employed by the original
story.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Michael Greene &LR; , CEO of NARAS, told the Chicago Tribune that
NARAS, outraged by the term, is having its lawyers contact Pulitzer
Prize officials.
</P>
<P>
   - When 12 children born blind were videotaped answering spoken
questions, the gestures they made with their hands proved that
gesturing is an innate human instinct.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Indiana University and the University of Chicago,
whose work is reported in Health magazine, found that blind
children moved their hands as sighted children do. When they talked
about pouring from a glass, for example, they cupped one hand and
tilted it. The blind children gestured as often as children who
could see.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think gesturing is part of the thinking process,'' said
 &UR; Jana Iverson &LR;  of Indiana University, explaining that somehow the
motion helps the brain define what in a thought needs emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   - Walking near a construction worker's pick- &LR; up at a building
site at Geary and Leavenworth,  &UR; Ken Maley &LR;  was astounded at the
sound of the truck's alarm, a voice that kept repeating, ``I've
been tampered with, I've been tampered ...''
</P>
<P>
   _Amorous young Middle Easterners, forbidden to directly approach
members of the opposite sex in public, are driving around with
pairs of cell phones in their cars, reports the Economist. If a
young woman catches a young man's eye, he tosses one of the phones
at her feet, then calls her and introduces himself.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Krause Publications, which puts out magazines about hobbies,
is joining forces with the online auction house eBay to create eBay
magazine, which they describe as ``a monthly lifestyle publication
... geared to millions of Internet-savvy collecting consumers.''
The first issue will be on newsstands in September.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Neve Campbell &LR;  told Jane magazine that she doesn't like being
waited on by aides when she's working. ``I don't like it when
people are touching me all day. I love doing things for people. I
would love to have the time to get my own coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   - Six  &UR; Joe DiMaggio &LR;  baseball cards will go on display in the
American Wing of the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York on
April 20, reports artnet.com. The exhibit is in conjunction with
DiMaggio Day, April 25, at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The cards were in a collection of 300,000 donated by
 &UR; Jefferson Burdick &LR; , an electrician who left them to the Met when he
died in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
