<HEADER>
A3382 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-     04-18 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CAMPAIGN, REFORM, AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, April 19:
</P>
<P>
   The fight over campaign finance reform has now begun in earnest.
By the close of business Friday, 189 Democrats in the House of
Representatives had signed a petition to force a floor vote on
legislation that would outlaw the unlimited, unregulated donations
to political parties that are known as soft money. The petition
strategy has been forced by the resolute refusal of the House
speaker, Dennis Hastert, to move quickly on the bill and thus leave
enough time to rally support in the Senate before the campaign
season begins next year _ and hundreds of millions of dollars from
special interests start polluting the system all over again.
Because the petition needs 218 signatures to succeed, and there are
only 211 Democrats, the Republicans will have to help.
</P>
<P>
   Where are those Republicans? For the most part, they are
cowering in silent obedience to Hastert's plea for party loyalty,
which in this case means acquiescing in his strategy for delay. The
speaker argues that discharge petitions are inherently disloyal,
and says prompt consideration of campaign finance reform would
disrupt his carefully calibrated timetable that calls for orderly
consideration of big-ticket items like the minimum wage, patients'
rights and the annual appropriations bills.
</P>
<P>
   There are two answers to the speaker's logic, which is
essentially a cover for his distaste for reform. First, the
legislation banning soft money, sponsored by Christopher Shays,
R-Conn., and Martin Meehan, D-Mass., was debated at length last
year. The same bill can thus be considered expeditiously this year,
without threatening measured discussion on other important matters.
Indeed, the petition expressly limits debate on this bill or any
reform alternative to 17 hours. Second, Hastert is demanding not
just ``loyalty,'' but a suspension of principle. When the speaker's
predecessor, Newt Gingrich, finally ran out of stalling tactics
last year, the House approved Shays-Meehan by a resounding
252-to-179 vote _ with plenty of Republican help. Many Republicans
still support reform. In effect, Hastert is asking them to abandon
their better judgment in the name of solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   That is manipulation of the most obvious sort, and somebody has
to call him on it. The most likely candidate is Shays, who has
worked too long and too hard for reform to see it defeated by the
speaker's transparent mind games. But other Republicans can help as
well. Last year, 12 Republicans signed a similar discharge
petition, including three regional representatives besides Shays _
Amo Houghton of New York, Marge Roukema of New Jersey and Nancy
Johnson of Connecticut. This page applauded their support then and
would obviously welcome it this time around.
</P>
<P>
   The sooner they speak out, the better. Last year's victory for
Shays-Meehan came too late in the session for reformers to muster
sufficient support in the Senate, which killed a companion measure
in a filibuster organized by the the Senate majority leader, Trent
Lott, and Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who heads his party's Senatorial
Campaign Committee. Although a majority of senators would vote
tomorrow for reform, there are not yet the 60 votes necessary to
block another filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   Quick action by the House could give reformers time to organize
a pressure campaign in the Senate. It could also greatly enhance
the prospects for fundamental reforms that the public has been
demanding for years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-99 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990418.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3385 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-BALKANS     04-18 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-BALKANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: WHO'S AFRAID OF THE BIG BAD BALKAN QUAGMIRE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The birth announcements for the new, isolationist Republican
Party seem to be somewhat premature. True, there has been a lot of
dark muttering about morasses and quagmires _ Yugoslavia has been
compared to every kind of bad-driving terrain known to mankind,
except perhaps really deep potholes. But this is a congressional
sentiment from the rapidly aging partisans of the Gingrich
revolution, most perfectly articulated by the House majority
leader, Dick Armey, the guy who declared that having been abroad
once, he saw no reason to ever go back. The Republican candidates
for president are a different matter entirely.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that the field is split on what to do about Kosovo,
but the avowed opponents of American involvement are all long,
long, long shots like Pat Buchanan, Gary Bauer and Sen. Bob Smith,
R-N.H. Saying that the Republican presidential candidates lean
toward isolation is like examining school spirit among teen-agers
and interviewing only those who did not get invited to the prom.
</P>
<P>
   The isolationists get more than their share of attention because
their leading light is so eminently loud and quotable. Buchanan,
who advocates less foreign intervention and more defense buildup,
keeps seconding Otto von Bismarck's remark on how the Balkans are
``not worth the healthy bones of a single Pomeranian grenadier.''
Talk-radio aficionados may be familiar with this reference, but the
rest of the nation has got to be thinking about an army of small
fluffy dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the real Republican field seems to be getting more
hawkish by the day, possibly because the Kosovo crisis has worked
so well for Sen. John McCain, the Republican presidential candidate
who has been the most outspoken voice for engagement. McCain has
been winning the talk-show war. A Vietnam war hero, he is perhaps
best positioned to get away with expressing confidence about how
quickly American troops and equipment could beat a small country
with a second-rate military. His reputation as the one
(non-Buchananite) Republican who is not afraid to say what he
thinks seems to be impressing the public, although to Washington
insiders, demonstrations of McCain's propensity for
straight-talking are superfluous. This is the man who is planning
to run in the Iowa primary as the Republican who led the battle
against federal subsidies for ethanol, a highly uneconomic but very
deeply corn-based fuel.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, the man with all the money and all the
endorsements and all of just about everything except positions,
clocked in late on Kosovo, with the air of someone who had just
finished an all-nighter, poring over lists of major exports,
historical highlights and regional cooking tips. Bush's latest
pronouncements can be read in William Safire's column on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a question-and-answer session with Texas journalists earlier
this month, Bush disassociated himself from the Armey school of
you've-seen-one-continent-you've-seen-them-all. Slobodan Milosevic,
he said, needs to be taught a ``lesson'' and NATO forces should be
satisfied with nothing less than ``an unconditional surrender.''
His only reservation, Bush added, was whether the bombing campaign
was being done with enough ``ferocity.'' He seemed to have been
breathing deeply from that Alamo-enhanced air.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole has called on President Clinton to build up and
deploy ``the forces necessary to win the war.'' Steve Forbes wants
to expand the bombing and arm the Kosovars. Dan Quayle is dead set
against ground troops, except that they might be inevitable. For
terseness, vagueness and grumpiness, none of them can hold a candle
to Al Gore's only Democratic competition, former Sen. Bill Bradley.
Bradley, you will be happy to know, has ``serious questions about
our policy'' and is worried about ``becoming bogged down in a
quagmire.''
</P>
<P>
   It is ironic that all this effort at being forceful on foreign
policy is now being directed at a military engagement engineered by
Bill Clinton. As a candidate, after all, the president's most
memorable statement on foreign affairs may have been his
explanation of how he would have voted in the Senate when George
Bush needed support for the Gulf War: ``I guess I would have voted
with the majority if it was a close vote. But I agree with the
arguments the minority made.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the leading Republican candidates have histories that
made it inevitable that they would land somewhere in the
internationalist camp. But polls showing increasing American
support for the effort in Kosovo may also have had an effect. Bill
Clinton has flummoxed the Republicans so often they may now suspect
that the man who got the public to overlook adultery may be able to
get the public enthusiastic about international quagmires, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-99 2028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990418.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3386 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-54     04-18 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORDER CROSSING TEMPORARILY CLOSED AFTER ANTI-TANK MINE KILLS 5 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORINI, Albania _ The hordes of people with frightened faces
crossing into Albania from Kosovo stopped temporarily early Sunday
after five refugees, including three children, died when their
small car was blown to bits by a powerful antitank mine placed at
the border as a defense against a possible NATO assault.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Yugoslav authorities reopened the border, however,
the flow resumed at the rate of about 1,000 refugees an hour. They
came on tractors with shot-out tires, in carts drawn by desperately
tired horses draped with incongruously decorative red tassels, and
thousands were said to be heading for the border on foot.
</P>
<P>
   With 30,000 refugees arriving in Albania and Macedonia on
Saturday, and another 40,000 either leaving Kosovo or massing at
its borders on Sunday, international monitors here believe this
could mark the beginning of another major effort by Serb forces to
purge Kosovo of its Albanian majority under cover of the NATO air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   With many villages already cleared, refugees report that Serb
forces are combing the hillsides for Albanians hiding there.
Refugee accounts also indicate that the central areas of cities
like Mitrovica are being cleared _ a description underscored by the
arrival of larger, more expensive automobiles that hurry past
tractors and horse-drawn wagons as soon as they arrive in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   And apparently reflecting tensions over the stepped-up NATO
military activity in Albania, Yugoslavia severed diplomatic
relations with Albania Sunday, the Albanian Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   While Serb forces are pushing Albanians across the border,
authorities have repeatedly and arbitrarily clamped the borders
shut. International monitors are not certain what this is intended
to accomplish, nor can they at times be certain what the lack of
refugees at certain crossings means. That was the case on April 7,
when thousands of refugees who were turned back at the border
seemed to vanish.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav authorities clamped the border shut again after Sunday
morning's explosion, chasing away other refugees who were
attempting to help the survivors. The bodies of three children in
the car were brought back to Yugoslavia, monitors said.
</P>
<P>
   The border crossing then was quiet through the early morning, as
a heavy rain again pounded this area of eastern Albania, turning
camps and fields housing more than 75,000 refugees into seas of
slimy mud and wet clothing.
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as the border reopened just after 9 a.m., the stream
of refugees resumed, with monitors reporting about 6,000 by
mid-afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   There may be as many as 60,000 refugees on their way to the
border crossing here, many of them moving on foot, said Owen
O'Sullivan, chief of the observer team from the Organization for
Cooperation and Security in Europe, which has been monitoring the
border.
</P>
<P>
   He said the presence of the mines on the Yugoslav side of the
border has been known since they were placed there about two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The mines are set on the asphalt just behind a series of squat
concrete pyramids that are lined up across the entrance to the
narrow bridge that joins the border crossing in Yugoslavia with
Albania.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sunday morning's deadly mine blast killed five of seven refugees
squeezed into a small white sedan. They were all members of a
family rousted from their home in the village of Belacevac, near
Pristina, by Serbian troops Friday afternoon. Witnesses said that a
tractor-pulled cart went off the asphalt roadway early Sunday
morning. Since the concrete barricades block most of the roadway,
there is only a narrow slot left through which refugees can pass.
</P>
<P>
   To get the wagon back on the road, the refugees tried to clear
some space by getting a few vehicles to back up. Ibush Berisha, 44,
of Belacevac, tried moving slowly in reverse to a position near the
concrete barricades
</P>
<P>
   ``The road was blocked so he pulled back and tried to park the
car right next to the barricades,'' said Saim Cucalli, 60, a
retired professor, also from Belacevac, whose cart had gone off the
road and caused the congestion. ``When Ibush backed up the car, it
exploded.''
</P>
<P>
   The rear half and roof of the small sedan were blown off.
Cucalli said several of the victims were thrown from the car by the
power of the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran to try to help them but the Serbian police told us to
get lost because the area was filled with mines,'' he said. ``So we
had to leave them.'' Bjork Therkildsen, a monitor with the European
group, said the bodies of the three children who died were taken
from the border by Yugoslav authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the car was treated at a local hospital in Kukes
and released. His wife and mother both died, while another son was
rushed to a hospital in Tirana, Albania.
</P>
<P>
   When Yugoslav guards reopened the border at 9:20, refugees
immediately began to cross, staring at the wreckage. Like most
other refugees, they carried stories of beatings and robbery by
Serbian police, and of a strong push by Serb authorities to expel
them.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees from around Belacevac, said that a few days ago there
was a skirmish between Serb troops and the Kosovo Liberation Army,
the separatist rebels. They also said that Serbs burned the house
of an Albanian family in Belacevac and wounded two women who tried
to run away.
</P>
<P>
   Since the NATO bombings began more than three weeks ago, more
than 600,000 Albanians have been forced out of Kosovo, according to
the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees. Well over half have come
to Albania, placing an enormous burden on aid groups and on
Europe's poorest country.
</P>
<P>
   The border crossing at Morini, as well as the city of Kukes,
about 10 miles away, have become increasingly dangerous. In the
past week, five cross-border rocket bombs presumably aimed at a
nearby rebel encampment fell just outside the city. And observers
have reported mortar fire across the border.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
