<SLUG> BC-CARIBBEAN-SUMMIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANANAS IS THE HOT TOPIC AT MEETING OF CARIBBEAN CHIEFS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic _ Venezuela's new president,
Hugo Chavez Frias, was supposed to deliver a closing thank you
speech at this weekend's Caribbean summit meeting here, but
speaking with the candor of the recently elected, he grumbled that
he had attended six meetings of heads of state in only 73 days in
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go from summit to summit, and our people go from abyss to
abyss,'' he said, telling the 24 other leaders of the Association
of Caribbean States meeting here on Saturday that they shared the
``same drama of terrible underdevelopment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the central core of all these summits?'' he asked.
``What is the nucleus? I think we are a little disorganized. I
think we should review all these summits to be more efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   The one-day session here was called to come up with a plan of
action for the next century. Leaders of countries with a Caribbean
coastline, including Ernesto Zedillo of Mexico, Fidel Castro of
Cuba and Andres Pastrana of Colombia, signed a declaration
declaring tourism the industry that can best increase employment
and income in the region.
</P>
<P>
   The declaration also condemned the transport of nuclear waste
shipments through the Caribbean and committed the members to pursue
bilateral pacts and tariff concessions for regional trade and
investment.
</P>
<P>
   But even though these countries have been striving for unity to
cope with economic globalization, the gathering failed to reach
consensus on some issues, underscoring the diversity of the
countries involved.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most divisive issues was the recent World Trade
Organization ruling allowing the United States to impose sanctions
against European-made goods in retaliation for the European Union's
trade preferences for bananas grown in its former colonies.
</P>
<P>
   The banana dispute pits small eastern Caribbean islands like St.
Vincent and the Grenadines against Central American countries,
where Chiquita Brands and other American companies are major banana
growers that contend they will be hurt by the European Union's
quota system.
</P>
<P>
   The issue was a hot topic in a closed-door session here in which
Cuba's Fidel Castro railed against the trade group, which regulates
international trade, as ``a fearful instrument of re-colonization
and exploitation of the world,'' the Cuban government news media
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Association of Caribbean States represents countries
on both sides of the banana dispute, it was up to the eastern
Caribbean islands that oppose the ruling to issue their first
formal statement on the decision. They did today, under the aegis
of another regional group, the Caribbean Community.
</P>
<P>
   Their statement called the ruling ``the single most dangerous
threat to the economies of the Caribbean banana exporting
countries'' and warned that putting it into effect ``without
consideration of the vulnerability of the Caribbean banana industry
would lead to severe social and economic dislocations.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the opening of the meeting in the National Theater
here Friday night, President Jules A. Wijdenbosch of Suriname used
the banana dispute to call for increased concerted action by
Caribbean states. He said that the battle was being fought by two
major economic powers, the European Union and the United States,
without direct involvement by the smaller countries most affected.
</P>
<P>
   One of the association's goals is for members, who represent 200
million people and a gross domestic product of $500 billion, to
coalesce in a trading bloc that would be one of the largest in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than ever it's our responsibility to demonstrate our
presence in international and regional organizations and demand
that our concerns are an integral part of the agenda, the debate
and the general solutions,'' Wijdenbosch said.
</P>
<P>
   But presidents also used the summit meeting, the second held by
the 5-year-old group, to seek cooperation on more individual
matters. President Armando Calderon Sol of El Salvador petitioned
Castro ``for clemency in the name of the families and all
Salvadorans'' for two Salvadorans who face the death penalty in
terrorist bombings in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents Pastrana and Chavez, who have had differences over
Chavez's sympathy for Colombian guerrillas, also held a private
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Dominican President, Leonel Fernandez, has solidified the
Dominican Republic's new stature as an international player after
years of isolation under a strongman, Joaquin Balaguer.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the presence of so many world leaders, parts of the
city were turned into maximum security areas, with armed military
police along many streets and with metal detectors at hotel
entrances.
</P>
<P>
   Castro, as usual, drew special attention without making public
speeches. He signed the meeting's joint declaration even though a
provision to ``reaffirm our commitment to preserve, consolidate and
strengthen democracy, political pluralism and a state of law as the
privileged backdrop that allows respect, defense and promotion of
human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   But the declaration also urged the United States to end the
Helms-Burton law, which toughened the America trade embargo against
Cuba, and it endorsed the principles of sovereignty and
nonintervention ``and the right of each country to build its own
political system in peace, stability and justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Foreign Ministry here restricted a news conference after the
signing of the ``Declaration of Santo Domingo'' Saturday night to
allow not more than two questions of any leader, apparently to keep
someone like Castro from monopolizing the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Castro bowed out of the news conference, the
only leader to do so. He cited ``unavoidable commitments,''
standing up two reporters _ one of them from the exile press in
Miami _ who were assigned the two questions for him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
