<HEADER>
A3402 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2KWATCH-Y2KWATCH_SFC     04-18 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2KWATCH-Y2KWATCH </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Protecting Credit Against Perils of Y2K
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Benny Evangelista &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
Financial regulators remained confident last week that the vast
majority of the nation's banks will be prepared for the Year 2000
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as with everything surrounding Y2K, no one is willing to
bet the mortgage on it.
</P>
<P>
   So a nonprofit Internet debt counseling service offered a
checklist for consumers who are worried about protecting their
credit. Tips include getting backup credit cards and keeping paper
records of everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are fairly commonsense things that people should do even
though everyone says it will be all right,'' said Steve Rhode,
president and co-founder of the Debt Counselors of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it would hurt just throwing your statements in a
box, saving them up so you have proof just in case there is a
problem. Consider it cheap insurance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K pundits say financial institutions recognized the problem
much sooner and have made more progress containing the Y2K problem
than government agencies or small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even the biggest federal financial industry regulators,
including the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., the Federal Reserve
System and the National Credit Union Administration, agree
consumers should take some steps to protect themselves just in case
the Y2K problem causes glitches in the banking system.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, those regulators issued a six-point ``Y2K Checklist
for Consumers.'' Every bank in the country is supposed to have free
copies available.
</P>
<P>
   The Debt Counselors of America, an online counseling agency in
Rockville, Md., covered the same ground, but with a more
comprehensive checklist. For example:
</P>
<P>
   _Starting in mid-1999, keep all paper records of bank
transactions, including ATM receipts, canceled checks and bank
statements. Rhode said he has encountered a surprising number of
bank customers who don't keep records or bother to balance their
checking accounts. But as the new year approaches, consumers
shouldn't rely solely on their bank to keep proper books, he said.
</P>
<P>
   _If you have a card that expires on or after Jan. 1, 2000,
consider getting a second card that expires in 2001 or later.
Merchants who aren't Y2K ready should be able to handle a card that
expires in a later year. Rhode cautions, however, that this no
excuse for consumers to max out another credit card and slip into
more debt.
</P>
<P>
   _Mail credit card bills due in the first weeks of January early,
in case there are problems with crediting payments or clearing
checks.
</P>
<P>
   _Ask your mortgage lender for a loan amortization schedule
several months before the end of the year, and keep track to see if
the payments are handled on schedule. The DCA notes the Federal
Trade Commission has suggested sending mortgage and loan payments
by certified mail for the months before and after Jan. 1, 2000, as
proof of the date the lender received payments.
</P>
<P>
   _Check your credit report before Sept. 9, 1999. Y2K watchers say
the date 9/9/99 could trigger older computer programs that used the
code ``99'' to signal ``end program'' or ``dump data.'' And check
again after New Year's.
</P>
<P>
   _Direct deposits and automatic transfers to pay bills should be
OK. The National Automated Clearing House Association, which
represents the four national operators that process automatic bank
transactions, reported last week that their systems have been
tested and are ready for Y2K. But Rhode said consumers should still
pay closer attention to automatic transactions before and after
January 1.
</P>
<P>
   The DCA's list is available for $2.50 online at
 &LR; www.getoutofdebt. &LR;   &LR; org &LR;  or for $5 by mail by writing to Debt
Counselors of America, Y2K Guide, P.O. Box 8587, Gaithersburg, Md.
20898-8587.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sth  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Y2K SCAMS: Several e-mail warnings making the rounds on the
Internet tell people to watch out for Y2K scams from con artists
posing as bank representatives.
</P>
<P>
   One warns of a phone caller who says he represents a bank that
is having Y2K problems, and gets the customer's account and Social
Security number to transfer money into a special account.
</P>
<P>
   Another warns of a caller from a securities company offering to
automatically transfer money from a checking or savings account
into a safe Y2K bond fund, then return the money on April 1, 2000.
Yet another warns of a man who obtains credit card numbers by
saying he needs to send out a new magnetic strip that is Y2K ready.
</P>
<P>
   But John Stafford, a spokesman for the California Bankers
Association, said these e-mail warnings appear to be urban legends
since there have been no documented reports of customers losing
money after falling for the purported trickers.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, whether real or not, Stafford said consumers
should heed the association's basic warning: Never give out bank
account or personal identification numbers to someone you don't
know.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
