<DOCNO> NYT19990418.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3403 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-950&AMP;ADD-N     04-18 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-950&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUT OIL DELIVERIES BY SEA TO YUGOSLAVIA, U.S. URGES
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ The United States wants NATO to plan ways of
blocking deliveries of oil to Yugoslavia by sea, allied officials
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Such deliveries have continued as allied warplanes have bombed
refineries and oil storage installations on land.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kosovo campaign is a war fought by committee, in this
case the 19-nation alliance, and NATO procedures first require a
plan acceptable to all. When the Americans requested a plan at a
closed-door meeting of allied delegates last week, they ran up
against objections from France.
</P>
<P>
   French officials questioned whether there was a legal basis to
stop and search ships without a new resolution from the U.N.
Security Council and expressed fears that such actions would widen
the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The behind-the-scenes dispute illustrates the difficulties that
NATO military commanders have encountered trying to wage a military
campaign in which every new tactic must be approved by 19
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's supreme commander, Gen. Wesley Clark of the
United States, wants to see the shipments stopped, Western
officials say. But NATO's military cannot do so unless the North
Atlantic Council, the political arm of the alliance, gives him the
authority first to plan and then to carry out an interdiction
effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous to risk the lives of allied pilots by bombing
oil refineries and supplies in Yugoslavia when they are getting the
oil some other way,'' an American official said.
</P>
<P>
   From the start of the allied bombing, the elimination of
Yugoslavia's oil supplies has been a major concern for the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Since the allies are not planning to use ground troops, they are
relying on air strikes to force Serbian forces out of Kosovo. A
major aim of the air campaign has been to destroy Yugoslavia's
ability to refine, store and transport fuel for its military.
</P>
<P>
   NATO said on Sunday, for instance, that allied planes had struck
the oil refinery at Novi Sad and that Yugoslavia no longer had the
ability to refine oil. Clark has also said 70 percent of
Yugoslavia's fuel-storage ability has been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The allies have been taking other steps to cut off Yugoslavia's
fuel. A pipeline from Croatia has been cut. Hungary went so far as
to limit fuel supplies accompanying a Russian relief convoy.
</P>
<P>
   But Yugoslavia has been trying to compensate for the allied
attack by importing refined oil by sea. The ships delivering the
fuel are generally registered in countries like Panama, making it
difficult to determine where their shipments originated.
</P>
<P>
   A Western official who has access to classified intelligence
reports said about half a dozen tankers had docked at the port of
Bar in Montenegro since the conflict began. He said they carried
tens of thousands of metric tons of refined fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Clark alluded to the problem of the oil tankers in a news
conference on Tuesday, referring to President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia and using the military acronym for petroleum: ``We know
that there are other sources of supply that he's doing. He's
scrambling very hard to try to receive additional POL.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the allies would soon take steps to cut off the supply
from the tankers. ``I think that in coming days we'll see
additional measures, diplomatic and otherwise, taken to further
constrain his POL resources,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomatic efforts to cut off the supply, however, have not
gone smoothly at NATO, reflecting difference in the alliance about
the scope of the war.
</P>
<P>
   The United States asked the North Atlantic Council late last
week to authorize NATO military planners to develop plans to cut
off the supply. A separate decision by the council would be needed
to start the interdiction campaign after the plans were developed
and debated.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of the French objections, however, the council
limited itself to asking the NATO military for a report on the
military implications of a maritime effort to step the flow of oil.
</P>
<P>
   In advancing their proposal, American officials argued that an
arms embargo imposed by the U.N. Security Council should be
interpreted broadly to include a ban on fuel for the Yugoslav
military machine, according to allied officials. Further, American
officials noted, NATO began its air strikes against Yugoslavia
without seeking a U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
   American officials also say stopping the shipments would be
militarily significant, because the Serbian military is now
hunkered down and not using much. That means a relatively small
amount of fuel can go a long way.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the fuel that is now being delivered is already
refined, which makes it especially useful given the destruction of
Yugoslavia's oil refineries.
</P>
<P>
   France, however, has questioned whether NATO has the legal
authority to stop and search the ships. During the Bosnia conflict
in the mid-1990s, NATO stopped oil tankers from reaching
Yugoslavia, but it did so under the terms of a resolution
restricting trade with Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   France also argued that to stop and search Panamanian and other
foreign ships at sea would broaden the military campaign, according
to allied diplomats familiar with the deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, some French officials have questioned the military
utility of an oil embargo. They say that according to NATO
estimates, Yugoslav's military has anywhere from 30 to 90 days of
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Stopping shipments by oil tankers, the French say, might hurt
only civilians. In any case, they say, supplies of fuel are being
smuggled in from Romania and the Bosnian Serb Republic.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Reflecting the importance of the issue, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright has pressed the request with allied officials,
according to her spokesman, James Rubin. One of the approaches
being discussed, Rubin said, ``includes visits and searches of
ships.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton also raised the matter when he spoke recently
with President Jacques Chirac of France, according to a senior
Clinton administration official.
</P>
<P>
   A senior French official in Paris confirmed that the presidents
had spoken, but declined to say whether the conversation included
the subject of fuel shipments to Yugoslavia. ``This is not the time
for a public debate about war aims,'' the French official said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the alliance knows how to interdict oil supplies,
since it did so together with the Western European Union during the
Bosnia operation.
</P>
<P>
   Allied warships set up two pickets, supported by aircraft
patrols. The first, in the Adriatic, checked passing ships. If the
ships seemed suspicious, they were boarded in the Adriatic or
diverted to ports in Italy. Another line of warships took up
positions 12 miles off the coast of Yugoslavia, as a final line of
defense.
</P>
<P>
   One allied officer who took part in that operation said it had
required about 15 ships and was generally effective.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-99 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
