<HEADER>
A3405 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETFILES-NETFILES_SFC     04-18 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETFILES-NET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NET FILES/JON SWARTZ  
  
</HEADLINE>
 FILES _ SF CHRON   Video Search, E-Commerce At Net Show 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
Bits, bytes and buzz from the Spring Internet World show in Los
Angeles last week:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Video portal.  &LR; Consumers itching for an online glimpse of
Michael Jordan in his 1984 rookie year, or for a mid-1970s segment
of ``Meet the Press,'' may not have to wait long. AT&AMP;T Labs is
developing video technology that will let cybersurfers search
thousands of Web sites for video clips. (Virage, a San Mateo
startup, has already developed the first video search engine that,
like AT&AMP;T's solution, lets online users type in a phrase or keyword
and then view only the video segments associated with those words.)
</P>
<P>
   Expect AT&AMP;T in the next few months to sell the software to
commercial Web sites, which would use it to archive their video and
make it available to consumers. NBC, for example, might list every
episode of ``Meet the Press'' on its site for free or a nominal
fee.
</P>
<P>
   Digital video libraries are part of a movement to
video-on-demand as faster online services become available,
according to industry insiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving from text-based portals to multimedia portals,''
said Alan Schwartz, new market development director for AT&AMP;T in
Florham Park, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _E-commerce, e-commerce, e-commerce &LR; . Did anyone mention that
e-commerce was the talk of the show?
</P>
<P>
   The E-word was prominently displayed in most of the show's 600
booths, on plenty of the goofy promotional giveaways that
exhibitors pass out to consumers (get your e-commerce cap, here)
and on the minds of every executive in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In less than three years, the network has changed
everything,'' Cisco Systems CEO John Chambers proclaimed in a
keynote speech on Thursday. ``The business and government can't
overlook that.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither, evidently, will consumers.
</P>
<P>
   By the year 2003, Chambers predicted e-commerce sales worldwide
will top a whopping $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Colorizing the Web.  &LR; Sonnetech ( &LR; www.sonnetech.com &LR; ) isn't
colorblind to the importance of online catalog sales. The San
Francisco company _ noting that nearly a third of cybershoppers
renege on a purchase because the shade or hue of a product is in
doubt _ has concocted software technology for delivering ``true
Internet color.'' J.Crew ( &LR; www.jcrew.com &LR; ) is the first e-tailer to
make use of the new ChromaServe software.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Departures.  &LR; Industry insiders were whispering in the hallways
of the Los Angeles Convention Center about the exits of two major
figures in the Internet market.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Homer, the fiery Netscape executive who ramrodded its
Netcenter portal site to success, told co-workers on Wednesday that
he is leaving on a six-week sabbatical, and at least one Netcenter
executive doubts he'll return. Homer's move isn't all that
surprising. Many expected him and others to move on following the
completion of America Online's $10.2 billion acquisition of
Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   Several other o_Ec,dg),t ``+rR7WK;Y:'% &QC; g+Vv9'
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
