<HEADER>
A3406 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GENE-STUDY-SPI &LR;      04-18 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENE-STUDY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW UNIV. OF WASHINGTON RESEARCH INSTITUTE MELDS BIOLOGY,
MEDICINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The University of Washington and high-profile gene
hunter Dr. Leroy Hood have launched an ambitious new public-private
research institute aimed at capitalizing on the international
effort to decipher the entire human genetic code.
</P>
<P>
   Hood, a world-renowned player in the race to unravel the details
of human DNA, isn't shy about his latest exploit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (the institute) will be a world leader in this new
kind of biology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Institute for Quantitative Systems Biology, the new
facility will operate as part of the University of Washington
School of Medicine but will be located off the Seattle campus, in
Seattle's South Lake Union area. Aiming for an annual budget of
$100 million, the institute will seek funding independently from
government, industry and other sources.
</P>
<P>
   Hood, along with institute co-founders Dr. Reudi Aebersold, an
expert in protein chemistry, and Dr. Robert Franza, who specializes
in computational biology, are among those who see the future of
biology and medicine as going beyond identifying specific genes
related to disorders or disease.
</P>
<P>
   The Human Genome Project is a federally funded effort to
decipher and describe the entire human genetic code (i.e., the
``genome''). The federal project, started in 1990, together with
private gene-hunting companies and other international scientific
groups, seeks to identify the 60,000 to 100,000 genes in the human
body within the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   The UW's new genomics institute, like others recently launched
at Harvard and Princeton, is aimed at making use of the genetic
information as it is discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Few processes or disorders in the body are the result of a
single gene malfunctioning, Hood said. The key to making use of all
this new knowledge in human genetics, he explained, is to
understand how genes and their protein products all work together
as a network in the body.
</P>
<P>
   ``The complexity is becoming mind numbing,'' Dr. Shirley
Tilghman, Princeton molecular biologist, said in a recent Science
magazine article describing her university's new Institute for
Genomic Analysis.
</P>
<P>
   What's needed to handle this complexity, Hood and others say, is
a systems approach that marries biology, computer science,
mathematics and other disciplines. That's the approach embraced by
the UW's new institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Institute researchers and collaborators will be at the
forefront in pioneering the emergence of the new discipline of
systems biology,'' Hood said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This represents the future of biomedical research,'' said Dr.
Paul Ramsey, dean of the University of Washington School of
Medicine. ``Ensuring the success of the institute is, and will
remain, among the School of Medicine's top priorities well into the
21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   But given the lack of the kind of endowment funding that other
research universities such as Harvard have at their disposal, the
UW isn't putting a lot of its own money into this top priority.
Instead, the UW is depending upon Hood's ability to raise cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know I'm good at raising money,'' Hood said. ``We already
have a large partner in Monsanto,'' he noted, based on the
agrichemical company's interest in plant genomics.
</P>
<P>
   Given the institute's plan to further consummate the marriage of
computers and biology, Hood said maybe Microsoft would be
interested.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intellectually, this is incredibly exciting,'' he said. ``We'd
like to talk to Microsoft about becoming an industrial partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Hood, as the UW's William Gates III Professor of Biomedical
Sciences, may have an edge on others who seek Microsoft's money.
</P>
<P>
   He was lured to the UW in 1992, away from the California
Institute of Technology, because of a $12 million donation to the
UW from Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates. The Gates donation created
the UW Department of Molecular Biotechnology for Hood.
</P>
<P>
   The task of rapidly sequencing DNA _ identifying it unit by unit
_ is an essential task of the Human Genome Project. The human
genome has perhaps as many as 100,000 genes, but each gene is
constructed of many units called ``base pairs'' and much of the
genome contains stretches of base pairs without genes. In total,
the entire human genome is believed to contain about 3 billion base
pairs.
</P>
<P>
   Hood, who with his colleagues at Caltech developed the
fundamental technologies allowing rapid automated sequencing of DNA
(the molecule that carries the hereditary information of living
cells), said he hopes the new UW institute will serve as a catalyst
for change in biology _ encouraging the kind of multidisciplinary
and scientific cross-fertilization that spawns innovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My vision of what's fun in science is very global,'' Hood
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey acknowledged that the new institute involves not just a
new scientific vision but also a complicated inter-relationship
between the UW and its industrial partners. Protecting academic
integrity and resolving issues of intellectual property will be of
major importance, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
