r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIOSCOPE-BIOSCOPE_SFC     04-18 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-BIOSCOPE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOSCOPE/TOM ABATE 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   The Cyber-Sleuth Investigates Mysteries of Biology and Genetics 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
Reader Geoff Noakes e-mailed me recently to ask that I suggest some
books or Web sites to help him explore the mysteries of
chromosomes, DNA and the other buzzwords of biology and genetics.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff must've been reading my mind, because I've been struggling
myself lately, trying to recall long-buried high school and college
lessons as I pound out biotech stories on deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring there might be others besides Geoff and me who might be
classified as biologically challenged, I asked some of my more
erudite sources to help devise a study list.
</P>
<P>
   My good friend and personal scientific trainer, Dr. Bob Whitmore
of Martinez, turned me on to the aptly titled book ``The Science
Class You Wish You Had.'' This $14 trade paperback, written by
David and Arnold Brody, covers key concepts in chemistry and
astronomy as well as biology and genetics _ all in a simple, lucid
style that won't insult the learned or overawe the novice.
</P>
<P>
   Desmond Mascarenhas, president of the biotech startup Protigen
Inc. and teacher of adult education classes in bioscience,
recommended several Web sites that cover the fundamentals of
biology and genetics. They include:
</P>
<P>
   _A Primer on Molecular Genetics, published by the Department of
Energy. Don't be frightened by the name. The site clearly and
simply defines terms like genome, ``The complete set of
instructions for making an organism.'' You can download the primer
at &LR;  www.bis.med.jhmi.edu/Dan/DOE/intro.html. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _If you're more a picture person, point your browser at Cells
Alive  &LR; (www.cellsalive.com) &LR;  for color images of microscopic
objects like swimming sperm cells and dividing bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   _Biology teachers (not to mention students) can find news and
activities at the Academic Excellence site  &LR; (www.gene.com/ae) &LR; 
maintained by Genentech, the South San Francisco biotech giant.
</P>
<P>
   _And if you come across a puzzling term, the University of
Texas's BioTech site  &LR; (biotech.icmb. &LR;   &LR; utexas.edu &LR;  contains a
useful dictionary and other resources.
</P>
<P>
   Last, but certainly not least, for employment or investment
information, longtime industry analyst Cynthia Robbins-Roth
recommends BioSpace  &LR; (www.biospace.com) &LR;  ``It's the best biotech
site around,'' she said. Based in San Francisco's Multimedia Gulch,
BioSpace offers a menu of breaking news, job listings and biotech
company profiles.
</P>
<P>
   THE PAYOFF:Lest you think all this scientific training might go
for naught, consider this: Of 100 biotech executives who made this
year's ``Molecular Millionaires'' list put out by Genetic
Engineering News, 89 held Ph.D.s or medical degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 15 years of publishing the list, we've never had more than
72 scientists on the list,'' said John Sterling, editor of the New
Yorktrade magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine surveyed executives at several hundred U.S. biotech
firms, and based their net worth on SEC documents showing their
stock holdings. Academic credits came off their resumes.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, the list of Ph.D. Molecular Millionaires
includes: Chiron Corp. Chairman William Rutter ($62 million);
Alejandro Zaffaroni, founder of Alza Corp. ($51 million); and David
Schwartz, founder and president of Bio-Rad Laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   California dominated the list, with 24 biotech millionaires,
followed by Massachusetts with 10. Maryland, New York and New
Jersey each put seven names on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling said the dominance of scientists in this year's ranking
_ in some years, as few as 35 Ph.D.s have made the grade _ showed
that a science education isn't incompatible with riches.
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, maybe. But I wonder how the Molecular Millionaires
would stack up to the ever-growing list of Internet whiz kids. I
used to cover them, and there were plenty who earned their riches
with little more than a working knowledge of how to make PowerPoint
presentations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
