<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUGH HOMETOWN DEBUT FOR METS' WATSON
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was as if Manager Bobby Valentine could see it
coming.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday's game against the Montreal Expos, Valentine was
asked what he was looking for from Allen Watson, his Queens-born
left-hander, who would be making his first start for the Mets a few
hours later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping he can get over the initial period that he will
probably be experiencing,'' Valentine said. ``He's starting his
first game of the season here at Shea Stadium. He's from the area.
So, I'm sure there's going to be some excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   By time Watson had thrown eight pitches, appearing in front of
his father and three dozen family members and friends, there was
excitement indeed, but it was generated by the Expos' batters. Two
pitches in, Montreal had a 2-0 lead. And after eight pitches, the
Mets were down, 3-0. The Expos coasted to a 4-2 victory as the Mets
closed out their homestand.
</P>
<P>
   On Watson's first pitch of the game, Orlando Cabrera grounded a
single. On his second pitch, Watson (1-1) went to a slide-step
delivery to keep Cabrera close at first. But Watson left a fastball
up and Jose Vidro slammed it some 418 feet to dead center field for
a home run.
</P>
<P>
   Six pitches later, on a 2-2 count, the next batter, Rondell
White, drilled a changeup inside the left-field foul pole for a
home run. The Expos added another run in the second on a one-out,
bad-hop single by pitcher Javier Vazquez, an opposite-field double
flared to right by Cabrera and a line-drive sacrifice fly by Vidro.
</P>
<P>
   Despite two home runs from John Olerud _ one in the first inning
and one in the fourth _ the Mets couldn't recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so quick,'' said Watson, who finally gathered enough
composure to last seven innings. ``Maybe I was a little jumpy, a
little anxious, and that's why I left that ball to Vidro up. But I
was getting better and better as the game went along.''
</P>
<P>
   Over his last five innings, Watson scattered three singles. But
by that time, it was too late. Later, Watson _ who allowed nine
hits and four runs with one walk and two strikeouts over his seven
innings _ said he did not want to offer any excuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you don't like to get beat with something you're working
on,'' Watson said, referring to the slide-step delivery he has
added this year. ``That was my mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson said his mother, Dorothea, was at his parents' home in
the Middle Village section of Queens because she becomes too
nervous when he pitches. Watson's father, Allen, was behind home
plate. Watson was asked if he looked over at his father after
allowing the consecutive home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' Watson said. ``He probably left.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury-depleted Mets did not have a lineup that could come
back for Watson. Mike Piazza was on the disabled list, Rickey
Henderson was still unavailable because of a tight right hamstring
and Brian McRae was undergoing a magnetic resonance imaging test in
Manhattan that determined he had a sprained left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Vazquez (1-1) came into the game with a 7.00 ERA, but
surrendered just five hits, including both of Olerud's homers, in
seven innings. And after Ugueth Urbina pitched the final one and a
third innings for his third save, the Expos had taken two of three
from the Mets this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Mets had opened the season by going 8-5 against two
teams that found success against them last year, the Expos and the
Florida Marlins. And by going 4-3 against Montreal the first two
weeks, the Mets equaled the number of victories they had against
the Expos all last year, when Montreal took the season series, 8-4.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' next six games are at Cincinnati and Chicago. Not
until June will they have to face the Marlins, and not until July
will they see the Expos (6-7) again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I'm glad I'm through with those two teams,'' Valentine
said, factoring in the eight games the Mets and Expos also played
during spring training and the four exhibitions the Mets and
Marlins played before the season began. ``I think they were sick of
seeing us and we were sick of seeing them.''
</P>
<P>
   As John Franco put it, ``Now it will feel like spring training's
finally over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
