</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES' POOR PLAY RESULTS IN SWEEP
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The cold and cracked steel and cement of Tiger Stadium
are 88 years old, and echoes rattle here, like lockers in a high
school hallway. ``Sweep,'' somebody in the small crowd yelled in
the bottom of the eighth inning Sunday, a concept that sounded so
hollow and outdated that a minute or two passed before others
joined in the chant. And then they were all yelling.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1988, the Tigers completed a three-game
sweep of the New York Yankees here, winning Sunday's game by 5-1.
And it is true that Detroit outperformed the Yankees all weekend,
pitching well and getting hits in crucial moments. Dave Mlicki
(1-0) threw five strong innings Sunday afternoon, Mel Rojas pitched
out of a jam in the seventh, and Tony Clark bashed a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   It is also true that the Yankees (7-5) played poorly again in
their fourth consecutive defeat, the conclusion to a week's worth
of bad baseball. They were one for 20 with runners in scoring
position in three games against Detroit (5-7), and committed five
errors.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch, whose third-inning throwing error led to two
runs, said ``it's not really fair'' to compare and contrast the
Yankees of '99 with the extraordinary Yankees of '98. Fair or not,
the comparisons are inevitable:
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have made seven errors during the four-game losing
streak; they did not commit seven errors over any four-game span
last year. The fewest runs they scored in any three-game span last
year was six; they scored three in the last three games. The bottom
third of their order, so instrumental to their success in 1998, has
been an offensive abyss this season. Scott Brosius batted .125
before spraining his ankle, Jorge Posada is hitting .105 and Ricky
Ledee .091. Collectively, the Nos. 7, 8 and 9 hitters in their
lineup are batting .163.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez has two runs batted in. The bullpen has an ERA of
5.27. The Yankees have stolen five bases; they swiped 24 in the
first 12 games last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers, shortstop Derek Jeter said, do not care that the
Yankees won the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come out to play,'' he said. ``We expect to win, expect
to win every day we come out. We just haven't scored any runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Paul O'Neill said: ``It's not a lack of effort.
When things aren't going well, they always say, `Well, they're
letting down.' We're not letting down. We got beat.''
</P>
<P>
   But they have beat themselves, over and over. After playing
errorless baseball in the first week of the season, they did not
play well in the first two games against Baltimore last week and
won anyway. Then their mistakes began strangling them. Jeter
dropped a pop-up Friday, and on Saturday Knoblauch was thrown out
at third with nobody out and Jeff Nelson made a pivotal two-base
throwing error.
</P>
<P>
   The score was tied, 1-1, in the third inning Sunday. Detroit's
Deivi Cruz hustled to beat out an infield single leading off, Brian
Hunter bunted him to second, and then Ramiro Mendoza (1-1) walked
Gregg Jefferies and gave up a single to Bobby Higginson. Bases
loaded, one out.
</P>
<P>
   With Clark, a slow-footed slugger, at the plate, Mendoza, a
sinkerball pitcher, wanted to get a ground ball and a double play.
Clark hit into 16 double plays last year. Sure enough, Clark hit
the ball on the ground, up the middle; Mendoza managed to tip the
ball with his glove, and Jeter fielded it and flipped to Knoblauch,
who stepped on second and turned and fired toward first. A double
play would have ended the inning; the rally would have been over.
</P>
<P>
   But Knoblauch's throw sailed high, tailing to the left and away
from Martinez, who reached and tried to maintain contact on the
first-base bag with a pointed toe.
</P>
<P>
   He could either catch the ball or keep his foot on the base: The
ball glanced off the webbing of his glove, rolling away, and Cruz
and Jefferies scored. ``I turned it the best I could,'' said
Knoblauch, charged with his third error in six games, ``and the
throw wasn't perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said: ``I should've just come off and tagged him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Stadium is a hitter's paradise. Left-handed batters easily
and often hit balls that span the short distance to the right-field
stands, and yet the Yankees were almost completely stifled. Bernie
Williams was one for 12 in the series, and in three days, the
Yankees did not get an RBI from the Nos. 3, 4, 5, 6 and 7 spots in
the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Angry with the losing, O'Neill nearly snapped in his final
at-bat of the series, arguing briefly when Joe Brinkman, the plate
umpire, called strikes on him and, when he grounded out, screaming
at Brinkman all the way to first base.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill was 0 for 11 in the series, stranding seven runners in
scoring position and prompting Don Zimmer, the interim manager, to
employ an old trick he sometimes uses with his fellow Cincinnatian.
When O'Neill complains how badly he is swinging, how he should just
quit and go home, Zimmer looks at him with the straightest of faces
and says, ``If you really feel that way, I've got a friend who owns
a cement-block company back in Cincinnati, and he could set you up
with a pretty good job.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees continue playing this badly and the frustration
keeps mounting, the employee rolls of a certain cement-block
company could swell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
