<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ROCKIES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves air out 20-5 win
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Braves had one last day to put the thin air of
Coors Field to good use. They took advantage of it, embarrassing
the Colorado Rockies 20-5 Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves scored the most runs in 42 years of franchise history
and acted like they didn't want to leave. Ten of those runs came in
the ninth, Atlanta's biggest inning of this decade. The Braves took
out any leftover frustration of two postponements and a
ninth-inning loss, and leave here for Los Angeles in an awfully
good mood.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta hitting coach Don Baylor got a little sweet revenge on
the team that fired him as manager as the Braves lineup put on a
hitting clinic and Greg Maddux got plenty of run support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tremendous,'' said Maddux of the most productive day by a
Braves offense since they were playing in Milwaukee and scoring 23
runs on the Cubs in 1957. ``That's a good month right there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves put a five-homer hurting on the Rockies and finished
with 24 hits. Eleven different Braves had hits, led by Andruw Jones
and Eddie Perez, who each had a career-high five.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've not played particularly well the first 10 games of the
year,'' said Chipper Jones, one of five Atlanta players to go deep
and the one to go deepest with a 431-foot shot. ``We needed a game
like this where everybody contributes. You know the next series we
have is going to be a pretty tough-pitched series. We've got some
guys going in with some confidence offensively.'' Brian Jordan
started the outburst in the first inning with an opposite-field
ride to right. The two-run shot was his third of the season. Two
innings later, Andruw Jones hit his first home run of the season,
for three runs and a 6-0 lead on Pedro Astacio.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth inning, Chipper Jones smashed a 1-0 offering from
left-hander Bobby Jones into the last row of seats in the
left-field stands. In only 14 at-bats against left-handers this
year, the switch-hitter has matched his home run total from the
right side last season with two and has three overall.
</P>
<P>
   Two batters later, Randall Simon, starting in place of an
injured Ryan Klesko for the second consecutive game, came through
with the first home run of his major-league career.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hunter capped it off with a pinch-hit two-run homer in the
ninth, starting the 10-run inning, the biggest ever in this
ballpark by a Rockies opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a veteran ball club,'' Colorado center fielder Darryl
Hamilton said. ``If the veterans aren't embarrassed by this, then
something's wrong with them. I know I'm embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockies manager Jim Leyland was just glad it ended.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
