<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tire-less drive gets Andretti win
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARTINSVILLE, Va. _ Petty Enterprises kicked off its 50th
anniversary season on April 7 with a gala at its racing shop in
Level Cross, N.C., but stock-car racing's first family saved the
fireworks for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   John Andretti, winless in his first 40 starts with the Richard
Petty-owned No. 43 Pontiac, stunned the field Sunday in the Goody's
Body Pain 500 at Martinsville Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti, who started 21st, spun out only 49 laps into the race
after getting tapped from behind by Ward Burton, causing Andretti
to lose a lap when a caution flag was not thrown.
</P>
<P>
   But Andretti, a former open-wheel racer, later regained the lap,
then threw himself into contention with a gutsy call during the
final pit stop. He passed Burton with only three laps left and beat
him to the finish by 1.066 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so mad it was too hard for me to deal with to even think
about winning,'' Andretti said.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was only the second of Andretti's seven-year Winston
Cup career and snapped a 57-race winless streak. It was Petty
Enterprises' first trip to victory lane since Bobby Hamilton won at
North Carolina Speedway in October 1997, snapping a string of 42
races.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good weekend,'' said Petty, NASCAR's career
winningest driver with 200 career victories. ``We got behind, got a
lap down and were able to make that back up. That was a heck of a
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Andretti, who jumped six spots to 14th in the points standings,
regained his lap when he passed Jeff Gordon on lap 135. Andretti
stayed in front of the two-time defending Winston Cup champion
until a caution flag was thrown on lap 184.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti still faced huge odds, as he was 11th with only 120
laps remaining. But he joined the leaders four laps later, when his
crew gambled and changed only two tires during a yellow-flag pit
stop. The move allowed Andretti to take fourth place, behind
Gordon, Mark Martin and Burton, who all took four tires during the
stop.
</P>
<P>
   None of the drivers anticipated running the final 116 laps on
those tires, but that's what happened as the rest of the race was
finished without a caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to do that because I kept getting caught up in the
back,'' Andretti said. ``I kept using my car up so much and having
to miss crashes. The car has a lot of damage on it, but the nose is
clean and that's all that is important.''
</P>
<P>
   After the final pit stop, Andretti lost fourth place to Rusty
Wallace. But Andretti started his move with about 50 laps
remaining, passing Martin and Wallace for third.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti eventually caught Gordon with only 12 laps left, and
then closed on Burton, moving door-to-door with the No. 99 Ford
with only six laps remaining. After the pair circled the half-mile
oval side-by-side for three laps, Andretti pushed his Pontiac ahead
in turn 4 of lap 297.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't much of a battle,'' Burton said. ``He was that much
better than we were. They came from the back and had the best car
and they deserved to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton finished second, and his points lead over Dale Jarrett
increased to 85. Gordon was third, followed by Mike Skinner and
Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``John and that Petty team have run well here many times,''
Gordon said. ``He was tough early on, but he got a lap down.
Somebody needed to keep him a lap down because I knew he was going
to be a threat at the end, and he certainly showed that.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Gibbs Racing teammates Bobby Labonte and Tony Stewart were
early factors in the race, but hard luck caught up with both of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, a rookie who earned his first pole in Friday's
qualifying, had problems from the start. Immediately after the
green flag fell, Stewart's No. 20 Pontiac wasn't up to speed and
quickly fell to sixth. After two laps, Stewart dropped to 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the setup errors, Stewart was able to stay on the lead
lap through the first half of the race, although he never
challenged the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's real troubles came on lap 267, when Jimmy Spencer
bumped the rear of Kenny Irwin's No. 28 Ford on the back
straightaway. The tap set Irwin's car on top of the inside wall,
and the pileup also collected the No. 7 Chevy of Michael Waltrip
and the No. 45 Pontiac of Rich Bickle. Stewart couldn't clear the
accident, as he rear-ended Andretti, who slammed on his brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's car sustained significant damage, but he was able to
return to the track without a hood and remained on the lead lap
until lap 379. Stewart, who had a strong outing negated by a wreck
for the second race in a row, finished 20th, but jumped two spots
to 10th in points.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, who was running seventh with 260 laps completed, was
able to avoid the wreck that caused Stewart's demise, but
mechanical problems in his No. 18 Pontiac creeped up about the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte pitted during the 12-lap caution caused by Irwin's
wreck. But Labonte's failed power steering couldn't be fixed, so
the Pontiac was nearly impossible to turn for Labonte, who's
recovering from a broken right shoulder suffered at Darlington a
month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte finished two laps down and finished 24th. He now trails
Burton by 184 points.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jeremy Mayfield, who came into Martinsville ninth in
points and 212 behind Burton, took the biggest hit of any driver.
Only eighth laps into the race, Mayfield's No. 12 Ford spun out
between turns 1 and 2 and he fell one lap down. On lap 80, Mayfield
and Rick Mast spun out in turn 4. By lap 200, Mayfield already
trailed the leaders by 29 laps.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield finished 41st, falling three spots in points and 347
behind Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
