<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McDonald's still Elliott's car sponsor
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARTINSVILLE, Va. _ Winston Cup veteran Bill Elliott seems to
have McDonald's secured as a sponsor through at least next season,
but the Dawsonville native is hinting at changes for his No. 94
Ford team.
</P>
<P>
   The Charlotte Observer, citing unnamed sources, reported
Saturday that McDonald's was considering pulling its sponsorship
from Elliott's car. The newspaper said the fast-food chain might
move its sponsor dollars to the No. 25 Chevy of Wally Dallenbach or
the No. 28 Ford of Kenny Irwin next year, or pull out of NASCAR
racing altogether.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Korbus, McDonald's motorsports manager, disputed the
report on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to unfounded reports, McDonald's is committed to Bill
Elliott Racing with its current sponsorship agreement through the
year 2000,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, who hasn't climbed higher than 18th in points in his
24th season on the circuit, says he isn't concerned about
speculation surrounding his team. But Elliott, one of only five
owner-drivers left in Winston Cup, agrees that his teams needs a
facelift.
</P>
<P>
   Like veteran Ricky Rudd, Elliott wants to get away from the
growing business aspects of the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that multi-cars are the way to go,'' Elliott
said. ``I've been there, and that didn't work, for whatever reason.
We've got to take this a step at a time, and right now I'm just
concentrating on this team and making it run better, and getting my
organization working better. Yes, I need to restructure. I don't
argue that point. You just have to keep changing things until it
all comes together.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott finished 30th on Sunday, after falling two laps down
before 100 were completed at Martinsville Speedway. He slipped to
21st in points, trailing leader Jeff Burton by 482.
</P>
<P>
   Rebound for Petree
</P>
<P>
   Elliott wasn't the only owner disheartened by his early-season
effort before Sunday's race.Andy Petree, in his fourth year as a
Winston Cup owner, said he was displeased with the performance of
his Nos. 33 and 55 Chevy teams, driven by Ken Schrader and Kenny
Wallace, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Before Martinsville, the pair had only one top-10 performance _
Schrader's sixth-place effort at Daytona _ in 14 combined starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't performed with (Wallace) like we needed to and
(Schrader) is not up to snuff either,'' Petree said, before
Sunday's race. ``I'm a little disappointed at this point, but we're
working on it. We've got a lot going on. We're working on a program
to try to get better aerodynamics and that's working. We're trying
to get caught up.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes must have worked because Wallace and Schrader
finished sixth and ninth, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Pit stops
</P>
<P>
   Driver Geoffrey Bodine turned 50 years old on Sunday....Georgia
tight ends coach Greg Adkins was a guest of Ernie Irvan's three
owners, all UGA graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
