<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLDRAFT2-LEDE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ditka, Johnson roll the draft dice
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two coaches regarded as short-timers by their peers,
Jimmy Johnson of Miami and Mike Ditka of New Orleans, rolled the
dice in the NFL draft. The results of the crap-shoots likely will
determine if either returns for the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   In a Saturday gambit praised by few and panned by most, Ditka
traded away his entire draft to move up in the first round for
Heisman Trophy running back Ricky Williams. The move resulted in
the lone one-player draft in league history and left other coaches
questioning the Saints' wisdom. San Francisco 49ers president Bill
Walsh likened Ditka's flight of fancy to the risks associated with
a flight into space.
</P>
<P>
   ``One rocket to the moon is all you get,'' Walsh said. ``You've
got 50 people on it. It better get up there, circle and land, or
else.'' Added Jacksonville coach Tom Coughlin: ``I really don't
know if it's a sound philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the era of the salary cap, it may not be. Every team needs
its draft choices to make the roster in order to have some players
with minimum salaries. The Saints now have no such pool because of
the trade. Ditka, who appeared at a press conference in a
dreadlocks wig to mimic the coif of his new star, and who promised
to get his tongue pierced like Williams, defended his strategy.
</P>
<P>
   He also offered an invitation to all undrafted players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on and sign with us,'' Ditka said. ``The opportunity is
terrific. You won't have any other rookies to beat out.'' Told that
his trade raised eyebrows, Ditka responded: ``Geez, who cares what
we do?''
</P>
<P>
   Expected to step aside after this season, Johnson gambled on
some players. First-round tailback James Johnson of Mississippi
State was drummed out of the Navy four years ago. In the fifth
round, Miami picked running back Cecil Collins, who came under
scrutiny when he was tossed out of LSU and McNeese State.
</P>
<P>
   Collins struck a plea bargain last week on two felony counts of
unlawful entry and was sentenced to four years probation. He tested
positive for marijuana three times at LSU and faces weekly
drug-testing by Louisiana authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team in the league wanted to take Cecil, but nobody else
had the guts,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
