<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOV-MANSION-ARRESTS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Protesters riled by Bush mansion arrests
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, trying to burnish his
national image, is squelching political criticism around the
historic Governor's Mansion by having his security detail move more
quickly to arrest protesters, said several activists who have been
arrested or witnessed arrests in the past few months.
</P>
<P>
   So convinced are protesters that Bush is trying to keep critics
away from the mansion that one environmental group, Texans United
Education Fund, plans today to test the resolve of the Department
of Public Safety, which protects the governor, the mansion and the
nearby Capitol, by returning to the scene where one of their
members was arrested earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``News Conference and Possible Arrests at Governor's Mansion,''
the group said in a press release issued last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a new game in play there,'' said Rick Abraham, the
environmental activist who was handcuffed on March 29 while on the
sidewalk in front of the mansion at 11th and Colorado streets and
jailed for 12 hours for blocking an entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Blocking an entrance is a Class B misdemeanor under Texas law.
The punishment can be up to 180 days in jail or a fine of up to
$2,000, or both.
</P>
<P>
   ` `I've been at and seen no telling how many demonstrations at
the Governor's Mansion over the years'' and never witnessed such a
willingness by DPS to make arrests, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said DPS officials in charge of protecting the mansion,
which has gained increased national visibility this year as
out-of-state dignitaries make almost weekly pilgrimages to pay
homage to the governor-who-would-be-president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules haven't changed,'' said R.K. Elliston, the
Department of Public Safety major in charge of Capitol police.
</P>
<P>
   DPS says what has changed is an increased concern for the safety
of protesters and others walking near the mansion as the historic
building undergoes a renovation that has temporarily dislocated
Bush and his family, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A protest area was designated in a parking lot across Colorado
Street from the front of the mansion as a safety measure for
passersby and protesters who might be crowded off the sidewalk and
into the street, said DPS Lt. Mike Escalante, head of the
governor's protection unit.
</P>
<P>
   This impromptu Lafayette Park _ a famous protest area across the
street from the White House _ allows renovation workers to get in
and out of the mansion with construction materials, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not ask for it, said his spokesman, Scott McClellan.
``This was a decision by the DPS,'' McClellan said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the stricter mansion perimeter policy say that at
least 18 demonstrators have been arrested for exercising their
First Amendment rights on public sidewalks at the official
residence.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Cox, a DPS spokesman, said his agency does not keep arrest
statistics for the mansion or the perimeter, so it is impossible to
compare arrests this year with past years.
</P>
<P>
   But Elliston points out that the 18 arrests were made on only
two occasions, when the protesters refused to comply with orders.
``They can't say we're arresting them every time they come up
here.''
</P>
<P>
   They were protesting Attorney General John Cornyn's decision to
participate in a lawsuit on a disability claim involving Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
