u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABY-DEATH-SPI &LR;      04-18 1667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-DEATH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDER CASE TESTS LEGAL LIMITS OF WHAT MAN TOLD PASTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELAINE PORTERFIELD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TACOMA, Wash. _ Everyone agrees what happened to little Devyn
Martin was tragic. The 3-month-old boy was shaken so violently one
day two years ago that his brain slammed repeatedly against his
skull, killing him.
</P>
<P>
   How to best seek justice for his death, though, has pitted
prosecutors against a pastor and ignited a national debate over
society's secular courts vs. religious freedom.
</P>
<P>
   It's also landed the case before the Washington state Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   The Pierce County Prosecutor's Office wants to try Devyn's
father, Scott Anthony Martin, in the baby's death, alleging he
committed second-degree murder when he shook his son to death in a
fit of frustration.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, they say they need to call as a witness a Tacoma
pastor to whom they believe Martin confessed the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   But the pastor refuses to take the stand despite the trial
judge's threat to jail him because he asserts anything confided to
him in his capacity as a clergyman must remain confidential.
</P>
<P>
   The pastor, 36-year-old Rich Hamlin, has the looks of the
boy-next-door: lanky, friendly, open. He once aspired to
professional basketball, and graduated from Pacific Lutheran
University, just down the road from his South Tacoma church.
</P>
<P>
   Hamlin taught high school for four years before becoming a
pastor. Today, he's the ordained minister of the 75-member,
independent Evangelical Reformed Church.
</P>
<P>
   He's mystified as to why the state would try to force him to
divulge something as sacrosanct as what a penitent told him in
confidence, a privilege he and his attorney claim is protected by
centuries of law and tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you approach clergy, you do so with confidence that it
will remain private,'' Hamlin said. ``It's really a part of Western
civilization. ... What they're trying to do here is fundamentally
change the relationship between clergy and parishioners. That
relationship is based on candor, trust and confidentiality.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamlin wants one thing known: Although he is bound by his faith
to remain silent, he, too wants whoever killed little Devyn Martin
to be punished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want justice,'' Hamlin said. ``My God is a just God. Let's
let the state do what they're ordained to do. And let me do what
I'm ordained to do.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what the state is doing, said Pierce County
Prosecutor Kit Proctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pastor Hamlin maybe feels we're pursuing him,'' Proctor said,
``but what we're really trying to do is get this before the
jury.... We believe the pastor does have relevant information about
how this baby was injured.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamlin was a pastor with the national organization of Youth for
Christ _ for which he still works part time _ when the organization
got a phone call in July 1997 saying a suicidal man in Lakewood,
north of Everett, Wash., needed to ``see a preacher.'' He responded
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The man was Scott Martin, now 22 years old.
</P>
<P>
   During that meeting at Martin's apartment, Hamlin will say only
that he offered spiritual guidance, prayer and counseling. He would
meet with Martin two more times in the next few days, at the
medical center where the baby died and the night before Martin
turned himself into police after he was charged in his son's death.
</P>
<P>
   What came next was something Hamlin never imagined could happen
when he was ordained: Prosecutors took him to court in January
1998, demanding he repeat what Martin had revealed to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was surreal, the questions they were asking me,'' he said,
staring off in the distance. ``The church and the civil magistrate,
if you will, were crossing paths.''
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Steve O'Ban, told the court that Hamlin had a
constitutional right not to testify. His silence also was protected
under the Washington state law known as the priest-penitent
privilege, O'Ban said.
</P>
<P>
   But Pierce County Superior Court Judge Brian Tollefson didn't
see it that way. He ruled Hamlin was in contempt of court and
ordered him to testify or go to jail.
</P>
<P>
   The pastor, who never dreamed he'd become a poster boy for the
priest-penitent privilege, made his stand. Despite having a wife
and three young children, he said he was prepared to go to jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recessed for lunch,'' Hamlin said. ``There were some
supporters with us in court. We prayed, and I kissed my wife
goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   But his attorney, O'Ban, received a week's extension from
Tollefson to make an emergency appeal to the state Court of
Appeals. That court accepted the issue on an expedited basis,
keeping Hamlin out of jail while the judges considered the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Then in July, the Appeals Court voted 3-0 in Hamlin's favor.
Pierce County prosecutors appealed to the state Supreme Court,
which heard arguments in the case last month. It's not known when
the high court will rule.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Martin remains in the Pierce County jail on $250,000
bail. His attorney, Gary Hood of Tacoma, said he is outraged that
Martin's trial has to be delayed again because of the Supreme Court
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Scott Martin's attorney, I'm very concerned about it, and
we're intending on challenging it on a speedy trial basis,'' Hood
said. ``Mr. Martin has been in jail almost two years now, and he's
not very happy about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hood said prosecutors should either reduce Martin's bail so he
can get out while the appeal is pending or dismiss the charges
without prejudice, meaning they could be refiled at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Hamlin has grown a little weary of the media
attention and feels burned by what he considers to be the
one-sideness of some of the coverage, especially on some radio talk
shows. ``Pastor protects possible baby killer'' has been the
general theme, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tiring, the media scrutiny,'' Hamlin said. ``I've
been roasted pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Proctor, who is handling appeals in the case for the
prosecutor's office, feels a little burned and misunderstood by the
media as well. She might sum up some of the coverage as
``Prosecutor attempts to imprison innocent pastor.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said the case is an important one. She said her office
believes its research shows that the state's priest-penitent law,
which dates to the 19th century, was written very narrowly and
doesn't apply to this situation. It's Proctor's legal opinion that
the law requires the person who hears the confession to be
ordained, which Hamlin is. But the person making the confession
must do so out of his or her religious beliefs, which she doesn't
think applies in this case.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the person making the confession must be a member of a
religion that has a formal rite of confession, such as the
Catholic, Orthodox and Episcopal churches, Proctor asserts. Again,
she said, that doesn't apply to Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of what I hear coming from Pastor Hamlin and his attorney
is that they keep arguing what the privilege should be,'' not what
it actually is, Proctor said. ``We don't make the law.... It was
our job to pursue this.''
</P>
<P>
   Proctor also points out that at least one other person was
present for part of the time when Martin and Hamlin spoke _
Martin's mother, which she says diminishes any claim of strict
confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   The mother has told authorities she doesn't remember what she
heard when Hamlin and her son spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Also, prosecutors say Hamlin spoke to two other pastors after he
initially counseled Martin. One of those pastors later called Child
Protective Services to report Martin had confessed to killing his
son, according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get down in this case to someone believing their testimony
would violate their religious beliefs,'' Proctor said. ``And
consistently, in these cases of your beliefs vs. the law, the law
take precedence.''
</P>
<P>
   But Steven McFarland, director of the national Center for Law
and Religious Freedom of the Christian Legal Society in Annandale,
Va., scoffs at that interpretation of the law as an improper
intrusion into fundamental religious rights that date back hundreds
of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least since the Reformation, the confessional has been
sacrosanct from state invasion,'' said McFarland, who entered
Hamlin's case on a friend-of-the-court basis for his appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clergy have not been allowed to be involuntary conscripted as
informers for the state,'' he said. ``That message apparently
hasn't gotten through to the Pierce County Prosecutor's Office.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Ban agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really a solitary key legal issue here, and that is
whether our state's clergy-penitent statute should be interpreted
to apply only to a favored few faiths, i.e., the Catholic Church
and possibly the Episcopal,'' he said. ``The way to avoid that is
to construe our state clergy-penitent statue as applying to all
faiths. We believe it is capable of that kind of broader
interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   McFarland also asserts that the prosecutor's office is capable
of making its case against Martin without Hamlin's testimony.
According to court documents, Martin's former wife told authorities
he had told her that ``Devyn was fussing, that he lost control,
that he picked up the child and shook him.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's mother also told a detective that her son admitted to
her that ``he did it,'' that he had shaken the baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who talked to the accused and heard him
confess,'' McFarland said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hamlin continues to visit Scott Martin in the Pierce
County Jail every two or three weeks to offer spiritual guidance,
meetings he has grown to treasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's grown into being a good time of accountability'' for
Martin, Hamlin said.
</P>
<P>
   And however wrenching it has been for him personally, Hamlin
said he'd do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about the legal precedent,'' he said. ``It's
distracted me somewhat as a pastor, but at the same time, it's
allowed me to raise the consciousness of people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
