<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLDRAFT2-FALCONS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons add depth through draft
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Falcons didn't address any pressing needs in the
NFL draft Sunday, but coach Dan Reeves doesn't feel they have any
that were urgent in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   So with 19 of 22 starters coming back to a Super Bowl team, and
the other three spots spoken for, the goal was to add depth.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials got more than they planned on when they picked
Utah State safety Johndale Carty in the fourth round, and Iowa
safety Eric Thigpen in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta didn't adhere strictly on Saturday to the ``best player
available'' strategy in rounds one through three, but they did in
rounds four through seven on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't anticipate getting two safeties,'' Reeves said. ``We
see (Carty) as a strong safety. He's a big hitter. On our board,
(Thigpen) was too good a player to pass up.''
</P>
<P>
   In between those picks, the Falcons drafted Kent wide receiver
Eugene Baker in the fifth round, and Kansas State middle linebacker
Jeff Kelly in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh round, Atlanta added LSU center Todd McClure and
Eastern Kentucky wide receiver Rondel Menendez, who's small _
5-feet-9, 178-pound _ but very fast.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' main needs appeared to be backup defensive end, and
a speedy wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   They picked picked defensive end Patrick Kerney in the first
round Saturday, tight end Reggie Kelly in the second, and fullback
Eric Paulk in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, like Menendez, is slight, at 6-feet and 162 pounds.
Though not as fast as Menendez, he had an incredible college
career.
</P>
<P>
   He led the nation in 1997 with 103 catches for 1,549 yards. He
missed five games last season, but had 10 catches for 124 yards
against Georgia, and 13 catches for 227 yards and two touchdowns
against Navy.
</P>
<P>
   Menendez has 4.24-second speed in the 40-yard dash, and averaged
nearly 20 yards per catch.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly is a hustle middle linebacker, Thigpen an All-Big 10 free
safety, and McClure an undersized (6-1, 283 pounds) but sound
center who earned All-SEC honors the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Carter may have been a steal. He had 248 tackles as a sophomore
and junior, when he also had six interceptions, before struggling
in a new defensive scheme last season.
</P>
<P>
   He also had shoulder surgery after nine games which some team
officials felt should have waited until after the season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
