<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A GENUINE BUDGET CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, April 19:
</P>
<P>
   The current budget impasse in Albany involves a disagreement
that is far more profound than New York's normal partisan
squabbling. The state is in danger of turning sane financial
priorities upside down, while undermining its own efforts to
improve public-school standards. Gov. George Pataki is the
politician most responsible for creating the mess, and it is up to
him to chart a way out.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Pataki proposed a $2.7 billion multi-year property tax
relief program, known as STAR, that was to become the centerpiece
of his re-election campaign. The measure targets wealthy suburbs,
which have long complained about the burden of school property
taxes. To that end, STAR compensates districts for cutting school
taxes through a formula that provides the most aid to counties
where home prices are highest. When fully financed, it will reduce
the base value of each home in wealthy Westchester County by
$72,000 for the purpose of assessing school taxes. Poor counties
where property values are below the state average will get $30,000
in exemptions on each home.
</P>
<P>
   To get STAR through the Democratic Assembly, Pataki also agreed
to phase in a $1.21 billion program to improve education statewide,
most notably by establishing universal pre-kindergarten classes and
reducing class size in the early grades.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main reasons the budget is stalled in Albany right
now is that Pataki is backtracking on his end of the commitment.
Pataki may be right that New York cannot afford all his
pre-election promises. But it is outrageous that he wants to
protect a property tax reduction geared to helping people who live
in expensive houses in wealthy suburbs over education aid that is
critical for children in poor districts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the state Board of Regents is in the process of
imposing stringent new graduation requirements on public-school
students and their teachers. But a recent dry run of the new tests
showed that more than a quarter of the state's high school seniors
and more than a third of those in the city would not have graduated
if the standards had been imposed this year. The public schools
will need every bit of aid the state has promised, along with
federal help and new mechanisms for financing school construction,
to prepare the next generation of students.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has been making some tentative moves toward a
presidential campaign, but he can hardly present himself to the
nation as a successful governor when back home he is robbing the
poor to give to the rich, leaving many of the state's public-school
students flailing helplessly. The governor must keep his commitment
to education, even if it means cutting back on the STAR program.
The Legislature must hold out until the governor comes to his
senses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-99 2133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
