<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN SAYS HE'S READY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
  
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Mo Vaughn took batting practice again Sunday.
He said if he wasn't on the 15-day disabled list he could have
played Sunday against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have,'' he said. ``If this was the playoffs, I would
play. I'm swinging the bat OK, it's just a matter of waiting. There
was no need to rush this (injury), it was just a matter of healing
and taking some time. Now I'm pretty much ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn injured his left ankle in his only game as an Angel when
he fell on the steps of the Cleveland Indians' dugout at Edison
Field on opening night. He plans on making the Angels' six-game
road trip to Toronto and Kansas City beginning Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived at the ballpark Sunday, he was still under the
impression he would come off the DL in time for Tuesday's game
against the Blue Jays. Actually, he comes off the DL on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my head I've been thinking Tuesday all along,'' said
Vaughn. ``It was just wishful thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   The last two weeks have been difficult for the new Angels
slugger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has, I mean, you're here to do a job and be there, then
this (injury) happens,'' he said. ``All I'm thinking about now is
starting the season again and putting this behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene's days: Todd Greene has hit safely in eight straight
games and had belted homers in three consecutive games entering
Sunday. He is tied for second in the American League with 15 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   It's welcome news for Greene, who spent the majority of the past
two seasons rehabbing his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just getting pitches up in the zone,'' Greene said.
``When I can consistently stick to my plan at the plate, I feel I
can hit the ball pretty hard.''
</P>
<P>
   His said his current hitting streak, the longest in his career,
is just one of those things that happens when mechanics feel right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I've just been getting my one hit a game,'' he
joked. ``It's playing, the more I play the more consistent I can
be. Right now I'm feeling pretty comfortable out there. It's just a
matter of keeping it going through the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   The day after: After a solid effort Saturday, Angels pitcher Ken
Hill said he is feeling much better. He worked seven innings,
giving up five hits and three earned runs. Hill is learning to
pitch without raising his arms over his head on his windup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just mechanics, that's it,'' Hill said. ``Last night it
felt better. It's coming around. It's just a matter of time. The
more I get out there, the better I will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley to go: Chuck Finley (1-1, 7.30 ERA) will start his third
game of the year Tuesday against Toronto. He has given up 10 earned
runs in 12 innings over his two previous starts.
</P>
<P>
   In three starts against the Blue Jays last season, Finley was
1-0 with a 3.43 ERA.
</P>
</TEXT>
