<HEADLINE>
FOR COLLEGES, A NEW FOCUS ON LABOR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Conn., Ohio, Calif.)   (jw) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ Yale and Harvard universities have long
dueled over who has the best students, best football team and best
law school, but over the weekend they competed with conferences
aimed at building academia's bonds with the labor movement.
</P>
<P>
   In sheer numbers, Yale won hands down, attracting 500 people to
Harvard's 150. But the Harvard students did not seem to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can only bode well for the labor movement that there are
two, three or four conferences taking place on the same weekend,''
said Aaron Bartley, a first-year Harvard law student who helped
organize the conference at his school. ``It indicates there is a
new level of attention and interest in labor issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Many participants said the fact that students from two of the
nation's most prestigious universities _ places hardly viewed as
bastions of the proletariat _were flocking to conferences on labor
illustrates just how far the union movement has come since four
years ago, when labor seemed comatose.
</P>
<P>
   The two conferences had somewhat different themes. At Harvard,
the focus was on creating a nationwide student-labor alliance to
build on recent anti-sweatshop demonstrations on campuses. The
students say they hope to use their voice to help unions on a
variety of issues, like increasing wages for university janitors.
</P>
<P>
   To make theirs a nationwide effort, the Harvard students worked
with students at Stanford in California and Kent State in Ohio, who
also held labor-related conferences this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   At Yale, one focus was on helping the university's more than
1,000 graduate teaching assistants form a union. The school has
refused to grant them union recognition, insisting that they are
students, not workers. The other focus was on protecting the right
of all workers to organize, as speakers asserted that hardball
corporate tactics, like firing union supporters and threatening to
close factories, had denied millions of American workers the right
to join unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harassment, intimidation and coercion are routine in union
elections across America,'' Linda Chavez-Thomson, AFL-CIO executive
vice president, said at the opening session of the Yale conference
on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Students, professors and union members crowded into the
185-year-old Center Church on the New Haven Green to hear labor
leaders and intellectuals talk about how the right to organize was
systematically trampled and how unions were pivotal in building
better lives for workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the great struggle to form unions in the 1930s and
1940s that led to the great middle class in the 1950s and 1960s,''
said John Wilhelm, president of the Hotel Employees and Restaurant
Employees Union.
</P>
<P>
   Wilhelm was the returning hero at the conference, having made a
name for himself in labor circles since graduating from Yale three
decades ago. Wilhelm, often mentioned as a possible future
president of the AFL-CIO, helped lead Yale's secretaries in a
unionization drive 15 years ago and more recently spearheaded one
of the nation's most successful unionization campaigns, in which
tens of thousands of Las Vegas hotel and casino workers have joined
his union.
</P>
<P>
   Wilhelm's appearance had an ulterior motive: to recruit some of
the nation's best and brightest into the union movement. He told
the students that the hotel workers' union had someone on hand, as
did the AFL-CIO, to sign up anyone interested in a career in the
labor movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-nine years ago, I answered an ad: `Labor trainees
wanted. Long hours. Low pay.' '' he said. ``We're still running the
same ad.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Clawson, a sociology professor at the University of
Massachusetts, one of the organizers of the Yale conference, said
the meeting was intended in part to attract students to labor
careers. The conference featured workshops on women and unions,
becoming an organizer, overhauling the health-care industry,
teaching social change and organizing graduate students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly hope it will help to show students a different
world and alternative possibilities,'' he said. ``There are
exciting events taking place and possibilities for engagement and
even employment outside the corporate world.''
</P>
<P>
   At the opening session of the Harvard conference, Marshall Ganz,
a former organizing director with the United Farm Workers who
teaches a course on organizing at the Kennedy School of Government,
said it was short-sighted of unions not to reach out to students in
the past. One reason unions declined in recent decades, he said,
was that they had largely shunned younger people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unions were afraid of universities in the 1960s, and they cut
themselves off to a critical source of renewal,'' Ganz said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Harvard conference was smaller than Yale's because it was
set up by students with little outside support. In contrast, the
Yale meeting had considerable financial and logistical assistance
from Connecticut unions, the AFL-CIO and Scholars, Artists and
Writers for Social Justice, a two-year-old group of intellectuals
that has made common cause with labor.
</P>
<P>
   As if to show that they were not elitists who had forgotten how
to take to the streets, the students at Harvard and Yale started
their conferences with protests. At Harvard, dozens of students
rallied at the Museum of Fine Arts to support museum workers in a
contract dispute.
</P>
<P>
   At Yale, undergraduates and union members braved the rain to
join hundreds of graduate students in their unionization drive. One
protest sign said, ``Union Power in Ivory Tower.'' The rally, like
the Yale conference, was a mixture of punkish graduate students,
clean-cut undergraduates, burly construction workers in union
parkas and graying faculty members and labor leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything said about unions this weekend was positive.
Pointing to the scandal at a union representing New York City
municipal workers, Katha Pollitt, the writer, told the Yale
conference that corruption had turned many people against unions.
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard, Amanda Cage, a union organizer, had a similar
message, saying, ``One of the biggest problems in organizing
workers is the workers who've had bad experiences with unions in
the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Harvard conference there was widespread concern
that it was hard to get more than 1 percent of the student body
involved in labor matters. Bill Capowski, executive director of a
group that seeks to mobilize students for pro-labor and progressive
causes, said, ``A troubling problem is that sometimes I see
thousands of students going to the World Wrestling Federation, and
we're wondering, `How come we can't get one or two volunteers for
our office?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
