<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-FIRES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As new week begins, so do new lives for many fire victims
 &HT;    By Thomas R. Collins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE _ Some residents who saw their homes go up in
smoke three days ago prayed for understanding and comfort at area
churches Sunday, a reprieve from the monumental tasks of starting
over again. Others sifted through the remains of their obliterated
homes in search of prized belongings as if they were on an
archaeological dig. But as the fire dwindled to tiny hot areas
underground, what residents haven't done is heal much.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's service, Raymond and Mary-Ellen Sanchez, both 33,
and their two daughters cried as one as they spoke with Fr. Frank
diPasquale near the altar in St. Elizabeth Ann Seton Church in
western Port St. Lucie, just blocks from the now-charred lands. The
fire leveled their house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no family here,'' Mary-Ellen said. ``This is my family
here, my church. I guess I need to let it out and what better place
to let it out than here?.... We have worked together for 14 years
and to see it washed away in seconds, it's heart-wrenching.''
</P>
<P>
   At Holy Family Catholic Church, Fr. Tom Cauley told his
parishioners to look to God and dwell on the positive: the massive
donations and the moral support.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has taught us in the past week something about our capacity
to do good,'' he said. ``He teaches us through life experience. We
have come together in our community.''
</P>
<P>
   On Franklin Street, 59-year-old Martha Brann dug through the
pool of dust, ash, and stones that used to be her house, trying to
recover buried, burned jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you, it's becoming real tiresome,'' she said. ``I mean
at night, last night, I might have gotten three hours sleep.'' In a
small but meaningful blessing, Red Cross volunteer Judi Arel
brought her a present: a diamond-studded cross Brann's son gave to
her last Christmas that Arel had found in the ruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what she wanted,'' Arel said. ``She's been telling me
for two days about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire was all but completely out Sunday, with two teams of
Navajo firefighters identifying and extinguishing hot spots.
Division of Forestry personnel stayed in St. Lucie County to
organize the final phases of eliminating the blazes' remnants and
to be available should another emergency arise, division senior
forester John Fish said. About 85 workers from his division, the
federal government, the South Florida Water Management District,
and other agencies were working Sunday, he said. Most of St. Lucie
County's firefighters were back to their normal schedules,
department firefighter Jeff Stabile said.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of burned land was scaled back to 759 acres from
previous reports of 2,400 acres, Fish said. The larger number
includes the area within a general fire perimeter, but not all of
the land inside that perimeter actually caught on fire, he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Power was restored to all 2,000 residents who had been without
electricity in the fire area, Bell South spokesman Rob Seitz said
in a news release. Telephone service was restored to everyone
without significant damage, spokeswoman Janice Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators still haven't determined what caused the fire,
Fish said. ``It's obviously human caused,'' he said. ``Just was it
malicious?'' Investigators may have an answer sometime this week,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though short-lived rains Saturday made brush less incendiary,
firefighters are still wary of the potential for more problems, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The possibility's always there.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing complaints that the ravaged neighborhoods should have
had fire hydrants, Fish said they wouldn't have made a difference
since Thursday's whipping winds caused the fire to turn into a
conflagration in such a short time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hydrants are only as good as the fire trucks you have
hooked to them,'' he said. ``Really, water was not a limiting
factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas R. Collins writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
