<HEADER>
A3452 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GRETZKY-PLAYERS-7     04-18 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETZKY-PLAYERS-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
(See also HKN-RANGERS-PENGUINS) 
(rk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While waiting in the tunnels of Madison Square Garden
before the start of the tributes to Wayne Gretzky, seated behind
the goal watching the game and appearing at the post-game
interviews, Mark Messier never removed his sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a look he sought to effect. It was simply that he
wanted protection from the flashing cameras if he could not hold
back the tears.
</P>
<P>
   Messier, Gretzky's teammate on the great Edmonton Oiler teams of
the 1980s and then on the New York Rangers, walked onto the ice
during the pre-game tribute Sunday after flying in from Vancouver.
The sound was deafening as fans roared their appreciation for the
greatness of Gretzky and for the enormous contributions of Messier.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps there was no greater measurement of the greatness of
Gretzky than the fact that he reduced players who would fill the
ladder below him to the level of fans.
</P>
<P>
   Messier stood on the ice beside Mario Lemieux before the game,
joined by Gretzky and his former coach and general manager in
Edmonton, Glen Sather. Also on hand were Paul Coffey, a vital
component of those Oiler teams; Mike Keenan, who coached Gretzky
briefly in St. Louis, and Ulf Samuelsson, who had been dealt by the
Rangers earlier this season. Gordie Howe presented a recorded video
message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have missed it for the world,'' Messier said. ``You
know, it was kind of fun sitting in the crowd tonight, too, and
just watching the whole show come down from a fan perspective. We
don't get that opportunity to sit in the stands with the people and
hear the comments and that's what I really wanted to do tonight, to
really come here and just _ I know it's hard because of all the
things going on _ but just try to take it all in like a fan would
and sit in the seats and watch the game. It was a great way to see
him play his last game.''
</P>
<P>
   Messier was showered with as much gratitude as anyone to take a
turn on the ice Sunday, the memory of the Stanley Cup he brought to
New York still vivid. But what brought Messier here, skipping a
Canucks team dinner to attend, was a chance to pay tribute to not
only a great player, but to a friend, and to honor a friendship
that began when the two were just kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Wayne and I have been growing up together as
18-year-olds and going through the things we did obviously cemented
a bond between us that is next to being brothers, so to speak,''
Messier said. ``I just think that there was so much pressure on him
and he knew he had some friends that he was able to talk to when we
were younger, where he could be Wayne Gretzky himself inside the
dressing room.''
</P>
<P>
   Messier said that in their conversations this week, he never
attempted to talk Gretzky out of his decision to leave the game,
but admitted that it made him reflect on the 20 years that have
passed and where his own career stands.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux, the Pittsburgh Penguins' star who retired early after
incurring Hodgkin's disease and then returned to back problems that
he could not overcome, understood Gretzky's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always too soon when you see a great player retire,''
Lemieux said. ``You always think they can play until they're 40, 45
years old. But there just comes a time when you step back and you
realize that, maybe you're not the player that you were years ago.
That's always frustrating for a great athlete, not being able to
play at the level they once played at and I'm sure that had an
effect on Wayne's decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very emotional today,'' he added of watching Gretzky
take those final laps around the ice, just as Lemieux had in
Pittsburgh. ``I almost cried a couple of times. I remember the way
I felt in Pittsburgh when I skated around and thanked the fans and
everybody that had been a part of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be on that score sheet with him some way
tonight,'' said Brian Leetch, the Ranger captain, who scored the
lone Rangers goal, on an assist from Gretzky and Mathieu Schneider.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we scored at the end of the second, I retaped my stick
like I usually do. Then I was looking at it and I said, `You know I
really shouldn't take this out on the ice in case it breaks or
something.' Wayne had just given me one of the sticks that he had
signed and I took those two and put them in the back.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sather also hurried to New York to see this final tribute to
Gretzky, who began his NHL career in Edmonton under his tutelage.
But he admitted that he had little to teach Gretzky, who arrived as
a slightly built 17-year-old, but armed with an intelligence for
the game that was unlike any other.
</P>
<P>
   ``His legacy is a million memories as far as I'm concerned,''
Sather said. ``Not only in the games, but in the practices, locker,
on the buses. I don't know what he's going to leave as far as the
fans are concerned, probably the way he sets up behind the net,
tricky behind-the-back passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is one thing. We used to play a game in
Edmonton of three-on-three, and he would fool around with us like
he'd fool around with his kids in the backyard, except he was
fooling around with pro players and guys who had played pro hockey
their entire lives. It was like he was just having a good time with
us and we couldn't get the puck off of him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The memories that I have about Wayne don't have too much with
what he did on the ice,'' Sather added. ``I think it's what he did
off the ice.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
