<SLUG> BC-NY-ABORTION-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEEK OF ABORTION PROTESTS BEGINS LOUDLY IN BUFFALO 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ On the first day of a much-anticipated weeklong
rally, anti-abortion protesters returned to the streets of Buffalo
in full-throated fashion Sunday, seven years after raucous
anti-abortion protests here triggered more than 600 arrests.
</P>
<P>
   There was an abundance of enthusiasm and displays of conviction
but no violence and no arrests in three events Sunday, a morning
church service, an afternoon news conference and an evening church
meeting filled with songs and videos. The events were organized by
the national anti-abortion group Operation Rescue, the sponsor of
the weeklong rally here and in other parts of western New York that
is being called Operation Save America.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a sign, perhaps, of the frenzied week to come when
abortion-rights supporters appeared, unannounced, at the
anti-abortion news conference and rally, held in downtown Buffalo.
They chanted slogans, hoping to drown out their opponents or to at
least provide a running commentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a blessing to be here at the epicenter of the spiritual
battle that's manifesting itself in western New York,'' said Jerry
Crawford, who is coordinating the efforts of Operation Save America
in Rochester. His voice bellowing with fortitude, he continued,
``There is a Holy God, and this nation has deeply, deeply offended
him!''
</P>
<P>
   To which an abortion-rights protester shouted, ``Are you God's
public relations assistant?''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Operation Save America seems to be an event made for
the cameras. The rally is taking place less than six months after
the as-yet unsolved killing of Dr. Barnett Slepian, a physician who
performed abortions and was shot in his home in a Buffalo suburb by
a sniper. And Buffalo is a city that, thanks to the Blizzard of '77
and the Spring of Life, as the abortion protests of 1992 were
known, is stuck with an image of being a magnet for unruly weather
and unruly demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers expect this week's rally to be smaller than the 1992
event, with perhaps 200 to 600 people from around the country,
compared with more than 1,000 people in 1992. They have also
broadened their protests this time to include child pornography,
school violence and teen-age sex. Anti-abortion demonstrators plan
to stake out positions in front of bookstores, schools and other
locations in addition to abortion clinics, including the one where
Slepian worked.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever the plans, abortion-rights protesters said they
expected to shadow their adversaries every step.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their kind of America is an America of male domination, of
racism, of theocracy,'' said Mary Lou Greenberg, a longtime
activist and abortion-rights supporter from Manhattan who
participated in the march across the Brooklyn Bridge in memory of
Amadou Diallo on Thursday before traveling to Buffalo on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the unexpected presence of abortion-rights supporters
providing a dueling soundtrack, Sunday's news conference was also
noteworthy for what the anti-abortion leaders said of their plans
to deal with a recent court decision.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, in a victory for abortion-rights activists and State
Attorney General Eliot Spitzer, U.S. District Judge Richard Arcara
agreed to expand to at least 50 feet the 15-foot buffer zones
between protesters and abortion clinics. Sunday, though, the Rev.
Flip Benham, the national director of Operation Rescue, hinted that
his followers would test the limit, if not flout the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you think those buffer zones are the most ridiculous
things you've ever heard of in your life?'' said Benham, clutching
a Bible and smiling on a chilly, blustery day under slate-gray
skies. ``We are going to honor the law of Almighty God and submit
to Him, no matter what the cost.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
