<SLUG> BC-FREAKNIK-COW-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Four-legged gal crashes street party
</P>
<P>
   By Ralph Ellis
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 COX NEWS SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Freaknik was three days of calm.
</P>
<P>
   Beefnik was 30 minutes of udder chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Duane Maxwell, 57, was hauling two newly purchased cows from
Fairburn, Ga. to his home in Braselton, Ga. on Sunday afternoon
when his cattle trailer overturned between Fifth and 10th streets
on the Downtown Connector. The cows broke away when Maxwell and
Atlanta police tried to transfer them to a police horse trailer.
One cow was quickly apprehended. The other became a four-legged
fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   With all northbound traffic backed up at the wreck scene, the
cow hoofed it down the empty northbound lanes of the connector,
ignoring police officers who surrounded the moving animal like a
cloud of flies. About 40 police made chase on foot, on motorcycles,
in patrol cars.
</P>
<P>
   The cow traveled down the exit lane, hung a quick right onto
Peachtree Place and ducked into an alley halfway up the block. She
scampered behind the building, crossed Spring Street and was
trapped in the walled corner of a parking lot across from a
Checkers hamburger restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   While helicopters from television stations hovered, police
closed in and finally lassoed the cow. Both cows were taken to the
mounted patrol facility in Grant Park until Maxwell finds a new
trailer.
</P>
<P>
   The massive response was available because so many officers were
on Freaknik duty. Atlanta Police Chief Beverly Harvard put the
episode into perspective: ``This is one female that didn't get the
word the nice girls were supposed to stay away.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Ellis writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
