<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; COMBAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO said Sunday that the previous 24 hours had been the
busiest in its 25 days of air strikes against Yugoslavia, with 500
sorties flown on Saturday afternoon and overnight. Officials in
Brussels said 36 targets were struck overnight, including an
explosives plant, a refinery complex and an airfield.
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO said the first of 24 U.S. Apache helicopter gunships were
expected in Albania from Italy by Monday, after severe storms
delayed deployment at least another day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REFUGEES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Ethnic Albanians continued to pour out of Kosovo at the rate
of 1,000 an hour, aid officials said. As an estimated 30,000
refugees arrived in Albania and Macedonia on Saturday, and an
additional 40,000 were either leaving Kosovo or massing at its
borders on Sunday, international monitors said they believed
Serbian forces may be poised for another major effort to purge
Kosovo of its Albanian majority.
</P>
<P>
   _ A car carrying seven people from Kosovo across the border to
Albania early Sunday struck a land mine, killing three children,
their mother and their grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIPLOMACY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Yugoslavia severed diplomatic relations with Albania, accusing
it of siding with NATO.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER DEVELOPMENTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The numbers of Albanian Kosovars killed by Serbs may be far
higher than the few thousand cited by NATO officials in recent
days, a U.S. official said. He said the fate of 100,000 ethnic
Albanian men is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO raised evidence of what it said were 43 mass grave sites
in Kosovo, some dug by groups of Kosovo Albanians rounded up by
Serbian forces to bury their countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ON THE WEB  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Continuous coverage of the conflict in Yugoslavia is available
from The New York Times on the Web: http://www.nytimes.com  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
