<SLUG> BC-HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NEVER A GAME QUITE LIKE IT
</HEADLINE>
   (See also HKN-RANGERS-PENGUINS) 
(rk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The other great ones never had an advertised last
game. Babe Ruth hit three home runs one day for the Boston Braves,
and left soon after. Michael Jordan's last shot won a sixth title
for the Chicago Bulls six months before he walked away. Joe Montana
threw his last pass, then announced his departure.
</P>
<P>
   But hockey's Great One, 38-year-old Wayne Gretzky, had an
advertised last game Sunday, and there has never been a game in any
sport quite like it.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the other great ones, the Great One had a last chance to
hear a last hurrah doing what he did. In a game. With the New York
Rangers long eliminated from the Stanley Cup playoffs, the 2-1
overtime loss to the Pittsburgh Penguins didn't mean as much as his
assist on Brian Leetch's goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian,'' he said later with a modest smile, ``will go down as
the guy who scored the last goal that I ever set up.''
</P>
<P>
   Engrave the numbers now in his NHL career records: 1,963 assists
to go with 894 goals for 2,857 points.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday's game wasn't so much a game as it was a celebration
of all the games in the Great One's career.
</P>
<P>
   He enjoyed commissioner Gary Bettman saying, ``When you take off
that sweater, your jersey, you will be the last player in the NHL
to ever wear 99.'' He appreciated the fond farewells from Mark
Messier, Mario Lemieux and, on the video board, Michael Jordan. He
peeked at the videotapes of his historic goals.
</P>
<P>
   When the game was over, he skated slowly around the Madison
Square Garden ice, waving to all the fans who were standing and
applauding. As if he didn't want to leave. And the game had
provided the perfect stage, the perfect ending for a career
arguably more dominant than that of any athlete in any sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a hockey player,'' he said Thursday night in Ottawa after
his last game in Canada. ``That's what I am. I play hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   He never tried to be anything else. Never wanted to be anything
else. And he played hockey more artistically than anyone ever has
in a sport known for its often brutal toughness.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sunday, that artistry was there, just not as much of it as
there once was. But whenever he touched the puck, the crowd roared,
hoping he would do something magical, as he so often had.
</P>
<P>
   John Muckler, the Rangers' coach, was hoping that, too, when he
called a timeout with about 30 seconds remaining in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked up,'' the Great One said later, ``and I said, `My
goodness, I've got 30 seconds to go.' That's when it hit me that I
was done.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes earlier, Muckler had received a note that his daughter
in Edmonton had given birth to a baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the timeout,'' Gretzky recalled, ``John said, `I just
had a grandson today in Edmonton and you've got to get the winner.'
And maybe when I was younger, I might have got that winner for him,
but I didn't get it for him today.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, on a breakaway, he appeared to have a chance for
that winner, but Tom Barrasso, the Penguins goaltender, swooped to
the puck first. And after only 1 minute 22 seconds of overtime,
Jaromir Jagr scored the winning goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it was fitting that the best young player in the game
scored in overtime,'' the Great One said, meaning Jagr. ``Everyone
talks about passing torches and all that stuff. He caught it.
That's what I told him. I said, `You caught it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Great One laughed, adding that Jagr told him, ``I didn't
mean to do that.'' Then Gretzky said he told Jagr, ``That's what I
used to say.''
</P>
<P>
   With the game decided, the Great One shook hands with the
Penguins as if a Stanley Cup playoff series had ended, hugged his
Ranger teammates, then skated in slow circles and waved to the
applause that had seemed almost continuous since he had glided onto
the ice for the warm-up before the last of all his games that began
with those one-on-one games as a youngster in Brantford, Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   ``I built our backyard rink,'' his father, Walter, remembered,
``because I was freezing waiting for him at the other rinks. He'd
go in our backyard with the kid next door the goaltender, Brian
Rizzetto.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 5, Wayne Gretzky's hockey genius was obvious. Playing
against 10- and 11-year-olds, he made the Brantford novice all-star
team. At age 11, he scored 378 goals in 68 games, including 3 in 45
seconds. But of all the games and all the goals, his father's
favorite occurred on Dec. 30, 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``The phone rang late that night,'' Walter Gretzky recalled.
``Wayne said, `I called to let you know I did it _ 50 goals in 39
games.' I said, `What took you so long?'''
</P>
<P>
   Maurice ``Rocket'' Richard had scored 50 goals in a 50-game
season for the Montreal Canadiens more than half a century ago and
Mike Bossy had scored 50 in 50 for the Islanders, but the Great One
had scored his 50 in only 39 games, en route to 92 goals that
season and a nickname that is almost an understatement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate mediocrity,'' the Great One once said. ``If there's one
thing I can't accept, it's mediocrity.''
</P>
<P>
   And even though Wayne Gretzky still has too much artistry to be
mediocre, the threat of mediocrity is as good a reason as any as to
why he played his advertised last game. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-99 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
