<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-OFFICER-SLAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN SAID TO HAVE CONFESSED TO KILLING OF POLICEWOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Hawaii, Ga., Va.)   (jw) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The man charged with killing an Orange, N.J., policewoman
confessed to his mother and to the authorities over the weekend
that he had committed the crime, a person close to his family said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Condell Woodson, 25, who was arrested early
Saturday at the home of a cousin in Newark, N.J., later told his
mother, Beverly Woodson, who visited him at the Essex County Jail,
that he had fatally shot the officer, Joyce Anne Carnegie, in
Orange on the night of April 8, said the person close to the
family, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The Essex County prosecutor's office declined Sunday to say if
Woodson had made a formal confession to authorities. But the person
close to the family quoted Woodson's sister, Natasha, as saying
that he had done so.
</P>
<P>
   Several family members who were detained and questioned by
authorities when Woodson was arrested in a predawn raid on Saturday
at the cousin's home in Newark refused to discuss the case Sunday,
and were reluctant even to give their names to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But one, the wife of Woodson's cousin, said Woodson had called
them from the Essex County Jail. ``He called us last night and said
he's not mad at us,'' said the woman, who asked to be identified
only as S. Shields, her maiden name. ``He said he loves us, and
he's just glad it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviews Sunday with Woodson's father and others who have
known the suspect provided a detailed portrait of Woodson as a
troubled young man, who grew up as an Army brat in New Jersey,
Hawaii and Virginia; became a gifted athlete and honor student at
Orange High School; struggled in recent years to hold jobs and
raise a 2-year-old son in Georgia, and has been convicted on a
variety of drug, weapons, robbery and assault charges.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had been living in Georgia since 1993, Woodson was
said to have traveled to New Jersey last month after the death of a
grandfather he had been close to. He had then stayed with relatives
and friends in Orange and, since Tuesday, at the home of the cousin
in Newark where he was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Some relatives, while reluctant to talk about the case, told of
being terrorized by a score of heavily armed federal agents and
police officers, who broke down the front and back doors of their
home in a 3:30 a.m. raid, pointed guns at infants and took eight
people, including three children, into custody.
</P>
<P>
   Woodson, who is charged with murder, felony murder, robbery and
weapons offenses in the death of Ms. Carnegie, is being held in
lieu of $1 million bail for an arraignment early this week in Essex
County Superior Court. If convicted, he could face life in prison
or the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Sunday that Woodson _ the fourth person
arrested in a convoluted case that began when Ms. Carnegie
approached a robbery suspect and was shot in the head and abdomen
11 days ago _ was traced through a pistol that authorities believe
was used in the shooting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
