u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TARGETS-1STLD-     04-18 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TARGETS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1250(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO SAID TO HIT PLANTS OWNED BY MILOSEVIC ASSOCIATES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Adds 5th and 6th grafs with results of the weekend's military
action)  (Exclusive) 
(rk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT AND STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In listing its bombing targets in Yugoslavia, NATO
has generally described them as facilities that feed Slobodan
Milosevic's war machine. What the Pentagon does not usually say is
that some of the refineries and factories have also been chosen as
targets because they are run by cronies of the Yugoslav president.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, according to senior NATO and Pentagon officials, is to
undermine Milosevic's control by chipping away at his system of
political and economic patronage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't care if his soldiers die in Kosovo, as long as he
stays in power,'' one senior military officer said of Milosevic.
``But if you blow up some things near and dear to him _ or to
somebody close to him _ then that could have an effect.''
</P>
<P>
   While NATO's bombing seems to have solidified popular support
for Milosevic, the officials said they hope the attacks against
some of the targets will turn loyal supporters against him by
destroying their own sources of wealth and power.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing continued over the weekend, with NATO saying Sunday
that the previous 24 hours had been the busiest to date in the
bombing campaign, with 500 sorties flown on Saturday afternoon and
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   During the night 36 targets were struck, officials in Brussels
said, including an explosives plant, a refinery complex, an
airfield, radar and communications sites and military vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's oil and gas industry, for example, has suffered
enormously under NATO's strikes. While the stated aim of those
attacks has been to choke off fuel to the armed forces operating in
Kosovo, the strikes must also be a blow to Dragan Tomic, the
director of Yugo Petrol, who as speaker of the federal Parliament
in Belgrade, is a close ally of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   On April 9, a missile strike destroyed the Zastava automotive
plant in Kragujevac. Its director, Milan Beko, has served under
Milosevic as minister of privatization.
</P>
<P>
   Four days earlier, NATO struck a tobacco factory and warehouse
in Nis, and damage to tobacco factories has been reported in other
cities. According to American intelligence reports, a major player
in Yugoslavia's tobacco distribution is Milosevic's son, Marko.
</P>
<P>
   So far, economic and industrial targets have made up only a
small portion of NATO's targets. Of the roughly 200 targets
attacked since the air war began on March 24, only a dozen have
been strictly industrial sites, like factories. That percentage
grows when those targets are combined with fuel storage and
ammunition factories.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO presses on with bombing that has done little to stop the
purging of ethnic Albanians from Kosovo, some NATO and Pentagon
military leaders have advocated striking still more economic and
industrial targets, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   These commanders, including the alliance's supreme commander,
Gen. Wesley K. Clark, believe that NATO has to escalate its efforts
to undermine Milosevic's 11 1/2-year grip on power.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we continue sustaining this air campaign and intensifying
it in a way that he sees he is slowly but surely starting to lose
those instruments of power that keep him in power, then he's going
to have to make a decision,'' Secretary of Defense William Cohen
testified on Capitol Hill last week.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen. Henry H.
Shelton, disclosed that NATO's political leaders had not yet
approved a small group of targets that he grouped together under
the objective ``decimate.'' He said NATO warplanes could begin
striking such targets ``in a few days.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelton declined to identify those targets, but the highly
classified list includes additional industrial and economic sites,
according to a senior administration official.
</P>
<P>
   Attacking those targets would carry a much higher risk of
civilian casualties and would cause the kind of profound disruption
of day-to-day life for ordinary Yugoslavs that NATO has so far
sought to avoid, that official said.
</P>
<P>
   Such strikes could also undercut NATO's stated rationale for its
bombing: to degrade the military and police forces involved in the
killings in Kosovo rather than wage war on the people of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Pentagon and NATO are looking for ways to
intensify pressure on Milosevic's government. ``We're trying to
make the price higher and higher,'' a senior defense official said.
``And there are lots of ways to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   While not aiming directly for Milosevic, American and NATO
officials say they are targeting what they describe as his four
pillars of power: the political machine, the media, military and
security forces, and the economic system.
</P>
<P>
   A senior American military officer said the targets on NATO's
list included strikes at ``the things that keep him afloat.'' The
idea, the officer said, is to instill fear in those whose economic
standing depends on Milosevic, to make them think ``we didn't
bargain for this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can achieve that mindset, then who knows what will
happen?'' the officer said.
</P>
<P>
   Allied warplanes and cruise missiles have struck half a dozen
targets considered to be part of the ``national command
authority,'' several of them in and around Belgrade. These include
headquarters and bunkers believed to be used by political and
military leaders _ although it is not clear whether anybody was
killed or injured.
</P>
<P>
   In Yugoslavia's state-run economy, virtually any industrial or
economic activity can be linked to Milosevic's government. Ever
since the former Yugoslavia collapsed into its rump state today,
and the economy was hit from 1992 to 1995 by comprehensive
sanctions, Milosevic, a former banker and Communist bureaucrat, has
been able to tighten his control of the little business left.
</P>
<P>
   The core elements of the economy _ including agriculture, fuel,
manufacturing and exports and imports _ are operated by Milosevic's
cronies virtually as fiefs, American officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has used funds gained from industry and his cronies
mostly to finance an effective security apparatus to maintain
political control, according to experts and intelligence estimates.
</P>
<P>
   But his family and associates also have benefited, living far
more lavishly than most Yugoslavs, whose standard of living has
declined markedly since the country began its bloody breakup in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook last week challenged
Milosevic to admit to his people that he has bought three villas in
Greece. European media reports also have spoken of the family
funneling money to Swiss banks through French accounts held by
Milosevic's wife, Mirjana Markovic.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's son, Marko, is also said to profit from his
position; his holdings are believed to include a discotheque and a
tobacco distribution network. Before the war, Yugoslav media
reported that he had announced plans to open a Disney-style theme
park, called Bambiland.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials have estimated damage from the bombing as
high as $100 billion, including damage to roads, destroyed bridges
and railways which has the ripple effect of disrupting commerce.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no signs that Milosevic has lost the backing of
his key supporters.
</P>
<P>
   One American government official familiar with the Yugoslav
economy said the prospects were slim that Milosevic's cronies,
however battered, would turn on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``A scenario that would involve these guys acting as a group
seems fairly unlikely,'' the official said. ``They don't have
anywhere to turn besides Milosevic.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic appoints the executives of each of the country's
monopolies, many of whom also serve as government ministers. Dejan
Kovacevic, the minister of construction, also heads Mastrogradnje,
one of the country's largest construction firms. Zivota Kosic, the
minister of energy and mining, also heads a natural resources
concern called Duvanksa Industrija Nis. Nis is southern Serbia's
largest city, and has been a repeated target of NATO bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Another state-run industry that has been severely disrupted is
ammunition production, which is overseen by an umbrella
organization headed by Maj. Gen. Jovan Cekovic.
</P>
<P>
   Although the industry has a clear military function, it has also
historically provided Yugoslavia with hard currency, and the
destruction of the plants has crippled another source of profits
for people close to Milosevic, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon and NATO officials declined to provide a list of
economic or industrial targets that have been struck. But
Yugoslavia's official news agencies have reported strikes against
several, in addition to oil depots and refineries. They include a
small-plane manufacturer in Pancevo, a construction-equipment plant
in Krusevac and a plastics factory in Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   NATO maintains that each of its targets has military value, even
if some have a benign civilian use, too. For example, NATO has
repeatedly struck a plant in Cacak that Yugoslav officials
portrayed as an appliance factory. Reporters allowed to tour the
scene described vacuum cleaners in various states of destruction.
Western officials say the plant also included a subterranean
ammunition section.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's targets are chosen by military aides to Clark in
Brussels, Germany and Italy. These targeting officials work closely
with a little known cell within the Joint Chiefs of Staff at the
Pentagon, called J-2T, where officers consider a range of technical
aspects, including which weapon is the most effective for a
particular mission and where exactly it should be aimed.
</P>
<P>
   The planners weigh the military value of a target against the
drawbacks, namely the risk to pilots if the target is in a heavily
defended area and the risk to civilians if it is in a heavily
populated area.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers at the Pentagon and at NATO's headquarters in Belgium
review each target carefully to justify striking it. Hitting
industrial and economic sites requires walking a fine line, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Planners have been restricted by NATO's political process..
Cohen said President Clinton, like leaders of other major NATO
countries, reviews the target list, considering ``the political
consequence of hitting a particular target.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials insist the bombing, which continued for a 26th
day Sunday, is taking a toll, wearing down Yugoslav materiel,
supplies and resolve. But the political process has kept some
targets off the list.
</P>
<P>
   Clark has sought approval _ so far unsuccessfully _ to attack
another of the pillars of Milosevic's support: the communications
industry. Control of radio and television has been a mainstay of
the Yugoslav leader's 11 1/2 years in power. One radio station is
even owned by his daughter, Marija.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-18-99 2229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
