<SLUG> BC-RAC-KRONE-FAREWELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRONE SAYS FAREWELL WITH THREE WINNERS TO FINISH WITH 3,546 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Texas) (rk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may not have drawn as much attention as Wayne Gretzky's
goodbye at Madison Square Garden, but Julie Krone also said
farewell Sunday when she rode three winners at Lone Star Park in
Grand Prairie, Texas, on the final day of her career at the races.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old Krone, the most accomplished female rider in the
world, ended her 18 years in the saddle with a flourish. But she
missed the big one when her mount, Desert Demon, could not quite
overtake the 30-1 long shot T.B. Track Star and lost the $300,000
Lone Star Derby by one length.
</P>
<P>
   Krone, who won her first race at Tampa Bay Downs in 1981, won
3,546 races that included 277 stakes, and her mounts won more than
$80 million in prize money. But she suffered severe injuries in
recent years, and announced two weeks ago that she would close her
career because she wanted to pursue new interests, had nothing left
to prove and did not want to risk more injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very relieved I had some winners today,'' Krone said.
``The competitive side of me wanted to go out as a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Krone shared the spotlight Sunday with another racing star, Real
Quiet, last year's winner of the Kentucky Derby and the Preakness,
who went off the 1-2 favorite in the $250,000 Texas Mile. But Real
Quiet could not catch Littlebitlively, who won the race for the
second straight year and was still in front by the length of his
neck when they crossed the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   The race marked the second defeat in a row for Real Quiet, who
also ran second on March 7 in the New Orleans Handicap at the Fair
Grounds. He is owned by Mike Pegram and trained by Bob Baffert, and
was ridden by his regular jockey, Gary Stevens. The winner, owned
by John Franks and trained by Bobby Barnett, ran the mile in 1:35
3/5 with Carlos Gonzalez riding. He was the second choice at 3-1,
and he set the pace throughout.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
