<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3486 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-WAR-BOS &LR;      04-18 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-WAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US OFFICIALS DENY REPORT THAT GROUND WAR IS PLANNED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As NATO bombs set off a series of spectacular
blazes at Serbian oil refineries, President Clinton vowed to
continue the air campaign until ``belligerent tyrant'' Slobodan
Milosevic withdraws his forces from Kosovo and allows the return of
ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton administration officials, appearing on a round of
Sunday television talk shows, once again said they had no plans to
send in ground troops, and they denied a British newspaper report
that NATO is preparing 80,000 troops for a ground war as early as
May.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright, asked whether US
troops are preparing for the possibility of a ground war, replied:
``There is not any training for such an operation.''
</P>
<P>
   US Senator John Kerry, a Massachusetts Democrat who has been
mostly supportive of administration policy, reacted on NBC-TV's
``Meet the Press'' by expressing concerns that the lack of a ground
war plan may be hurting the war effort.
</P>
<P>
   While not calling for a ground war, Kerry said: ``We should have
a plan. We never should have taken it off the table. I think we may
have complicated the equation here by having it off the table as
way back as last fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   --Yugoslavia broke off diplomatic relations with Albania, saying
that Albania is helping NATO bomb Belgrade and other Yugoslav
targets.
</P>
<P>
   --Scores of ethnic Albanians still inside Kosovo were killed in
new clashes with the Serbian forces in the central portion of the
republic.
</P>
<P>
   --The expected arrival of Apache helicopters Sunday was delayed
by poor weather conditions at the airport in Tirana, Albania. The
Apaches are expected to go after Serbian ground forces and tanks
inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade and elsewhere, the sky was filled with black smoke
after NATO warplanes hit several plants. NATO officials said they
had struck oil facilities and had devastated Yugoslavia's ability
to refine crude oil.
</P>
<P>
   A strike on a refinery in Novi Sad injured eight people,
according to the state-run Tanjug news agency.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said Sunday's bombing knocked out 13 military
vehicles, hit two MiG-21 fighter jets on the ground, and struck
supply lines. Serbian media said they also struck several bridges,
including one near the southern Serbian town of Raska that serves
as a major rail link to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our air campaign is getting stronger,'' Albright said on
ABC-TV's ``This Week.'' ``I think if you listen day by day to the
damage assessments, you can see that greater damage is being done
to the things that really matter to Milosevic, those that he holds
dear. Those are being damaged.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a letter published Sunday in The Times of London,
made clear that he wants to replace Milosevic as Yugoslav president
and also that he does not want to see Kosovo become an independent
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe that the solution to hatred in the Balkans is
even greater Balkanization,'' Clinton wrote. ``Once we start
redrawing maps, the disputes and displacement of people would be
hard to stop. The best solution is not the endless shifting of
Europe's borders along ethnic lines, but rather integration among
European states that work together to make a virtue, not a blood
feud, out of diversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically, the realization of this vision will require a
democratic transition in Serbia itself, for the region cannot be
secure with a belligerent tyrant in its midst.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also focused on Yugoslavia's neighbors, talking with the
presidents of Albania, Hungary, and Romania. Clinton promised to
fulfill his promise of returning the Kosovars to their home and
also told the leaders that he would focus new attention on
rebuilding southeastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   While administration officials played down speculation about
ground troops, there was frustration with the delay in bringing 24
Apache helicopters to Albania. The low-flowing choppers carry chain
guns and 16 laser-guided anti-tank missiles.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO spoke about another night of successful bombing,
contending that Milosevic's army is losing much of its
functionality, there was also an array of evidence that things are
getting worse for the Kosovar Albanians. NATO officials said they
had evidence of mass graves in Kosovo, some apparently dug by the
Albanians under forced labor conditions.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 200,000 more refugees are expected to cross the
border from Kosovo in coming days, NATO officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic, speaking on
``This Week,'' denied that Serb forces were killing anyone in
Kosovo or elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``All citizens in Yugoslavia are safe, free, and equal,''
Jovanovic said. ``There is no killing, no raping, no depriving of
anybody of any human or national minority of citizen's rights.
These accusations are a mere NATO propaganda aimed at justifying a
blunt aggression against Yugoslavia as a sovereign European
state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Richard Lugar, an Indiana Republican, criticized fellow
Republicans who he said are reluctant to support Clinton in the
wake of the impeachment trial. ``They've got to get over it,''
Lugar said on ``Meet the Press.'' ``NATO is on the right side of
history. Ethnic cleansing has got to stop. And the American people
support that. They're prepared really to support a ground war.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press and Reuters contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
