<HEADER>
A3487 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBI-JACKSON-SPI &LR;      04-18 1701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBI-JACKSON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI FILES DETAIL THREATS AGAINST LATE SEN. HENRY JACKSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The late Sen. Henry Jackson's ardent support for
Israel brought him a string of death threats laced with vitriolic
anti-Semitic rhetoric, according to documents in the senator's FBI
files.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, a Democrat from Everett, was subjected to a variety of
harassment as a result of being a prominent public official. Once
he was spat on by a Yippie demonstrator in Wisconsin, protesters
twice pelted him with marshmallows, and once his Everett, Wash.
home was vandalized.
</P>
<P>
   But the FBI files, obtained by the Seattle Post-Intelligencer
under a Freedom of Information Act request, reveal for the first
time the extent and intensity of threats against his life. They
increased in the mid-1970s, as Jackson prepared for his 1976
presidential run.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and his family took the threats seriously. He often had
more security around him than any politician in state history. He
was taken off airplanes through special doors, driven off the
tarmac at Sea-Tac International Airport, and had both state patrol
and U.S. Marshal escorts for such mundane duties as a speech at
Western Washington University in Bellingham. The reason for the
security wasn't explained at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's son, Peter Jackson, said in an interview that Black
September, the Palestinian terrorist group responsible for the 1972
Munich Olympics massacre, threatened to assassinate his father. As
a result, the family's mail at home was X-rayed, and Jackson
secretly wore a bullet-proof vest during an Everett Fourth of July
parade.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to prevent the senator's children from being
kidnapped, his home was placed under police surveillance and his
children were kept indoors whenever possible and watched whenever
they left the house.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson received about a dozen death threats during the 1970s,
when he was highly visible as a leading voice on U.S. foreign
policy, as a presidential candidate, as the chairman of the Senate
Energy Committee during the oil crisis, and as a frequent guest on
television talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   The threats were occasionally graphic _ one writer suggested
that Jackson should be killed and that some of his remains could
then be used as fuel during an energy crisis. Others were oddly
respectful, with one reading, ``The Honorable Henry Jackson. This
is a warning to you and your wife. If you win you are a dead man.''
</P>
<P>
   Most threats were investigated by the FBI, but in the few cases
when letter writers were identified, prosecutors generally deemed
that the threats were too vague to warrant prosecution. Many of
those making threats seemed to be unbalanced _ one threat was
traced to someone trying to frame an ex-spouse; another to a
homebound 70-year-old Pennsylvania woman who was apparently whiling
the hours away by penning vicious notes to elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   Security for Jackson was increased several times _ in 1975, when
someone threatened to shoot him at the Tampa Airport; in 1976, when
someone threatened to bomb a speech by Jackson in Buffalo; and in
1979, when the senator's trip to Israel was preceded by several
fliers purportedly from the Red Brigade, a European terrorist
organization, that depicted Jackson with a Star of David on his
forehead and bore the caption, ``Sen. Jackson Sentenced to Death.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is one of the legendary giants of Washington state
political history. Jackson served in the House of Representatives
from 1941 until 1952 and in the Senate from 1953 until his death in
1983.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI files reveal nothing that might sully Jackson's place in
history; there is not a hint of personal or professional
impropriety. In fact, the one time the FBI investigated Jackson, in
1948, the worst thing the agents could come up with was that
Jackson ``is considered `liberal' in that he advocates social
legislation and pro-labor measures for the benefit of the working
class.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI claimed that Jackson had been supported by the Communist
Party during his 1944 House campaign. But the files also note that
``reliable confidential informants have advised that Jackson has no
Communist Party connections.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, by the end of his career, Jackson was one of the
strongest anti-Communist voices in Congress, a leading architect of
U.S. Cold War foreign policy and a determined critic of detente.
Some of his foreign policy aides later held key posts in the Reagan
administration.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson also had little patience for the excesses of the Red
Scare. Even before the height of Congress' frenzied quest to find
domestic subversives, Jackson had repeatedly rebuffed pressure from
House leaders to accept the chairmanship of the House Un-American
Activities Committee, according to a memo from an FBI agent in
Jackson's files.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike many conservative anti-Communists, Jackson emphasized
more the external danger posed by the Soviet Union than the
internal problem of subversion,'' said Robert Kaufman, a University
of Vermont political scientist whose biography of Jackson is
scheduled to be published by the University of Washington press
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the speaker of the House, Sam Rayburn, asked Jackson to
serve on the committee that Martin Dies Jr. of Texas had chaired
with a wild degree of irresponsibility, Jackson refused to do that.
... Then his first major committee responsibility in the senate was
to serve on (Joseph) McCarthy's committee, where he played an
honorable role in bringing McCarthy down and exposing his
recklessness,'' Kaufman said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Jackson's long career as a federal officeholder, most
of his contacts with law enforcement were with the FBI. The files
provide a detailed catalog of every incident and episode that
provoked suspicion, starting with the night in 1956 when someone
broke into Jackson's car in Hoquiam, Wash., and stole his shaving
kit, a pair of binoculars, and a notebook in which Jackson, using a
secret code he had developed, jotted down thoughts during a trip to
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The files include an assortment of warm correspondences between
Jackson and longtime FBI Director J. Edgar Hoover, newspaper
clippings about Jackson's wedding, and the threatening missives.
</P>
<P>
   The threats appear to have been largely motivated by Jackson's
strong identification with Israel. Jackson was the most prominent
champion of American military and economic aid to Israel and of the
emigration rights of Soviet Jews at a time when those causes were
not popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was viewed as a real hero, not just by Russian Jews but by
Jews in this country and throughout the world,'' said Ester Kurz,
legislative strategy director for the American Israel Public
Affairs Committee, a lobbying organization. ``He clearly thought
there was a moral component to our obligation to Israel following
World War II, and he was a strategic thinker very engaged in the
Cold War and the need to counter Soviet influence who saw Israel
playing an important role in that effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson traced his support for Israel to two incidents. In 1939,
as Snohomish County prosecutor, he claimed to have effectively shut
down a group of fascist sympathizers in Everett called the Silver
Shirts, and in 1945, on a trip with a group of other congressmen,
Jackson visited the Buchenwald concentration camp three days after
it was liberated. He also credited his mother for instilling in him
the value of tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   The threats began after Jackson's first abortive presidential
campaign in 1972. On Oct. 9, 1973, Jackson received a two-sentence
letter typed on the letterhead of the Islamic Center of San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Sir,'' the letter began. ``On behalf of the more than
14,000 Muslims in the Bay Area, I condemn you as an immoral man. We
earnestly pray to God for your destruction and the destruction of
all you stand for.''
</P>
<P>
   Several writers, including the 70-year-old Pennsylvania woman,
clearly associated Jackson with support for Jewish causes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, the woman wrote to Jackson, ``If you want to stay
alive, shut up about American oil men and their dollars. You don't
understand inflation and the Jews. Ask Germany about inflation
and... Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   Another writer, from Michigan, wrote to ``the very soon late
Henry Jackson,'' warning that Jackson would be killed if he took
any pro-Jewish positions. Yet another, identifying himself as ``a
patriot'' who hates your... guts,'' wrote ``I hope the Arabs run
every damn Jew into the sea and you with them.''
</P>
<P>
   A Floridian who complained to Jackson that ``you come from the
wrong side of the country in the first place,'' also complained of
Jackson's support for Jewish causes, and said ``please keep out of
Florida before something happens to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Another writer penned a series of threats involving Jackson,
Massachusetts Sen. Edward Kennedy, and U.S. District Judge John
Sirica in 1974 and 1975. This writer complained that by traveling
to Colorado and New Mexico, Jackson had been ``spending the
people's money wasting gasoline and polluting the air with Henry
Jackson's special kind of hot air.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is true that Washington, D.C. is probably somewhat cleaner
without you and that the Senate is lacking one of its most
dishonest members... (and) the state of Washington is getting a
break,'' the writer said before launching into an ominous
prediction. ``(Astrologist) Jean Dixon and I agree on one thing _
that 1975 is the year of your death and that of Ted Kennedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the threats, the FBI records contain no evidence of any
attempts on Jackson's life, and the senator died of natural causes
in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   The lengthy FBI files end abruptly with a copy of a two-sentence
telegram FBI Director William Webster sent to Jackson's wife,
Helen, upon the senator's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us in the FBI were shocked and saddened by the sudden
death of your husband, and I extend our heartfelt sympathy to you
and your family,'' Webster wrote. ``His many contributions to our
nation will ensure for him a place in our history, and we join with
all Americans in mourning his death.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
