<HEADLINE>
KINGS' ROBINSON FACES UNCERTAIN FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ At 8:30 this morning, Larry Robinson will walk into
general manager Dave Taylor's office, at which time he expects to
learn whether or not he has a future as the coach of the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   If Robinson's tenure is over, it won't be a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday afternoon, Robinson quite possibly concluded his
four-year stint with a 3-2 loss to the St. Louis Blues before a
sellout crowd of 16,005 attending the last regular-season game at
the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Jason Blake, signed to an amateur tryout contract Friday
night, scored his first NHL goal in his first game and was the
Kings' best player. The final details of a three-year,
$1.85-million contract for Blake are being worked out. As for
Robinson: Taylor and team president Tim Leiweke addressed
season-ticket holders before the game, and when the subject of the
coach arose, Taylor was lukewarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody is aware of the situation with Larry,''
Taylor said. ``We did offer him an extension at the start of the
year. He refused it. We'll sit down and resolve his situation. I
can't tell you much more than that now.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Robinson sounded like a man preparing for the
worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'd still like to remain in hockey,'' Robinson said.
``It's whether they want me or not.... All I know is, myself and
the coaching staff, (whether) we had anything we could have done
differently, I don't think so. Given the circumstances, I think we
did a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he felt on the last game of the season, he said: ``I'm
going to relish this day, the players we have, the staff. I have to
think about the happy times, the great friendships. There's no
sense getting upset worrying about things when you don't know
what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   What irrefutably did happen was a 32-45-5 season that may turn
Robinson _ a finalist for Coach of the Year in 1997-98 _ into a
scapegoat. If Robinson did have a failing, some of his players said
after the game, it was that he was too patient with players who
weren't performing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's not back, it's unfortunate,'' center Ray Ferraro said.
``If it's true he's not back, it won't be the only change. It's not
Larry's personality to be a (jerk). He's about as nice a guy as you
could play for and about as nice a guy as I've ever played for.
Most of us who got second and third chances better keep our heads
up if a new guy comes in. Larry gave every guy the benefit of the
doubt, and in some cases he was taken advantage of.''
</P>
<P>
   Luc Robitaille added: ``I respect Larry. I love playing for him.
He's a good person. Sometimes, he was too nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding Jason Blake, he agreed to join the Kings late Friday
night after receiving a call in Cleveland while on a trip with the
International Hockey League's Orlando Solar Bears, for whom he will
play in the postseason. In his one-game showcase, the 5-foot-10,
180-pound Blake displayed a combination of speed and skill not seen
by the Kings this season at the center position.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best feeling I had was obviously scoring the goal, but
also how welcome I was,'' said Blake, who completed his college
career at North Dakota this season and is no relation to Kings
captain Rob Blake. ``Luc Robitaille came to me 10 times to give me
a hug after I scored the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Defenseman Doug Bodger, 32 and an unrestricted free
agent, said there's a 50-percent chance he'll retire.... Defenseman
Rob Blake said he'll play for Canada in the upcoming World
Championships in Oslo, Norway.... The Kings assigned wingers Pavel
Rosa and Jason Podollan, defensemen Jan Nemecek and Jaroslav Modry
and goalie Ryan Bach to the Long Beach Ice Dogs.... The Kings will
play one exhibition game at the Forum in the fall, which will be
the going-away party for the building.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
