<SLUG> BC-REFUGEE-CRIMINALS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT BATTLE LOOMS OVER LONG-TERM DETENTION OF REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LISE OLSEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Seattle will be the stage for one of the nation's
biggest court battles over whether the U.S. government violates the
rights of non-citizens by indefinitely jailing those who cannot be
deported.
</P>
<P>
   Called ``lifers'' or ``unremovables,'' around 150 of these
non-citizens are held long-term in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Most committed criminal offenses, served time and were then
ordered deported but have remained locked in limbo because their
governments refuse to take them back.
</P>
<P>
   Under an unusual agreement, the claims to liberty of five
``lifers'' will be considered when all five federal district court
judges in Seattle meet jointly to review central arguments on both
sides. That could happen as early as June.
</P>
<P>
   At the core of the controversy is whether the government has
failed to give aliens fair treatment before holding them
indefinitely or whether detainees lost their due process rights
when they were ordered deported.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to hold a joint hearing on the first five cases was
crafted by Seattle federal judges as part of a strategy to handle
an estimated 50 cases from long-term detainees expected to flood
the federal court this year, said Jay Stansell, assistant federal
public defender.
</P>
<P>
   Stansell participated in the talks with the judges and the U.S.
Attorney's office about the cases.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the population of indefinite detainees has grown
quickly because the state has many refugees from Southeast Asia,
the former Soviet Union, Somalia and other nations that don't
accept deportees.
</P>
<P>
   The men expected to be included in the first five cases reflect
the nationalities of Washington's long-termers: two are Vietnamese,
one is Laotian, one is Cambodian and one is from the former Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   Their individual circumstances are very different. But all are
refugees who settled in the Northwest. All have criminal
convictions, mostly for property crimes, though one served time for
manslaughter. And all have been held months or even years by the
Immigration and Naturalization Service because they cannot be
deported and the INS considers them a flight risk or a safety
threat.
</P>
<P>
   One of the five, Son Thai Huynh, 31, a convicted burglar and
Vietnamese refugee, has been in INS custody for two years.
</P>
<P>
   The INS has justified Huynh's long detention because of his
criminal convictions and an alleged association with a Seattle
gang, according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   But the joint hearing has given Huynh some hope of a second
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned a lot in these years. I've thought a lot,'' said
Huynh, whose parents and siblings live in Seattle. ``I'd like a
chance to go back with my family and prove myself _ that I'm a good
man.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other detained refugees, Huynh and others in the first
five cases arrived here as youths, most of them with their
families, and quickly got into trouble that eventually resulted in
a deportation order.
</P>
<P>
   Huynh harbors strong fears _ bolstered by bad memories _ about
what could happen to him if he were sent back to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Huynh, whose features reflect more his American father than his
Chinese mother, was ostracized in Vietnam as a ``G.I. soldier
kid.'' He was not allowed to attend school, and was taunted and
beaten up, he says. When he arrived in the United States, as a
teen, he was illiterate and he has never been able to learn to read
or write.
</P>
<P>
   Though some long-termers have no criminal records, none of those
in the first five cases was hand-picked as ``Mother Teresas,''
Stansell said.
</P>
<P>
   Huynh and the other four all have criminal convictions.
Cambodian Kim Ho Ma served time for manslaughter. Huynh, Dennis
Batyuchenko, from Belarus, Khamseane Sivongxay, a Laotian, and Bin
Phanh, a Vietnamese, all have property crime convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Stansell said the issues in the cases go far beyond the criminal
histories of the individuals.
</P>
<P>
   He believes the U.S. government clearly is violating the
constitutional rights of ``lifers.'' Some detainees spend years in
prison, while the INS makes no progress toward deporting them to
their home countries _ the government's justification for
detention.
</P>
<P>
   Stansell also argues that existing periodic reviews are
inadequate. And, he notes, the process is far less strict than a
civil commitment procedure _ the way that U.S. citizens can be
locked up indefinitely under U.S. law.
</P>
<P>
   In a civil commitment hearing, the government must prove that a
person is a danger to himself or others and is unable to control
his or her actions. That's far different than immigration reviews
where the burden of proof is on the detainee to prove he's not
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   But INS officials _ and the federal attorneys who represent them
_ say that they're protecting citizens by keeping dangerous aliens
locked up long-term and that existing reviews are sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   They point to studies of how aliens who were released in the
past often reoffend.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Christopher L. Pickrell, the lead
attorney arguing the cases for the INS in Seattle, said that
detainees are not truly held indefinitely since there is some
possibility that countries like Vietnam will change their policies.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam, for example, recently negotiated a treaty to take
deportees from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Pickrell also said the U.S. government has argued that aliens
who are ordered deported lose all the rights that they formerly
enjoyed and thus are not entitled to due process.
</P>
<P>
   In the Seattle cases, the potential exists that all five federal
district court judges could issue separate decisions on the common
issues at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   That action would send a message that would be heard not only in
Western Washington, but in legal circles across the country where
the debate is intensifying over an estimated 3,000 long-term
detainees held So far, California's Eastern District is the only
other federal court to have seriously grappled with the issue of
long-term detainees since Congress significantly changed
deportation laws in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   There, district judges have ruled in favor of detainees in
several individual cases, essentially agreeing that indefinite
detention violates their rights and that the federal court has the
power to act in these kinds of cases.
</P>
<P>
   Here, advocates for long-term detainees are hoping that progress
will be quicker because all five district judges will be reviewing
the issue at about the same time. That way, any appellate court
reviews would come faster and perhaps even a ruling by the U.S.
Supreme Court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
