<SLUG> BC-TELE-MERGER-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO EUROPEAN PHONE GIANTS KEEP TALKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Italy and Germany gave their approval Sunday for Telecom
Italia SpA to continue discussions about a possible merger with
Deutsche Telekom AG. The decision is expected to complicate the
struggle for control of Telecom Italia, which faces a $65 billion
hostile bid from its Italian rival, Olivetti SpA.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions toward a merger, if successful, would create one
of the world's largest phone companies. But numerous obstacles
remain, not least of which are the Italian government's concerns
about the German government's majority stake in Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   German and Italian ministers disclosed their governments'
approval of the talks in Dresden, Germany, on Sunday where they had
attended a meeting of European finance officials the day before.
</P>
<P>
   German Finance Minister Hans Eichel said his nation had ``a
fundamental sympathy for the idea that the two companies could get
together.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea uniting both sides, Eichel said, was that such a
combined European giant would have a ``big advantage'' competing
with global Japanese and American telecommunications giants.
</P>
<P>
   His Italian counterpart, Vincenzo Visco, agreed, saying both
governments had concluded ``that the matter should be examined
attentively and that it is interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it is doable,'' he added, ``we do not know.''
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to the companies said a deal could be announced as
early as Tuesday or Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema had laid the ground work
for Sunday's discussions in a phone conversation on Friday with
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for Italy, Visco said, it was clear a merger was only
feasible if the German state divested its 72 percent share in
Deutsche Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, the Italian minister of the treasury,
which formally holds Italy's remaining 3.4 percent share of Telecom
Italia, seconded his colleague, saying there ``has to be a balanced
relationship between both sides.'' Telecom Italia is the former
national phone company.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Visco suggested that the problem was not insurmountable,
saying that the crucial issue was ``that ownership does not
interfere in management.''
</P>
<P>
   One idea being considered to assure equal representation,
advisers to the companies said, is to create a holding company that
would control the shares of Deutsche Telekom and Telecom Italia and
its mobile phone subsidiary.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many analysts note that since the deregulation of European phone
markets in 1997, Deutsche Telekom, despite the Bonn government's
large stake, has received far less protection from the German
government and far tougher scrutiny from German phone regulators
than the Rome government and Italian regulatory authorities have
given Telecom Italia.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia's chief executive, Franco Bernabe, has sought a
white knight to thwart the hostile bid from Olivetti. For his part,
Ron Sommer, the Deutsche Telekom chief, has assembled a fund for
strategic acquisitions to fortify Deutsche Telekom's position
against strong European and domestic competitors, including the
German steel and machinery group, Mannesmann A.G., which has
emerged in recent years as a powerful European phone company and an
ally of Olivetti in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom's intention to sell as much as $12.7 billion in
fresh stock, which was announced on Thursday, will dilute the
German government's stake to about 62 percent, and Eichel Sunday
reaffirmed Germany's intention to gradually reduce its stake
further, though he said it would do so only under favorable terms.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers to Bernabe said that he had been casting about for a
strong industrial partner even before the Olivetti bid. Among his
arguing points to Deutsche Telekom, one adviser said, was that the
proposed merger would greatly enhance the combined companies'
liquidity and produce a ``nice balance sheet.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the German government's planned steps to dilute its
stake in Deutsche Telekom would help overcome the Italian
government's resistance to the merger, Bernabe has argued.
</P>
<P>
   The principal complications, this adviser said, are the
challenge posed by merging two former state monopolies, with
sharply contrasting Italian and German business cultures and
bloated work forces that are only gradually getting used to the
idea of competition.
</P>
<P>
   For Deutsche Telekom, this adviser said, a further challenge
would be sorting out its industrial and financial ties with France
Telecom, with which Deutsche Telekom is allied in two alliances.
Their future, this person said, would be ``precarious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
