<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3493 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-NATO-HICKMAN-ART-NY     04-18 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NATO-HICKMAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HER HANDS, SECURITY AT A GATHERING OF WORLD LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATS to add photo note. No other changes.)  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Of all the crowds Kathleen Hickman has warily
surveyed for security risks in 15 years with the Secret Service,
none comes close to the exotic high-wire gathering of world leaders
massing on her watch this week.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hickman, a cool, well-tailored professional, has worked her
way up from the ennui of the service's check-fraud squad and the
electricity of the presidential campaign vigil to become overall
coordinator of security for the throng of NATO leaders and their
entourages gathering here for their 50th anniversary celebration.
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, that means no fewer than 44 motorcades _ 19 NATO
members plus 25 aligned nations _ traipsing the city for much of a
week, tightly shepherded from airport to hotel and embassy by an
armada of assorted police and security forces, from G-men and
-women to city subway detectives. Coordinating all this is Ms.
Hickman, one of the Secret Service's master planners who learned
the ropes in having advanced the protection of presidents and
potentates, but never on a scale such as this.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've implanted a security plan that we have always been
comfortable with,'' Ms. Hickman said, offering not a murmur of
complaint when asked whether her yearlong, highly complex
assignment took on an even graver degree of watchfulness when NATO
began its air assault on Yugoslavia in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not adjusted the security plan but we are more aware
of what's going on overseas,'' the slender, 41-year-old Texan said
evenly, as vigilant in an interview as any agent out on a
dignitary's rope line. ``We feel comfortable with our plan.''
</P>
<P>
   All about her as she talked in the Secret Service visitors
museum were woeful reminders from the past of the high-stakes task
before her, from ``Kennedy Shot'' headlines to pistols seized from
would-be assassins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I insure that everyone is working together as a team,'' Ms.
Hickman said, her faith in the plan manifest as she emphasized the
critical role played by the FBI and a dozen other organizations on
guard for everything from hidden bombs to bacteria assault.
</P>
<P>
   For the three business days of this supersummit meeting that
begins on Friday, the downtown heart of the city will be turned
into a virtual moated citadel of rulers and bodyguard brigades. Ms.
Hickman's office will track the principals and their thousands of
protectors, keeping ambulances roving about the inner sanctum and
anti-terrorist snipers watching from the rooftops.
</P>
<P>
   Federal office employees in a 12-by-15-block core around the
White House have been told not to show up on Friday, while vehicles
and even pedestrians will be barred through the weekend from the
Federal Triangle center of the summit gathering. Among the many
human inconveniences, Ms. Hickman will be desk- and phone-bound
with no time for her favorite idea of relaxation, jogging with her
19-month-old son as he rides like a dignitary in his baby chariot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's harder on me than it probably is on him,'' she said,
guardedly declining to specify all sorts of details from her life,
from individual names to the family time she plans with her husband
and son after the last VIP's wend their way out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how she arrived at the heart of all the programmed
wariness of the NATO gathering, the dedicated planner had to
finally admit that life can be serendipitous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nothing I planned on doing,'' Ms. Hickman said. ``I
come from a background of hard work,'' she added, referring
particularly to her father's labors in the Texas furniture
business. Her education degree from Texas Tech University opened no
job opportunity, so she took a management job in a Dallas hotel for
a few years. And there, President Ronald Reagan's Secret Service
detail appeared one day, all wired and efficient, and she had to
work with them on hotel security.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were recruiting at that time, especially for females,''
said Ms. Hickman, who eventually applied, passed the intelligence
test and found that with the addition of some weight-lifting to her
jogging regimen, she could handle the physical side, too. Her four
brothers, who work in private businesses like restaurants and
electronic communications, were delighted, she said, at the
emergence of the family's first law-enforcement professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're our best recruiters,'' Ms. Hickman said of the service,
which has 2,304 agents, including 217 women. ``We know the life. We
know what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond her adventurous younger years of darting with the
presidential party to Russia, Nepal and Australia, Ms. Hickman said
she came to love the service as much for its mundane tasks _
getting wet, cold and exhausted for the team's success, running a
polygraph machine, plodding after a check forger. ``I think if you
see the bad times as well as the good times, you just feel that the
Secret Service is like a family,'' said the agent, who has never
had to fire her pistol beyond the practice range and never hopes
to.
</P>
<P>
   As she awaits the NATO leaders, Ms. Hickman seems the
personification of a laconic, watchful, unflappable guardian.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father has always been a hard worker all his life, you know
_ Depression era and all,'' she explained when asked about the art
of her job. For all the service's high-tech watchdog tools, the
agent insisted the key to the coming week remains a blue-collar
sort of esprit. ``Part of this job is discipline. Showing up when
you need to show up. Being on time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
