<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-CART-SIDE-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANAAN'S RUN HITS A WALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ (setital)Screeeeeetch . . . (endital)
</P>
<P>
   Tony Kanaan's run with his first pole position as a CART driver
came to a screeching end on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   After leading from the second lap to lap 45, the 24-year-old
Brazilian took turn six too hard in lap 45, barreled into tires and
was knocked out of the CART Championship at the Toyota Grand Prix
of Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake,'' Kanaan said. ``The track was breaking up,
and I just ran off line a little bit and lost it. It was tough.
Sometimes you learn the hard way.''
</P>
<P>
   Kanaan's mistake, hence, dropped him the furthest of any driver
in the CART race. He started the day with the pole position and
ended up 22nd of 27 drivers. His drastic plummet, forcing him out
of the final 40 laps, appeared to blast his morale.
</P>
<P>
   The rising star, CART's Rookie of the Year last season, exited
the Grand Prix soon after the crash. That was even before Juan
Montoya had his champagne celebration as the victor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened today hurt,'' Kanaan said. ``But I proved to
myself that I can run up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Kanaan's premature departure changed the Grand Prix's
tenor. A yellow flag popped up from lap 46 to lap 51 because of his
miscue, but that wasn't the significant change.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the departure may have paved the way to Montoya's
victory. The 23 year old from Bogota, Columbia led from Kanaan's
exit to the checkered flag. Unlike Kanaan, Montoya didn't have the
luxury of a pole position and had to advance from his fifth
starting position for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bryan (Herta) was the toughest guy to get by,'' Montoya said.
``And it was too bad what happened to Tony (Kanaan).''
</P>
<P>
   Herta finished third, behind Dario Franchitti. Not only was
Herta a menace to Montoya, but he also was to Kanaan briefly. Herta
stole Kanaan's lead in the first lap, but Kanaan reclaimed the lead
in the second lap.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the majority of the race while Kanaan was in it had
Kanaan leading in front of Montoya and Franchitti, the three raced
tight and appeared on track to jockey for position. But Kanaan's
exit prevented that and perhaps took away some of the race's
thrill. The race became a dogfight between Montoya and Franchitti,
yet Montoya never relinquished his lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan (Montoya) passed us on the restart, and then the three of
us (Kanaan, Montoya and Franchitti) were going at it, nose to
tail,'' Franchitti said. ``It was a shame for Tony. I think we
would have had a pretty good battle the rest of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Kanaan's race lasted 53 minutes, 59 seconds. Montoya's was 52:29
longer than Kanaan's. On Saturday, when he won the pole position,
he also won several wristwatches from his race engineers. They bet
him that he couldn't have a best lap quicker than 1:02.5. He
finished 1:02.332, claiming the watches, including a Rolex.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday, especially after his fate, he may have not wanted
the watches. He could have wanted time to move faster, pushing him
to May 2 in Nazareth, Penn., CART's next race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good until 40 laps to go,'' he said. ``I am very
disappointed, but you learn from your mistakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
