<DOCNO> NYT19990418.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3546 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONFEDERATE-COX     04-18 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONFEDERATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Man fighting for `Confederate History Month'
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Larry Powell is Southern and proud.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, who had five great-great-uncles fight for the
Confederate States of America, is urging city and county leaders to
recognize April as Confederate History Month.
</P>
<P>
   But images die hard.
</P>
<P>
   An officer in the local chapter of Sons of Confederate Veterans,
Powell has spent his adult life challenging the idea that the
Confederacy was only about slavery. He believes Floridians _
two-thirds of them, by last count, from somewhere else and many of
them unable to say which side Florida fought for in the Civil War _
need to know the state's history, good or bad. And he says he wants
to honor Floridians who died for a cause they believed in, even if
other Americans disagreed and some called it treason.
</P>
<P>
   West Palm Beach, Boca Raton, Jupiter, Hypoluxo and Tequesta have
issued the proclamations _ without dissension, but the Palm Beach
County Commission hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expressed my displeasure by not sponsoring the
proclamation,'' said County Commission Chairwoman Maude Ford Lee,
who is black. ``It's a very offensive time in history for my people
and I would not be supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a century and a half after the United States fought a
four-year campaign to keep 11 Southern states from setting up their
own nation, the war still draws powerful emotions and opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't they call it Civil War History Month? Why take only
one side of it?'' asked Lyman Stanford, a professor of social
science at Florida Atlantic University.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, then mostly agricultural and home to only 140,000
people, was the third state to secede in 1861, and sent the largest
percentage of soldiers of any Confederate state. It is now
America's fourth most populous state, a demographic tossed salad,
and easily the most assimilated and least Southern of the former
states in rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   For the past seven years, Gov. Lawton Chiles issued a carefully
worded proclamation. ``Whereas, we study the war between the blue
and the gray for the same reason we study all wars, with a view to
understanding the historical events which compelled them, so we may
continue to learn to live together and seek to avoid future
conflicts,'' says the decree, which urges Floridians to ``engage in
historical study of the events of 1861 to 1865 and to solemnly
contemplate that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeb Bush's office has not decided whether to issue a
proclamation, a spokeswoman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Powell said Floridians can mark the commemoration without
endorsing the Confederacy's causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strictly part of history,'' Powell said. ``Florida was a
major part of the Confederacy. The main idea is to encourage people
to go out and read about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell is an officer of the Sons of Confederate Veterans'
15-member West Palm Beach chapter _ the next nearest chapters are
based in Fort Lauderdale and Vero Beach. Powell and his Vero Beach
counterpart did not approach any local governments in Martin or St.
Lucie counties.
</P>
<P>
   The Memphis native, raised in South Florida and descended, on
his mother's side, from turn-of-the-century Miami pioneers, is a
retired Hialeah firefighter of 22 years who moved to Palm Beach
County in 1997. Powell, who participates in Civil War reenactments,
said his group has fought the use of Confederate images by hate
groups. The association's Internet Web page lists a procedure for
members to report such ``heritage violations'' _ use of Confederate
symbols to promote racism or intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our biggest struggle,'' Powell said. ``They use the
American flag and the cross, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Confederate Memorial Day, April 26, is still a state holiday, as
are Confederate military commander Robert E. Lee's birthday, Jan.
19, and Confederate President Jefferson Davis' birthday, June 3.
The state also marks the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King's birthday,
the third Monday in January, and Emancipation Day, June 19, the
anniversary of the occupation of Tallahassee and enforcement of the
Emancipation Proclamation. Of those, only King's commemoration
closes state offices.
</P>
<P>
   The Civil War Roundtable, a discussion group with members from
Broward County to the Treasure Coast, does not support or oppose
the proclamation, President Gerridine La Rovere said. She said she
couldn't speak for the group, whose members represent all positions
on the Civil War, but that she'd support the goal of raising
consciousness about the war and its causes and effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's exactly what we do with the Roundtable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Rivers, a professor of history at predominantly black
Florida A&AMP;M University in Tallahassee, said he believes the war was
mostly about slavery. He said most Northerners fought to preserve
the Union and didn't care about blacks or slavery. But those
Southerners who did not openly support slavery, or claimed to be
fighting strictly for their homeland, countenanced the institution
with their silence _ much like Americans who looked the other way
during this century's darkest racial times share the blame for
them, Rivers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need to necessarily honor them or understand their
motives, ideas and attitudes,'' Powell said. ``You can have a
Confederate history (month) without legitimizing the Confederacy,
if you are holistic enough to look at the entire role _ not only of
the Confederacy, but the role of blacks. And women. . . . You have
to look at all the other players.''
</P>
<P>
   Eliot Kleinberg writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
