<SLUG> BC-TEN-FEDCUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH SELES AT HER BEST, U.S. ROMPS IN FED CUP
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ Fifteen years ago, a stunning prospect named
Monica Seles moved from Yugoslavia to Florida, seeking the ideal
setting in which to become a world No. 1. Five years ago, Seles, in
the midst of a 27-month exile from tennis after her 1993 stabbing
in Germany, became an American citizen.
</P>
<P>
   The new allegiance not only gave Seles a sense of validation at
her Florida address; it also qualified her to represent the United
States in Olympic and Fed Cup competition, and her desire to play
on both teams figured prominently in her return to tennis in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Performing to the hilt for her adopted home country Sunday, the
25-year-old Seles clinched the first-round Fed Cup confrontation
between the United States and Croatia. With a purposeful 6-0, 6-3
mauling of Iva Majoli, the 1997 French Open champion, Seles not
only gave the United States a 3-0 lead in the best-of-five-match
series, which it went on to sweep, but also improved her Fed Cup
record to 10-0.
</P>
<P>
   Seles felt she could safely play in the event only after it was
moved from Zagreb, Croatia, to the Raleigh Racquet Club, whose
2,500-seat stadium sold out on two weeks' notice. She experienced
mixed emotions during the weekend: not only were many members of
the Croatian delegation old friends of her late father and coach,
Karolj, but she was aware that the NATO bombings that forced the
relocation of this round from Croatia had targeted her Yugoslav
hometown of Novi Sad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a difficult three weeks,'' said Seles, who has been
in contact with friends and relatives by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Seles insisted the hostilities overseas did not affect her
relationship with the Croatian team. ``We see each other as
friends, as tennis players; we're not the politicians,'' said
Seles, who kissed Majoli at netside after their match.
</P>
<P>
   Seles encountered little resistance from Majoli, who admitted to
still feeling the effects of the demanding 7-6 (7-5), 4-6, 10-8
loss to Chanda Rubin on Saturday that kicked off this series.
Majoli identified the pulverizing shots bearing down on her from
all angles of the court Sunday as vintage Seles. ``It was more like
her playing perfect and I could do nothing,'' Majoli said.
</P>
<P>
   As Croatia's Fed Cup captain, Vjeran Friscic, put it: ``Monica
doesn't give you time even to think. She's so good a player that
even if you give your 100 percent, you can lose, you can maybe get
four games.'' That was all Silvija Talaja got from Seles in
Saturday's second singles match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always seem to produce the best tennis for Fed Cup, and I'm
really focused,'' said the third-ranked Seles, who prepared for
this team event by capturing her first clay court title in seven
years last week in the Bausch &AMP; Lomb Championships at Amelia
Island, Fla. Sunday's victory took Seles, whose ferocity in the
18-minute opening set induced virtual paralysis in Majoli, only 43
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Like Seles, the 23rd-ranked Rubin, who replaced the injured
Davenport in singles, posted a 2-0 singles record over the weekend
and, according to King, re-established herself as a major contender
after a slow rehabilitation from major wrist surgery in 1996.
Sunday Rubin, a 23-year-old from Louisiana, took a less arduous
route to success than in her near-three-hour marathon with Majoli.
She pounded the 70th-ranked Talaja into submission, 6-3, 6-4, in 71
minutes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
