<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ENID NEMY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   My fellow commuters and I were in the last minutes of the Long
Island Rail Road ride into New York City. Suddenly, the conductor
announced we would not be able to enter Pennsylvania Station but
would be diverted to the Hunters Point Avenue stop. As we
disembarked to make our way to the No. 7 subway station, the
conductor announced the subway ride would be free to compensate for
the inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   When we arrived at the station, the ticket booth workers could
not open the gate to the platform. Passengers were permitted to
jump the turnstiles. It was amazing to watch the various styles.
The younger folks easily lifted themselves up and over. Some
elderly people were hoisted over by other passengers. One creative
type went over hands first and somersaulted upon landing.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have dreamed that a workday commute could turn into an
Olympic event?
</P>
<P>
   _ RITA GOLDBERG
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. James Gilhooley had grave doubts as to whether he would
make the 10:05 a.m. train from Cold Spring, N.Y., to the city. As
he was rushing to the station, he prayed that there would be a
delay, but when he finally got to the station, he found he had two
minutes to spare. Human nature being what it is, Gilhooley was then
more than a little annoyed when he heard an announcement that the
train would be 10 minutes late. On reflection he calmed down. ``I
recalled my almost hysterical prayer to my employer,'' he said,
``and realized that it was I who was responsible for the delay.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   At a Rangers game at Madison Square Garden last month the puck
flew over the glass and into the hands of a spectator. The lucky
man impressed the rest of us by walking over to a young boy five
seats away and giving him the souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was delighted and there was a general murmur of
appreciation, except for a heavy beer-swilling man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a son, too,'' he grumbled loud enough for the boy to
hear, ``and he's in the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone thought the remark in poor taste but no one knew what
to say. Then a woman spoke up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your son's in the hospital?'' she asked politely.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we speak,'' the man said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what are you doing here?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ KIT TROYER
</P>
<P>
   Jane Block, shopping in her local health food store, placed a
container of fresh tofu in her basket. A well-dressed man
approached her and in a clipped British accent asked exactly what
she did with the tofu. She replied that normally she put it in her
refrigerator, looked at it for several weeks and then threw it
away. The man replied: ``That's exactly what my wife does with it.
I was hoping you had a better recipe.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a little early in life for such angst, Lorrie Stuart
thought. She was on a Second Avenue bus as a small boy walked down
the aisle with his mother. The boy was whimpering, ``I can't take
it, I can't take it, I can't take it.'' When they reached their
seats, she heard the youngster continue his lament, indicating a
New Yorker is a New Yorker at any age: ``I can't take the bus,
Mommy, I want to take a taxi,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ONE NEVER KNOWS
</P>
<P>
   You hail a cab and settle inside
</P>
<P>
   You tell the driver where to ride
</P>
<P>
   You notice his license, you read his name
</P>
<P>
   And things are never again the same
</P>
<P>
   You start to converse and learn where he's from
</P>
<P>
   And that's just the opener for what is to come.
</P>
<P>
   He'll say he's from India, Brazil or Mali
</P>
<P>
   Or even from Russia or far-off Bali.
</P>
<P>
   You'll hear his life story, his dreams and his hopes
</P>
<P>
   And all the while with the traffic he copes.
</P>
<P>
   And you'll take off your hat to each of these guys
</P>
<P>
   Who work long hard hours and always try
</P>
<P>
   To take you, with safety, to airport or zoo
</P>
<P>
   Or Saks or St. Patrick's, to name just a few.
</P>
<P>
   And it would be lovely some day in the rain
</P>
<P>
   To jump in the very same taxi again.
</P>
<P>
   _ MARIE K. ALLEN
</P>
<P>
   It was 1954 when Abraham Bunis, who grew up in Brooklyn,
returned from his service in the Army and found the girl of his
dreams, who grew up in the Bronx. They decided to marry and live in
neutral territory _ Manhattan. Bunis informed his mother that he
and his fiancee had found a wonderful apartment in Washington
Heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a sunken living room and overlooks the Hudson River,''
he said with enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abelah,'' his mother replied, ``when you live in Manhattan,
you have to be able to overlook a great many things.''
</P>
<P>
   DAYLIGHT SAVING TIME
</P>
<P>
   Every spring I feel regret
</P>
<P>
   That I my clocks must newly set.
</P>
<P>
   Every spring I feel dismay
</P>
<P>
   That I must act against the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spring ahead,'' the TV warns.
</P>
<P>
   And yearly I am fiercely torn.
</P>
<P>
   Still I do it with a nod
</P>
<P>
   A little man
</P>
<P>
   improving on
</P>
<P>
   the hands of God.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVAN LEVINSON
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   My friend and I were at City Opera for a charming performance of
``Madame Butterfly.'' Sitting next to us was an attractive young
woman. For three solid hours she cried, continuously wiping her
eyes and sniffling.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the performance, she smiled and apologized for
being so emotional. She added, ``Didn't her mother ever teach her
about men?''
</P>
<P>
   _ MARVIN ALEXANDER
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it takes someone like Chief Judge Arthur J. Doran Jr. of
Yonkers City Court to have noticed the four-line classified ad in
his local paper earlier this month. It announced a four-grave
cemetery plot for sale. The reason: ``Must relocate.'' The judge's
comment: ``The person selling apparently cannot rest in peace, at
least not at the current address.''
</P>
<P>
   Selma Stone and her husband were in the Delegates' Dining Room
at the United Nations and were walking down to the lower level to
browse in the shops. They ended up walking with a family, the
father and very young daughter in front of them and the mother and
perhaps 9-year-old son behind them. Mrs. Stone asked the mother if
she would like to go ahead to join her husband. The woman declined
politely but then said to her son, ``You see, that's why it's good
to come to New York _ you learn good manners. ''
</P>
<P>
   Scene: Bloomingdale's
</P>
<P>
   Dramatis Personae: Karen Franklin and a young saleswoman
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Franklin: ``I have good news and bad news. The bad news is
I lost my son. The good news is he's 19 and a hunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Saleswoman, not missing a beat and pointing to the left: ``He
went thataway.''
</P>
<P>
   Observations for this column may be sent to Metropolitan Diary,
Style Department, The New York Times, 229 W. 43rd Street, New York,
N.Y. 10036. lease include your name, address and daytime telephone
number (required); upon request, names may be withheld in print.
Letters become the property of The Times and cannot be returned.
They may be edited, and may be republished in all media.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
