<DOCNO> NYT19990418.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3604 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GRETZKY-FATHER-AR     04-18 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETZKY-FATHER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRETZKY'S FATHER COACHES TO THE END
</HEADLINE>
   (See HKN-RANGERS-PENGUINS) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like any father watching one of his son's hockey
games, Walter Gretzky looked on intently from the stands Sunday,
his hands cupped around his mouth. Sometimes he offered his son
advice, sometimes encouragement and sometimes well-deserved
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did you miss that?'' he hollered, after Wayne Gretzky,
Walter's son, whiffed on a shot in front of an open net during the
Rangers' 2-1 loss to the Penguins, the final game of a glorious
20-year career in the NHL. Moments later, it was, ``That's the
way,'' after Wayne helped set up Brian Leetch for the Rangers' goal
with another one of his signature passes.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day of mixed emotions for Walter, 60, who sat with his
wife, Phyllis, his daughter-in-law, Janet Jones, and his three
grandchildren in the lower-section seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very sad,'' said Walter, who retired in 1991 after 37
years with the telephone company in Brantford, Ontario. ``But at
the same time, it's what he wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like just yesterday he skated for the first time,''
he added. ``I just can't find the words to say how proud I am of
Wayne. He's accomplished so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Several times during play stoppages, fans formed a line on the
stairs next to Walter, hoping to get an autograph. With a warm
smile, and sometimes with a story about Wayne, he obliged every
request.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky credits his father as the greatest influence in
his life, both on and off the ice. Walter was his son's first
coach, and he remains his close friend and confidant.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne has sought Walter's advice on nearly everything over the
years, especially when faced with a tough decision. But when Wayne
was faced with his hardest choice _ deciding whether to retire from
the game he has dominated across two decades _ Walter was left out
of the loop, saying Sunday that his son never consulted him.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Walter said that Wayne did not inform him of his
decision until last week, and that Wayne told his mother first, two
months before. The reason Wayne never asked for advice on this one
was simple, Walter said. It was because he would have done and said
everything to keep Wayne from hanging up his skates.
</P>
<P>
   ``About a year ago, I asked him, When are you going to retire,
when are you going to quit?'' Walter said. ``And he says, `Well,
Dad, you have to understand something. Every year you go to camp,
the guys are bigger, faster, stronger, smarter. They are better,
and I'm getting older.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he wanted to quit when he was still an asset to the
team, not a drag on anybody. He didn't want to be told, `Maybe you
should retire, Wayne.' He made this decision on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he added, ``I would have liked to see him play another
year, maybe two.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne was 6 years old when Walter flooded the backyard of the
family's home in Brantford, creating the rink where Wayne would
play for six hours every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks I made the rink so that Wayne could be a
hockey player,'' Walter said, holding court with the news media
outside the Rangers' locker room before the game. ``But the truth
is, I used to take him to the outdoor rink at the park, and I used
to freeze to death. Kids don't get cold, especially when they are
playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I came home one night and said this is ridiculous,'' he
added. ``You know what I'm going to do? I'm going to make a rink in
the backyard so that he can go out there when he wants, and for as
long as he wants. And I could sit in the house where it was nice
and warm. So it was self-preservation. That's the honest truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne said that the most touching moment Sunday was when his
father came up to him after the game and told him how proud he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a son, you want to hear it,'' Gretzky said with
moist eyes. ``He told me he was very proud of me.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
