<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GRETZKY-FANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIANS FLOCK TO SEE THE GREAT ONE ON ICE ONE LAST TIME
</HEADLINE>
   (See also HKN-RANGERS-PENGUINS) 
(rk) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If Sunday was a sad day to be Canadian, it was an
even sadder day to be a Canadian standing outside Madison Square
Garden at 3:14 p.m., holding a small sign that said, ``I need 1
please.''
</P>
<P>
   But such was Rick Laliberte's plight. As Wayne Gretzky, hockey
legend and native of Brantford, Ontario, began skating for the
Rangers in his last professional game, Laliberte, member of
Parliament from Beauval, Saskatchewan (pop. 717), strode up and
down a chilly Seventh Avenue in a state of increasing desperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our national sport,'' Laliberte, a strikingly tall man
clad in black shorts, whose haircut looked something like a
coonskin cap, said distractedly. ``Got to get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Laliberte did not need to be warned about fake tickets. He had
already given a scalper $300 (about $450 Canadian), only to be told
at the gate that the tickets were counterfeit. ``It's luck,'' he
said. ``It's a game of luck, isn't it, eh?''
</P>
<P>
   Even as the game wore on, Laliberte's countrymen stood on the
steps of the Garden, hoping for a last-minute godsend while
reflecting on the day's significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a Canadian, it's an identity thing, but it's also a piece
of history,'' said Romen Abergel, a transplanted Torontonian who
lives on the Upper West Side of Manhattan. ``I only watch hockey
now because of Gretzky _ it's too rough now. And I don't think I'm
going to watch much more after this.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Huber, an investment banker from Calgary who recalled
skating against a 12-year-old Gretzky in a Pee Wee League game in
which the little Great One scored 11 goals, said that by doing so
much to popularize hockey in the United States, Gretzky had
indirectly undermined the game in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's two things that symbolize the Americanization of
hockey,'' Huber said as he politely turned down offers from several
scalpers. ``One is when the Americans won the Olympics in 1980. The
other is when Gretzky was traded to L.A. He opened up the market,
but now Canadian teams like Calgary can't afford marquee players
anymore. I wouldn't be surprised if it's just down to Montreal,
Toronto and Vancouver soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone tried to get in. At Charley O's restaurant and
sports bar on the north side of the Garden, John Durko, another
transplant from Toronto, was happy to watch the game on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been passing off the whole game,'' Durko said a few
minutes into the second period, as he dug into a plate of Buffalo
wings. ``That's the kind of player he is. He's still got eyes in
the back of his head.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as the game ended, the competition outside the Garden
remained fierce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even want a ticket,'' said Glenn Jamieson, an oil rig
worker from Nova Scotia. ``All I want is a stub. I'm Canadian,
Gretzky's from Canada, hockey's Canada and Canada's hockey. He's
never coming back.'' He approached a woman passing by. ``Were you
at the game, Sweetie?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who asked to be identified as ``the otherwise
honorable and eminent Raina Perlmutter'' of Cedarhurst, Long
Island, had not been at the game. She, too, had come to scavenge
for stubs, for her brother, a die-hard Ranger fan who moved to
Toronto several years ago. ``I thought they'd be laying on the
ground here,'' she said, adding she was ``too old to be doing this.
Isn't this pathetic?''
</P>
<P>
   Jamieson returned a few minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you'll get a nice ending,'' he said, flashing a pair of
glossy stubs. ``I got two $105 tickets. This'll go in my
scrapbook.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
