<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-MTSAC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES WINS HEATED 400
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALNUT, Calif. _ Appropriately for April, Marion Jones was taxed
to the limit Sunday in the Mt. San Antonio College Relays.
</P>
<P>
   On an afternoon when temperatures reached into the low 90s,
Jones timed 50.79 seconds in a rare appearance in the 400 meters to
win by more than two seconds over LaDonna Antoine.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-time state champion at Thousand Oaks High, however,
slowed noticeably over the final 50 meters. She collapsed on the
infield for nearly 20 minutes before gaining enough strength to
meet a media phalanx and sign autographs from the crowd of 8,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's race marked the only appearance this year in Southern
California and in the 400 for Jones, the 1998 world leader in the
100, 200 and long jump who now resides in North Carolina. Jones,
23, whose goal is to win five gold medals in the 2000 Olympics,
fell short of her goal to break 50 seconds as well as her meet
record of 50.36 set last year.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said her only other 400 this season might come in the
World Championships in Seville, Spain, in August as a member of the
U.S. 1,600-meter relay team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels good to run against the best in the world,'' Jones
said. ``When I have time to sit down and say I am the best, then I
have too much time on my hands. I try to keep myself busy and train
hard. Then, I can step on the track and say I am the best in the
world. It is not being cocky. It is just being confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Ato Boldon couldn't ask for better conditions or a faster track
in the 200 heat. A new pair of spikes, though, would have come in
handy for the 1997 world 200-meter champion.
</P>
<P>
   Despite running gingerly because of sore toes from a change to a
new design, Boldon, a Trinidad native and former NCAA champion from
UCLA, tiptoed to victory in 20.19 seconds, the fourth-fastest time
in the world this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This track always does amazing things, but I had to take what
my foot gave me,'' said Boldon, who posted the world's fastest
100-meter time of 1998 in last year's Mt. SAC Relays. ``I was not
able to move on the second half where I usually move.''
</P>
<P>
   C.J. Hunter, Jones' husband, won the shot put in a world-leading
and career-best 70 feet, 3 inches to upset world champion John
Godina. Godina rebounded to win the discus at 213-3. Tisha Waller
won the women's high jump with a yearly world-best of 6-6}.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Marsh and Inger Miller were winners in the men's and
women's 100 in wind-aided marks of 10.06 and 10.92. For Marsh, 31,
the 1992 Olympic champion in the 200 meters, it was only the second
race in two years after being sidelined for 18 months because of
bone spurs in his left heel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
