<HEADER>
A3629 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-KRONE-TEX     04-18 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-KRONE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PRINCESS RIDES OFF LIKE A QUEEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE _ On a January day in 1981 in Tampa, Fla., Julie
Krone made her first ride as a professional jockey.
</P>
<P>
   The horse, appropriately enough, was named Tiny Star.
</P>
<P>
   On her best day, wearing her best shoes, Krone has been checking
in at 4 feet, 10 inches.
</P>
<P>
   But at Lone Star Park on Sunday, there was little doubt who was
the day's giant.
</P>
<P>
   Five races. Three victories. A dozen long and loud ovations. One
messy congratulatory cake. And one final stretch drive in the Lone
Star Derby that almost gave the day a storybook finish.
</P>
<P>
   With all that, Julieann Louise Krone said goodbye to racing
Sunday. On a day spiced by champions and by upsets, the tiniest
star stole the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just about as perfect as it could be,'' said
history's winningest female jockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was princess for a day at Lone Star.''
</P>
<P>
   After 18 years, after more than 20,000 mounts and 3,546 winners,
after horrific, rag-doll spills in 1993 and 1995 that left her
wondering if she'd ever ride again, Krone went out a winner by all
but the pickiest of bettor's standards.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, she left on her own terms, on the strong back of a
horse gallantly driving for the finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be able to walk out and realize that, OK, that was the last
time, is important,'' Krone said afterwards. ``I've been on both
ends of the rainbow.''
</P>
<P>
   Krone rode big-stakes winners, none bigger than Colonial Affair
at the Triple Crown's Belmont Stakes in '93. And she encountered
grim setbacks _ ``laying on the grass,'' as she put it, ``with
bones poking through my skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Her first major spill on the track came at Meadowlands (N.J.) in
1989 and shattered Krone's left arm. Doctors had to insert a plate
and seven screws.
</P>
<P>
   On the last day of the Saratoga (N.Y.) season in 1993, Krone was
thrown again. Her right ankle was so shattered, her doctor said the
only worse ankle injury he had seen had been on an airplane-crash
victim. Nine months later, Krone was riding again.
</P>
<P>
   But when she was involved in yet-another spectacular spill, this
one at Gulfstream (Fla.) Park in January, 1995, Krone needed the
help of a psychiatrist to heal the mental scars.
</P>
<P>
   In her autobiography, ``Riding for My Life'', Krone wrote about
the demons that visited her when she was recovering from the
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were on a morphine drip for 18 days, you'd be seeing
the devil, too,'' Krone said, able to smile about it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if I had to choose all over again, knowing the spills and
everything that lay ahead, for the chance to experience the joy and
the recognition, I would definitely choose to go through it again _
devil or no devil.''
</P>
<P>
   Krone came back from the mental traumas and returned to become
one of racing's leading jockeys again. Her victory in February at
the Fair Grounds in New Orleans was the 3,500th of her career.
</P>
<P>
   But no star, even the tiniest and brightest ones, is forever.
</P>
<P>
   Once a high school dropout, she returned home to Michigan in
1997 and received her high school diploma. Through her therapy,
Krone became interested in psychology and wants to get a college
degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's not as if something is pushing me out of the sport,''
she said. ``It's more something pulling me.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely, Krone, 35, will go down as a pioneer in women's sport.
The little girl who grew up on a farm, riding her pony Dixie, is
proud of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Athletes tend to be known for their successes,'' she said.
``But I would rather have some little girl say, ``Oh, Julie Krone
fell down but she came back. She wasn't afraid.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Don't remember her for her smiles in the winner's circle, Krone
said. Remember her for her persistence.
</P>
<P>
   Krone won Lone Star Park's second race Sunday aboard Dance to
Fit. Atop Executive Girl in the third race _ christened the Julie
Krone Classic _ she won again. After the race, fellow jockeys
presented her with a big cake ... and then promptly, playfully,
dumped it on her.
</P>
<P>
   Her final victory came aboard Paris Jet in the fifth race _
three races, three consecutive wins. As Krone hit the finish line,
track announcer John Dooley cried, ``Julie Krone ... When will it
end?''
</P>
<P>
   Like all good princess stories, this ending was a happy one. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
