<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE IS IN AWE AS GRETZKY PASSES THE TORCH
</HEADLINE>
   (See also HKN-RANGERS-PENGUINS) 
(rk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Manny Malhotra, a wide-eyed and grinning 18-year-old,
may not have looked much different from any other fan crammed into
Madison Square Garden Sunday. But he was wearing a Rangers jersey
with No. 6 and his name stitched on the back rather than the No. 99
jerseys that pervaded the arena.
</P>
<P>
   Pushed into the corner of the bench nearest center ice as Wayne
Gretzky was honored before his final game, Malhotra watched
carefully. Not yet born when Gretzky scored his first goal in the
NHL and not 1 year old by the time Gretzky had 100 goals, he was
now a successor to Gretzky's center position, a teammate and, oddly
enough, a friend of the superstar 20 years his senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year I've been alive, he's been in the league,''
Malhotra said. ``It's kind of almost an eerie feeling to think that
after this we're not even going to see him on the ice anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gretzky concluded the most brilliant career in NHL history
Sunday, Malhotra finished his rookie season, well aware that his
career would never reach the heights that Gretzky's had, but
touched that Gretzky had allowed the two to bond without a hint of
difference in age or skills.
</P>
<P>
   When Gretzky beckoned his teammates to join him on his final lap
around the ice, they trailed in his wake as they had all during his
tenure here. But even if he was the center of attention, having
them beside him was the only way he would have it. ``That was
pretty special to me,'' Malhotra said. ``All of us wanted to hoist
him off the ice, but he didn't want that. He wanted to be with the
guys. That was another thing that represents what Wayne is all
about. He wanted everybody to share in this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The first week of training camp, Gretzky issued a dinner
invitation to Malhotra, who was the Rangers' first-round pick in
the 1998 NHL entry draft and the seventh selection over all. As the
months and games passed this year, Gretzky's everyman persona in
the locker room caused Malhotra to sometimes forget that this was
his boyhood idol.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great friend,'' Malhotra said. ``He treats everybody
equally. From day one he was very kind to me. He's said a lot of
nice things about me and to me and allowed me to relax a lot. He's
been really a great friend and a great teammate.''
</P>
<P>
   It came to an end Sunday, a day that Gretzky's teammates knew
might be coming but hoped until last week to avoid. It was not
until Thursday night in Ottawa that Gretzky told them that his
decision had been made to step away from the game at 38 years old.
After the players heard the word from Gretzky, it was the reaction
from the fans that shook Malhotra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starting in Ottawa it was pretty special, and you had a sense
of just how big he is in the hockey industry, in the world, as a
role model,'' Malhotra said. ``We were in an opposing building, and
every time he touched the puck everybody was going nuts. They
wanted him to be a hero that night. Friday with the press
conference, to see how many news stations, how many people, were
there to cover it, it was another big event. You can see how big it
is. But still, it's nice to have that feeling that he's a normal
guy and I have that opportunity to speak with him as a normal guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody ever will play the way he does. I
learned a lot of the way he handles himself off the ice, with
media, with fans, just the way he carries himself in general. He's
a real classy man. Next year, I'll obviously have more
responsibility on the ice. But in terms of coming up after Wayne, I
don't think anybody is ever going to fill that void that he's left.
No one is ever going to be 99.''
</P>
</TEXT>
