<SLUG> BC-CAR-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DRIVERS PICK UP SPEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ It took 25 years, but the Long Beach Grand
Prix has finally run out of Unsers and Andrettis.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1983, the race through the streets of
Long Beach was not graced by the presence of six-time winner Al
Unser, Jr. Little Al, the most veteran driver on the Championship
Auto Racing Teams (CART) circuit at 18 years, was home
rehabilitating a broken ankle.
</P>
<P>
   For the eighth straight time here, Michael Andretti, the 1986
winner and heir to his dad Mario's legacy, finished down the track.
He's gone 7, 21, 22, 7, 9, 6, 16 and 16 his last eight tries here,
and in general has been a non-factor. He last led a lap here in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   This is a dynamic change for a race which has traded on auto
racing royalty for most of its 25 years, one in which an Unser or
an Andretti won 10 of 12 races between 1984 and 1995. It's a given
that half of the crowd on hand Sunday was there to see and display
skin. But even the half on hand for the exhaust probably never
heard of winner Juan Montoya until he got the checkered flag.
</P>
<P>
   Or runnerup Dario Franchitti, or pole sitter Tony Kanaan, and
certainly not those three Brazilians in the field named Cristiano,
Helio and Tarso. There were six rookies in the field and more than
half of the 27 entrants have been on the circuit four years or
less.
</P>
<P>
   So as Long Beach prepares for its next 25 years, becoming
acquainted with the next generation of driver is a priority. And
this is only bad for those tethered to the familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Zanardi, now racing Formula One, emerged here with wins in
1997 and 1998 and should be back in 2001. Scotland's Franchitti and
Valencia's Brian Herta have finished 2-3 here in consecutive years.
Kanaan impressed everyone before losing control of his vehicle on
lap 45. Rookie Montoya, meanwhile, won his his first race in just
his third CART ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing good young rookie crops come along every year,''
said Chip Ganassi, whose career as a team owner has been much more
successful than his driving career. He finished 25th in 1984, but
Target/Ganassi racing has won three straight CART season titles and
now four straight in Long Beach. ``I only wish they all had an
equal opportunity to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   CART success trades on the speed of the car. On a narrow and
unpassable road circuit like Long Beach, there is much more driving
than racing. Franchitti said the difference Sunday was Montoya's
Honda handling the turns better than his.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more to finding a winning driver than what Ganassi
called ``DFL,'' an embellishment of dumb luck. Montoya, 23, began
driving karts at the age of five and has been competing since he
was nine. He attended the Skip Barber driving school at the age of
17 and has dominated every step he's taken in racing. He won the
European Formula 3000 championship last year.
</P>
<P>
   That success led Ganassi to put him into the Target/Ganassi
number four car that Zanardi drove the previous two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we have high expectations, and anyone we would have
put into number four would have faced expectations,'' said Ganassi.
``I knew Juan had the talent. I didn't know he had the mental
toughness to put the challenges (of the last two races) behind him
like he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Mechanical problems cost Montoya a higher finish in his first
race in Miami (he finished tenth), and he ran out of gas late last
week in Japan. ``We (the team) let him down in his first two races,
but he came in focused on what he had in hand instead of the last
two races.''
</P>
<P>
   Ganassi said Montoya and the team crew share a dynamic that is
as healthy as it is important. ``A certain bit of (driver)
impatience can prod a team. It's a push-pull thing. You have to
push the driver, and to an extent, the driver has to push back. A
little bit of impatience in a driver can help ... a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya aside, other new Beach names have a little bit of
talent. Last season, runnerup Franchitti won three races and
finished in the top five nine times, and he and Montoya have the
best road cars.
</P>
<P>
   Herta has 27 top ten finishes in the last three seasons and has
been third in back-to-back LBGP's. Sunday's show came in his backup
car because of a fuel problem. ``We didn't have the car to race
with the leaders today, so getting on the podium is a great
finish,'' said Herta.
</P>
<P>
   Herta said some of the day's best driving was done by Kanaan, a
24-year-old Brazilian who was the 1998 rookie of the year with four
top five finishes. He led 44 laps Sunday before a turn nine miscue.
``Sometimes you learn the hard way,'' he said. ``It hurts, but I
proved to myself that I can run up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Fernandez won in Japan last week on an oval and was
fourth in Sunday's road course in a brand new chassis. Canada's
Greg Moore has 20 top five finishes in three seasons and doesn't
turn 24 until next week. And Christian Fittipaldi, the nephew of
racing legend Emerson Fittipaldi, was about the only driver
attempting to pass on a day in which the race had more parade-like
qualities.
</P>
<P>
   For tradition's sake, it's nice to have an Unser or an Andretti
around. But it's also nice to know Long Beach won't have to depend
on them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
