<HEADLINE>
LONG SHOT'S NAME HAS BETTER RING AFTER LONE STAR DERBY WIN
</HEADLINE>
 STAR DERBY-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ Chris Candies liked everything about T.B.
Track Star except the name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was terrible,'' he said. ``Until now.''
</P>
<P>
   What changed the mind of the 29-year-old trainer was hearing
T.B. Track Star called as the long shot winner of Sunday's $300,000
Lone Star Derby. The name has a certain ring to it now, Candies
concedes.
</P>
<P>
   T.B. Track Star, a 31-to-1 long shot ridden by Eddie Martin,
finished 11/4 lengths clear of Desert Demon and Julie Krone to
spoil Krone's swan song as a jockey. Congratulate, who opened an
eight-length backstretch lead in swift fractions, held on for
third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to catch him,'' said Krone, whose
high-pitched voice was audible on ESPN's replay as she screamed at
her mount in the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Black Mercury, the even-money favorite trained by Bob Baffert,
was never in the hunt. He finished fourth in the 11/16 mile race
after breaking awkwardly from the gate and getting sandwiched into
the first turn. Baffert saddled odds-on favorite Real Quiet to a
runner-up finish in the Texas Mile an hour earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The victory by T.B. Track Star helped erase the memory of a
bitter loss he suffered at Fair Grounds on March 29, when he was
disqualified from an allowance win in one of the most controversial
calls of the New Orleans track's season.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Sunday's race, he had officially won once in six
starts. But Candies was confident in the gray colt, claimed for
$20,000 in January by co-owner and previous trainer Forrest Lanning
of Kenner, La.
</P>
<P>
   Candies, a Thibodaux, La., native, said he had watched T.B.
Track Star for two months and tried to claim him out of the same
Fair Grounds maiden race, but lost the drawing to Lanning. He
finally got to train the horse when he purchased a half-interest
from Lanning for $40,000 on behalf of his father, Kevin, after the
race lost by disqualification.
</P>
<P>
   Candies decided to run T.B. Track Star in the Lone Star Derby
because the competition didn't appear formidable. And as the race
approached, he liked what he saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got stronger every day this week,'' Candies said. ``He
blossomed right before my eyes. He kind of put it all together for
us today. I thought maybe we could sit tactically in the race and
make a big-time move and win it, kind of like what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   T.B. Track Star patiently chased Congratulate for nearly a mile
before taking command in midstretch. He was timed in 1:42.92, and
paid $65.60, by far the highest price in three runnings for a Lone
Star Derby winner.
</P>
<P>
   None of the horses in the race will try the May 1 Kentucky
Derby, and T.B. Track Star is likely to run again at Lone Star this
season.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, T.B. Track Star was named by his Florida
breeder, Theodore Bottomley, a farm night watchman. Bottomley
acquired the colt's dam, She's a Barron, for free in lieu of
payment for services rendered. He names each of his mare's foals
with his initials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made the mistake of looking up his breeding,'' Lanning said
of T.B. Track Star. ``It's zero out of zero, by zero out of zero.
He's got no pedigree at all. But this horse is just an athlete.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
