<HEADLINE>
GENTILOZZI WINS AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Chris Neville, the reigning Trans-Am rookie
of the year, didn't waste any time before he pulled a big-time
rookie maneuver. Brian Simo, who founded the clothing company No
Fear, drove as if he had No Brain.
</P>
<P>
   With the two top qualifiers out of his way virtually before
Sunday's race began, Paul Gentilozzi cruised to his second
consecutive Trans-Am victory at Long Beach and third in the eight
races run here.
</P>
<P>
   Gentilozzi finished 2.7 seconds ahead of John Miller IV and 4.7
seconds ahead of Michael Lewis in a race that was shortened to 32
laps due to several cautions. This one, though, wasn't determined
at the finish but at the start.
</P>
<P>
   Neville, a promising 27-year-old who on Saturday had captured
his first pole, was pushed down Shoreline Drive and into the first
turn by Simo, who had won the final two races of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Neville, in trying to hold off Simo, hit his brakes too late,
spun 180 degrees and came to a stop in the middle of the track.
</P>
<P>
   Simo and Lewis skated past him to the right and Gentilozzi
squeaked past to the left. But Stu Hayner, who finished second last
year and had jumped from 10th to fifth on the start, came around
the corner and plowed into Neville knocking them both from the
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Brian was going to be aggressive he's from Southern
California and Chris is young and a little impetuous,'' said
Gentilozzi. ``I knew I only wanted to win the race (not the
start).''
</P>
<P>
   The pileup caused race officials to restart the race and when
they did, Simo drew a black flag and a stop-and-start penalty for
jumping the pace car.
</P>
<P>
   Simo went back to 19th and was eventually knocked out on the
eighth lap when he was part of a three-car pileup that started when
actor Craig T. Nelson, making his Trans-Am debut, crashed into the
tire barrier in front of the Aquarium of the Pacific fountain.
</P>
<P>
   Simo and Neville were unavailable for comment after the race,
but Gentilozzi said he was the benefactor of testosterone run amok.
</P>
<P>
   When Gentilozzi, who had won nine poles and seven of the 13
Trans-Am races last season, scrambled in the last week with changes
to his car and banged it up Saturday in qualifying, the rest of the
top contenders suddenly felt hope especially on a course in which
there are only two good passing opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were relegated to third (in qualifying) and when that
happened, everybody else starts feeling their oats and feels
immortal,'' Gentilozzi said. ``It was obvious that going into Turn
1 that Brian did a good job messing with Chris' head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what it's like to have your first pole. There's a lot
of pressure. ... I can remember the feeling that Chris was having
and I can sympathize with the way he feels now. He feels he got
robbed.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Simo's gaffe?
</P>
<P>
   ``He was going to the Queen Mary,'' said Gentilozzi. ``I don't
know where he was going. The rest of the field hadn't even passed
the hairpin (leading onto Shoreline Drive and the starting line)
and he took off. It was way too early.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who overtook Lewis for second after the caution was
lifted on Nelson's wreck, made a few nominal runs at Gentilozzi but
never mounted a serious charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to chase Paul down,'' said Miller, who finished third
in Long Beach last year. ``We got close a couple of times. The care
made a couple of mistakes and I made a couple of mistakes. We'll
just chase him some more.''
</P>
<P>
   It's something Neville and Simo would have loved to try Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
