<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: COUCH GETS SQUEEZED BEFORE FIRST GAME
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 12 hours before the NFL draft, Leigh Steinberg, the agent
for Oregon quarterback Akili Smith, had reached a tentative deal
with the Cleveland Browns, owners of the first pick.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg is one of the most skilled negotiators in the
business, and, being a draft-day veteran, he can smell a setup.
Something just did not feel right. So Steinberg went to the Browns
and pleaded with them: draft Kentucky's Tim Couch if you want, but
don't use Smith to make Couch more signable. The Browns said they
would not.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg's instincts proved accurate. The Browns indeed used
Smith to make sure Couch's signing bonus, which ended up being a
record $12.2 million, did not enter into the $14 million to $15
million stratosphere. It was a ruthless tactic but, to be blunt,
also a smart one. The Browns not only got their man, but also got
him at their price. The fat paycheck being earned by Carmen Policy,
the team president, is paying off.
</P>
<P>
   Policy is a shark, and it is that quality that allowed him to
keep the hands of the 49ers flush with Super Bowl rings. He will do
the same with the Browns. Make no mistake: Policy will have his new
franchise in the Super Bowl within five years.
</P>
<P>
   There were several teams that had excellent drafts , but the
Browns head the list because not only did they draft Couch, a
skilled passer with good character, but Policy also made sure the
finances stayed within reason. A signing bonus that could finance
two small countries would hurt the Browns in the long term, and
Policy needed to make sure Couch did not break the bank.
</P>
<P>
   As the two-day draft concluded Sunday night, the Browns were not
the only team to do well.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Cardinals, Minnesota Vikings, Tampa Bay Buccaneers,
Detroit Lions and Washington Redskins got A's. Arizona picked up
two starters in Ohio State wide receiver David Boston and Eastern
Michigan offensive tackle L.J. Shelton.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota drafted a talented protege to Randall Cunningham in
Central Florida quarterback Daunte Culpepper. The Vikings also
selected offensive lineman Jay Humphrey from the University of
Texas, the only decent long-snapper in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay can pair Louisiana State defensive tackle Anthony
McFarland with Warren Sapp. The Redskins made a blockbuster trade
to get cornerback Champ Bailey from the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The NFC East also got better. Quarterback Donovan McNabb is in
Philadelphia, Bailey is in Washington, Cardinals quarterback Jake
Plummer has a new target in Boston and protection for his backside
in Shelton. The Cowboys, facing life without Leon Lett because of a
drug suspension, picked a talented defensive tackle in North
Carolina's Ebenezer Ekuban.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some teams got better right away,'' Dave Campo, the Cowboys'
defensive coordinator, said of his division rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Chargers and the Giants made some of the more
questionable moves. Oklahoma running back Jermaine Fazande was
taken in the second round by the Chargers and South Dakota State
tight end Steve Heiden was picked in the third. Both are
fourth-rounders at best.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Accorsi, the Giants' general manager, is one of the
smartest personnel men in the business, but his second-round pick,
Ohio State running back Joe Montgomery, had some in the league
scratching their heads. Why take Montgomery in the second round
when he would have easily been there much later?
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the Miami Dolphins, who took one of the biggest
known risks in the draft by selecting troubled running back Cecil
Collins, a first-round talent with second-rate character. Collins
was arrested for unauthorized entry and battery while in college
and he also failed a drug test for marijuana while at McNeese
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deserves an opportunity,'' Miami coach Jimmy Johnson said
of Collins, a fifth-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing about Collins, former Giants running back Tyrone
Wheatley, now with the Dolphins, requested a trade, saying the
six-man backfield is too crowded.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Already there were some coaches and executives in the league who
were privately patting themselves on the back, saying that Collins
going low is proof that the league is learning its lessons when it
comes to troubled players. Then one assistant coach put things in
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   The coach said his team's security report, a document that
details players' arrests, listed some two dozen players who had
been accused of the same crimes as Collins or worse. The coach said
the litany of arrests included spousal abuse, armed robbery and gun
possession charges.
</P>
<P>
   And many of those players, the coach said, were drafted in the
first four rounds. They didn't suffer the same kind of news media
scrutiny that Collins did, so their alleged crimes were mostly
unknown. Thus, teams felt comfortable drafting them because their
misdeeds would most likely never become public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams want to do the right thing, honestly,'' the coach said,
``but then they see that big, fast back or that quarterback with
the great arm and go gaga. Teams want to win; that's the bottom
line of a draft.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
